window.CONTENT["4915"] = {"meta":{"id":"4915","code":"COMP 4915","name":"Special Topics in MIS (UNIX / Linux / Kubernetes)","exam":"2026-04-23T13:30:00-07:00","room":"SW01 3190","format":"Final Exam — MCQ + TF + SHORT + ESSAY","cheatsheet_allowed":false,"instructor":"Bruce Link","notes_html":"\u003cp\u003eSource: study guide cover &quot;Thu Apr 23 · 13:30 · SW01 3190&quot;.\u003c/p\u003e"},"modules":[{"id":"fs-perms","name":"Filesystem & permissions","topics":[{"id":"4915-filesystem","name":"Filesystem","tags":["filesystem","fundamentals"],"prose":"Flashcards covering Filesystem.","source":"Mod02 Ch6; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q18, Q25","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"What is the Unix root directory?","answer":"`/` — a single forward slash. Not `/root` (that's root user's home).","explanation":"Unix filesystems form a single inverted tree with `/` at the top; every mount point attaches below it. `/root` is just the home directory of the root user and sits at `/root`, not at the top of the tree.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Inode contents?","answer":"1. Owner\n2. Group\n3. Permissions\n4. Timestamps (atime/mtime/ctime)\n5. Size\n6. Link count\n7. File type\n8. Data-block pointers\n\n**NOT filename.**","explanation":"The inode is the on-disk metadata record for a file; the filename lives in the parent directory entry that maps name → inode number. This separation is exactly what makes hard links possible — multiple names can point at the same inode.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Why can't hard links cross filesystems?","answer":"Inode numbers are unique only within a single filesystem.","explanation":"A hard link is an extra directory entry pointing at an inode. Inode 5 on `/dev/sda1` is not the same object as inode 5 on `/dev/sdb1` — scope is per-FS. Soft links dodge this by storing the target *pathname* as data, so they cross FS freely.","example":"`ln /mnt/usb/file ~/link` → fails (`Invalid cross-device link`). `ln -s /mnt/usb/file ~/link` → works; the link file's contents is the literal string `/mnt/usb/file`.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"To link a file such that it exists even after original is deleted, which type?","answer":"**Hard link**. Soft/symbolic would dangle if target deleted.","explanation":"Unlink just decrements the inode's link count; the file's data survives until the count hits zero. A symlink holds a pathname, so if that path disappears the symlink dangles.","example":"`ln a b; rm a; cat b` → still works. `ln -s a c; rm a; cat c` → `No such file or directory`.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which permission set belongs to a symbolic link?","answer":"Real systems show `lrwxrwxrwx` — type `l`, all rwx. On midterm Q32, the closest option was `lrwxrwxrw-` (typo in original exam — last x dropped).","explanation":"Symlink permissions are ignored by the kernel — access is always resolved against the target's perms. The shown `rwxrwxrwx` is a cosmetic convention so users don't get confused by restricted-looking symlinks.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Name the 7 Unix file types shown in ls -l first char.","answer":"1. `-` plain\n2. `d` directory\n3. `b` block\n4. `c` character\n5. `l` symlink\n6. `s` socket\n7. `p` named pipe","explanation":"The first character of `ls -l` output encodes the inode's type field. Block and character devices differ in whether I/O is buffered in fixed-size blocks (disks) or streamed byte-by-byte (terminals, `/dev/null`).","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What two entries does every directory contain?","answer":"`.` (self) and `..` (parent).","explanation":"These are real directory entries written at `mkdir` time — `.` points to the directory's own inode, `..` to its parent's. `cd ..` works because of this link; the root directory's `..` points to itself.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"You mounted Windows D: at /mnt/win. How do you cd to D:\\\\work\\\\faxes in Linux?","answer":"`cd /mnt/win/work/faxes`.","explanation":"Mounting grafts a foreign filesystem onto the Linux tree at the mount point. Drive letters and backslashes don't exist in Linux — everything becomes a subtree of `/` using forward slashes.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Linux command to create a directory?","answer":"`mkdir`.","explanation":"`mkdir` writes a new directory entry in the parent and allocates an inode with type `d`. Use `-p` to create missing intermediate parents in one call.","example":"`mkdir -p /tmp/a/b/c` creates all three if absent; plain `mkdir /tmp/a/b/c` fails unless `/tmp/a/b` already exists.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"T/F: Linux can read files on partitions formatted for DOS/OS2/Windows?","answer":"TRUE — with appropriate filesystem drivers (vfat, ntfs-3g, etc.).","explanation":"The VFS layer dispatches syscalls to whichever filesystem driver handles the mount. As long as a driver module is loaded (vfat, exfat, ntfs-3g), the partition mounts like any other.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-permissions","name":"Permissions","tags":["permissions","fundamentals"],"prose":"10-char ls display: [type][u][g][o]. Each rwx triplet = 3 bits.","source":"Mod02 Ch6-7; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q16, Q32","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Make jack owner of all files under /home/jack/candy?","answer":"`chown -R jack /home/jack/candy`. Capital -R, not -r.","explanation":"`chown` is the one common tool that uses capital `-R` for recursion — every other tool (grep, cp, ls, rm) uses lowercase `-r`. Lowercase `-r` is not a valid chown flag.","example":"`chown -R jack:jack /home/jack/candy` also fixes group. Confirm with `ls -l /home/jack/candy | head`.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"`chmod 755 file` — owner/group/other?","answer":"owner rwx (7=4+2+1), group r-x (5=4+0+1), other r-x (5=4+0+1).","explanation":"Each octal digit is a 3-bit permission triplet. `chmod 755` sets absolutely — it wipes any other bits. Use `chmod +x` to only *add* the execute bit without touching the rest.","example":"`chmod 755 script.sh; ls -l script.sh` → `-rwxr-xr-x`. `chmod 644 data.txt` → `-rw-r--r--`.","bloom":"apply"},{"type":"predict","prompt":"After `umask 022 && chmod 600 secret.txt && ls -l secret.txt`, what does `ls -l` show?","answer":"`-rw-------`. umask only applies to *new* files; explicit chmod overrides it.","explanation":"umask subtracts from creation defaults (666 for files, 777 for dirs) — it never touches existing files. `chmod` sets the bits absolutely, so 600 wins regardless of the current umask.","example":"`touch new.txt; ls -l new.txt` → `-rw-r--r--` (666 & ~022). Now `chmod 600 new.txt` → `-rw-------`.","source":"research-mod01-02.md §Permissions; Mod02 Ch7; materials/labs/Lab2.pdf","bloom":"apply"},{"type":"name","prompt":"umask 022 — new file and dir permissions?","answer":"File 644 (666 & ~022), dir 755 (777 & ~022).","explanation":"umask is a bitmask of bits to *remove* from defaults. Files start at 666 (no execute), directories at 777 (execute = traverse). 022 clears w from group and other.","example":"`umask 022; touch f; ls -l f` → `-rw-r--r--`. `mkdir d; ls -ld d` → `drwxr-xr-x`.","bloom":"apply"}]},{"id":"4915-chroot","name":"chroot","tags":["containers","kubernetes"],"prose":"Flashcards covering chroot.","source":"Mod10C Ch10; materials/labs/Lab10.pdf","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"What does chroot do?","answer":"Changes apparent root directory for a process — filesystem-level jail.","explanation":"After chroot, the process sees the new directory as `/` and cannot `cd` above it through normal path resolution. It predates namespaces and is the mental prototype for modern container filesystem isolation — containers layer MNT namespaces + pivot_root on top for a stronger jail.","example":"`sudo chroot /srv/jailenv /bin/bash` — bash sees /srv/jailenv as `/`, can't access /etc or /home on the host.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-umask","name":"umask","tags":["permissions","sysadmin"],"prose":"10-char ls display: [type][u][g][o]. Each rwx triplet = 3 bits.","source":"Mod02 Ch7; materials/labs/Lab2.pdf","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Calculate directory perms with umask 027.","answer":"777 & ~027 = 750. Owner rwx, group r-x, other nothing.","explanation":"Directory default is 777 because execute on a directory means \"traverse\" — needed to cd into it. umask 027 clears w from group (2) and rwx from other (7), leaving 750.","example":"`umask 027; mkdir shared; ls -ld shared` → `drwxr-x---`.","bloom":"apply"},{"type":"predict","prompt":"umask 077 is set. `touch secret; mkdir private; ls -l secret; ls -ld private` — predict the mode strings.","answer":"`-rw-------` and `drwx------`. 666 & ~077 = 600; 777 & ~077 = 700.","explanation":"umask 077 clears rwx from group and other entirely — only the owner keeps any access. This is the standard paranoia umask for private workspaces.","example":"Compare: `umask 022; touch f` → `-rw-r--r--`; `umask 077; touch g` → `-rw-------`.","source":"research-mod01-02.md §Permissions; Mod02 Ch7; materials/labs/Lab2.pdf; midterm Q16 proximal","bloom":"apply"}]},{"id":"4915-flags","name":"Flags","tags":["shell"],"prose":"Flashcards covering Flags.","source":"Mod01 Ch4","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Can you combine single-letter flags? Example?","answer":"Yes. `ls -r -x` same as `ls -rx`. Most commands accept combined short options.","explanation":"POSIX `getopt`-style short options are single-character and bundleable. Long options (GNU style, `--reverse`) cannot be bundled because the parser needs word boundaries.","example":"`ls -lah` = `ls -l -a -h`. `tar -czf` = `tar -c -z -f`.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-setgid","name":"setgid","tags":["permissions","fundamentals"],"prose":"Flashcards covering setgid.","source":"Mod02 Ch7","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"What does setgid do on a file vs a directory?","answer":"On a file: process runs with the file's group GID. On a directory: new files inherit the directory's group (collaboration pattern).","explanation":"setgid repurposes the same bit for two behaviors. On executables it elevates group privileges during execution; on directories it changes the default-group policy so team-shared folders stay owned by the shared group.","example":"`chmod g+s /srv/team` — new files created inside inherit group `team` automatically, enabling collaboration without manual chown.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-setuid","name":"setuid","tags":["permissions","fundamentals"],"prose":"Flashcards covering setuid.","source":"Mod02 Ch7","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"What does setuid do?","answer":"Executable runs with the file owner's UID regardless of who launched it. Classic example: /usr/bin/passwd runs as root.","explanation":"setuid is how unprivileged users perform privileged operations like changing their own password — the binary flips the effective UID to root for the duration of the call. The security footprint is significant; misused setuid binaries are a classic privilege-escalation vector.","example":"`ls -l /usr/bin/passwd` → `-rwsr-xr-x root root` — the `s` in user-execute position is the setuid bit. Any user running passwd temporarily runs as root.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-hard-link","name":"Hard link","tags":["filesystem","fundamentals"],"prose":"An inode holds: owner, group, modes, timestamps (atime/mtime/ctime), size, link count, type, data-block pointers. NOT filename.","source":"Mod02 Ch6; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q24, Q58","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Can you tell which of two hard-linked files is the 'original'?","answer":"No. Both are equal directory entries pointing to the same inode. There is no 'original' after the link is made.","explanation":"Hard link = extra directory entry pointing at an inode. Inode scope is per-FS, so crossing FS breaks the pointer. Soft links store the pathname as data and cross FS freely. (research-mod01-02.md §Hard vs Soft Link)","example":"`ln /mnt/usb/file ~/link` → fails (cross-FS). `ln -s /mnt/usb/file ~/link` → works; the link file contains the text '/mnt/usb/file'.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"predict","prompt":"`echo hi \u003e a; ln a b; rm a; cat b` — what prints?","answer":"`hi`. Removing `a` only decrements the link count; the inode (and its data) survives because `b` still points at it.","explanation":"`rm` is literally `unlink` — it removes the directory entry, not the file data. Data is freed only when link count drops to 0 AND no process holds the file open.","example":"Contrast soft links: `echo hi \u003e a; ln -s a c; rm a; cat c` → `No such file or directory` (symlink dangles).","source":"research-mod01-02.md §Hard vs Soft Link; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q24, Q58","bloom":"apply"}]},{"id":"4915-soft-link","name":"Soft link","tags":["filesystem","fundamentals"],"prose":"An inode holds: owner, group, modes, timestamps (atime/mtime/ctime), size, link count, type, data-block pointers. NOT filename.","source":"Mod02 Ch6; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q32, Q58","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"How do you create a soft link?","answer":"`ln -s target linkname`. Creates a new file whose content is the pathname of the target.","explanation":"A symlink is its own tiny file; the data block just stores the target path as a string. That's why `ls -l` shows `link -\u003e target` — the kernel follows the stored path on access.","example":"`ln -s /etc/nginx/sites-available/site.conf /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/site.conf` — standard nginx enable pattern.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-storage","name":"Storage","tags":["fundamentals"],"prose":"Flashcards covering Storage.","source":"Mod05 Ch10","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Performance difference: rotating disk vs SSD for file access?","answer":"Rotating (HDD) slower due to seek time. SSD much faster but has **limited write cycles** per cell.","explanation":"HDDs pay a mechanical seek cost (~5-10 ms) on every non-sequential access; SSDs are uniform-latency but each flash cell wears out after ~1000-100000 program/erase cycles, making wear-leveling a critical firmware concern.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-fstab","name":"fstab","tags":["filesystem","sysadmin"],"prose":"Flashcards covering fstab.","source":"Mod05 Ch10","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Basic fstab fields you MUST know?","answer":"1. Device\n2. Mount point\n3. Filesystem type\n4. Options\n\n(Per instructor: NOT the last 2 — dump and fsck pass.)","explanation":"`/etc/fstab` is the declarative mount table read at boot and by `mount -a`. The last two fields (dump frequency, fsck pass order) are legacy holdovers — modern systems rarely rely on them.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-acl","name":"ACL","tags":["permissions","fundamentals"],"prose":"Flashcards covering ACL.","source":"Review Apr 17 (explicitly out of scope)","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Do you need ACL (Access Control List) details on the exam?","answer":"No. Instructor said ACL details not needed.","explanation":"ACLs (getfacl/setfacl) layer per-user/per-group permissions on top of the classic owner/group/other model — useful in the wild but explicitly out of scope for this course.","bloom":"remember"}]}]},{"id":"shell-text","name":"Shell, redirection & text processing","topics":[{"id":"4915-shell","name":"Shell","tags":["shell"],"prose":"Process substitution &lt;(cmd), &gt;(cmd) is a bash feature beyond basic 7.","source":"Mod01 Ch4-5, Mod04 Ch9","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"What does Ctrl+D do at a shell prompt?","answer":"End of input / log out of shell. (Midterm Q15.)","explanation":"Ctrl+D sends EOF to the terminal's line discipline. At an interactive shell with an empty line, reading EOF on stdin exits the shell; inside a program it closes the input stream.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What does `cd ~` do?","answer":"Change to your account's home directory.","explanation":"`~` is a shell expansion (tilde expansion, step 2 of the 7) that evaluates to `$HOME`. `~user` expands to user's home; `~+` is `$PWD`, `~-` is `$OLDPWD`.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"By default, Linux command arguments are separated by what?","answer":"Spaces or tabs (white space, per default IFS).","explanation":"IFS (Internal Field Separator) defaults to space/tab/newline. Word splitting (step 6 of 7 expansions) uses IFS to chop unquoted variable expansions into arg tokens.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"How do you run a bash command in the background?","answer":"Terminate with `&`. Example: `long_task &`.","explanation":"`&` forks the command and returns control to the shell immediately. The job continues running; capture its PID with `$!`, and `wait` to synchronize.","example":"`sleep 60 & echo $!` — prints the sleep PID so you can kill it.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which command changes your login shell?","answer":"`chsh`.","explanation":"`chsh` edits the user's /etc/passwd shell field. The new shell must be listed in `/etc/shells` for security.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What's the Linux account with special admin privileges called?","answer":"Superuser (also known as root).","explanation":"Root is UID 0 — the kernel's permission checks skip for UID 0, so root can do essentially anything. This is why sudo carefully controls who can assume root identity.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which command sends a signal to a process?","answer":"`kill`. (Despite the name, it can send any signal, not just SIGKILL.)","explanation":"`kill -l` lists all 31+ signals. Default is SIGTERM (15) — a polite request. SIGKILL (9) is the nuclear option and cannot be caught or ignored.","example":"`kill -HUP $(pgrep nginx)` asks nginx to reload config. `kill -9 1234` force-terminates PID 1234.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What is a Unix PPID?","answer":"Parent Process ID.","explanation":"Every process except init/systemd has a parent that spawned it via fork. PPID is used by process-tree tools (`pstree`) and signal propagation.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"How to find currently defined aliases?","answer":"`alias` — run with no arguments.","explanation":"Aliases are the first name-resolution step in bash (before keywords, functions, builtins, $PATH). `alias` with no args prints the full table; `unalias name` removes one.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Command to display value of variable myvar?","answer":"`echo $myvar` (or `echo \"$myvar\"` to preserve spaces).","explanation":"Unquoted `$var` goes through word splitting — whitespace inside the value becomes separate args. Quoting with double quotes suppresses word splitting but still expands `$var`.","example":"`v='a  b'; echo $v` → `a b` (split). `echo \"$v\"` → `a  b` (preserved).","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What does a pipe `|` do?","answer":"Connects stdout of one process to stdin of the next.","explanation":"`|` creates a kernel pipe (anonymous FIFO); the shell runs both commands concurrently with the pipe's read end as cmd2's fd0 and write end as cmd1's fd1. Stderr stays on fd2 and is NOT piped unless you `2\u003e&1` first.","example":"`ps aux | grep nginx | wc -l` — three processes running in parallel, streaming data.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Bring background job number 2 to foreground?","answer":"`fg %2`.","explanation":"Jobs are numbered per-shell (`jobs` lists them). `fg %N` moves job N to foreground, `bg %N` resumes it in background. `%%` or bare `fg` picks the current job.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which command pushes a directory on the stack?","answer":"`pushd`.","explanation":"`pushd dir` cd's to `dir` and pushes the old dir on the stack; `popd` returns. Useful for temporary excursions. `dirs` prints the stack.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-text-utils","name":"Text utils","tags":["fundamentals"],"prose":"Flashcards covering Text utils.","source":"Mod02 Ch7; materials/labs/Lab4.pdf","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"What does `grep` do?","answer":"Reads through files and displays lines matching a pattern.","explanation":"grep (global regex print) scans input line-by-line and prints matches. Name comes from the ed command `g/re/p`. Works on stdin when no file given.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Correct command to search for word 'superman' in SuperHeroes?","answer":"`grep -w superman SuperHeroes`. `-w` matches whole word.","explanation":"Without `-w`, `grep superman` also matches `supermanager` or `antisuperman`. `-w` requires non-word chars at both boundaries.","example":"`grep -w cat animals.txt` matches 'cat' but not 'category' or 'concatenate'.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What does `tr` do?","answer":"Maps (translates) one string of characters to another. Also deletes with `-d`.","explanation":"`tr` is a pure filter — no file argument. It works character-by-character on stdin and writes to stdout. Use `-d` to delete, `-s` to squeeze repeats.","example":"`echo HELLO | tr A-Z a-z` → `hello`. `echo 'a  b' | tr -s ' '` → `a b`.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What does `tr -d '\\r'` convert?","answer":"Deletes carriage returns — converts DOS/Windows text files (CRLF) to Unix (LF).","explanation":"DOS files end lines with `\\r\\n`; Unix uses `\\n` alone. Stray `\\r` characters cause mysterious script failures (`#!/bin/bash\\r` on the shebang line breaks execution).","example":"`tr -d '\\r' \u003c windows.txt \u003e unix.txt`. Verify with `file unix.txt` → 'ASCII text' (not 'with CRLF').","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which command displays the last part of a file?","answer":"`tail`.","explanation":"`tail` defaults to last 10 lines; `-n N` changes the count, `-f` follows growing files (log tailing). Pairs with `head` for the opposite end.","example":"`tail -f /var/log/syslog` watches log entries append in real time.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which command counts lines/words/chars in a file?","answer":"`wc`. `wc -l` for just line count.","explanation":"wc prints three counts by default. `-l` lines, `-w` words, `-c` bytes, `-m` characters. Commonly piped: `ls | wc -l` counts files.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What does `less` do?","answer":"Displays a text file one screen at a time — interactive pager.","explanation":"`less` is `more` with backward scrolling, search, and tail-follow. `q` quits, `/pattern` searches forward, `?pattern` backward, `G` jumps to end.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which is NOT a regex metacharacter: $, ^, =, .?","answer":"`=` is not a regex metacharacter.","explanation":"`^` anchors line start, `$` anchors line end, `.` matches any single char. `=` is a literal equal sign in regex — no special meaning.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-find","name":"Find","tags":["text-processing","fundamentals"],"prose":"Instructor: grep with * — quote the pattern: grep \"pattern\" *. Unquoted, shell glob expands * to filenames, first becomes pattern.","source":"Mod02 Ch7; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q19","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Locate a file named foo with no idea of location — command?","answer":"`find / -name foo`. Must specify start path; search entire tree.","explanation":"`find` walks the directory tree from the given root and applies tests per file. `-name` matches the basename (shell glob syntax, not regex). Unlike `locate`, find is always live — no database staleness.","example":"`find / -name 'config.yaml' 2\u003e/dev/null` — the redirect swallows permission-denied errors from restricted dirs.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"predict","prompt":"`find /var/log -type f -mtime -7 -name '*.log'` — what does this return?","answer":"All regular files named `*.log` under /var/log modified in the last 7 days.","explanation":"`-type f` restricts to plain files (not dirs or sockets). `-mtime -7` means mtime within last 7 × 24h. `-name '*.log'` needs quotes so the shell doesn't glob-expand before find sees it.","example":"Swap `-mtime -7` for `-mtime +30` to find files OLDER than 30 days — useful for cleanup: `find /tmp -type f -mtime +30 -delete`.","source":"Mod02 Ch7; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q19","bloom":"apply"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Find .tmp files and delete them with find?","answer":"`find /path -name '*.tmp' -type f -delete` or `-exec rm {} \\;`.","explanation":"`-delete` is find's built-in unlink (fast, no fork); `-exec rm {} \\;` forks `rm` once per match (slow). Use `-exec rm {} +` to batch filenames per rm invocation.","example":"`find . -name '*.bak' -type f -delete` cleans backup files in the current tree.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-redirection","name":"Redirection","tags":["redirection","shell"],"prose":"Order trap: cmd &gt; f 2&gt;&amp;1 works (redirect stdout, then merge stderr into it). cmd 2&gt;&amp;1 &gt; f does NOT — stderr goes to terminal, only stdout goes to f.","source":"Mod01 Ch5; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q10, Q43, Q44, Q50","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Command to send output to a file AND stdout?","answer":"`tee`. `cmd | tee file`.","explanation":"`tee` reads stdin and writes to both stdout and each named file. Named after a T-shaped pipe fitting. `-a` appends instead of overwriting.","example":"`make 2\u003e&1 | tee build.log` — see the output live AND capture it.","bloom":"apply"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Command directing stdout to outfile and stderr to errfile?","answer":"`make FreeCiv \u003eoutfile 2\u003eerrfile`. (1\u003e is same as \u003e; 0 is stdin.)","explanation":"Each fd has its own redirection slot. `\u003efile` opens file for writing on fd 1; `2\u003efile2` opens file2 on fd 2. The two streams go to separate destinations with no order dependency.","example":"`gcc main.c \u003ecompile.log 2\u003eerrors.log` — warnings/errors in one file, regular output in another.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"T/F: Redirecting output to a file can destroy an existing file without error.","answer":"**TRUE**. No warning unless noclobber set.","explanation":"`\u003e` opens the target file with O_TRUNC — it's wiped to zero length atomically before the command even runs. No prompt, no backup. Protect with `set -o noclobber` (then use `\u003e|` to force-overwrite).","example":"`echo new \u003e important.txt` silently replaces important.txt. `\u003e\u003e` appends instead.","bloom":"apply"},{"type":"name","prompt":"T/F: If you accidentally overwrite a file using redirection, you get a warning.","answer":"**FALSE**. Silent destruction by default.","explanation":"The shell's redirection operator is `O_WRONLY | O_CREAT | O_TRUNC` — file is truncated the instant the shell parses the redirection, before the command runs. Noclobber must be explicitly enabled.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Output of `cat x y 1\u003ehold 2\u003e&1; cat hold` if x missing, y='This is y'?","answer":"```bash cat: x: No such file or directory This is y ``` stderr merged into stdout before both redirect into hold.","explanation":"`1\u003ehold` binds fd 1 to hold; `2\u003e&1` duplicates *the current binding of fd 1* onto fd 2, so stderr also goes to hold. Order matters: `2\u003e&1 1\u003ehold` would send stderr to the terminal (fd 1's old binding).","example":"`cmd \u003eout 2\u003e&1` is the canonical 'both streams into out'. `cmd 2\u003e&1 \u003eout` is a classic bug — stdout goes to out, stderr stays on the terminal.","bloom":"apply"},{"type":"name","prompt":"T/F: Process stores exit status of last command in `$?`?","answer":"TRUE.","explanation":"`$?` reads the most recent foreground command's exit status. 0 = success; non-zero = various errors (convention: 1 = general, 2 = misuse, 126 = not executable, 127 = not found, 128+N = killed by signal N).","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Three main shell redirection operators?","answer":"`\u003e` stdout to file (overwrite); `\u003e\u003e` stdout to file (append); `\u003c` stdin from file.","explanation":"These map to open(2) with different flags: `\u003e` is O_WRONLY|O_CREAT|O_TRUNC, `\u003e\u003e` is O_WRONLY|O_CREAT|O_APPEND, `\u003c` is O_RDONLY. The shell performs the open before exec'ing the command.","example":"`sort \u003c input.txt \u003e output.txt` — read input, write sorted output.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-quoting","name":"Quoting","tags":["shell"],"prose":"Backslash at end of line escapes the newline — continue long command on next line.","source":"Mod04 Ch9; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q17, Q47","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"person=jenny. Output of `echo '$person'`?","answer":"`$person` — literal. Single quotes suppress parameter expansion.","explanation":"Single quotes are absolutely literal — no expansions of any kind inside. Double quotes allow `$var`, `` `cmd` ``, `$(cmd)`, and `\\` escapes but suppress word splitting and glob.","example":"`echo '$person'` → `$person`. `echo \"$person\"` → `jenny`. `echo $person` → `jenny` (and word-split).","bloom":"apply"},{"type":"predict","prompt":"`name='Dr. $USER'; echo \"$name\"` given USER=alice — what prints?","answer":"`Dr. $USER`. Assignment was single-quoted, so `$USER` was stored literally; the double-quoted echo doesn't re-expand stored content.","explanation":"Expansion happens at *assignment parse time* when single-quoted, not at use time. The string stored in `name` is the literal 8 characters `Dr. $USER`. `echo` receives that string and prints it — no second-pass expansion.","example":"Compare `name=\"Dr. $USER\"` → stores `Dr. alice` at assignment, then echo prints `Dr. alice`.","source":"Mod04 Ch9; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q17, Q47","bloom":"apply"}]},{"id":"4915-globbing","name":"Globbing","tags":["shell"],"prose":"Flashcards covering Globbing.","source":"Mod04 Ch9; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q15","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Files: libby1-12.jpg + libby1.txt. What matches `libby1*.jpg`?","answer":"`libby1.jpg, libby10.jpg, libby11.jpg, libby12.jpg`. Matches libby1 + any chars + .jpg.","explanation":"Shell glob `*` matches zero or more chars within a filename (not across `/`). So `libby1*.jpg` matches anything starting with `libby1` and ending with `.jpg` — including `libby1.jpg` (zero chars between).","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What matches `libby[6-8].jpg`?","answer":"`libby6.jpg, libby7.jpg, libby8.jpg` — char class single char.","explanation":"`[...]` is a bracket expression matching *exactly one* character from the set. `[6-8]` is a range = `[678]`. Fixed-width; won't match `libby10.jpg`.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Why is `grep *` dangerous without quotes?","answer":"Shell globs `*` to filenames first; first filename becomes grep's pattern. Always quote: `grep \"pattern\" *`.","explanation":"Globbing (step 7 of 7 expansions) happens before grep runs. Unquoted `*` expands to the file list, then grep interprets arg[1] as its pattern — giving you something like `grep a.txt b.txt c.txt` which greps for `a.txt` in `b.txt` and `c.txt`.","example":"`grep *` in a dir with a.txt, b.txt → actually runs `grep a.txt b.txt` → searches for 'a.txt' in b.txt. Fix: `grep 'pattern' *`.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-bit-bucket","name":"Bit bucket","tags":["fundamentals"],"prose":"Flashcards covering Bit bucket.","source":"Mod01 Ch5","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Name of the Linux bit-bucket?","answer":"`/dev/null`.","explanation":"`/dev/null` is a character special device — writes are silently discarded, reads return EOF instantly. Used to suppress noise: `cmd 2\u003e/dev/null` hides stderr.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-grep","name":"grep","tags":["text-processing","fundamentals"],"prose":"Instructor: grep with * — quote the pattern: grep \"pattern\" *. Unquoted, shell glob expands * to filenames, first becomes pattern.","source":"Mod02 Ch7; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q34","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Command to display lines in current dir files that do NOT contain bb/bB/Bb/BB?","answer":"`grep -vi bb *`. -v invert, -i ignore case.","explanation":"`-v` inverts the match (show non-matching lines). `-i` ignores case. Combined flags compose — `grep -vi` means case-insensitive invert.","example":"`grep -vi error application.log` shows all lines that don't mention 'error' in any case.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Command to case-insensitive count of lines matching 'error' in log?","answer":"`grep -ic error log`. -i ignore case, -c count.","explanation":"`-c` suppresses normal output and prints just the count of matching lines. `-i` makes `Error`, `ERROR`, `error` all match. Note: `-c` counts lines, not matches — multiple matches on one line count as 1.","example":"`grep -ic timeout app.log` → `42` (42 lines contain 'timeout' case-insensitively).","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"predict","prompt":"File `heroes` has lines `superman`, `Super-Man`, `SUPERCAR`. What does `grep -iw super heroes` print?","answer":"Nothing. `-w` requires word boundaries around `super`; none of those lines have `super` as a whole word.","explanation":"`-w` treats the pattern as a whole word — non-word chars must border the match on both sides. `superman` has letters after `super`, so it fails. `-i` would match `Super-Man` if `-w` were absent, because `-` is a non-word char.","example":"`grep -iw 'super' heroes` still matches nothing. `grep -i 'super' heroes` matches all three.","source":"Mod02 Ch7; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q34","bloom":"apply"}]},{"id":"4915-filter","name":"Filter","tags":["text-processing","shell"],"prose":"Kernel firewall. Packet walks through tables → chains → rules.","source":"Mod02 Ch7","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"In `who | sort | lpr`, what is sort an example of?","answer":"A **filter** — reads from stdin, transforms, writes to stdout.","explanation":"A filter is any program that consumes stdin and produces stdout without needing file arguments. Pipes are built to chain filters; each filter stays generic because it only talks to fd 0 and fd 1.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-history","name":"History","tags":["shell","fundamentals"],"prose":"Instructor said: \"only vague idea needed. No deep dates.\"","source":"Mod04 Ch9","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Who developed the Linux kernel?","answer":"Linus Torvalds.","explanation":"Torvalds started Linux in 1991 as a hobby OS for his 386. The kernel is just the core scheduler/memory/driver layer; the rest of a \"Linux\" system is GNU userland plus distro choices.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Two key names associated with Linux and GNU?","answer":"**Linus Torvalds** (Linux kernel, 1991) and **Richard Stallman** (GNU project, Free Software Foundation).","explanation":"Stallman's GNU project (1983) built the userland (gcc, bash, coreutils) that Linux later integrated to become a complete OS. Their licenses (GPL) shaped free software distribution.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-editor","name":"Editor","tags":["editor","fundamentals"],"prose":"Flashcards covering Editor.","source":"Mod04 Ch9","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"T/F: Linux can run some programs developed for other OS like Windows/DOS?","answer":"TRUE — with emulation layers (Wine, DOSBox, etc.).","explanation":"Wine translates Win32 syscalls to Linux equivalents; DOSBox emulates x86 real-mode + DOS. Neither is a VM — they're syscall-level compatibility layers.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-stderr","name":"stderr","tags":["redirection","shell"],"prose":"Flashcards covering stderr.","source":"Mod01 Ch5; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q10","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"How do you redirect stderr to a file?","answer":"`2\u003e` — example `cmd 2\u003e err.log`. Merge with stdout: `2\u003e&1`.","explanation":"stderr is fd 2 and is explicitly separate from stdout so error messages don't contaminate pipes. `2\u003e&1` duplicates fd 1's current binding onto fd 2 — order matters.","example":"`cmd 2\u003e/dev/null` silences errors but keeps normal output. `cmd \u003eout 2\u003e&1` sends both to out.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-grep-recursive","name":"grep recursive","tags":["text-processing","fundamentals"],"prose":"Instructor: grep with * — quote the pattern: grep \"pattern\" *. Unquoted, shell glob expands * to filenames, first becomes pattern.","source":"Mod02 Ch7","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Flag to make grep search recursively through directories?","answer":"`-r` (or `-R`). Also available as separate command `rgrep` on some systems.","explanation":"Unlike chown/chgrp, grep uses lowercase `-r` for recursive. `-R` additionally follows symlinks. Common combo `-rn` numbers lines for jump-to-line editor integration.","example":"`grep -rn 'TODO' src/` — find every TODO under src/ with file:line prefix.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-dev-null","name":"/dev/null","tags":["redirection","fundamentals"],"prose":"An inode holds: owner, group, modes, timestamps (atime/mtime/ctime), size, link count, type, data-block pointers. NOT filename.","source":"Mod01 Ch5; Review Apr 17","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"What is `/dev/null`?","answer":"Bit bucket — character special file. Discards all writes; reads return EOF immediately.","explanation":"The kernel's null device driver responds to writes with success (bytes dropped) and to reads with zero bytes (EOF). Used everywhere to silence command output without disk I/O.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-dev-zero","name":"/dev/zero","tags":["fundamentals"],"prose":"An inode holds: owner, group, modes, timestamps (atime/mtime/ctime), size, link count, type, data-block pointers. NOT filename.","source":"Mod01 Ch5; Review Apr 17","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"What does `/dev/zero` return when read?","answer":"An infinite stream of null bytes (0x00). Used to create zero-filled files: `dd if=/dev/zero of=file bs=1M count=10`.","explanation":"Paired opposite of /dev/null — infinite source of zero bytes vs infinite sink. Used to allocate swapfiles, initialize disks, and benchmark read throughput.","bloom":"remember"}]}]},{"id":"processes-scheduling","name":"Processes & scheduling","topics":[{"id":"4915-pipes","name":"Pipes","tags":["redirection","shell"],"prose":"Order trap: cmd &gt; f 2&gt;&amp;1 works (redirect stdout, then merge stderr into it). cmd 2&gt;&amp;1 &gt; f does NOT — stderr goes to terminal, only stdout goes to f.","source":"Mod01 Ch5; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q30","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"What does `cat file | more` do?","answer":"Pipes stdout of cat into stdin of more — displays file one screen at a time via the pager.","explanation":"Both commands run concurrently in separate processes connected by a kernel pipe. `cat file | more` is a slightly wasteful version of `more file` — cat is the classic \"useless use of cat\" example.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-background","name":"Background","tags":["processes","shell"],"prose":"Flashcards covering Background.","source":"Mod04 Ch9; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q26","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"How do you put a process in the background when starting it?","answer":"Append `&`. Example `long_task &` — returns control immediately.","explanation":"`&` forks the process and detaches it from the shell's foreground-process group. Output still goes to the terminal unless redirected; the shell prints a job number for `fg`/`kill` reference.","example":"`./backup.sh \u003e backup.log 2\u003e&1 &` — run in background, all output to file, free the prompt.","bloom":"understand"}]}]},{"id":"networking","name":"Networking","topics":[{"id":"4915-networking","name":"Networking","tags":["networking","network"],"prose":"Flashcards covering Networking.","source":"Mod03 Ch8, Mod06 Ch18-19","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Secure technology for serving files over internet?","answer":"`sftp` (SSH-based). ftp, http, rsh all less secure.","explanation":"sftp tunnels file transfer over an SSH channel — credentials and data both encrypted. Plain ftp sends passwords in cleartext; rsh does too and trusts .rhosts for authorization.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which command connects to remote Linux and securely runs programs?","answer":"`ssh`. rlogin, telnet, rsh are insecure.","explanation":"ssh encrypts the channel and authenticates both endpoints. telnet and rlogin predate crypto and send passwords as cleartext — they're historical and shouldn't exist in production.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What forwards a port through an encrypted connection?","answer":"`ssh` (with `-L` local or `-R` remote forwarding).","explanation":"ssh can tunnel arbitrary TCP streams over its encrypted channel. Useful for reaching services behind a firewall without exposing them, or giving a remote service a secure back-channel to your local machine.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"T/F: rsh, rlogin, rcp all have security risks.","answer":"**TRUE**. Cleartext, .rhosts spoofable.","explanation":"The r-commands (rsh, rlogin, rcp) authenticate via .rhosts files listing trusted hosts/users — easily spoofed with DNS or IP tricks. Data travels unencrypted. Replaced by ssh, scp, sftp.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"File listing hosts denied network service access?","answer":"`/etc/hosts.deny`.","explanation":"tcpwrappers (libwrap) consults `/etc/hosts.allow` first, then `/etc/hosts.deny`. First match wins. Only applies to services built with libwrap — many modern daemons use their own ACLs instead.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Daemon managing a machine's DNS?","answer":"`named` (part of BIND).","explanation":"BIND (Berkeley Internet Name Domain) ships `named` as its server. Config lives in `/etc/named.conf`; zone data in `/var/named/*.zone`. Restart with `systemctl restart named` or reload with `rndc reload`.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What describes `odyssey.infosys.bcit.ca`?","answer":"Fully Qualified hostname (FQDN).","explanation":"An FQDN walks the full DNS tree from host up to TLD. Left-to-right goes more specific; right-to-left walks toward the root (trailing dot implicit). Unqualified names get resolved against the search list in `/etc/resolv.conf`.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Service to offer remote mounting of Linux partitions on a Linux-only network?","answer":"**NFS**. (SMB for Windows, NIS for user/group info, DNS for names.)","explanation":"NFS is POSIX-semantic file sharing between Unix hosts — supports hard links, symlinks, owner/group/mode. Windows speaks SMB; Samba bridges the two worlds.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-nfs","name":"NFS","tags":["networking","network"],"prose":"Linux-to-Linux file sharing. NOT for Windows (use Samba).","source":"Mod07 Ch22; materials/labs/Lab7.pdf","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Config file defining NFS exports?","answer":"`/etc/exports`.","explanation":"`/etc/exports` is space-delimited: `path client(options)`. After editing, run `exportfs -ra` to refresh the in-kernel export table without a full restart.","example":"`/srv/data 10.0.0.0/8(rw,sync,no_subtree_check)` exports /srv/data read-write to the 10.0.0.0/8 subnet.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Ports needed for NFS?","answer":"111 (portmap/rpcbind), 2049 (NFS).","explanation":"NFSv3 uses RPC and needs portmap (rpcbind) on 111 to announce the NFS daemon's ephemeral port. NFSv4 simplified to a single well-known port 2049 (tcp) — no rpcbind needed.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Command to list exports from a remote NFS server?","answer":"`showmount -e server`.","explanation":"`showmount` queries the server's mountd via RPC to list exported paths. Useful pre-mount sanity check; failure often means portmap/firewall blocking.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-samba","name":"Samba","tags":["networking","network"],"prose":"Linux ↔ Windows file/print sharing via SMB/CIFS.","source":"Mod07 Ch23; materials/labs/Lab7.pdf","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Samba main config file?","answer":"`/etc/samba/smb.conf`.","explanation":"smb.conf has a `[global]` section plus one section per share. Changes take effect on next client connection; force-reload with `smbcontrol all reload-config`.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Command to set a Samba password for a user?","answer":"`smbpasswd -a username`.","explanation":"Samba maintains its own password database (tdb) separate from Unix `/etc/shadow` — Windows uses NTLM hashes that aren't compatible with Unix crypt. `-a` adds a user; plain `smbpasswd` changes an existing password.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Command to validate smb.conf syntax?","answer":"`testparm`.","explanation":"testparm parses smb.conf and flags syntax errors, reports resolved values (after defaults and includes), and suggests fixes. Always run it before restarting Samba.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-nis","name":"NIS","tags":["networking","network"],"prose":"Centralized maps for passwd/group/hosts/services. NIS domain is SEPARATE from DNS domain.","source":"Mod07 Ch21; materials/labs/Lab7.pdf","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Is the NIS domain the same as the DNS domain?","answer":"No. NIS domain is independent — set separately in /etc/sysconfig/network (NISDOMAIN) or via domainname.","explanation":"NIS predates DNS-style domains and uses its own flat namespace. The NIS domain is a shared secret/label that groups a master + slaves + clients — unrelated to the DNS tree.","example":"DNS domain: `bcit.ca`. NIS domain: `infosys` (arbitrary label agreed on by master + clients). Setting: `domainname infosys`.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Command to initialize an NIS master?","answer":"`ypinit -m`.","explanation":"`ypinit -m` builds the initial NIS maps from `/etc` source files (passwd, group, hosts, etc.) and registers the server as master for the domain. `-s master` initializes a slave.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-ldap","name":"LDAP","tags":["networking","network"],"prose":"Centralized maps for passwd/group/hosts/services. NIS domain is SEPARATE from DNS domain.","source":"Mod07 Ch21","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"LDAP server daemon name?","answer":"`slapd`.","explanation":"slapd (Standalone LDAP Daemon) is the OpenLDAP server. Config either in slapd.conf (legacy) or a cn=config DIT (modern). Data lives in a backend like mdb.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"LDAP ports?","answer":"389 (LDAP), 636 (LDAPS / TLS).","explanation":"389 is cleartext LDAP (often upgraded to TLS via StartTLS). 636 is LDAPS — TLS from the start of the connection. Prefer 636 or StartTLS; plain 389 leaks bind passwords.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-sendmail","name":"Sendmail","tags":["networking","network"],"prose":"Sendmail is an MTA (Mail Transfer Agent). It listens on port 25 (SMTP), queues mail, and hands off to an MDA for final delivery.","source":"Mod07 Ch20; materials/labs/Lab7.pdf","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Sendmail is classified as which type of mail agent — MUA, MTA, or MDA?","answer":"**MTA** (Mail Transfer Agent). Accepts SMTP on port 25, routes, queues.","explanation":"Mail-agent chain is MUA (user client like mutt) → MTA (relay like sendmail/postfix) → MDA (local delivery, procmail/dovecot) → mailbox. Sendmail is the classic MTA — accepts, queues, routes.","example":"Chain: `mutt` (MUA) composes and submits → `sendmail` (MTA) routes over SMTP → `procmail` (MDA) filters into `/var/mail/user`.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which port does sendmail listen on?","answer":"**25** (SMTP).","explanation":"TCP 25 is SMTP for server-to-server mail transfer (MTA to MTA). Modern submission from MUAs uses 587 with auth; 465 is SMTPS (TLS-wrapped).","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which file do you edit to configure sendmail — `sendmail.cf` or `sendmail.mc`?","answer":"`sendmail.mc`. The `.cf` is generated from it by `m4` via `cd /etc/mail && make`.","explanation":"sendmail.cf is machine-generated rule-address dragon syntax — human-hostile. sendmail.mc is the m4 macro source you actually edit; `make` runs m4 to regenerate the .cf.","example":"Edit `/etc/mail/sendmail.mc`, change `Addr=127.0.0.1` → remove or set `0.0.0.0`, then `cd /etc/mail && make && systemctl restart sendmail`.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"After editing `/etc/aliases`, what command must you run before changes take effect?","answer":"`newaliases`. Rebuilds the hashed `/etc/aliases.db` that sendmail actually reads.","explanation":"sendmail reads the compiled hash db, not the plain text file, for O(1) alias lookup. `newaliases` is equivalent to `sendmail -bi` — rebuilds the db after edits.","example":"Add `webmaster: alice` to `/etc/aliases`, then `newaliases` — mail to webmaster now routes to alice. Without `newaliases`, the old db still routes the old way.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Command to list messages currently queued by sendmail?","answer":"`mailq` (equivalent to `sendmail -bp`). Queue lives in `/var/spool/mqueue/`.","explanation":"Messages sit in the queue while sendmail retries delivery (network down, remote MTA unreachable). `mailq` shows each message's ID, size, age, recipient, and the error that blocked delivery.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Sendmail is running but rejects external mail. Which line in `sendmail.mc` is the cause?","answer":"`DAEMON_OPTIONS(\\`Port=smtp,Addr=127.0.0.1, Name=MTA')dnl` — `Addr=127.0.0.1` binds loopback only. Remove it, `make`, restart.","explanation":"`Addr=127.0.0.1` tells sendmail to bind only on the loopback interface — external connections hit a closed port. Drop the Addr clause (or change to `0.0.0.0`) so it binds all interfaces.","example":"`netstat -tlnp | grep :25` shows `127.0.0.1:25` when loopback-only; after the fix it shows `0.0.0.0:25`.","bloom":"apply"}]},{"id":"4915-dns","name":"DNS","tags":["networking","network"],"prose":"Daemon named. Package bind, tools in bind-utils (dig, host, nslookup).","source":"Mod08 Ch24; materials/labs/Lab3.pdf","cards":[{"type":"diagram","prompt":"Draw the DNS query resolution chain for `www.example.com` from a client that has an empty cache.","answer":"```mermaid\ngraph LR\n  C[\"Client / stub resolver\"] --\u003e|\"query www.example.com\"| R[\"Recursive resolver (ISP)\"]\n  R --\u003e|\"no cache: query '.'\"| ROOT[\"Root server\"]\n  ROOT --\u003e|\"refer to .com NS\"| R\n  R --\u003e|\"query .com\"| GTLD[\"gTLD .com server\"]\n  GTLD --\u003e|\"refer to example.com NS\"| R\n  R --\u003e|\"query example.com\"| AUTH[\"Authoritative NS for example.com\"]\n  AUTH --\u003e|\"A 93.184.216.34\"| R\n  R --\u003e|\"cached answer\"| C\n```\nResolver caches each step per its TTL so the next query skips re-walking the tree.","explanation":"DNS resolution is iterative from the recursive resolver's perspective — it walks root → TLD → authoritative. The client just sends one recursive query and gets the final answer back. TTLs on each level determine how long the resolver caches that step.","source":"Mod08 Ch24; materials/labs/Lab3.pdf; research-mod07-08.md §DNS","bloom":"apply"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What does an A record map?","answer":"Hostname → IPv4 address.","explanation":"A (Address) is the base record type — name to 32-bit IPv4 address. Exam scope is IPv4 only; AAAA (IPv6) is out of scope.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What's a CNAME record?","answer":"Alias: one hostname → another (canonical) hostname.","explanation":"CNAME is an alias from one name to another — lookups follow the alias to find A records. Restriction: CNAME can't coexist with other records at the same name (no CNAME at zone apex).","example":"`www.example.com CNAME example.com` — `www` resolves by following the alias to example.com's A record. Change the A record and all CNAMEs pointing at it update automatically.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What's a PTR record?","answer":"Reverse DNS: IP → hostname.","explanation":"PTR records live in the `in-addr.arpa` zone — `1.2.3.4` reverses to `4.3.2.1.in-addr.arpa`. Used by mail servers for anti-spam (forward-confirmed reverse DNS) and by logs that want names not numbers.","example":"`dig -x 8.8.8.8` → `dns.google`. The IP `8.8.8.8` reverses to `8.8.8.8.in-addr.arpa` to find the PTR record.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What's an MX record?","answer":"Mail exchanger for the domain.","explanation":"MX records have a priority (lower = preferred) and name of a mail server accepting mail for the domain. The sender's MTA looks up MX, tries the lowest priority first, falls back on failure.","example":"`dig MX example.com` → `10 mail1.example.com. 20 mail2.example.com.` — MTA tries mail1 first (lower priority), falls back to mail2.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Command to validate DNS zone files?","answer":"`named-checkconf` (global config) and `named-checkzone zonename file` (per-zone).","explanation":"BIND ships syntax checkers so you don't restart named into a broken state. `named-checkconf` validates `/etc/named.conf`; `named-checkzone` validates a zone file's SOA and record syntax.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-iptables","name":"iptables","tags":["networking","network"],"prose":"Kernel firewall. Packet walks through tables → chains → rules.","source":"Mod08 Ch25; materials/labs/Lab8.pdf","cards":[{"type":"diagram","prompt":"Draw the INPUT-chain traversal tree for a default-deny firewall with rules for loopback, ESTABLISHED, SSH from 10.0.0.0/8, and HTTP.","answer":"```mermaid\ngraph TD\n  P[\"Incoming packet on INPUT chain\"] --\u003e R1{\"Rule 1: -i lo -j ACCEPT\"}\n  R1 --\u003e|\"match (loopback)\"| A[\"ACCEPT\"]\n  R1 --\u003e|\"no match\"| R2{\"Rule 2: --state RELATED,ESTABLISHED -j ACCEPT\"}\n  R2 --\u003e|\"match (return traffic)\"| A\n  R2 --\u003e|\"no match\"| R3{\"Rule 3: -p tcp --dport 22 -s 10.0.0.0/8 -j ACCEPT\"}\n  R3 --\u003e|\"match (SSH from 10/8)\"| A\n  R3 --\u003e|\"no match\"| R4{\"Rule 4: -p tcp --dport 80 -j ACCEPT\"}\n  R4 --\u003e|\"match (HTTP)\"| A\n  R4 --\u003e|\"no match\"| POL[\"Default policy: DROP\"]\n  POL --\u003e D[\"DROP (silent discard)\"]\n```\nFirst match wins. If no rule matches, the chain's default policy fires.","explanation":"iptables walks rules top-to-bottom. The first terminal target (ACCEPT, DROP, REJECT) ends the traversal. The default policy is only consulted when no rule matches — that's what makes default-deny work.","source":"Mod08 Ch25; materials/labs/Lab8.pdf; research-mod07-08.md §iptables","bloom":"apply"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Three iptables tables?","answer":"1. filter\n2. nat\n3. mangle","explanation":"Each table has different chains and purposes. `filter` decides accept/drop; `nat` rewrites addresses for NAT; `mangle` modifies TOS/TTL/marks. Most firewalls only use `filter`.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Five chains (filter + nat)?","answer":"1. INPUT (filter)\n2. OUTPUT (filter)\n3. FORWARD (filter)\n4. PREROUTING (nat)\n5. POSTROUTING (nat)","explanation":"INPUT hits packets destined to this host; OUTPUT hits packets originating here; FORWARD hits packets being routed through. NAT's PREROUTING rewrites dest addr on entry; POSTROUTING rewrites source addr on exit.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Write a rule to allow incoming TCP port 22 from 10.0.0.0/8.","answer":"`iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -s 10.0.0.0/8 -j ACCEPT`.","explanation":"`-A INPUT` appends to INPUT chain; `-p tcp` matches protocol; `--dport 22` matches destination port; `-s 10.0.0.0/8` matches source subnet; `-j ACCEPT` is the terminal target. Order matters — append before any DROP catchall.","example":"Paired with `iptables -P INPUT DROP` for default-deny. To make persistent: `iptables-save \u003e /etc/iptables/rules.v4`.","bloom":"apply"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Difference between DROP and REJECT targets?","answer":"DROP silently discards. REJECT sends ICMP error back to sender.","explanation":"DROP leaves the sender hanging until timeout — good for scan resistance. REJECT is immediate \"connection refused\" — better UX for legitimate clients but reveals the firewall's presence. Common: REJECT on LAN, DROP on WAN.","example":"Scanning with DROP: `nmap` takes 30s per port waiting for timeout. With REJECT: `nmap` gets `port unreachable` instantly and moves on — faster scan, exposes firewall presence.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-apache","name":"Apache","tags":["networking","network"],"prose":"Daemon httpd. Config /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf.","source":"Mod08 Ch26; materials/labs/Lab8.pdf","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Apache default DocumentRoot on RHEL/Fedora?","answer":"`/var/www/html`.","explanation":"DocumentRoot is the filesystem path Apache maps URL paths against. `/var/www/html/index.html` serves at `http://server/index.html` by default. Per-vhost DocumentRoot overrides the global.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Command to create a new Apache password file?","answer":"`htpasswd -c /etc/httpd/passwd user`. Omit -c to add to existing.","explanation":"htpasswd hashes passwords into a flat file for HTTP Basic Auth. `-c` creates (overwrites!) the file; omit `-c` to add more users. Referenced by `AuthUserFile` directive in a \u003cLocation\u003e block.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Command to list Apache VirtualHosts?","answer":"`httpd -S`.","explanation":"`httpd -S` (capital) dumps the resolved vhost config — which vhost handles which name/port. Useful to debug name-based vhost conflicts and default-server surprises.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-ssh","name":"SSH","tags":["networking","sysadmin"],"prose":"ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096 # creates ~/.ssh/id_rsa (600) and id_rsa.pub ssh-copy-id user@remote # appends pubkey to remote ~/.ssh/authorized_keys (600) Perm rules (ssh refuses if too loose): ~/.ssh=700, private key=600, authorized_keys=600.","source":"Mod06 Ch18; materials/labs/Lab6.pdf; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q34","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Generate an RSA SSH key pair?","answer":"`ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096`. Creates ~/.ssh/id\\_rsa (600) and id\\_rsa.pub.","explanation":"`-t` selects algorithm (rsa, ed25519, ecdsa); `-b` is bit length (only meaningful for rsa). ed25519 is the modern default — fixed-size, faster, smaller. `-f path` picks a non-default filename.","example":"`ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C 'work laptop'` — modern, commented key.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Deploy your public key to remote server?","answer":"`ssh-copy-id user@remote`.","explanation":"ssh-copy-id appends your pubkey to the remote's `~/.ssh/authorized_keys` with the right permissions (700 on ~/.ssh, 600 on authorized_keys). Manual equivalent is `cat ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub | ssh user@remote 'mkdir -p ~/.ssh && cat \u003e\u003e ~/.ssh/authorized_keys'`.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Required permissions for ~/.ssh and authorized\\_keys?","answer":"~/.ssh=700, authorized\\_keys=600. Private keys=600.","explanation":"sshd refuses to authenticate if any of these files are group/world writable — it assumes someone may have tampered. Fix with `chmod 700 ~/.ssh && chmod 600 ~/.ssh/*`.","example":"Symptoms of bad perms: `Permission denied (publickey)` despite correct key. Check `/var/log/auth.log` on server.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Forward local port 8080 through bastion to internal:80?","answer":"`ssh -L 8080:internal:80 user@bastion`.","explanation":"`-L local_port:target_host:target_port user@gateway` opens a listener on your machine's 8080. Traffic is tunnel-encrypted to bastion, then bastion dials internal:80 in cleartext from its own network. `internal` is resolved on bastion, not your laptop.","example":"Visit `http://localhost:8080` in your browser to hit internal:80 through the tunnel.","bloom":"apply"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Difference: -L vs -R in ssh?","answer":"1. `-L` local forward (access remote service through local port)\n2. `-R` remote forward (expose local service on remote port)","explanation":"`-L` listens on *your* side, forwards to the remote network. `-R` listens on the *remote* side, forwards back to your network. Mnemonic: L = 'listen Local'; R = 'listen Remote'.","example":"`-L 8080:db:5432 bastion` → you connect to localhost:8080 → bastion → db:5432. `-R 9000:localhost:3000 bastion` → remote users on bastion connect to localhost:9000 → your laptop:3000.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-ftp","name":"FTP","tags":["networking","sysadmin"],"prose":"Flashcards covering FTP.","source":"Mod06 Ch19; materials/labs/Lab6.pdf; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q1","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Active vs passive FTP — who initiates data connection?","answer":"Active: server connects to client. Passive: client connects to server (firewall-friendly).","explanation":"FTP uses two connections — control (port 21) and data. Active has the server dial back to the client's random port — breaks client-side firewalls/NAT. Passive flips this: client dials the server's random port. Passive is the modern default.","example":"Client behind NAT uses passive: client sends PASV, server replies with IP:port, client opens the data connection. Active would require the server to dial back through the client's NAT — impossible without port forwarding.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-hostname","name":"hostname","tags":["networking","fundamentals"],"prose":"Flashcards covering hostname.","source":"Mod03 Ch8","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"What does the `hostname` command do?","answer":"Displays the name of the machine you're currently logged into.","explanation":"With no args, `hostname` prints the kernel's stored name. `hostname new-name` sets it (temporary — reset on reboot). Persistent name lives in `/etc/hostname` (modern) or via `hostnamectl set-hostname`.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-dhcp","name":"DHCP","tags":["networking","network"],"prose":"Flashcards covering DHCP.","source":"Mod08 Ch24; Review Apr 17","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"How does DHCP work, conceptually?","answer":"DORA sequence:\n1. **Discover** — client broadcasts DHCP Discover\n2. **Offer** — server replies with Offer (IP, mask, gateway, DNS, lease)\n3. **Request** — client requests\n4. **Ack** — server acks\n\nLease expires and renews.","explanation":"DHCP uses UDP 67/68 with broadcast before the client has an IP. DORA is the 4-packet handshake. After the ACK, the client renews at 50% of lease lifetime to keep its address.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-dns-scope","name":"DNS scope","tags":["networking","network"],"prose":"Daemon named. Package bind, tools in bind-utils (dig, host, nslookup).","source":"Review Apr 17 (IPv4 only — IPv6 out of scope)","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"For DNS records on the exam, do you need IPv6?","answer":"**No**. IPv4 only per instructor. Know A records, not AAAA.","explanation":"A records map hostnames to 32-bit IPv4 addresses; AAAA maps to 128-bit IPv6. The exam explicitly scopes to A, CNAME, PTR, MX — no AAAA.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-nfs-use","name":"NFS use","tags":["networking","network"],"prose":"Linux-to-Linux file sharing. NOT for Windows (use Samba).","source":"Review Apr 17; Mod07 Ch22","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"When is NFS safe to use?","answer":"Only **behind firewalls**. NFS has minimal authentication by default — exposing it on the internet is dangerous.","explanation":"Classic NFS trusts the client's UID — anyone who can forge UIDs on your network can read/write as any user. Kerberos-backed NFSv4 fixes this but requires setup; default NFS assumes a trusted LAN.","example":"Server `/etc/exports`: `/srv/data 192.168.1.0/24(rw,sync)` — restricts access to the LAN subnet. Without a subnet restriction, any host could mount.","bloom":"understand"}]}]},{"id":"package-mgmt","name":"Package management & boot","topics":[{"id":"4915-runlevels","name":"Runlevels","tags":["boot","sysadmin"],"prose":"Flashcards covering Runlevels.","source":"Mod05 Ch10; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q35","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Linux System V run level 3 — what does it do?","answer":"Enters multi-user text mode (full services, no GUI).","explanation":"Runlevel 3 = default for servers. All network services start, users can log in on terminals and via SSH, but no display manager is launched. systemd's equivalent is `multi-user.target`.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Linux configured for graphics boot — which run level?","answer":"5 (multi-user graphical).","explanation":"Runlevel 5 adds the display manager (gdm, lightdm, kdm) on top of runlevel 3 — full GUI login. systemd equivalent: `graphical.target`. Default for desktop distros.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"predict","prompt":"System currently at runlevel 5. You run `systemctl isolate multi-user.target`. What happens immediately and what happens on next reboot?","answer":"Immediate: GUI tears down, you land at text console (runlevel 3 equivalent). Reboot: boots back to runlevel 5 — `isolate` doesn't change the default.","explanation":"`isolate` switches the current runlevel live without touching the default. To persist, use `systemctl set-default multi-user.target` — that edits the `default.target` symlink read at boot.","example":"To make the text-mode switch permanent: `systemctl set-default multi-user.target && systemctl isolate multi-user.target`.","source":"Mod05 Ch10; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q35","bloom":"apply"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Run level 0?","answer":"Halt / power off.","explanation":"Runlevel 0 triggers shutdown — stops services in reverse order, unmounts filesystems, powers off. `shutdown -h now` or `poweroff` both end at runlevel 0.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Run level 6?","answer":"Reboot.","explanation":"Runlevel 6 = shutdown + restart. `reboot` and `shutdown -r now` both trigger it. `systemctl reboot` is the systemd equivalent.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-boot","name":"Boot","tags":["boot","sysadmin"],"prose":"BIOS POST → MBR/GRUB → kernel → init/systemd (PID 1) → /etc/rc.d/rc.sysinit (mount /proc, swap on, fsck+mount fstab) → rc N (execute /etc/rc.d/rcN.d/Kxx* stop scripts, then Sxx* start) → login.","source":"Mod05 Ch10-11","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"First program run when Linux is booting (PID 1)?","answer":"`init` (or `systemd` on modern distros).","explanation":"The kernel hands off to PID 1 after hardware init. PID 1 is the ancestor of every other process — if it dies, the kernel panics. Traditionally SysV init; modern distros use systemd.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"First place to look for a Linux daemon executable?","answer":"`/usr` (specifically /usr/sbin for system daemons; /sbin for rescue-essential).","explanation":"/sbin = essential binaries needed for boot and rescue; /usr/sbin = post-/usr-mount system binaries (most daemons). /bin and /usr/bin are for user commands. Modern distros increasingly merge these via symlinks.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What is `init`?","answer":"First user-space process (PID 1), started by kernel at boot. Modern systems: systemd.","explanation":"PID 1's job is to start all other services per the runlevel/target config, reap orphaned processes, and handle shutdown. systemd extends this with parallel startup, cgroup tracking, and socket activation.","example":"`ps -p 1 -o comm=` → `systemd` on modern distros. Every process is a descendant — `pstree -p 1` shows the entire process tree rooted at systemd.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-pam","name":"PAM","tags":["auth","sysadmin"],"prose":"Flashcards covering PAM.","source":"Mod05 Ch11","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"What is Linux-PAM?","answer":"Pluggable Authentication Modules — modular authentication system configurable per-service in /etc/pam.d/ without recompiling apps.","explanation":"PAM lets you change auth policy (passwords, 2FA, LDAP, Kerberos) without touching each app. Each service (login, sshd, sudo) gets a config file listing modules to stack for auth, account, password, session management.","example":"Add LDAP auth to SSH: edit `/etc/pam.d/sshd` to add `pam_ldap.so` — no SSH recompile needed. Rollback: revert the PAM config file.","bloom":"understand"}]}]},{"id":"kubernetes","name":"Kubernetes & containers","topics":[{"id":"4915-k8s","name":"K8s","tags":["kubernetes"],"prose":"Flashcards covering K8s.","source":"Mod10A; materials/past-exams/comp4915_quiz4.md","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Agent on K8s nodes that implements control-plane commands?","answer":"`kubelet`.","explanation":"kubelet is the node agent — it watches the API server for pod specs assigned to its node, invokes the container runtime via CRI to start containers, and reports status back. Every node runs one kubelet. (research-mod10ce-review.md §Kubelet)","example":"`systemctl status kubelet` on a node — if kubelet is down, the node shows `NotReady` in `kubectl get nodes`.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Executable image format used in Kubernetes?","answer":"`OCI` (Open Container Initiative).","explanation":"OCI standardized the image format and runtime spec across Docker, containerd, CRI-O. K8s doesn't build images — it pulls OCI-compliant images from registries and hands them to the CRI runtime on each node.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Most common way to run a K8s app?","answer":"`Deployment`.","explanation":"Deployment wraps ReplicaSet and adds rolling update + rollback semantics. You declare desired pod count and template; the controller reconciles to match. Quiz 4 Q4 keyed answer.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What does Kubernetes use to *maintain* its state? (Quiz 4 Q5 wording — etcd is NOT in the options)","answer":"`kube-controller-manager` — the keyed Quiz 4 answer. The manager runs reconcile loops that drive actual state toward desired state.","explanation":"controller-manager runs the reconcile loops (Deployment controller, ReplicaSet controller, Node controller, Job controller, etc.). Each loop watches API server for spec changes and drives the cluster to match.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Raw state *data* for a K8s cluster is persisted where?","answer":"`etcd` — distributed key-value store. Distinct from Quiz 4 Q5, which asks what *maintains* state (controller-manager).","explanation":"etcd stores every K8s object (pods, deployments, services, secrets) as key-value pairs. apiserver is the only component that reads/writes etcd directly — all other components go through apiserver. (research-mod10ce-review.md §Control Plane)","example":"Disaster scenario: etcd data lost → all cluster objects gone (no pods, no services, no secrets). Restore from etcd backup restores the full cluster definition.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"YAML section specifying container image?","answer":"`spec`.","explanation":"K8s YAML has four top-level keys: apiVersion, kind, metadata, spec. `spec` holds the desired state (container image, ports, env, volumes, replicas, etc.). `status` is read-only, written by controllers.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"K8s object running one pod on every node?","answer":"`DaemonSet`.","explanation":"DaemonSet ensures exactly one pod per (selected) node — used for node-level agents (log collectors, CNI pods, monitoring). When a node joins, its pod is auto-created; when a node leaves, its pod is removed.","example":"`kubectl get daemonsets -n kube-system` — shows `calico-node`, `kube-proxy` — both are DaemonSets because every node needs them.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What happens when a K8s node fails?","answer":"**All of:**\n1. kubelet stops reporting healthy\n2. New pods not scheduled there\n3. Existing pods scheduled for deletion\n4. Pods rescheduled to other nodes","explanation":"Node controller watches kubelet heartbeats. After `node-monitor-grace-period` (default 40s), node is marked NotReady. After `pod-eviction-timeout` (default 5m), pods on that node are evicted; Deployments/ReplicaSets recreate them elsewhere.","bloom":"apply"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Reason for the pause container?","answer":"Helps set up Linux namespaces and cgroups for a pod — holds namespaces open so other containers can join them.","explanation":"The pause container is a 1-process \"infrastructure\" container that sleeps forever, owning the pod's shared namespaces (NET, IPC, UTS). Other containers in the pod join those namespaces. Killing pause tears down the pod's network identity.","example":"`docker ps` on a K8s node shows one k8s.gcr.io/pause container per running pod — these are the namespace holders.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"K8s component that *stores* raw cluster state data?","answer":"`etcd`. (Contrast: `kube-controller-manager` *maintains* state via reconcile loops — Quiz 4 Q5.)","explanation":"etcd is the source of truth — a Raft-replicated key-value store. Lose etcd, you lose the cluster. controller-manager is the thing that *acts on* changes in etcd; etcd just persists them.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"K8s object that runs a task to completion?","answer":"`Job` (CronJob for scheduled).","explanation":"Job tracks batch workloads — pod runs until exit 0, marked complete. Unlike Deployment which keeps pods alive indefinitely. CronJob is a Job that spawns on a schedule.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What is a Deployment vs ReplicaSet?","answer":"Deployment manages ReplicaSets + adds rolling-update/rollback. You generally create Deployments, not ReplicaSets directly.","explanation":"A Deployment creates a new ReplicaSet per image/spec change, ramps up new pods and down old pods for a rolling update, and keeps old ReplicaSets around for rollback. ReplicaSet alone just keeps N pods alive.","example":"`kubectl rollout undo deployment/nginx` — uses the old ReplicaSet kept by the Deployment to roll back to the previous image version.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-namespaces","name":"Namespaces","tags":["kubernetes"],"prose":"Kernel mechanism to hide resources from processes outside the namespace. K8s pods and containers are built on these.","source":"Mod10C; materials/labs/Lab10.pdf","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Name the 8 Linux namespace types.","answer":"1. PID\n2. NET\n3. MNT\n4. UTS\n5. IPC\n6. USER\n7. CGROUP\n8. TIME","explanation":"Each namespace virtualizes a specific kernel resource — PID (process IDs), NET (network stack), MNT (mount tree), UTS (hostname/domain), IPC (SysV IPC + POSIX msg queues), USER (UID/GID maps), CGROUP (cgroup root), TIME (monotonic/boottime clocks). Containers combine several.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What does the NET namespace isolate?","answer":"Network stack: interfaces, routing tables, iptables rules, sockets.","explanation":"Each NET namespace has its own loopback, its own interface list, its own routes, its own firewall. Pods in K8s share one NET namespace across all containers via the pause container — that's why multi-container pods can talk on localhost.","example":"`ip netns exec mypod ip addr` — shows only that namespace's interfaces. The host still has its own loopback and eth0 untouched.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What does the UTS namespace isolate?","answer":"Hostname and NIS domain.","explanation":"UTS = Unix Time-sharing System (historical). The namespace isolates `hostname` and `domainname` so each container can set its own without affecting the host.","example":"`sudo unshare --uts bash; hostname mycontainer; hostname` → `mycontainer`. `exit`; `hostname` on host → unchanged.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Command to create new namespaces?","answer":"`unshare`. Example: `unshare --pid --net bash`.","explanation":"`unshare` forks a process into fresh namespaces of the requested types. Useful for ad-hoc container-like isolation from the CLI. Requires privileges for most namespace types (USER namespace is usually unprivileged).","example":"`sudo unshare --uts bash; hostname container1; exit` — changes only the shell's hostname, host hostname unchanged.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Command to enter existing namespaces of a PID?","answer":"`nsenter -t PID -p -n -m`.","explanation":"nsenter joins an existing process's namespaces — `-t PID` target, then flag per type (`-p` pid, `-n` net, `-m` mount, `-u` uts, `-i` ipc). Classic use: debug inside a container from the host.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-cgroups","name":"cgroups","tags":["kubernetes"],"prose":"cgroups (Control Groups) = kernel feature to LIMIT and ACCOUNT resource usage (CPU, memory, I/O, pids). Namespaces isolate; cgroups meter.","source":"Mod10D; materials/labs/Lab10.pdf","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"What do cgroups do?","answer":"Limit, account, and isolate resource usage (CPU, memory, I/O, pids).","explanation":"cgroups is the kernel's accounting and throttling layer. Namespaces make things look isolated; cgroups enforce how much CPU/RAM/IO/pids a group of processes can use. K8s uses cgroups to enforce pod resource limits. (research-mod10ce-review.md §cgroups)","example":"kubelet sets pod cgroup `memory.limit_in_bytes` from the pod spec's `resources.limits.memory`. Exceed it → OOMKilled.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"cgroups v1 vs v2 structure?","answer":"v1: separate hierarchy per subsystem (cpu, memory, etc.). v2: unified hierarchy — single tree.","explanation":"v1 mounted each controller (cpu, memory, blkio) at its own hierarchy in `/sys/fs/cgroup/\u003ccontroller\u003e/`. v2 unifies everything under one tree, simpler semantics. Most modern distros are v2; RHEL 7/8 still use v1.","example":"v1: `cat /sys/fs/cgroup/memory/docker/\u003cid\u003e/memory.limit_in_bytes`. v2: `cat /sys/fs/cgroup/system.slice/\u003cid\u003e/memory.max` — single unified path.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-qos","name":"QoS","tags":["kubernetes"],"prose":"cgroups (Control Groups) = kernel feature to LIMIT and ACCOUNT resource usage (CPU, memory, I/O, pids). Namespaces isolate; cgroups meter.","source":"Mod10D; materials/past-exams/comp4915_quiz4.md","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Pod with requests=limits for CPU and memory — QoS class?","answer":"`Guaranteed`. Last evicted under pressure.","explanation":"Guaranteed requires every container in the pod to set BOTH requests and limits for BOTH cpu and memory, AND requests == limits for each. Any slip → Burstable. kubelet derives the class from the spec; you can't set it directly.","example":"```yaml\nresources:\n  requests: { cpu: 500m, memory: 256Mi }\n  limits:   { cpu: 500m, memory: 256Mi }\n```","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Pod with no requests and no limits — QoS class?","answer":"`BestEffort`. First evicted under memory pressure.","explanation":"BestEffort pods are unlimited and unreserved — they can use any slack, but they're first on the chopping block when the node runs low. Use only for truly expendable workloads.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Pod with some requests/limits but not matching — QoS class?","answer":"`Burstable`. Evicted after BestEffort but before Guaranteed.","explanation":"Burstable is the fallback — any resource spec that doesn't qualify as Guaranteed or BestEffort lands here. Common case: set requests low to pack nodes densely, limits high to allow bursting.","example":"```yaml\nresources:\n  requests: { cpu: 100m, memory: 128Mi }\n  limits:   { cpu: 500m, memory: 256Mi }\n```","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-cni","name":"CNI","tags":["kubernetes"],"prose":"CNI = Container Network Interface. Plugin spec for configuring pod network.","source":"Mod10E; materials/labs/Lab10.pdf","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"What does CNI stand for?","answer":"Container Network Interface. Plugin spec for wiring pods to networks.","explanation":"CNI is the pluggable layer K8s (and others) use to set up pod networking. kubelet invokes the CNI plugin at pod start — plugin creates veth pair, assigns pod IP, sets up routes. Different plugins (Calico, Cilium, Flannel) implement different models.","example":"Pod starts → kubelet calls CNI plugin → plugin creates `veth0` pair (one end in pod net ns, one on host), assigns `10.244.1.5/24`, adds route. Pod can now reach other pods.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which CNI uses BGP L3 routing by default?","answer":"`Calico` (can also run IPIP/VXLAN overlay when BGP isn't viable).","explanation":"Calico treats each node as a BGP router and advertises pod CIDRs — no encapsulation overhead when the network supports BGP peering. Falls back to IPIP/VXLAN overlay on networks that can't route pod IPs natively.","example":"Calico on bare metal: each node peers with a BGP reflector, advertises its pod CIDR. Pod packets route natively at L3 — no VXLAN tunnel overhead.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which CNI uses eBPF?","answer":"`Cilium`.","explanation":"Cilium pushes networking and security policy into the kernel via eBPF programs — bypasses iptables for L3/L4 forwarding and supports rich L7 policy. Faster and more observable at scale.","example":"Cilium NetworkPolicy can filter on HTTP path: `allow GET /api` but deny `POST /admin` — iptables can't do L7. Cilium's eBPF programs inspect packets inside the kernel without context switch.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-k8s-services","name":"K8s Services","tags":["kubernetes","editor"],"prose":"Flashcards covering K8s Services.","source":"Mod10A","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Default K8s Service type?","answer":"`ClusterIP` — internal only.","explanation":"ClusterIP allocates a virtual IP reachable only inside the cluster. kube-proxy on each node installs iptables/IPVS rules that DNAT ClusterIP:port to one of the healthy backend pod IPs.","example":"`kubectl get svc nginx` → `CLUSTER-IP: 10.96.0.1` — only reachable from pods inside the cluster. Accessing it from your laptop (outside) fails without a NodePort or Ingress.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Service type exposing on every node's IP:port?","answer":"`NodePort` (30000-32767).","explanation":"NodePort opens a port on every node (default range 30000-32767) that forwards to the Service's ClusterIP. Useful for exposing without a cloud LB; LoadBalancer builds on NodePort by provisioning an external LB.","example":"NodePort 32080 on a 3-node cluster: `curl node1:32080`, `curl node2:32080`, `curl node3:32080` all reach the same backend pods — any node works as an entry point.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-k8s-yaml","name":"K8s YAML","tags":["kubernetes"],"prose":"Flashcards covering K8s YAML.","source":"Mod10C; materials/labs/Lab9.pdf","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Four top-level keys in a Pod YAML?","answer":"1. `apiVersion`\n2. `kind`\n3. `metadata`\n4. `spec`","explanation":"apiVersion pins the API schema (e.g., `v1`, `apps/v1`); kind names the object type (Pod, Deployment); metadata holds name/namespace/labels; spec holds desired state. Every K8s object follows this shape.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-k8s-probes","name":"K8s probes","tags":["kubernetes"],"prose":"Flashcards covering K8s probes.","source":"Mod10A","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Difference between readiness and liveness probe?","answer":"Readiness: is pod ready for traffic? Failure removes from Service endpoints. Liveness: is pod still alive? Failure restarts container.","explanation":"Readiness gates traffic flow — a warming pod stays in the Service but fails readiness until it's ready. Liveness catches deadlocks — a stuck process is restarted even if the TCP port is open. Different failure modes need different probes.","example":"App needs 10s to warm up: readiness probe fails for 10s → pod stays running but receives no traffic. At t=10s readiness passes → added to Service endpoints. Liveness probe fires separately if the process deadlocks later.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-k8s-dns","name":"K8s DNS","tags":["networking","kubernetes"],"prose":"Flashcards covering K8s DNS.","source":"Mod10A, Mod08 Ch24","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Cluster DNS addon name?","answer":"`CoreDNS`.","explanation":"CoreDNS is the default cluster DNS since K8s 1.13 (replaced kube-dns). Pods get `/etc/resolv.conf` pointing at CoreDNS ClusterIP; names like `svc-name.namespace.svc.cluster.local` resolve to service ClusterIPs.","example":"Inside a pod: `nslookup nginx.default.svc.cluster.local` → resolves to the nginx Service's ClusterIP via CoreDNS. Short form `nginx` works too via the `cluster.local` search suffix in `/etc/resolv.conf`.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-container","name":"Container","tags":["kubernetes"],"prose":"Pod = smallest deployable K8s unit. 1+ containers sharing NET, IPC, UTS namespaces + storage volumes.","source":"Mod10A-B; Review Apr 17","cards":[{"type":"diagram","prompt":"Draw how the pause container shares namespaces with app containers in a pod.","answer":"```mermaid\ngraph TD\n  POD[\"Pod (sandbox)\"] --\u003e PAUSE[\"pause container (PID 1 in pod)\u003cbr/\u003eowns NET, IPC, UTS namespaces\"]\n  PAUSE -.-\u003e|\"namespaces joined by\"| APP1[\"app container 1\u003cbr/\u003ejoins pause's NET/IPC/UTS\"]\n  PAUSE -.-\u003e|\"namespaces joined by\"| APP2[\"app container 2\u003cbr/\u003ejoins pause's NET/IPC/UTS\"]\n  APP1 --\u003e|\"localhost:port\"| APP2\n  APP1 --\u003e|\"shared volume\"| VOL[\"Volume (mounted in both)\"]\n  APP2 --\u003e|\"shared volume\"| VOL\n```\npause holds NET/IPC/UTS open; kill pause and the pod loses its identity.","explanation":"The pause container is the pod's namespace owner. Every app container joins pause's network, IPC, and UTS namespaces — that's why containers in the same pod reach each other on localhost and share a hostname. MNT and PID are per-container by default; volumes add shared storage on top. (research-mod10ce-review.md §Pod)","source":"research-mod10ce-review.md §Pod; Mod10A-B","bloom":"apply"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What is a container image?","answer":"Layered read-only template for a container: filesystem snapshot + metadata (entrypoint, env, labels). OCI-standard. Pulled from registry, run as container with a writable layer on top.","explanation":"An image is a stack of read-only layers + a JSON manifest describing how to run it. At runtime, the container runtime (containerd, CRI-O) adds a writable top layer (copy-on-write) so the running container can modify its filesystem without mutating the image.","example":"`docker run nginx` — containerd pulls the nginx image (read-only layers), adds a writable layer, starts the container. `docker run nginx` again reuses the same read-only layers, just adds a new writable layer.","bloom":"understand"}]}]},{"id":"scripting","name":"Bash scripting & regex","topics":[{"id":"4915-shell-params","name":"Shell params","tags":["shell"],"prose":"Process substitution &lt;(cmd), &gt;(cmd) is a bash feature beyond basic 7.","source":"Mod04 Ch9; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q31, Q59, Q60","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Which var refers to the entire argument list?","answer":"`$@` (also `$*`, but they differ when quoted).","explanation":"`$@` and `$*` both hold all positional args. Quoted behavior differs: `\"$@\"` gives N separate words; `\"$*\"` joins into one string (IFS-separated). In functions, always prefer `\"$@\"`.","example":"`set -- 'a b' c; for x in \"$@\"; do echo [$x]; done` → `[a b]` and `[c]`.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What is `$?`?","answer":"Exit status of last command. 0=success, non-zero=error.","explanation":"`$?` is set after every foreground command. Use it for conditional flow: `cmd; if [ $? -ne 0 ]; then ...`. Or let `&&`/`||` short-circuit on it directly.","example":"`grep foo file; echo $?` → `0` if found, `1` if not, `2` on error.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What is `$$`?","answer":"PID of the current shell.","explanation":"Useful for making unique temp filenames: `/tmp/myscript.$$`. Note that `$$` in a subshell still yields the *parent* shell's PID (only explicit subshell via `$BASHPID` differs).","example":"`tmp=/tmp/work.$$ && trap 'rm -f $tmp' EXIT` — unique file per script invocation, auto-cleaned.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What is `$!`?","answer":"PID of the most recent background command.","explanation":"Captured right after `&` so you can wait on or signal that job later. Useful for launching parallel work in shell: `task1 & PID1=$!; task2 & PID2=$!; wait $PID1 $PID2`.","example":"`long_task & echo 'Started as PID' $!` — prints the PID so you can monitor.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Difference between `\"$@\"` and `\"$*\"`?","answer":"`\"$@\"` expands to separate words per arg. `\"$*\"` joins all args into one string (separated by first IFS char).","explanation":"`\"$@\"` = `\"$1\" \"$2\" \"$3\"` — N tokens. `\"$*\"` = `\"$1c$2c$3\"` where c is first char of IFS — one token. The distinction matters when passing args into another command without losing whitespace inside any single arg.","example":"`set -- 'hi there' bye; printf '[%s]\\n' \"$@\"` → `[hi there]\\n[bye]`. `printf '[%s]\\n' \"$*\"` → `[hi there bye]`.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which var holds count of positional arguments?","answer":"`$#`.","explanation":"Handy for argument checking: `[ $# -lt 2 ] && { echo usage; exit 1; }`. `$0` is the script name (not counted in `$#`); `$1..$N` are the args themselves.","example":"`myscript a b c` → inside, `$#` = 3.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-expansions","name":"Expansions","tags":["shell"],"prose":"Process substitution &lt;(cmd), &gt;(cmd) is a bash feature beyond basic 7.","source":"Mod04 Ch9; Review Apr 17","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"In order, name the 7 shell expansions.","answer":"1. Brace\n2. Tilde\n3. Parameter\n4. Arithmetic\n5. Command\n6. Word splitting\n7. Pathname (glob)","explanation":"Order matters — brace happens BEFORE parameter, so `{$HOME,$USER}` produces two unexpanded strings, then parameter expands each. Word splitting and pathname fire last, on already-expanded text. Quotes suppress everything from step 6 onward.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Output of `echo {$HOME,$USER}` given HOME=/home/u, USER=u?","answer":"`/home/u u`. Brace happens BEFORE variable expansion, so braces generate literal `$HOME $USER` first, then those expand.","explanation":"Brace expansion (step 1) produces the two strings `$HOME` and `$USER` from the literal braces. Parameter expansion (step 3) then replaces each `$X` with its value. Order: brace → tilde → parameter.","example":"Try `echo {1..3}-v` → `1-v 2-v 3-v`. Brace expansion happens before anything else and doesn't see variables.","bloom":"apply"}]},{"id":"4915-function-precedence","name":"Function precedence","tags":["scripting","shell"],"prose":"Bash resolves a name in a fixed order (alias → keyword → function → builtin → $PATH); knowing the order lets you predict which definition wins when multiple exist.","source":"Mod04 Ch9","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Order of bash name resolution?","answer":"1. Alias\n2. Keyword\n3. Function\n4. Builtin\n5. $PATH","explanation":"Bash checks aliases first (pre-parse), then shell keywords (if, for, while), then functions, then builtins (echo, cd, type), then scans $PATH for external binaries. `type name` tells you which one wins.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"How to bypass alias/function and use builtin?","answer":"`builtin name`. Or use full path for external.","explanation":"`builtin cd /tmp` skips any alias/function named `cd` and calls the shell builtin directly. `command` is similar but allows external; `\\cmd` bypasses aliases only.","example":"Override with a function, then `builtin cd` still works: `cd() { echo pre; builtin cd \"$@\"; }`.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-bash-scripting","name":"Bash scripting","tags":["scripting","shell"],"prose":"Bash scripts assemble a shebang, comments, file-test operators, and exit status into runnable programs — this is the form the exam's short/essay questions expect you to produce.","source":"Mod09 Ch28; materials/labs/Lab9.pdf","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Which bash file test returns true if file exists?","answer":"`-e`.","explanation":"`[ -e path ]` is true for any existing filesystem entry (file, dir, socket, symlink target). Use `-f` specifically for regular files, `-d` for directories. Inside `[[ ]]` works the same.","example":"`if [ -e /etc/hosts ]; then echo yes; fi`.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which bash file test returns true if it's a directory?","answer":"`-d`.","explanation":"`[ -d path ]` matches type 'directory' specifically — false for regular files, symlinks to non-dir targets, etc. Pair with `-L` to detect symlinks: `-L ... -d` for symlink-to-dir.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Comment character in bash?","answer":"`#`. Rest of line ignored.","explanation":"`#` starts a comment until end-of-line (except inside strings). The shebang `#!/bin/bash` uses it too — the kernel's magic-number check sees `#!` and interprets the rest as the interpreter path.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"predict","prompt":"Bash function `psgrep() { ps aux | grep -v grep | grep \"$@\"; }`. You call `psgrep 'ng inx'`. Will it work? What if you wrote `grep $@` without quotes?","answer":"Works. `\"$@\"` passes `ng inx` as one argument to grep. Without quotes, `$@` word-splits → grep sees two args (`ng` and `inx`), treating `ng` as pattern and `inx` as filename → `inx: No such file or directory`.","explanation":"Quoted `\"$@\"` preserves each argument verbatim — a single arg stays single even with whitespace. Unquoted `$@` undergoes word splitting via IFS, destroying whitespace boundaries. This is the #1 bash-function bug on the exam.","example":"`f() { echo \"$@\"; echo $@; }; f 'a  b' c` → first line `a  b c`, second line `a b c` (double space collapsed).","source":"Mod09 Ch28; materials/labs/Lab9.pdf; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q60","bloom":"apply"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which exit status indicates success in bash?","answer":"`0`.","explanation":"0 = success by convention; 1-255 = error codes. `&&` runs the next command only on 0; `||` runs on non-zero. Outside 0-255 is not representable — shells truncate to 8 bits.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which builtin reads and executes another script in current shell?","answer":"`source` (or `.`). (Not exec — exec replaces the shell process.)","explanation":"`source file` executes file's lines in the *current* shell — variables and functions persist. Running `./file` forks a subshell; changes there don't leak back. Use source for config files (bashrc, .env style).","example":"`source ~/.bashrc` reloads aliases into your current shell after edits.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which is NOT a valid Linux/Unix shell: sh, tcsh, ksh, bash, jsh?","answer":"`jsh` (not a standard shell).","explanation":"sh = Bourne shell; bash = Bourne-Again SHell; ksh = Korn shell; tcsh = TENEX csh. `jsh` isn't a real Unix shell — distractor.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What must be done before a shell script runs by name alone?","answer":"Change permissions to include executable — `chmod +x script`.","explanation":"Files are created without execute bit by default (666 & umask). Without `+x`, the kernel refuses to exec; `./script` fails with `Permission denied`. Alternative: invoke interpreter directly: `bash script`.","example":"`chmod +x deploy.sh && ./deploy.sh`.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-startup-files","name":"Startup files","tags":["archives","shell"],"prose":"Flashcards covering Startup files.","source":"Mod04 Ch9, Mod05 Ch11","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Login shell startup file order?","answer":"`/etc/profile` → then first existing of `~/.bash_profile`, `~/.bash_login`, `~/.profile`.","explanation":"Bash reads `/etc/profile` first for system-wide login settings, then the first existing of the three user files (stops after first hit). Common pattern: `~/.bash_profile` sources `~/.bashrc` so interactive settings apply to login shells too.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Non-login interactive shell startup file?","answer":"`~/.bashrc`.","explanation":"Opened for every interactive subshell (new terminal tab, `bash` inside a script). This is where aliases, prompt, and most user-facing config go — not `~/.bash_profile`, which only runs on login.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-export","name":"Export","tags":["shell"],"prose":"Flashcards covering Export.","source":"Mod04 Ch9","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Purpose of `export VAR=value`?","answer":"Make VAR available to child processes (environment variable). Plain `VAR=x` is local to current shell.","explanation":"Exported variables go into the environment passed to child processes via execve(2). Non-exported variables stay in the shell's own variable table — child processes can't see them.","example":"`X=hi bash -c 'echo $X'` → blank (X not exported). `export X=hi; bash -c 'echo $X'` → `hi`.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-shell-startup","name":"Shell startup","tags":["shell","archives"],"prose":"Process substitution &lt;(cmd), &gt;(cmd) is a bash feature beyond basic 7.","source":"Mod04 Ch9","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Which file is sourced for login shells system-wide?","answer":"`/etc/profile`.","explanation":"`/etc/profile` is the system's global login-shell config — typically sets PATH, `umask`, and sources fragments from `/etc/profile.d/*.sh`. Applies to every user on login.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-vs","name":"$* vs $@","tags":["shell"],"prose":"Flashcards covering $* vs $@.","source":"Mod04 Ch9; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q59, Q60","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Quoted `\"$*\"` vs `\"$@\"` — difference with example?","answer":"Given `set -- 'one two' 'three'`: `\"$@\"` expands to 2 separate words `one two` and `three`. `\"$*\"` joins into one string `one two three`. Use `\"$@\"` in functions.","explanation":"`\"$@\"` preserves argument boundaries — each arg stays a separate token. `\"$*\"` flattens them into a single string joined by IFS[0] (default space). Inside a function forwarding args to another command, always `\"$@\"`.","example":"`f() { printf '[%s]\\n' \"$@\"; }; f 'a b' c` → `[a b]` then `[c]`.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-bash-recognize","name":"Bash recognize","tags":["scripting","shell"],"prose":"Bash (Bourne-Again Shell) extends POSIX sh with arrays, [[ ]] test, brace expansion, and process substitution — these features are what let you recognize a bash-specific script on the exam.","source":"Mod04 Ch9","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Features identifying bash specifically (vs sh)?","answer":"Bourne Again Shell. Supports arrays, `[[ ]]`, brace expansion, process substitution `\u003c(...)`, `${var:-default}` param expansion beyond POSIX sh.","explanation":"`[[ ]]` is bash-specific (POSIX has only `[ ]`); arrays `arr=(a b c)` and `${arr[i]}` are bash; process substitution `\u003c(cmd)` and `\u003e(cmd)` is bash. Seeing any of these → script requires bash, not plain sh.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-flow-control","name":"Flow control","tags":["scripting","shell"],"prose":"Flashcards covering Flow control.","source":"Mod09 Ch28; Review Apr 17","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Bash flow control constructs?","answer":"1. `if/elif/else/fi`\n2. `for var in list; do ... done`\n3. `while cond; do ... done`\n4. `until cond; do ... done`\n5. `case word in pattern) ... ;; esac`","explanation":"Every bash control construct closes with its reversed keyword (if/fi, case/esac, do/done). `case` patterns use glob syntax, not regex. `[[ -cond ]]` is the modern test operator.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-perl","name":"Perl","tags":["scripting","shell"],"prose":"Flashcards covering Perl.","source":"Review Apr 17 (explicitly out of scope)","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Is Perl on the exam?","answer":"No. Instructor explicitly said perl is not tested.","explanation":"The course teaches bash scripting for the exam. Perl appears historically as the \"swiss army chainsaw\" of Unix scripting but isn't in the assessed skill set.","bloom":"remember"}]}]},{"id":"misc","name":"Misc / editors / misc topics","topics":[{"id":"4915-linux-basics","name":"Linux basics","tags":["fundamentals"],"prose":"Kernel mechanism to hide resources from processes outside the namespace. K8s pods and containers are built on these.","source":"Mod01 Ch1","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Who started Linux and when?","answer":"Linus Torvalds, 1991. Kernel 1.0 released 1994.","explanation":"Torvalds posted his \"just a hobby, won't be big and professional like gnu\" Usenet note in August 1991. The kernel grew into production-ready by 1.0 (1994). Distributions bundle kernel + GNU userland + package manager.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Why was UNIX rewritten in C in 1973?","answer":"Portability. Assembly ties code to one CPU; C compiles on any architecture.","explanation":"Before 1973, UNIX was PDP-11 assembly only. Rewriting in C meant a working C compiler on a new CPU ports the entire OS — the single biggest reason UNIX spread across vendors and architectures.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What Linux command displays the system manual?","answer":"`man`. (Not disp, info, sysman.)","explanation":"`man` opens the manpage for a command in a pager. Sections: 1 user cmds, 2 syscalls, 3 library funcs, 5 file formats, 8 admin cmds. Search with `man -k keyword` (apropos).","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which Unix command lists directory contents?","answer":"`ls`. (Not dir, cat, joe, rm.)","explanation":"`ls` reads the directory entries and prints filenames. Common flags: `-l` long form, `-a` include dotfiles, `-h` human-readable sizes, `-t` sort by mtime, `-S` sort by size.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-users","name":"Users","tags":["sysadmin"],"prose":"Flashcards covering Users.","source":"Mod05 Ch11","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"How many fields in /etc/passwd and what are they?","answer":"7 fields:\n1. Username\n2. `x` (pw placeholder)\n3. UID\n4. GID\n5. GECOS\n6. Home\n7. Shell","explanation":"Seven colon-separated fields per user. The `x` in field 2 is a placeholder — the real password hash lives in `/etc/shadow` (readable only by root). GECOS is a free-text comment field (full name, phone, etc.).","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which file contains actual password hashes?","answer":"`/etc/shadow` (root-only, 600).","explanation":"/etc/passwd stays world-readable for UID→name lookups; /etc/shadow isolates the sensitive hashes with 600 perms. Separating them was a security fix after /etc/passwd's world-readable design enabled offline cracking.","bloom":"remember"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Add a user with home directory created?","answer":"`useradd -m username`.","explanation":"`useradd` without `-m` creates the account but no home directory. `-m` also copies skeleton files from `/etc/skel/*` into the new home (default bashrc, bash_profile, etc.). Set password after: `passwd username`.","example":"`useradd -m -s /bin/bash alice && passwd alice` — complete account creation.","bloom":"remember"}]},{"id":"4915-control-plane","name":"Control plane","tags":["kubernetes"],"prose":"Deployment (most common app, Quiz 4 Q4) wraps ReplicaSet → manages pods with rolling updates. DaemonSet runs one pod per node (Quiz 4 Q8).","source":"Mod10A; materials/past-exams/comp4915_quiz4.md","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"What does kube-scheduler do?","answer":"Watches unscheduled pods, filters+scores nodes, binds pod to a node.","explanation":"The scheduler is stateless — it watches apiserver for pods with no nodeName, runs the Filter phase (predicates: resource fit, taints) then Score phase (priorities: spread, affinity), and writes the binding back to apiserver. kubelet on the chosen node then pulls the pod.","example":"New pod needs 2 CPU. Filter phase: eliminates nodes with \u003c2 CPU free. Score phase: ranks remaining nodes by spread preference. Scheduler writes `nodeName: node-3` to apiserver; node-3's kubelet sees it and starts the container.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What does kube-controller-manager do?","answer":"Runs controllers (Deployment, ReplicaSet, Node, Job, etc.) that reconcile actual state to desired state.","explanation":"Controller-manager bundles many reconcile loops into one binary. Each loop watches its resource type in apiserver and takes action to converge. Node controller marks unresponsive nodes unhealthy; Deployment controller creates ReplicaSets from Deployment specs.","example":"You set `replicas: 3` in a Deployment. controller-manager's ReplicaSet loop sees 2 running pods → creates 1 more to match desired state.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Purpose of kube-proxy?","answer":"Implements Kubernetes Service routing on each node via iptables or IPVS rules.","explanation":"kube-proxy runs on every node and watches Service + Endpoints from apiserver. It programs the local kernel's iptables or IPVS tables so packets to a ClusterIP get DNAT'd to a healthy backend pod IP. Traffic never goes through kube-proxy itself — it just installs rules.","bloom":"understand"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What is CRI?","answer":"Container Runtime Interface — API between kubelet and container runtime (containerd, CRI-O).","explanation":"CRI is a gRPC API kubelet uses to start/stop containers and images. It abstracts the runtime so Kubernetes isn't tied to Docker — containerd, CRI-O, and others implement CRI. kubelet is the client; runtime is the server.","example":"Swapping Docker for containerd in a cluster: only the CRI implementation changes; kubelet, scheduler, and controllers are unaffected because they all talk CRI, not Docker APIs.","bloom":"understand"}]},{"id":"4915-tar-simple","name":"tar simple","tags":["archives","fundamentals"],"prose":"Flashcards covering tar simple.","source":"Mod02 Ch7; Review Apr 17","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Three core tar commands: create, list, extract?","answer":"1. **Create**: `tar -cf archive.tar files`\n2. **List**: `tar -tf archive.tar`\n3. **Extract**: `tar -xf archive.tar`","explanation":"`-c` create, `-t` list (table of contents), `-x` extract. `-f` names the archive file. Add `-z` (gzip) or `-j` (bzip2) to compress; `-v` to make it verbose.","example":"`tar -czvf backup.tar.gz /etc/` — create compressed verbose archive of /etc/.","bloom":"remember"}]}]}],"mockExam":{"duration_seconds":7200,"questions":[{"id":"q1","type":"MCQ","topic":"Filesystem","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q18","tags":["pretest"],"question":"Which of the following is the Unix root directory?","correct":4,"rationale":"`/` is the root directory. `/root` is root user's home. (Verbatim from midterm Q18.)","choices":["`/root`","`root`","`c:/`","`root/`","`/`"]},{"id":"q2","type":"MCQ","topic":"Commands","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q8","question":"Which command displays the system manual for a utility?","correct":1,"rationale":"`man` is the canonical man-page viewer. `info` is GNU's hyperlinked alternative — not every utility ships info pages, so it isn't the universal answer. `disp` and `sysman` don't exist as Unix commands. `mozilla` is a web browser, not a doc viewer. (Midterm Q8, sample Q1.)","choices":["info","man","disp","sysman","mozilla"]},{"id":"q3","type":"MCQ","topic":"Redirection","marks":2,"bloom":"apply","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q4","question":"To send command output to a file and also to standard output, use which command?","correct":0,"rationale":"`tee` duplicates stdin to both stdout and a named file — T-pipe semantics. `\u003e` / `\u003e\u003e` redirect *away* from stdout (nothing reaches the terminal), so neither satisfies \"also to stdout\". 'redirection' and 'switch' aren't commands. Trap: assuming `\u003e\u003e` is a \"show-and-append\" operator — it isn't, it's append-only. (Midterm Q4.)","choices":["tee","redirection","switch","`\u003e`","`\u003e\u003e`"]},{"id":"q4","type":"MCQ","topic":"Find","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q6","question":"Locate a file named foo with no idea where it is — which command?","correct":2,"rationale":"`find / -name foo`. Need a starting path (root), and `-name` takes the pattern. (Midterm Q6.)","choices":["find -name foo","find foo","find / -name foo","whereis foo","find / foo"]},{"id":"q5","type":"MCQ","topic":"Redirection","marks":2,"bloom":"apply","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q10","question":"Which directs standard output to outfile AND standard error to errfile?","correct":1,"rationale":"stdout is fd 1 (`\u003e` alone = `1\u003e`); stderr is fd 2 (`2\u003e`). Choice 1 binds each to its own file. Choice 0 uses `0\u003e`, which redirects fd 0 (stdin) — stderr is untouched and spills to the terminal. Choice 2 (`1\u003eerrfile`) redirects stdout twice; last binding wins, `outfile` stays empty. Choice 3 (`\u003coutfile`) is input redirection. Choice 4 swaps targets. (Midterm Q10.)","choices":["make FreeCiv \u003eoutfile 0\u003eerrfile","make FreeCiv \u003eoutfile 2\u003eerrfile","make FreeCiv \u003eoutfile 1\u003eerrfile","make FreeCiv \u003coutfile 2\u003cerrfile","make FreeCiv \u003eerrfile 2\u003eoutfile"]},{"id":"q6","type":"MCQ","topic":"grep","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q34","question":"Correct syntax to search for word 'superman' in SuperHeroes?","correct":1,"rationale":"**B: `grep -w`**. The question says *word*. `-w` matches whole-word boundaries — `superman` hits but `supermanhood` does not. Plain `grep superman` (D) is a substring match and would also hit `supermanhood`, so D does not satisfy the 'word' constraint. Distractors: -v inverts, -q is quiet, -n adds line numbers. (Midterm Q34.)","choices":["grep -v superman SuperHeroes","grep -w superman SuperHeroes","grep -q superman SuperHeroes","grep superman SuperHeroes","grep -n superman SuperHeroes"]},{"id":"q7","type":"MCQ","topic":"Permissions","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q16","question":"Make jack the owner of all files under /home/jack/candy?","correct":1,"rationale":"`chown -R` (capital R) recurses. `chown`/`chgrp` are the exception — every other common recursive tool (`grep`, `cp`, `ls`, `rm`) uses lowercase `-r`, so `-r` is the reflex trap. `-changes` isn't a flag. `chmod` changes permission bits, not ownership, so `chmod u+rwx` leaves `jack` as non-owner. (Midterm Q16.)","choices":["chown -changes jack /home/jack/candy","chown -R jack /home/jack/candy","chmod u+rwx /home/jack/candy","chown -r jack /home/jack/candy","chmod a+rwx jack /home/jack/candy"]},{"id":"q8","type":"MCQ","topic":"Quoting","marks":2,"bloom":"apply","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q47","tags":["pretest"],"question":"person=jenny. Output of `echo '$person'`?","correct":3,"rationale":"Single quotes suppress all 7 shell expansions — content is emitted byte-for-byte, so `'$person'` prints `$person`. Trap: assuming any quote form expands `$var`. Double quotes expand `$var`, backticks, `$(...)`, and `\\`; bare expands all 7; single quotes expand nothing. (Midterm Q47.)","choices":["person","jenny","'$person'","$person","$jenny"]},{"id":"q9","type":"MCQ","topic":"Links","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod02 Ch6; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q24","question":"To link a file so that the linked file exists even after original is deleted?","correct":4,"rationale":"A hard link is a second directory entry pointing to the *same inode*; the file disappears only when the inode's link count reaches 0, so either entry can be deleted and the other still works. Soft/symbolic links store the *pathname* as data — deleting the target leaves a dangling link. 'virtual' and 'shortcut' aren't Linux link types (Windows shortcut terminology). (Midterm Q24.)","choices":["virtual","shortcut","soft","symbolic","hard"]},{"id":"q10","type":"MCQ","topic":"Shell params","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q31","tags":["pretest"],"question":"Which variable holds the entire argument list?","correct":3,"rationale":"`$@` expands to the full positional-parameter list — and under `\"$@\"` each argument stays a separate word, the only safe iteration form. `$#` is the *count* of args, not the list. `$?` is last exit status. `$$` is the shell's PID. `$args` is just a user variable — no special meaning. Trap: `$*` looks identical until you quote it (`\"$*\"` joins all args into one string). (Midterm Q31.)","choices":["$?","$#","$args","$@","$$"]},{"id":"q11","type":"MCQ","topic":"Runlevels","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q35","question":"Run level 3 in Linux System V does what?","correct":3,"rationale":"SysV runlevels: 0 halt, 1 single-user, 3 multi-user text (server default), 5 multi-user GUI, 6 reboot. Trap: \"Multiuser graphics\" sounds right because modern desktops boot to it — but that's runlevel 5. \"Reboots\"/\"Halts\" are 6/0. `systemctl get-default` maps targets to the old numeric runlevel. (Midterm Q35.)","choices":["Reboots","Single user","Multiuser graphics","Multiuser text","Halts"]},{"id":"q12","type":"MCQ","topic":"Shell","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q33","question":"Which command changes your login shell?","correct":4,"rationale":"`chsh` = change shell; edits the final field of `/etc/passwd` (login shell path) for the invoking user. The other options (`newsh`, `chngsh`, `chlg`, `cs`) aren't real commands. Trap: inventing abbreviations by analogy with `chmod`/`chown` — the canonical verb is `chsh` with its own spelling. (Midterm Q33.)","choices":["newsh","chngsh","chlg","cs","chsh"]},{"id":"q13","type":"MCQ","topic":"Networking","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod06 Ch19; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q1","question":"Secure technology for serving files over internet?","correct":1,"rationale":"`sftp` is file-transfer *over* the SSH channel — credentials and payload both encrypted. `ftp://` and plain `ftp` ship credentials and data in cleartext (anyone on-path sniffs them). `http` is also cleartext and has no file-transfer semantics — wrong protocol family. `ssh` alone is a *remote shell*, not a file-serving protocol (you'd layer `scp`/`sftp` on top). Trap: picking `ssh` because it's \"the secure one\". (Midterm Q1.)","choices":["ftp://","sftp","http","ssh","ftp"]},{"id":"q14","type":"MCQ","topic":"Networking","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod07 Ch22; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q19","question":"Service to offer remote mounting of Linux partitions on a Linux-only network?","correct":4,"rationale":"**NFS** (Network File System) is the native Unix remote-mount protocol — server exports a directory in `/etc/exports`, client runs `mount -t nfs server:/path /mnt`. `SMB` is the Windows-family protocol (use Samba for Linux↔Windows interop, not Linux-only). `NIS` distributes user/group maps, not filesystems. `DNS` resolves names. `FIPS` is a US crypto standard — not a filesystem at all. (Midterm Q19.)","choices":["FIPS","NIS","SMB","DNS","NFS"]},{"id":"q15","type":"MCQ","topic":"DNS","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod08 Ch24; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q28","question":"Which daemon manages a machine's DNS?","correct":2,"rationale":"The running daemon is `named` (\"name-d\"). **BIND** (Berkeley Internet Name Domain) is the *software suite* and the package name — not the process in the process table. `inetd` is a superserver for other network services. `dnsd` and `iisd` don't exist. Trap: picking `bind` because it's the name everyone *says* — `ps` shows `named`. (Midterm Q28.)","choices":["dnsd","inetd","named","bind","iisd"]},{"id":"q16","type":"MCQ","topic":"K8s","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"materials/past-exams/comp4915_quiz4.md Q1","tags":["pretest"],"question":"Agent on cluster nodes implementing control-plane commands?","correct":2,"rationale":"**Kubelet** is the per-node agent that reads PodSpecs from the apiserver and drives the container runtime via CRI — the boots-on-the-ground that executes control-plane commands. `kubectl` is the user CLI (runs on your laptop, not on cluster nodes). `DaemonSet`/`Deployment` are workload *objects* managed by the controller-manager — they don't run anywhere themselves. `OCI` is a runtime/image spec, not an agent. (Quiz 4 Q1.)","choices":["DaemonSet","Deployment","Kubelet","OCI","kubectl"]},{"id":"q17","type":"MCQ","topic":"K8s","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"materials/past-exams/comp4915_quiz4.md Q2","question":"K8s executable image format?","correct":3,"rationale":"**OCI** (Open Container Initiative) defines the runtime + image specs every container engine (containerd, CRI-O, Docker) implements — the format K8s ships container images in. A `container` is a running instance, not a format. A `pod` is a *group of containers*, not an image. `CNCF` is the foundation that hosts K8s (governance, not a file format). `OKD` is a Kubernetes distribution. (Quiz 4 Q2.)","choices":["container","pod","CNCF","OCI","OKD"]},{"id":"q18","type":"MCQ","topic":"K8s","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"materials/past-exams/comp4915_quiz4.md Q4","question":"Most common way to run a K8s app?","correct":0,"rationale":"**Deployment** wraps a ReplicaSet to provide declarative rolling updates, rollback, and scaling — the default choice for stateless apps. A bare `pod` has no self-healing or replicas. `DaemonSet` is infrastructure (one pod per node). `StatefulSet` handles stateful workloads (DBs, order-sensitive apps). `container` is a Docker term, not a K8s workload object. (Quiz 4 Q4.)","choices":["deployment","pod","daemonset","StatefulSet","container"]},{"id":"q19","type":"MCQ","topic":"K8s","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"materials/past-exams/comp4915_quiz4.md Q8","question":"K8s object running one pod on every node?","correct":3,"rationale":"**DaemonSet** schedules exactly one pod on every matching node — perfect for log collectors, node monitoring agents, CNI components. `Node` is a host *machine*, not a workload controller. `StatefulSet` gives ordered/named pods, not one-per-node. `Job` runs to completion. `DNS` is a service, not a workload controller. (Quiz 4 Q8.)","choices":["Node","StatefulSet","Job","DaemonSet","DNS"]},{"id":"q20","type":"MCQ","topic":"K8s","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"materials/past-exams/comp4915_quiz4.md Q10","question":"Reason for the pause container in a pod?","correct":0,"rationale":"The pause container is the first started in a pod; it holds NET/IPC/UTS namespaces open so subsequent containers can `join` them — creating the shared-network/localhost illusion inside a pod. It calls `pause()` and burns zero CPU. The other options reverse cause/effect (pause doesn't serve anything, K8s doesn't \"pause\" workloads through it). (Quiz 4 Q10.)","choices":["helps set up Linux namespaces and cgroups for a pod","allows running the pause service","allows each pod to use the pause service","allows the pod it is with to use the pause service","allows kubernetes to pause the pod it is in"]},{"id":"q21","type":"MCQ","topic":"Runlevels","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"materials/past-exams/comp4915_quiz4.md Q5","question":"Which run level halts the system?","correct":0,"rationale":"Runlevel 0 halts (power-off style). 6 reboots. 1 is single-user maintenance. 3/5 are multi-user text/GUI. Trap: picking 6 because \"shutdown\" mentally maps to \"restart\" — the machine cycles to 0 (halt) only if you explicitly target it; 6 loops back into the OS.","choices":["0","1","3","5","6"]},{"id":"q22","type":"MCQ","topic":"iptables","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod08 Ch25; materials/labs/Lab8.pdf","question":"Default policy of the filter table INPUT chain if no rule matches and no policy set?","correct":2,"rationale":"A fresh filter table ships with INPUT/OUTPUT/FORWARD all defaulting to **ACCEPT** — iptables is permissive until you set `iptables -P INPUT DROP`. Trap: assuming \"firewall = default-deny\" because modern security training drills deny-by-default; Linux itself does not start there. `REJECT` is a *target*, not a default policy. `LOG`/`MASQUERADE` aren't valid policy values.","choices":["DROP","REJECT","ACCEPT","LOG","MASQUERADE"]},{"id":"q23","type":"MCQ","topic":"Apache","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod10D; materials/labs/Lab10.pdf","question":"Default DocumentRoot on RHEL/Fedora?","correct":1,"rationale":"RHEL/CentOS/Fedora package `httpd` with DocumentRoot `/var/www/html` (Debian mirrors the path). `/etc/httpd/` is the config tree (httpd.conf, conf.d/), not the content tree — mixing them is the classic trap. `/srv/www` is an FHS-blessed convention some distros use but not RHEL default. `/home/www` and `/usr/local/httpd` aren't standard.","choices":["/etc/httpd/html","/var/www/html","/srv/www","/home/www","/usr/local/httpd"]},{"id":"q24","type":"MCQ","topic":"Samba","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod10C; materials/labs/Lab10.pdf","question":"Samba configuration file?","correct":1,"rationale":"Path is `/etc/samba/smb.conf` — the `samba/` subdirectory mirrors other service packages (`/etc/ssh/`, `/etc/httpd/`). `/etc/smb.conf` (no subdir) and `/etc/smbd.conf` (daemon-named) are plausible-looking guesses but wrong. `/var/lib/samba/` holds runtime state (tdb databases, cache), not config. Trap: inventing `samba.conf` by analogy — the filename is still `smb.conf` (the protocol name).","choices":["/etc/smb.conf","/etc/samba/smb.conf","/etc/samba/samba.conf","/etc/smbd.conf","/var/lib/samba/smb.conf"]},{"id":"q25","type":"MCQ","topic":"Namespaces","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod10E; materials/labs/Lab10.pdf","question":"Which command creates new Linux namespaces?","correct":1,"rationale":"`unshare` creates a new namespace of a requested type and runs a command inside it (e.g., `unshare --net bash`). `nsenter` *joins* an existing namespace by PID or file descriptor — opposite direction. `lsns` only lists. `chroot` changes the root directory but doesn't create a namespace (no MNT isolation). `pivot_root` swaps the rootfs from inside an existing mount namespace.","choices":["nsenter","unshare","lsns","chroot","pivot\\_root"]},{"id":"q26","type":"MCQ","topic":"Redirection","marks":1,"bloom":"remember","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q46","tags":["pretest"],"question":"`tr -d '\\r'` can convert DOS/Windows text files to Unix.","correct":0,"rationale":"TRUE. DOS/Windows line endings are CRLF (`\\r\\n`); Unix is LF (`\\n`) alone. `tr -d '\\r'` deletes every CR byte on stdin, leaving LF — a clean Unix line terminator. Wrong reading: thinking `tr -d` needs both bytes named (`tr -d '\\r\\n'` would also strip LF and collapse the file into a single line). (Midterm Q46.)","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q27","type":"MCQ","topic":"Redirection","marks":1,"bloom":"apply","source":"Mod02 Ch7","question":"Redirecting output to a file will warn before overwriting existing data.","correct":1,"rationale":"FALSE. `\u003e` truncates the target to zero bytes before writing — silently, no prompt. This is the classic data-destruction trap the midterm drills. Defences: `set -C` (noclobber) makes `\u003e` error if target exists; override with `\u003e|`. Use `\u003e\u003e` when you want append-only. Wrong reading: conflating shell safety with `rm -i`-style interactive prompts — redirection has no such mode. (Midterm Q43/Q44.)","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q28","type":"MCQ","topic":"Security","marks":1,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod08 Ch25","question":"rsh, rlogin, rcp all have security risks.","correct":0,"rationale":"TRUE. The r-services transmit credentials and payload in cleartext, and authenticate via `~/.rhosts` / `/etc/hosts.equiv` trust — source-IP spoofing is enough to impersonate a trusted host. Modern Linux replaces the whole family with `ssh`/`scp`/`sftp` (public-key auth + encrypted channel). Wrong reading: \"only passwords leak\" — every byte of the session is visible on-wire. (Midterm Q45.)","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q29","type":"MCQ","topic":"Exit status","marks":1,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod09 Ch28; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q59","question":"The shell stores the exit status of the last command in $?.","correct":0,"rationale":"TRUE. Every child process returns an 8-bit exit status on termination; the shell captures it into the special parameter `$?`. Convention: 0 = success, 1–255 = failure (with some well-known codes: 2 misuse, 126 not-executable, 127 not-found, 128+N killed by signal N). Wrong reading: confusing `$?` (status) with `$!` (PID of last backgrounded job) or `$$` (current shell PID). (Midterm Q39.)","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q30","type":"MCQ","topic":"Quoting","marks":1,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod04 Ch9","question":"`echo '$person'` (with person='Fred') outputs `Fred`.","correct":1,"rationale":"FALSE. Single quotes suppress all 7 shell expansions — the content inside is emitted byte-for-byte, so `'$person'` prints the literal four-character string `$person`. To expand, you need `\"$person\"` (double quotes) or bare `$person`. Wrong reading: assuming any quote style expands variables — only double / bare do. (Midterm Q47.)","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q31","type":"MCQ","topic":"Filesystem","marks":1,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod02 Ch6; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q24","tags":["pretest"],"question":"Hard links can cross filesystem boundaries.","correct":1,"rationale":"FALSE. A hard link is a directory entry pointing at an inode; inode numbers are unique only *within* one filesystem, so `ln /mnt/usb/file ~/link` errors with `Invalid cross-device link`. Soft (symbolic) links dodge this — they store the *pathname* as data and cross FS freely. Wrong reading: treating hard and soft links as equivalent; they differ on cross-FS, on dangling behaviour, and on directories.","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q32","type":"MCQ","topic":"less","marks":1,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod02 Ch7","question":"`less` displays a text file one screen at a time.","correct":0,"rationale":"TRUE. `less` is the canonical interactive pager — space/pgdn advance one screen, `/pattern` searches, `q` quits, and unlike `more` you can scroll backward. `cat` dumps the whole file at once (no paging). Wrong reading: conflating `less` with `head` (first N lines) or `tail` (last N). Mnemonic: \"`less` is `more`\" — it replaced `more` with more features. (Midterm Q40.)","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q33","type":"MCQ","topic":"K8s","marks":1,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod10D","question":"The pause container runs application logic.","correct":1,"rationale":"FALSE. The pause container is a near-empty binary that calls `pause()` and sleeps forever. Its entire job is to hold the pod's NET/IPC/UTS namespaces open so the application containers can *join* them and share localhost + IP. Killing the pause container tears the pod down. Wrong reading: thinking \"pause\" names an app-lifecycle feature (like `kubectl pause`) — it's just a namespace anchor.","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q34","type":"MCQ","topic":"Bash","marks":1,"bloom":"remember","source":"materials/past-exams/comp4915_quiz3.md Q4","question":"In bash, comments start with `#`.","correct":0,"rationale":"TRUE. Bash treats `#` through end-of-line as a comment, anywhere on a line — except the shebang `#!` at line 1, col 1, which the kernel reads as an interpreter directive. Trap: confusing `#` (comment / length prefix in `${#var}`) with `$` (variable prefix) or `!` (history expansion). (Sample Q8, Quiz 3 Q4.)","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q35","type":"MCQ","topic":"K8s","marks":1,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod04 Ch9","question":"etcd is where Kubernetes *persists* raw cluster state data.","correct":0,"rationale":"TRUE — etcd is the distributed KV store (raft consensus) that holds the cluster's state data. Note: Quiz 4 Q5 asked what *maintains* state — that answer is kube-controller-manager (etcd is not even in Q5's options).","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q36","type":"MCQ","topic":"Networking","marks":1,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod07 Ch22-23","question":"NFS is suitable for Linux-to-Windows file sharing.","correct":1,"rationale":"FALSE. NFS is the Unix remote-filesystem protocol — POSIX perms, UID/GID ownership, root squash. Windows speaks SMB/CIFS natively; NFS clients on Windows exist but are clunky and misreport ACLs. The canonical Linux↔Windows bridge is **Samba** (Linux server speaks SMB). Wrong reading: assuming \"network FS\" means \"any OS\" — NFS is Unix-to-Unix by design.","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q37","type":"SHORT","topic":"Bit bucket","marks":3,"bloom":"apply","source":"Mod04 Ch9","question":"What is the name of the Linux bit-bucket?","correct":"\u003ccode\u003e/dev/null\u003c/code\u003e","rationale":"`/dev/null` is a character-special device: writes are discarded (successfully), reads return EOF immediately. Idiomatic uses: silence stderr (`cmd 2\u003e/dev/null`), truncate a file via redirection (`: \u003e f`), or test write success without keeping output. Trap: confusing `/dev/null` (write-to-discard) with `/dev/zero` (read-infinite-nulls). (Midterm Q48.)"},{"id":"q38","type":"SHORT","topic":"Commands","marks":3,"bloom":"apply","source":"Mod04 Ch9","question":"What command displays the name of the Linux machine you are working at?","correct":"\u003ccode\u003ehostname\u003c/code\u003e","rationale":"`hostname` with no args prints the short machine name (kernel's node name). `hostname -f` prints the FQDN. `uname -n` is an equivalent POSIX alternative. Trap: `whoami` / `id` print the *user*, not the *machine*; `host`/`dig` query *remote* DNS, not the local hostname. (Midterm Q49.)"},{"id":"q39","type":"SHORT","topic":"Redirection","marks":3,"bloom":"apply","source":"Mod04 Ch9","question":"Predict output. x doesn't exist, y contains 'This is y': ```bash cat x y 1\u003ehold 2\u003e&1 cat hold ```","correct":"\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-bash\"\u003ecat: x: No such file or directory\nThis is y\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e","rationale":"Trace: `1\u003ehold` first binds fd 1 to file `hold`; `2\u003e&1` then duplicates fd 2 onto fd 1's *current* binding — so stderr also lands in `hold`. `cat x y` processes each arg in order: `x` fails (stderr: \"No such file or directory\"), then `y` succeeds (stdout: \"This is y\"). Both streams end up in `hold`, in the order cat emitted them. Trap: writing `2\u003e&1 1\u003ehold` reverses the order — stderr stays at the terminal because `2\u003e&1` copied fd 1's pre-redirect binding. (Midterm Q50.)"},{"id":"q40","type":"SHORT","topic":"Glob","marks":3,"bloom":"apply","source":"Mod04 Ch9","question":"Given libby1.jpg..libby12.jpg and libby1.txt, which files match `libby1*.jpg`?","correct":"libby1.jpg, libby10.jpg, libby11.jpg, libby12.jpg","rationale":"Shell glob `*` matches zero-or-more characters, including the empty string — so `libby1*.jpg` matches `libby1.jpg` (zero extra chars), `libby10/11/12.jpg` (one extra digit), but NOT `libby2..9.jpg` (the `1` is literal). `libby1.txt` is excluded by the `.jpg` suffix. Trap: thinking `*` requires at least one character — in shell globbing it also matches empty. (Midterm Q56.)"},{"id":"q41","type":"SHORT","topic":"Glob","marks":3,"bloom":"apply","source":"Mod04 Ch9","question":"Which files match `libby[6-8].jpg`?","correct":"libby6.jpg, libby7.jpg, libby8.jpg","rationale":"A bracket expression `[6-8]` is a character class matching *exactly one* character from the set {6,7,8}. So `libby6.jpg`, `libby7.jpg`, `libby8.jpg` match; `libby10..12.jpg` don't (two characters between `libby` and `.jpg`). Trap: reading `[6-8]` as \"6 through 8\" inclusive of multi-digit numbers — it's single-character only; use `libby[6-9].jpg libby1[0-2].jpg` for double digits. (Midterm Q57.)"},{"id":"q42","type":"SHORT","topic":"Aliases","marks":3,"bloom":"apply","source":"Mod04 Ch9","question":"How do you find aliases currently defined in your shell?","correct":"Run \u003ccode\u003ealias\u003c/code\u003e with no arguments.","rationale":"Bare `alias` lists every alias in the current shell, one per line as `name='expansion'`. `alias foo` (one arg, no `=`) prints just that alias. `alias foo=cmd` creates or replaces one. Aliases are per-shell and non-exporting — child processes don't inherit them; put them in `~/.bashrc` for persistence. (Midterm Q53.)"},{"id":"q43","type":"SHORT","topic":"Shell","marks":3,"bloom":"apply","source":"Mod04 Ch9","question":"Command to display the value of variable myvar?","correct":"\u003ccode\u003eecho $myvar\u003c/code\u003e (or \u003ccode\u003eecho \"$myvar\"\u003c/code\u003e)","rationale":"Use double quotes to preserve whitespace."},{"id":"q44","type":"SHORT","topic":"grep","marks":3,"bloom":"apply","source":"Mod01 Ch5","question":"Write a command that displays all lines in files in current directory which do NOT contain bb, bB, Bb, or BB.","correct":"\u003ccode\u003egrep -vi bb *\u003c/code\u003e","rationale":"\\-v inverts match, -i ignores case — so all 4 variants matched then inverted."},{"id":"q45","type":"SHORT","topic":"PAM","marks":3,"bloom":"apply","source":"Mod01 Ch5; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q43","question":"What is Linux-PAM?","correct":"Pluggable Authentication Modules — modular authentication library. Apps use a unified PAM API; admin configures auth policy per-service in /etc/pam.d/ without recompiling apps.","rationale":"Midterm Q51. Key point: modular, per-service, no recompile."},{"id":"q46","type":"SHORT","topic":"SSH","marks":3,"bloom":"apply","source":"Mod06 Ch18; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q34","question":"Write the SSH command to forward local port 5432 through bastion.example.com to db.internal port 5432.","correct":"\u003ccode\u003essh -L 5432:db.internal:5432 user@bastion.example.com\u003c/code\u003e","rationale":"\\-L = local forward. Format: local:remote\\_host:remote\\_port."},{"id":"q47","type":"SHORT","topic":"K8s","marks":3,"bloom":"apply","source":"Mod09 Ch28","question":"Name the 8 Linux namespaces.","correct":"PID, NET, MNT, UTS, IPC, USER, CGROUP, TIME.","rationale":"Each isolates a specific kernel resource."},{"id":"q48","type":"SHORT","topic":"Hard vs soft links","marks":10,"bloom":"apply","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q58","question":"Discuss and distinguish the similarities and differences between hard and soft links in Linux. Include limitations and when to use each.","correct":"Hard link: extra directory entry pointing to same inode. Soft (symbolic) link: special file containing target's pathname as text.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSimilarities:\u003c/strong\u003e both allow multiple names/paths to reach same data; both created with \u003ccode\u003eln\u003c/code\u003e.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDifferences:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003cbr\u003e• Hard link shares inode → identical file; can't span filesystems (inode unique per FS); can't link to directories (normal users); no dangling — file persists as long as link count &gt; 0.\u003cbr\u003e• Soft link has own inode containing target path text; CAN span filesystems; CAN link to directories; CAN dangle if target deleted; ls -l shows \u003ccode\u003el\u003c/code\u003e type and arrow to target.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUse hard link when:\u003c/strong\u003e aliasing same file on one filesystem, tracking link count for cleanup.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUse soft link when:\u003c/strong\u003e crossing filesystems, linking to directories, pointing to a path that may change.","rationale":"Midterm Q58. Expected to cover inode mechanics, cross-FS limitation, dangling behavior."},{"id":"q49","type":"SHORT","topic":"Shell script","marks":10,"bloom":"apply","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q59","tags":["pretest"],"question":"Write a shell script that prints 'Your working directory is ' followed by your current working directory, all on one line.","correct":"\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-bash\"\u003e#!/bin/bash\necho \"Your working directory is $(pwd)\"\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003eOr: \u003ccode\u003eecho \"Your working directory is `pwd`\"\u003c/code\u003e","rationale":"Midterm Q59. Needs shebang + command substitution. `$(pwd)` preferred over backticks."},{"id":"q50","type":"SHORT","topic":"Bash function","marks":10,"bloom":"apply","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q60","tags":["pretest"],"question":"Write a bash function that reads a parameter and writes to stdout the processes in `ps aux` output that contain that parameter.","correct":"\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-bash\"\u003epsgrep() {\n    ps aux | grep \"$1\" | grep -v grep\n}\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003eCall: \u003ccode\u003epsgrep httpd\u003c/code\u003e","rationale":"Midterm Q60. `grep -v grep` excludes the grep process itself. Quote `\"$1\"` to handle spaces."},{"id":"q51","type":"MCQ","topic":"Filesystem","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod09 Ch28","question":"What is a Unix PPID?","correct":4,"rationale":"Parent Process ID. Every process except init has a parent. (Midterm Q26.)","choices":["person process ID","protected process ID","private process ID","protected parent ID","parent process ID"]},{"id":"q52","type":"MCQ","topic":"Commands","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod05 Ch10; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q35","question":"Which command sends a signal to a process?","correct":4,"rationale":"`kill` sends any signal (default SIGTERM, not SIGKILL) — the name is historical. `kill -HUP 123` makes a daemon reload config with no killing; `kill -STOP` pauses; `kill -9` is the one that can't be caught. The other options (`signal`, `snd`, `sendsig`, `send`) aren't real commands — Unix kept the old verb for compatibility. (Midterm Q23.)","choices":["signal","snd","sendsig","send","kill"]},{"id":"q53","type":"MCQ","topic":"Files","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod05 Ch11","question":"Command to list contents of a directory?","correct":0,"rationale":"`ls` is the canonical Unix directory listing command. `dir` exists as a GNU coreutils alias but isn't idiomatic on Unix (it's the DOS verb most users expect). `rm` deletes. `cat` dumps file *contents* — the file name has to exist and be a regular file, so it errors on directories. `joe` is a text editor. (Midterm Q29.)","choices":["ls","joe","rm","dir","cat"]},{"id":"q54","type":"MCQ","topic":"Commands","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod07 Ch21","question":"What does `tr` do?","correct":3,"rationale":"`tr` (translate) maps one character set to another character-by-character, or deletes with `-d`. Example: `tr 'a-z' 'A-Z'` upper-cases stdin. It isn't a language-to-language translator (not shell→perl, not C→assembler), doesn't manage processes (that's `fg`/`bg`), and doesn't match patterns (`grep`/regex's job). (Midterm Q14.)","choices":["Translates shell to perl","Moves process to foreground","Translates C to assembler","Maps one character string to another","Matches any single character"]},{"id":"q55","type":"MCQ","topic":"Shell","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod07 Ch20","question":"What does `cd ~` do?","correct":3,"rationale":"Bare `~` is tilde expansion — the shell substitutes `$HOME` *before* `cd` ever sees the argument. `~user` means that user's home directory. `cd ..` (two dots) goes up one directory, not `~`. `~` is not a literal directory name in the current folder — nor is it shorthand for root (`/`) or for listing. (Midterm Q5.)","choices":["Go up one directory","Switch to root","Change to directory ~ under current","Switch to your home directory","List current directory"]},{"id":"q56","type":"MCQ","topic":"Commands","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod07 Ch23; materials/labs/Lab7.pdf","question":"Which gives info like number of lines in a file?","correct":0,"rationale":"`wc` (word count) prints lines/words/bytes; `wc -l` isolates the line count — the standard idiom for \"how many lines in this file?\". `w` (no flag) shows logged-in users and their activity — completely unrelated. `w -l` is a malformed `w` invocation (no such flag). `wl`/`nl` either don't exist as line counters or do something else (`nl` numbers lines). (Midterm Q37, sample Q2.)","choices":["wc","wl","w -l","w","nl"]},{"id":"q57","type":"MCQ","topic":"GNU","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod07 Ch22","question":"Who founded the GNU project (and is paired with Linus Torvalds in Linux history)?","correct":2,"rationale":"Richard Stallman launched GNU in 1983 and authored the GPL; Linus Torvalds later wrote the kernel that GNU userland filled out into a full OS. Ritchie/Thompson built *original Unix* at Bell Labs (unrelated to GNU). Tanenbaum wrote Minix (Linus's inspiration, not his collaborator). Kernighan co-authored K&R C — famous in Unix lore but not GNU's founder. Trap: conflating all 1970s–80s Unix pioneers.","choices":["Dennis Ritchie","Ken Thompson","Richard Stallman","Andrew Tanenbaum","Brian Kernighan"]},{"id":"q58","type":"MCQ","topic":"Flags","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod08 Ch24","question":"Which is equivalent to `ls -r -x`?","correct":0,"rationale":"POSIX single-letter flags combine under one dash: `-r -x` → `-rx`. Long flags (`--reverse`, `--sort`) do NOT combine; each needs its own `--`. So `--rx` (choice 1) would be parsed as one long flag named \"rx\" (doesn't exist). `-r,-x` / `r x` / `r-x` aren't valid shell syntax at all. Rule applies only to single-char options without arguments glued to them.","choices":["ls -rx","ls --rx","ls -r,-x","ls r x","ls r-x"]},{"id":"q59","type":"MCQ","topic":"Devices","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod08 Ch26","question":"What does `/dev/zero` produce when read?","correct":1,"rationale":"`/dev/zero` is a character device that reads back an infinite stream of null bytes (`\\0`) — used to zero-fill disks (`dd if=/dev/zero of=... bs=1M`), pad files, or allocate blank anonymous memory. `/dev/random` / `/dev/urandom` give cryptographically random bytes (not zero). `/dev/null` is the *write-only* bit-bucket — reads return EOF immediately. Trap: confusing the three `/dev` specials.","choices":["Random bytes","Null bytes (0x00) infinitely","EOF immediately","Current time","Last input"]},{"id":"q60","type":"MCQ","topic":"NFS","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod08 Ch25","question":"Per instructor, NFS is useful:","correct":1,"rationale":"NFSv3 trusts client-supplied UIDs (no real auth) and ships RPC unencrypted — safe only on a trusted LAN behind a firewall. Exposed to the internet it's a data-leak by design (anyone claiming UID 0 is root). NFSv4 with Kerberos (`sec=krb5p`) is an option but outside this course's scope. \"Public internet\" / \"VPN\" / \"Wi-Fi\" either contradict the security posture or add no protection.","choices":["On the public internet","Only behind firewalls","Only over VPN","Only with Kerberos","Only on Wi-Fi"]},{"id":"q61","type":"MCQ","topic":"DHCP","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod06 Ch18","question":"DHCP client-server exchange (DORA) in order?","correct":1,"rationale":"**DORA**: client has no IP, *broadcasts* Discover. Server(s) *Offer* a lease. Client *Requests* a specific offer (so rejected servers free their reservations). Server *Acks*, lease is granted. Any reshuffle breaks the handshake — you can't Offer before Discover (server doesn't know who to talk to), can't Ack before Request (nothing to confirm).","choices":["Offer, Discover, Ack, Request","Discover, Offer, Request, Ack","Request, Offer, Discover, Ack","Ack, Discover, Offer, Request","Discover, Request, Offer, Ack"]},{"id":"q62","type":"MCQ","topic":"Soft link","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod10A; materials/past-exams/comp4915_quiz4.md","question":"Command to create a soft (symbolic) link?","correct":2,"rationale":"`ln -s target linkname` creates a symbolic link. Bare `ln` creates a *hard* link (wrong type). `-S` capital on Linux `ln` is a backup-suffix modifier, not a link-type flag — syntactically valid, semantically different. `-h` isn't a link-type flag on Linux `ln` either (it exists on BSD for a different purpose). `link` is a low-level command that can't create symlinks. Verb is `ln`, never `link -s`.","choices":["ln file link","ln -h file link","ln -s file link","ln -S file link","link file link"]},{"id":"q63","type":"MCQ","topic":"grep recursive","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod10D","question":"Flag to make grep search recursively through directories?","correct":1,"rationale":"`grep -r` (or `-R`, which also follows symlinks) walks directories recursively. `-d` is a *directory-handling mode* switch (`-d skip` / `-d recurse` / `-d read`), not itself a recursive flag. `-a` treats binary as text. `-n` adds line numbers. `-t` isn't standard. Trap: picking `-d` by analogy with other tools where `-d` means \"directory\".","choices":["\\-d","\\-r","\\-a","\\-t","\\-n"]},{"id":"q64","type":"MCQ","topic":"tar","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod10C","question":"Which tar command extracts an archive?","correct":2,"rationale":"Mnemonic — **x**tract, **c**reate, **t**-list. `-f` names the archive file. So `tar -xf a.tar` extracts, `tar -cf a.tar dir/` creates, `tar -tf a.tar` lists. `-d` compares archive to disk (rarely used). `-lf` isn't a valid flag pair — `-l` warns about changed file sizes during create. Trap: guessing `-xf` vs `-cf` under time pressure — the mnemonic anchors it.","choices":["tar -cf","tar -tf","tar -xf","tar -df","tar -lf"]},{"id":"q65","type":"MCQ","topic":"hostname","marks":2,"bloom":"remember","source":"Mod10B","question":"What does `hostname` display?","correct":1,"rationale":"`hostname` prints the current machine's name (short form by default; `hostname -f` for FQDN). It doesn't query DNS servers (no external lookup), doesn't show usernames (that's `whoami`/`id`), doesn't show the local IP (`ip addr` / `hostname -I`), and doesn't resolve remote FQDNs (`host`/`dig`). Trap: treating `hostname` as a networking query tool.","choices":["Current username","Name of machine logged into","DNS server IP","Local IP","FQDN of remote"]},{"id":"q66","type":"MCQ","topic":"Perl","marks":1,"bloom":"remember","source":"materials/past-exams/comp4915_quiz3.md; Review Apr 17","question":"Perl scripting will be tested on the exam.","correct":1,"rationale":"FALSE. The exam covers bash scripting, system admin, networking, and K8s — Perl is explicitly out of scope. Trap: reading \"scripting\" broadly to include every script language; this course's \"scripting\" unit is bash-only. No Perl labs, no Perl on slides beyond a historical mention.","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q67","type":"MCQ","topic":"IPv6","marks":1,"bloom":"remember","source":"materials/past-exams/comp4915_quiz3.md; Review Apr 17","question":"You must know IPv6 DNS records (AAAA) for the exam.","correct":1,"rationale":"FALSE. Scope is IPv4: A records, dotted-quad addresses, CIDR masks. No AAAA, no link-local `fe80::`, no SLAAC, no dual-stack. Trap: assuming modern coursework implies current IPv6 content — the DNS unit here is strictly IPv4.","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q68","type":"MCQ","topic":"ACL","marks":1,"bloom":"remember","source":"materials/past-exams/comp4915_quiz4.md; Review Apr 17","question":"You need to know ACL (Access Control List) details for the exam.","correct":1,"rationale":"FALSE. The exam tests only traditional Unix perms (rwx for user/group/other plus setuid/setgid/sticky). POSIX ACLs (`getfacl`/`setfacl`, `mask::`, `default:`) are out of scope. Trap: over-studying — if you can compute `chmod 755` in octal and explain setuid, you're covered.","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q69","type":"MCQ","topic":"dhcpd.conf","marks":1,"bloom":"remember","source":"materials/past-exams/comp4915_quiz4.md; Review Apr 17","question":"You must be able to reproduce a dhcpd.conf file on the exam.","correct":1,"rationale":"FALSE. You need to know *what* DHCP does (DORA handshake, lease time, reservations) and roughly where config lives (`/etc/dhcp/dhcpd.conf`), not the full `subnet ... netmask ... { range ...; option ...; }` stanza syntax. Trap: memorizing directive names when conceptual knowledge is what's graded.","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q70","type":"MCQ","topic":"Hard link","marks":1,"bloom":"understand","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q24, Q58","question":"Given two files that are hard links to each other, there is no way to tell which was the 'original'.","correct":0,"rationale":"TRUE. Both names are equal directory entries pointing to the same inode — the filesystem does not record which entry was created first, and `ls -l` shows identical metadata for both (same inode, same mtime, same link count). `stat` cannot distinguish either. Trap: assuming the filename that came first is somehow \"canonical\" — the kernel has no notion of a primary name among hard links.","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q71","type":"MCQ","topic":"SSDs","marks":1,"bloom":"understand","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md; Mod02 storage","question":"SSDs have effectively unlimited write cycles.","correct":1,"rationale":"FALSE. NAND flash cells physically wear with each program/erase cycle (typically 1k-100k for consumer drives, more for enterprise). Wear-leveling algorithms spread writes across cells to extend useful life, but the ceiling is still finite — which is why log-heavy workloads on cheap SSDs are a bad idea. Trap: conflating \"effectively unlimited for typical desktop use\" with \"physically unlimited\"; the exam asks the physical truth.","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q72","type":"SHORT","topic":"Expansions","marks":3,"bloom":"apply","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md + Review Apr 17","question":"Given `set -- 'alpha beta' 'gamma'`, show the difference between `for x in \"$@\"` and `for x in \"$*\"`.","correct":"\u003ccode\u003e\"$@\"\u003c/code\u003e iterates twice: x='alpha beta' then x='gamma' (preserves separation). \u003ccode\u003e\"$*\"\u003c/code\u003e iterates once: x='alpha beta gamma' (all args joined). Use \u003ccode\u003e\"$@\"\u003c/code\u003e in functions.","rationale":"`\"$@\"` expands each positional parameter as its own word (preserves argument boundaries in quoted strings), so the loop body runs once per arg. `\"$*\"` joins all positional parameters into a single word separated by the first character of `$IFS` (space by default), so the loop body runs once. Use `\"$@\"` when forwarding args to another command; use `\"$*\"` only for display. Past-exam trap: writing `$@` (unquoted) — word splitting still fires and the 'alpha beta' arg splits into two. (Midterm Q60 pattern.)"},{"id":"q73","type":"SHORT","topic":"Container","marks":3,"bloom":"apply","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md + Review Apr 17","question":"What is a container image?","correct":"A layered, read-only template used to instantiate containers. Includes filesystem snapshot, entrypoint, env vars, and metadata. Standardized by OCI. Pulled from a registry; runtime adds a writable layer per container.","rationale":"Image vs container is the core distinction: image is read-only and versioned; container is a running instance with its own writable layer on top. Layered FS (overlayfs) dedupes common parts across images. OCI standardizes the format so any compliant runtime (containerd, CRI-O, Podman) can run the image. Common wrong answers: \"a running container\" (that's the instance), \"a VM snapshot\" (no kernel included), \"same as a Docker file\" (Dockerfile builds the image, isn't the image). (Mod10A container basics.)"},{"id":"q74","type":"MCQ","topic":"Quoting","marks":2,"bloom":"apply","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q47; Mod04 Ch9","tags":["quoting","variant"],"question":"Given `name=world`, what does `echo \"Hello, $name!\"` print?","correct":0,"rationale":"**A: Hello, world!**. Double quotes preserve the literal string but still expand `$var`, `` `cmd` ``, and `$(cmd)`. So `$name` interpolates to `world`. Distractors: `Hello, $name!` would require single quotes (literal); `Hello, !` assumes `$name` is unset (it isn't); `Hello, world` drops the `!` which is not special inside double quotes (only special in history expansion at the prompt, not in scripts).","choices":["Hello, world!","Hello, $name!","Hello, !","Hello, world","syntax error"]},{"id":"q75","type":"MCQ","topic":"Redirection","marks":2,"bloom":"apply","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q10, Q50; Mod04 Ch11","tags":["redirection","variant"],"question":"Which form sends BOTH stdout and stderr to `log.txt`?","correct":0,"rationale":"**A: `cmd \u003e log.txt 2\u003e&1`**. Redirections are evaluated left-to-right; `\u003e log.txt` binds fd 1 to log.txt first, then `2\u003e&1` points fd 2 at whatever fd 1 currently points to — log.txt. (B) `cmd 2\u003e&1 \u003e log.txt` looks symmetric but isn't: `2\u003e&1` fires first and points fd 2 at the terminal (stdout hasn't been redirected yet), then `\u003e log.txt` redirects stdout — stderr still goes to the terminal. (C) `cmd &\u003e log.txt` is bash-only shorthand for the same thing as A; valid in bash but not POSIX, so A is the safe pick when both are listed. (D) uses `1\u003e2` which is invalid syntax (no `&`). (E) sends stdin, not output.","choices":["`cmd \u003e log.txt 2\u003e&1`","`cmd 2\u003e&1 \u003e log.txt`","`cmd 1\u003e2 \u003e log.txt`","`cmd \u003e\u003e log.txt 2\u003e\u003e log.txt`","`cmd \u003c log.txt`"]},{"id":"q76","type":"MCQ","topic":"Hard link","marks":2,"bloom":"apply","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q24, Q32; Mod02 Ch6","tags":["inode","links","variant"],"question":"`/boot` is mounted as a separate filesystem. You run `ln /boot/vmlinuz ~/vmlinuz-link`. What happens?\n","correct":2,"rationale":"**C: Invalid cross-device link error.** Hard links share an inode number, and inode numbers are unique only within a single filesystem — so a hard link cannot cross FS boundaries. The kernel returns `EXDEV`, and `ln` prints `Invalid cross-device link`. (A) would happen with `ln -s`, not a hard link. (B) silent success is impossible — the syscall rejects it. (D) `~/vmlinuz-link` as a copy would need `cp`, not `ln`. (E) link count rises only on a successful hard link creation.","choices":["Symlink created at ~/vmlinuz-link","Hard link succeeds silently","Error: Invalid cross-device link","Copy of vmlinuz at ~/vmlinuz-link","Link count on vmlinuz increases to 2"]},{"id":"q77","type":"MCQ","topic":"Permissions","marks":2,"bloom":"apply","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q16; Mod02 Ch7","tags":["permissions","chown","variant"],"question":"Recursively change ownership of `/srv/data` to user `alice` AND group `devs`. Which command?\n","correct":1,"rationale":"**B: `chown -R alice:devs /srv/data`**. Syntax is `user:group` (colon-separated) and `-R` (capital R) is recursive. (A) uses lowercase `-r` which is not a valid chown flag — the midterm Q16 trap. (C) `chgrp` only sets group, missing the user change. (D) `chown.chgrp` is invalid; commands are run separately, and this joins them with `.` (a legacy BSD separator that modern GNU chown accepts for user.group but not for chaining). (E) reverses the order to `group:user` — colon semantics are strictly user then group.","choices":["`chown -r alice:devs /srv/data`","`chown -R alice:devs /srv/data`","`chgrp -R devs /srv/data`","`chown.chgrp -R alice devs /srv/data`","`chown -R devs:alice /srv/data`"]},{"id":"q78","type":"MCQ","topic":"Find","marks":2,"bloom":"apply","source":"Mod04 Ch13; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q6","tags":["find","variant"],"question":"List all *directories* under `/var/log` modified in the last 7 days. Which command?\n","correct":2,"rationale":"**C: `find /var/log -type d -mtime -7`**. `-type d` restricts to directories; `-mtime -7` means \"modified less than 7 days ago\" (negative = within). (A) `-type f` is files only. (B) `-mtime +7` is older than 7 days (opposite). (D) `-newer` takes a filename, not a day count. (E) uses `-name d` which matches entries literally named `d`. The sign on `-mtime` is the common trap: `-N` = newer than N days, `+N` = older than N.","choices":["`find /var/log -type f -mtime -7`","`find /var/log -type d -mtime +7`","`find /var/log -type d -mtime -7`","`find /var/log -type d -newer 7`","`find /var/log -name d -mtime -7`"]},{"id":"q79","type":"MCQ","topic":"grep","marks":2,"bloom":"apply","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q34; Mod04 Ch14","tags":["grep","variant"],"question":"Find case-insensitive whole-word matches of `error` in `app.log`. Which command?\n","correct":1,"rationale":"**B: `grep -iw error app.log`**. `-i` is case-insensitive, `-w` matches whole-word boundaries. Flags compose: `-iw` applies both. (A) `-i` only also matches `errorcode`, `syserror` — not whole-word. (C) `-w` only misses `Error`, `ERROR`. (D) `-v` inverts — returns lines *without* the match. (E) `-wi` is functionally equivalent to B (flag order doesn't matter), but `error` is quoted there in a way that disables globbing irrelevantly; B is the canonical form listed.","choices":["`grep -i error app.log`","`grep -iw error app.log`","`grep -w error app.log`","`grep -v error app.log`","`grep error -i app.log`"]},{"id":"q80","type":"MCQ","topic":"Runlevels","marks":1,"bloom":"understand","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q35; Mod05 Ch11","tags":["runlevels","variant"],"question":"A desktop Linux box normally boots to full GUI. You want to boot once into multi-user *without* the\ndisplay manager (e.g. to debug an Xorg config) without editing `/etc/inittab` or the systemd default.\nWhich runlevel do you temporarily request at the GRUB prompt?\n","correct":2,"rationale":"**C: 3**. Runlevel 3 = multi-user text, runlevel 5 = multi-user graphical. Appending `3` (or `systemd.unit=multi-user.target`) at the GRUB kernel line boots once into text-only. (A) 1 = single user (maintenance, root-only — overkill for a GUI debug). (B) 2 = multi-user without networking on Debian convention; not the right target for an Xorg debug where you want full networking. (D) 5 is the current default, changes nothing. (E) 6 reboots.","choices":["1","2","3","5","6"]},{"id":"q81","type":"MCQ","topic":"Exit status","marks":2,"bloom":"apply","source":"Mod09 Ch28 bash scripting","tags":["exit-status","short-circuit","variant"],"question":"After `false && echo A || echo B`, what prints and what is `$?` at the end?\n","correct":3,"rationale":"**D: B prints, `$?` = 0**. `false` exits 1. `&&` short-circuits — `echo A` is skipped. `||` then sees the preceding nonzero status and runs `echo B`, which exits 0. So stdout is `B`, and `$?` reflects the *last* command run (echo B → 0). (A) A prints is wrong — the `&&` blocks it. (B) both print is wrong — short- circuiting skips one. (C) neither is wrong — `||` catches the failure. (E) `$? = 1` mis-remembers which command ends the chain; it's `echo B`, not `false`.","choices":["A, `$?` = 0","A and B, `$?` = 0","nothing, `$?` = 1","B, `$?` = 0","B, `$?` = 1"]},{"id":"q82","type":"MCQ","topic":"Synthesis","marks":2,"bloom":"apply","source":"Mod04 Ch9 + Ch11 quoting × redirection","tags":["quoting","redirection","synthesis"],"question":"You want the file `out.txt` to contain the literal four characters `$USER` (not the expanded username).\nWhich command does the job?\n","correct":1,"rationale":"**B: `echo '$USER' \u003e out.txt`**. Single quotes suppress parameter expansion; `$USER` passes through literally. `\u003e` then writes those four bytes to the file. (A) uses double quotes, which expand `$USER` to the login name. (C) `echo \\$USER \u003e out.txt` also works (backslash escape), but (B) is the cleaner idiom — the question asks which form is correct, and both (B) and (C) are valid; B is listed correctly. (D) `\u003e\u003e` appends, which still works if the file doesn't exist, but (B) is the straightforward answer. (E) writes `'$USER'` including the quotes themselves because single-quote literals are stripped by the shell before `echo` sees them — no, shell does strip quotes, so E would also print `$USER` unexpectedly. Stick with B as the canonical.","choices":["`echo \"$USER\" \u003e out.txt`","`echo '$USER' \u003e out.txt`","`echo $USER \u003e out.txt`","`echo $USER \u003e\u003e out.txt`","`echo \\$USER \u003e out.txt`"]},{"id":"q83","type":"MCQ","topic":"Synthesis","marks":2,"bloom":"apply","source":"Mod08 Ch25 iptables × Ch24 SSH tunnels","tags":["ssh","iptables","synthesis"],"question":"From your laptop you run `ssh -L 5432:db.internal:5432 user@bastion` to reach a Postgres server through\na bastion host. The bastion has `iptables -P OUTPUT DROP` with a narrow allow list. Which outbound rule\non the bastion does the tunnel actually need?\n","correct":2,"rationale":"**C: Allow TCP to `db.internal:5432`**. The `-L` local-forward makes bastion open a connection on *your behalf* from bastion to `db.internal:5432`. The outbound packet originates on bastion — so bastion's OUTPUT chain evaluates it. (A) SSH/22 is the incoming connection and is handled by INPUT, not OUTPUT. (B) the 5432 tunnel endpoint on your laptop is irrelevant to bastion's firewall. (D) 80 is HTTP, not Postgres. (E) the loopback rule helps local IPC but not this cross-host forward.","choices":["Allow outbound TCP 22 (SSH) on bastion","Allow outbound TCP 5432 to the laptop's IP","Allow outbound TCP 5432 to `db.internal`","Allow outbound TCP 80 on bastion","Allow loopback on bastion"]},{"id":"q84","type":"MCQ","topic":"Synthesis","marks":2,"bloom":"understand","source":"Mod10B kubelet × Mod10D QoS × cgroups","tags":["kubernetes","cgroups","qos","synthesis"],"question":"Which Kubernetes component writes pod-level CPU/memory limits into Linux cgroups to enforce QoS?\n","correct":2,"rationale":"**C: kubelet**. The scheduler picks a node (consuming the resource *requests*), the apiserver stores the spec, but enforcement is physical — it happens on the node. kubelet is the per-node agent that invokes the container runtime via CRI and programs cgroup v1/v2 files (`cpu.shares`, `memory.limit_in_bytes`, or `cpu.weight`/`memory.max`) to match the pod spec. (A) kube-proxy handles service virtual IPs, not limits. (B) scheduler only selects nodes. (D) etcd stores desired state. (E) container runtime enforces, but it does so under kubelet's direction — kubelet is the one that translates spec → cgroup writes.","choices":["kube-proxy","scheduler","kubelet","etcd","apiserver"]},{"id":"q85","type":"MCQ","topic":"Synthesis","marks":2,"bloom":"understand","source":"Mod07 Ch21 NFS × Mod02 Ch7 perms × UID mapping","tags":["nfs","permissions","uid","synthesis"],"question":"An NFS client mounts `/srv/exports` from a server. A user on the client with UID 1001 tries to read a\nfile owned by UID 500 on the server, mode 0640. The client gets `Permission denied`. Why?\n","correct":1,"rationale":"**B: NFS uses numeric UID matching — 1001 ≠ 500 and mode 0640 denies 'other'.** Default NFS (AUTH_SYS) trusts the client's UID and compares it numerically with the file's owner UID on the server. UID 1001 is neither the owner (500) nor in the owning group (also 500), so 'other' permissions apply — 0640 grants 'other' nothing, hence denied. (A) UID squashing only maps root (UID 0) by default, not 1001. (C) the filesystem permissions do enforce, not just network ACLs. (D) NFSv4 adds krb5 auth but not by default; AUTH_SYS is still the common case. (E) mount options don't bypass file perms.","choices":["NFS root-squashes UID 1001 to nobody","Numeric UID mismatch: 1001 ≠ 500, and mode 0640 denies 'other'","NFS doesn't enforce filesystem permissions","NFSv4 kerberos rejected the unauthenticated client","The client mount was `ro` — reading is blocked"]},{"id":"q86","type":"MCQ","topic":"Synthesis","marks":2,"bloom":"apply","source":"Mod04 Ch11 redirection × pipes","tags":["redirection","pipes","synthesis"],"question":"Run `cmd1 | cmd2 2\u003e&1 \u003e out.log`. Which stream ends up in `out.log`?\n","correct":1,"rationale":"**B: Only cmd2's stdout.** Parse left-to-right: `|` first connects cmd1's stdout to cmd2's stdin. Then `cmd2 2\u003e&1 \u003e out.log` runs: `2\u003e&1` fires first and points cmd2's fd 2 at wherever fd 1 currently points — which is the pipe back to cmd1 (not useful, goes nowhere since cmd1 is the pipe writer). Then `\u003e out.log` redirects cmd2's stdout to out.log. Net result: cmd2's stdout → out.log; cmd2's stderr → the pipe (lost); cmd1's stderr → terminal. (A) both streams would need `cmd2 \u003e out.log 2\u003e&1` (order flipped). (C) no, cmd1's stdout goes into the pipe. (D) `|&` is bash shorthand for pipe-with-stderr, not used here. (E) nothing is wrong — out.log does get cmd2's stdout.","choices":["cmd2's stdout and cmd2's stderr","Only cmd2's stdout","cmd1's stdout and cmd2's stdout","cmd2's stderr only","Nothing — the redirection fails"]}]},"lessons":[{"n":0,"id":"4915-exam-strategy","title":"Exam strategy and top pitfalls","hook":"Time allocation, top pitfalls, when to skip.","tags":["strategy","exam-prep"],"module":"Exam prep","kind":"strategy","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md + comp4915_quiz3.md + comp4915_quiz4.md; materials/slides/Mod{01-10}*.pdf","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"Midterm was 144 marks in 100 minutes — that&#39;s 1.4 marks/minute. The final follows the same cadence. Every minute spent on exam craft beats another minute re-reading a slide deck, because the exam tests \u003cem\u003erecognition and recall under time pressure\u003c/em\u003e, not deep reasoning.","text":"Midterm was 144 marks in 100 minutes — that's 1.4 marks/minute. The final follows the same cadence. Every minute spent on exam craft beats another minute re-reading a slide deck, because the exam tests *recognition and recall under time pressure*, not deep reasoning."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Time allocation","text":"Time allocation"},{"kind":"p","html":"The midterm mark scheme: 2 marks per MCQ, 1 mark per T/F, 3 marks per SHORT, 10 marks per ESSAY. The final mirrors that. Budget by marks-per-minute.","text":"The midterm mark scheme: 2 marks per MCQ, 1 mark per T/F, 3 marks per SHORT, 10 marks per ESSAY. The final mirrors that. Budget by marks-per-minute."},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eType\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eMarks each\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eRough count\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eTime budget\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eMCQ\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e2\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e~37\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e~50 min (80 s each)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eT/F\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e1\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e~10\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e~5 min (30 s each)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSHORT\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e3\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e~7\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e~20 min (3 min each)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eESSAY\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e10\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e~3\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e~20 min (7 min each)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBuffer\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e—\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e—\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e~5 min\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Essays are the highest-leverage block — skip one and you lose as much as nine MCQs. Never blank an essay; a rough structure scores 5–6/10.","text":"Essays are the highest-leverage block — skip one and you lose as much as nine MCQs. Never blank an essay; a rough structure scores 5–6/10."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Part-1 vs Part-2 strategy","text":"Part-1 vs Part-2 strategy"},{"kind":"p","html":"No split — it&#39;s one continuous 100-minute block. Your only choice is order.","text":"No split — it's one continuous 100-minute block. Your only choice is order."},{"kind":"p","html":"Recommended order:","text":"Recommended order:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMCQ first\u003c/strong\u003e (~50 min). Warm up on easy ones. Flag 3–4 hard ones and move on.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eT/F\u003c/strong\u003e (~5 min). Quick confidence. Always guess — 1 mark for 30 seconds is the best ROI on the exam.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSHORT\u003c/strong\u003e (~20 min). Command syntax, grep/find/tar, regex. These are facts, not reasoning.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eESSAY\u003c/strong\u003e (~20 min). Outline first (2 min), then flesh out. 7 min each.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eReturn to flagged MCQs\u003c/strong\u003e in the final minutes.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. **MCQ first** (~50 min). Warm up on easy ones. Flag 3–4 hard ones and move on.\n2. **T/F** (~5 min). Quick confidence. Always guess — 1 mark for 30 seconds is the best ROI on the exam.\n3. **SHORT** (~20 min). Command syntax, grep/find/tar, regex. These are facts, not reasoning.\n4. **ESSAY** (~20 min). Outline first (2 min), then flesh out. 7 min each.\n5. **Return to flagged MCQs** in the final minutes."},{"kind":"p","html":"If you hit 60 minutes and are still on MCQ, you&#39;re too slow — move to SHORT immediately and come back to hard MCQs last.","text":"If you hit 60 minutes and are still on MCQ, you're too slow — move to SHORT immediately and come back to hard MCQs last."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Top 5 pitfalls","text":"Top 5 pitfalls"},{"kind":"p","html":"Ranked by appearance count in midterm + quiz3 + quiz4.","text":"Ranked by appearance count in midterm + quiz3 + quiz4."},{"kind":"h3","html":"1. Quoting — single vs double vs bare (midterm Q17, Q47)","text":"1. Quoting — single vs double vs bare (midterm Q17, Q47)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Single quotes: literal, no expansion. Double quotes: \u003ccode\u003e$var\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e`cmd`\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e$(cmd)\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e\\\u003c/code\u003e expand. Bare: all 7 expansions fire.","text":"Single quotes: literal, no expansion. Double quotes: `$var`, `` `cmd` ``, `$(cmd)`, `\\` expand. Bare: all 7 expansions fire."},{"kind":"p","html":"Drill:","text":"Drill:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"person=jenny\necho '$person'   # → $person    (literal)\necho \"$person\"   # → jenny      (expanded)\necho $person     # → jenny      (expanded, plus word-splitting + glob)"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&#39;don\\&#39;t&#39;\u003c/code\u003e does NOT escape. Single quotes can&#39;t contain a single quote even with a backslash. Use \u003ccode\u003e&quot;don&#39;t&quot;\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003e$&#39;don\\&#39;t&#39;\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`'don\\'t'` does NOT escape. Single quotes can't contain a single quote even with a backslash. Use `\"don't\"` or `$'don\\'t'`."},{"kind":"h3","html":"2. Redirection order — \u003ccode\u003e&gt;file 2&gt;&amp;1\u003c/code\u003e ≠ \u003ccode\u003e2&gt;&amp;1 &gt;file\u003c/code\u003e (midterm Q10, Q50)","text":"2. Redirection order — `\u003efile 2\u003e&1` ≠ `2\u003e&1 \u003efile` (midterm Q10, Q50)"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003e2&gt;&amp;1\u003c/code\u003e duplicates the \u003cem\u003ecurrent\u003c/em\u003e binding of fd 1. If stdout hasn&#39;t been redirected yet, \u003ccode\u003e2&gt;&amp;1\u003c/code\u003e sends stderr to the terminal, not the file.","text":"`2\u003e&1` duplicates the *current* binding of fd 1. If stdout hasn't been redirected yet, `2\u003e&1` sends stderr to the terminal, not the file."},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"cmd \u003eout 2\u003e&1    # both stdout and stderr → out\ncmd 2\u003e&1 \u003eout    # stdout → out; stderr → terminal (order wrong)"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eRedirection binds descriptors left-to-right at the moment of each redirect. \u003ccode\u003e2&gt;&amp;1\u003c/code\u003e copies fd 1&#39;s \u003cem\u003ecurrent\u003c/em\u003e destination, not &quot;wherever stdout ends up eventually&quot;.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Redirection binds descriptors left-to-right at the moment of each redirect. `2\u003e&1` copies fd 1's *current* destination, not \"wherever stdout ends up eventually\"."},{"kind":"h3","html":"3. \u003ccode\u003echown -R\u003c/code\u003e (capital R), not \u003ccode\u003e-r\u003c/code\u003e (midterm Q16)","text":"3. `chown -R` (capital R), not `-r` (midterm Q16)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Every other recursive tool uses lowercase \u003ccode\u003e-r\u003c/code\u003e (grep, cp, ls). \u003ccode\u003echown\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003echgrp\u003c/code\u003e use capital \u003ccode\u003e-R\u003c/code\u003e. Lowercase \u003ccode\u003e-r\u003c/code\u003e is not a valid flag — the command errors out.","text":"Every other recursive tool uses lowercase `-r` (grep, cp, ls). `chown` and `chgrp` use capital `-R`. Lowercase `-r` is not a valid flag — the command errors out."},{"kind":"h3","html":"4. Runlevel 3 vs 5 (midterm Q35)","text":"4. Runlevel 3 vs 5 (midterm Q35)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Both are multi-user. The only difference is the UI:","text":"Both are multi-user. The only difference is the UI:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eRunlevel 3 = multi-user, text mode. Default for servers.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eRunlevel 5 = multi-user, graphical (X11). Default for desktops.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eRunlevel 0 = halt; 1 = single-user rescue; 6 = reboot.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- Runlevel 3 = multi-user, text mode. Default for servers.\n- Runlevel 5 = multi-user, graphical (X11). Default for desktops.\n- Runlevel 0 = halt; 1 = single-user rescue; 6 = reboot."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003esystemctl get-default\u003c/code\u003e shows the current target (\u003ccode\u003emulti-user.target\u003c/code\u003e = RL3, \u003ccode\u003egraphical.target\u003c/code\u003e = RL5).","text":"`systemctl get-default` shows the current target (`multi-user.target` = RL3, `graphical.target` = RL5)."},{"kind":"h3","html":"5. Hard vs soft links (midterm Q24, Q32, Q58 essay)","text":"5. Hard vs soft links (midterm Q24, Q32, Q58 essay)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Hard link shares the inode → cannot cross filesystems → survives original deletion (link count &gt; 1 keeps the inode alive).","text":"Hard link shares the inode → cannot cross filesystems → survives original deletion (link count \u003e 1 keeps the inode alive)."},{"kind":"p","html":"Soft link stores a pathname as data → can cross filesystems → dangles if the target is deleted. \u003ccode\u003els -l\u003c/code\u003e shows \u003ccode\u003elrwxrwxrwx\u003c/code\u003e regardless of the target&#39;s perms.","text":"Soft link stores a pathname as data → can cross filesystems → dangles if the target is deleted. `ls -l` shows `lrwxrwxrwx` regardless of the target's perms."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003ePermissions on a symlink are meaningless — the link always shows \u003ccode\u003elrwxrwxrwx\u003c/code\u003e. The effective permissions are the target&#39;s.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Permissions on a symlink are meaningless — the link always shows `lrwxrwxrwx`. The effective permissions are the target's."},{"kind":"h2","html":"When to skip and return","text":"When to skip and return"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMCQ\u003c/strong\u003e stuck &gt;1 minute → flag, move on. Return in the last 10 minutes.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eT/F\u003c/strong\u003e always guess. 1 mark for 30 seconds is the best trade on the exam.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSHORT\u003c/strong\u003e write partial even if unsure. 1 mark &gt; blank.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eESSAY\u003c/strong\u003e never fully blank. Outline for 2 minutes, write for 5. Even rough prose scores 5–6/10.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **MCQ** stuck \u003e1 minute → flag, move on. Return in the last 10 minutes.\n- **T/F** always guess. 1 mark for 30 seconds is the best trade on the exam.\n- **SHORT** write partial even if unsure. 1 mark \u003e blank.\n- **ESSAY** never fully blank. Outline for 2 minutes, write for 5. Even rough prose scores 5–6/10."},{"kind":"p","html":"Specific triage:","text":"Specific triage:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e$@\u003c/code\u003e vs \u003ccode\u003e$*\u003c/code\u003e questions → hard under pressure; skip first pass, return fresh.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eGrep flag combinations (\u003ccode\u003e-w\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e-v\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e-n\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e-i\u003c/code\u003e) → lookup items, skip if blank.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eExact file locations (e.g. &quot;which daemon manages NIS?&quot;) → skip if not obvious.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- `$@` vs `$*` questions → hard under pressure; skip first pass, return fresh.\n- Grep flag combinations (`-w`, `-v`, `-n`, `-i`) → lookup items, skip if blank.\n- Exact file locations (e.g. \"which daemon manages NIS?\") → skip if not obvious."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Exam-day order","text":"Exam-day order"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eScan all questions (~2 min).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eEasy MCQs.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eT/F (fast while warm).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eMedium MCQs.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSHORT.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eESSAY — 7 min each, outline first.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eHard/skipped MCQs.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eProofread, fill any remaining blanks.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. Scan all questions (~2 min).\n2. Easy MCQs.\n3. T/F (fast while warm).\n4. Medium MCQs.\n5. SHORT.\n6. ESSAY — 7 min each, outline first.\n7. Hard/skipped MCQs.\n8. Proofread, fill any remaining blanks."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003cp\u003e— first 30 minutes of the 100-minute block\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e0:00-0:02\u003c/strong\u003e Scan all pages. Note essay topics (e.g. &quot;hard vs soft links&quot;). Brain queues them up while you do MCQ.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e0:02-0:05\u003c/strong\u003e First 4 easy MCQs: command names, file locations. Bank 8 marks fast.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e0:05-0:15\u003c/strong\u003e T/F — 10 questions in 10 minutes, never blank. 1-mark ROI in 30 s each beats grinding on a hard MCQ.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e0:15-0:18\u003c/strong\u003e Essay outlines — spend 1 minute per essay jotting a three-bullet spine. Flesh out later; brain keeps chewing in the background.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e0:18-0:30\u003c/strong\u003e Middle MCQs. Stuck &gt; 1 min → mark with a star, move on. Do not let a 2-mark MCQ steal 5 minutes.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAt 0:30 you should have ~20 MCQs done, all T/F done, essay skeletons sketched. That&#39;s ~35 marks locked in.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDerail sign: still on MCQ at 0:45 → jump to SHORT immediately. Hard MCQs come last, not never.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"— first 30 minutes of the 100-minute block\n1. **0:00-0:02** Scan all pages. Note essay topics (e.g. \"hard vs soft links\"). Brain queues them up while you do MCQ.\n2. **0:02-0:05** First 4 easy MCQs: command names, file locations. Bank 8 marks fast.\n3. **0:05-0:15** T/F — 10 questions in 10 minutes, never blank. 1-mark ROI in 30 s each beats grinding on a hard MCQ.\n4. **0:15-0:18** Essay outlines — spend 1 minute per essay jotting a three-bullet spine. Flesh out later; brain keeps chewing in the background.\n5. **0:18-0:30** Middle MCQs. Stuck \u003e 1 min → mark with a star, move on. Do not let a 2-mark MCQ steal 5 minutes.\n6. At 0:30 you should have ~20 MCQs done, all T/F done, essay skeletons sketched. That's ~35 marks locked in.\n7. Derail sign: still on MCQ at 0:45 → jump to SHORT immediately. Hard MCQs come last, not never."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eThe exam rewards finishing over perfection. Budget by marks-per-minute, skip stuck MCQs, never blank an essay. Know the five pitfalls cold: quoting single/double/bare, redirection order, \u003ccode\u003echown -R\u003c/code\u003e, runlevel 3 vs 5, and hard-vs-soft link semantics. Recite them the morning of.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"The exam rewards finishing over perfection. Budget by marks-per-minute, skip stuck MCQs, never blank an essay. Know the five pitfalls cold: quoting single/double/bare, redirection order, `chown -R`, runlevel 3 vs 5, and hard-vs-soft link semantics. Recite them the morning of."}]},{"n":1,"id":"4915-lesson-what-linux-actually-is","title":"What Linux actually is","hook":"You can't understand Kubernetes without understanding the Linux primitives it's built on. Start here.","tags":["linux"],"module":"Misc / editors / misc topics","source":"Mod01 Ch1","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"A coworker says: \u003cem\u003e&quot;Linux doesn&#39;t come with a text editor.&quot;\u003c/em\u003e Another says: \u003cem\u003e&quot;Linux is Fedora 39.&quot;\u003c/em\u003e A third says: \u003cem\u003e&quot;Linux was written by Torvalds in 1991.&quot;\u003c/em\u003e","text":"A coworker says: *\"Linux doesn't come with a text editor.\"* Another says: *\"Linux is Fedora 39.\"* A third says: *\"Linux was written by Torvalds in 1991.\"*"},{"kind":"p","html":"All three are talking about &quot;Linux.&quot; All three mean something different. And \u003cstrong\u003eat most one of them\u003c/strong\u003e is saying something that is unambiguously true.","text":"All three are talking about \"Linux.\" All three mean something different. And **at most one of them** is saying something that is unambiguously true."},{"kind":"p","html":"Before reading on, try to answer: which of the three statements is strictly correct, and which two are sloppy? Hold that guess — we&#39;ll come back to it.","text":"Before reading on, try to answer: which of the three statements is strictly correct, and which two are sloppy? Hold that guess — we'll come back to it."},{"kind":"h3","html":"The trick: &quot;Linux&quot; is three stacked things","text":"The trick: \"Linux\" is three stacked things"},{"kind":"p","html":"When you say the word, you could be pointing at any of these:","text":"When you say the word, you could be pointing at any of these:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eThe kernel\u003c/strong\u003e — a single program that talks to hardware.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eThe userland\u003c/strong\u003e — the commands you actually type (\u003ccode\u003els\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003egrep\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ebash\u003c/code\u003e).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eThe distribution\u003c/strong\u003e — the bootable bundle someone hands you (Fedora, Ubuntu, RHEL).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1.  **The kernel** — a single program that talks to hardware.\n2.  **The userland** — the commands you actually type (`ls`, `grep`, `bash`).\n3.  **The distribution** — the bootable bundle someone hands you (Fedora, Ubuntu, RHEL)."},{"kind":"p","html":"The exam leans on this ambiguity hard. If you can name which layer a question is pointing at, half the Mod01 MCQs collapse to one-word answers. Let&#39;s build each layer before we reassemble them.","text":"The exam leans on this ambiguity hard. If you can name which layer a question is pointing at, half the Mod01 MCQs collapse to one-word answers. Let's build each layer before we reassemble them."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Layer 1 — The kernel (this is &quot;Linux&quot; proper)","text":"Layer 1 — The kernel (this is \"Linux\" proper)"},{"kind":"p","html":"The kernel is one program. It lives in one file on your disk: \u003ccode\u003e/boot/vmlinuz-*\u003c/code\u003e. When you boot, the bootloader loads that file into memory and jumps to it. From that moment on, the kernel is the \u003cem\u003eonly\u003c/em\u003e code on your machine that is allowed to touch hardware directly.","text":"The kernel is one program. It lives in one file on your disk: `/boot/vmlinuz-*`. When you boot, the bootloader loads that file into memory and jumps to it. From that moment on, the kernel is the *only* code on your machine that is allowed to touch hardware directly."},{"kind":"p","html":"What does it actually do?","text":"What does it actually do?"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSchedules processes\u003c/strong\u003e — decides which program runs on the CPU right now.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eManages memory\u003c/strong\u003e — hands out RAM, protects each process from the others.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDrives I/O\u003c/strong\u003e — reads disks, writes to the network card, talks to USB.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **Schedules processes** — decides which program runs on the CPU right now.\n-   **Manages memory** — hands out RAM, protects each process from the others.\n-   **Drives I/O** — reads disks, writes to the network card, talks to USB."},{"kind":"p","html":"It does \u003cstrong\u003enot\u003c/strong\u003e contain \u003ccode\u003els\u003c/code\u003e. It does \u003cstrong\u003enot\u003c/strong\u003e contain \u003ccode\u003ebash\u003c/code\u003e. It does \u003cstrong\u003enot\u003c/strong\u003e contain a text editor. The kernel is scheduler + memory manager + drivers, and that&#39;s it.","text":"It does **not** contain `ls`. It does **not** contain `bash`. It does **not** contain a text editor. The kernel is scheduler + memory manager + drivers, and that's it."},{"kind":"p","html":"So how do your commands ever reach it? Through \u003cstrong\u003esystem calls\u003c/strong\u003e — a tiny, fixed set of entry points the kernel exposes. You&#39;ll see a handful repeatedly in this course: \u003ccode\u003efork\u003c/code\u003e (clone a process), \u003ccode\u003eexec\u003c/code\u003e (replace a process with a new program), \u003ccode\u003eread\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ewrite\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eopen\u003c/code\u003e. Every user program that does anything interesting eventually calls into this list.","text":"So how do your commands ever reach it? Through **system calls** — a tiny, fixed set of entry points the kernel exposes. You'll see a handful repeatedly in this course: `fork` (clone a process), `exec` (replace a process with a new program), `read`, `write`, `open`. Every user program that does anything interesting eventually calls into this list."},{"kind":"p","html":"When Torvalds wrote Linux in 1991, \u003cstrong\u003ethis\u003c/strong\u003e is what he wrote. Nothing else. So when someone says &quot;Linux was written by Torvalds,&quot; they mean this layer only.","text":"When Torvalds wrote Linux in 1991, **this** is what he wrote. Nothing else. So when someone says \"Linux was written by Torvalds,\" they mean this layer only."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Layer 2 — GNU userland (the commands you actually use)","text":"Layer 2 — GNU userland (the commands you actually use)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Open a terminal, type \u003ccode\u003els\u003c/code\u003e. That&#39;s not the kernel. That&#39;s a separate program called \u003ccode\u003els\u003c/code\u003e, living at \u003ccode\u003e/usr/bin/ls\u003c/code\u003e. It runs, it asks the kernel to read a directory, it prints the result, it exits.","text":"Open a terminal, type `ls`. That's not the kernel. That's a separate program called `ls`, living at `/usr/bin/ls`. It runs, it asks the kernel to read a directory, it prints the result, it exits."},{"kind":"p","html":"All the commands you think of as &quot;Linux commands&quot; — \u003ccode\u003els\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ecp\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003egrep\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003esed\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ebash\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003egcc\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ecat\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003efind\u003c/code\u003e — are \u003cstrong\u003eseparate binaries\u003c/strong\u003e that ship under the \u003cstrong\u003eGNU project\u003c/strong\u003e, started by Richard Stallman in 1983. Eight years \u003cem\u003ebefore\u003c/em\u003e the Linux kernel existed.","text":"All the commands you think of as \"Linux commands\" — `ls`, `cp`, `grep`, `sed`, `bash`, `gcc`, `cat`, `find` — are **separate binaries** that ship under the **GNU project**, started by Richard Stallman in 1983. Eight years *before* the Linux kernel existed."},{"kind":"p","html":"This is the part most students miss on first pass: GNU predates Linux. Stallman&#39;s goal was a free UNIX-like system, and by 1991 GNU had finished most of the userland tools but was still struggling to finish their own kernel. Torvalds&#39; kernel arrived at exactly the moment GNU needed one. The two fused, and the combined system is what you actually use.","text":"This is the part most students miss on first pass: GNU predates Linux. Stallman's goal was a free UNIX-like system, and by 1991 GNU had finished most of the userland tools but was still struggling to finish their own kernel. Torvalds' kernel arrived at exactly the moment GNU needed one. The two fused, and the combined system is what you actually use."},{"kind":"p","html":"This is why purists insist on &quot;GNU/Linux&quot; — the kernel alone is Torvalds, but the thing on your screen is GNU tools calling Torvalds&#39; kernel. On an exam where the question is &quot;who authored the command \u003ccode\u003egrep\u003c/code\u003e?&quot; — the answer is GNU, not &quot;Linux.&quot;","text":"This is why purists insist on \"GNU/Linux\" — the kernel alone is Torvalds, but the thing on your screen is GNU tools calling Torvalds' kernel. On an exam where the question is \"who authored the command `grep`?\" — the answer is GNU, not \"Linux.\""},{"kind":"p","html":"The userland is also \u003cstrong\u003ereplaceable\u003c/strong\u003e. Alpine Linux and BusyBox strip out GNU and substitute tiny alternatives. Same kernel; different userland; still &quot;Linux&quot; in the loose sense.","text":"The userland is also **replaceable**. Alpine Linux and BusyBox strip out GNU and substitute tiny alternatives. Same kernel; different userland; still \"Linux\" in the loose sense."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Layer 3 — The distribution (what you actually install)","text":"Layer 3 — The distribution (what you actually install)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Hand someone a kernel file and the GNU source tarballs and they cannot boot a machine. Something has to:","text":"Hand someone a kernel file and the GNU source tarballs and they cannot boot a machine. Something has to:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003epick versions of each component that work together,\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eadd a package manager (\u003ccode\u003ednf\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eapt\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003epacman\u003c/code\u003e),\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eadd a bootloader, init system, default shell, default desktop,\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ebundle it all into installer media.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   pick versions of each component that work together,\n-   add a package manager (`dnf`, `apt`, `pacman`),\n-   add a bootloader, init system, default shell, default desktop,\n-   bundle it all into installer media."},{"kind":"p","html":"That bundling job is a \u003cstrong\u003edistribution\u003c/strong\u003e. Fedora, RHEL, CentOS, Ubuntu, Debian, Arch, Alpine — all of these are distributions. Same kernel family, same GNU userland (mostly), but different defaults and different package managers.","text":"That bundling job is a **distribution**. Fedora, RHEL, CentOS, Ubuntu, Debian, Arch, Alpine — all of these are distributions. Same kernel family, same GNU userland (mostly), but different defaults and different package managers."},{"kind":"p","html":"This course focuses on \u003cstrong\u003eFedora / RHEL\u003c/strong\u003e. The labs, the package names (\u003ccode\u003ednf install\u003c/code\u003e), the service manager (\u003ccode\u003esystemd\u003c/code\u003e), the config paths (\u003ccode\u003e/etc/sysconfig/...\u003c/code\u003e) — all of those are distribution choices, not kernel choices. When you move to Ubuntu later in your career, the kernel is the same, but \u003ccode\u003ednf\u003c/code\u003e becomes \u003ccode\u003eapt\u003c/code\u003e and the config paths shift.","text":"This course focuses on **Fedora / RHEL**. The labs, the package names (`dnf install`), the service manager (`systemd`), the config paths (`/etc/sysconfig/...`) — all of those are distribution choices, not kernel choices. When you move to Ubuntu later in your career, the kernel is the same, but `dnf` becomes `apt` and the config paths shift."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Seeing all three on one real box","text":"Seeing all three on one real box"},{"kind":"p","html":"You don&#39;t have to trust any of this — you can ask a running Linux system to point at each layer itself:","text":"You don't have to trust any of this — you can ask a running Linux system to point at each layer itself:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"console","code":"$ uname -a\nLinux odyssey 5.14.0-427.el9.x86_64 #1 SMP Mon Apr 8 UTC 2026 x86_64 GNU/Linux\n\n$ cat /etc/os-release\nNAME=\"Fedora Linux\" VERSION=\"39 (Workstation Edition)\" ID=fedora VERSION_ID=39\n\n$ which bash ls grep\n/usr/bin/bash /usr/bin/ls /usr/bin/grep"},{"kind":"p","html":"Read carefully. \u003ccode\u003euname -a\u003c/code\u003e talks to the \u003cstrong\u003ekernel\u003c/strong\u003e and reports its version — 5.14. \u003ccode\u003e/etc/os-release\u003c/code\u003e names the \u003cstrong\u003edistribution\u003c/strong\u003e — Fedora 39. The three \u003ccode\u003ewhich\u003c/code\u003e paths point at \u003cstrong\u003eGNU binaries\u003c/strong\u003e. One box; three layers; three different answers to &quot;what Linux am I running?&quot;","text":"Read carefully. `uname -a` talks to the **kernel** and reports its version — 5.14. `/etc/os-release` names the **distribution** — Fedora 39. The three `which` paths point at **GNU binaries**. One box; three layers; three different answers to \"what Linux am I running?\""},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You ran `uname` and saw `5.14`. Your classmate ran `cat /etc/os-release` and saw `Fedora 39`. You both claim to be running \"the same Linux.\" Are you right?","a":"Depends on which layer. You're both probably running kernel 5.14 (same Linux-the-kernel) *and* Fedora 39 (same Linux-the-distribution). The point is that \"same Linux\" is only meaningful once you pick a layer — the exam will set up questions where a student treats them as interchangeable and picks the wrong MCQ option."},{"kind":"p","html":"Now go back to the three opening statements:","text":"Now go back to the three opening statements:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cem\u003e&quot;Linux doesn&#39;t come with a text editor&quot;\u003c/em\u003e — \u003cstrong\u003etrue of the kernel\u003c/strong\u003e, false of any real distribution. Sloppy unless the speaker meant layer 1.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cem\u003e&quot;Linux is Fedora 39&quot;\u003c/em\u003e — \u003cstrong\u003etrue of the distribution only\u003c/strong\u003e. A layer-3 statement dressed as a definition.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cem\u003e&quot;Linux was written by Torvalds in 1991&quot;\u003c/em\u003e — \u003cstrong\u003estrictly correct for the kernel\u003c/strong\u003e, misleading for the stack. Torvalds did not write \u003ccode\u003ebash\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003egcc\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   *\"Linux doesn't come with a text editor\"* — **true of the kernel**, false of any real distribution. Sloppy unless the speaker meant layer 1.\n-   *\"Linux is Fedora 39\"* — **true of the distribution only**. A layer-3 statement dressed as a definition.\n-   *\"Linux was written by Torvalds in 1991\"* — **strictly correct for the kernel**, misleading for the stack. Torvalds did not write `bash` or `gcc`."},{"kind":"p","html":"All three speakers had a point. None of them named the layer. That&#39;s the game.","text":"All three speakers had a point. None of them named the layer. That's the game."},{"kind":"h3","html":"How a single command exercises all three layers","text":"How a single command exercises all three layers"},{"kind":"p","html":"To cement the picture, walk through what really happens when you type \u003ccode\u003els\u003c/code\u003e and hit Enter. The same seven steps happen for almost every command you&#39;ll ever run — learning this loop once pays off forever.","text":"To cement the picture, walk through what really happens when you type `ls` and hit Enter. The same seven steps happen for almost every command you'll ever run — learning this loop once pays off forever."},{"kind":"p","html":"You type \u003ccode\u003els\u003c/code\u003e at the prompt. Now:","text":"You type `ls` at the prompt. Now:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ebash parses\u003c/strong\u003e the line. (Layer 2 — GNU.)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ebash calls \u003ccode\u003efork()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — a system call. The kernel clones the shell process. (Layer 1.)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eIn the child, \u003cstrong\u003ebash calls \u003ccode\u003eexecve(&quot;/usr/bin/ls&quot;, ...)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — the kernel replaces the child&#39;s process image with the \u003ccode\u003els\u003c/code\u003e binary. (Layer 1 carrying a Layer 2 program in.)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003els\u003c/code\u003e calls \u003ccode\u003egetdents()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — asks the kernel to hand over directory entries. (Layer 1.)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003els\u003c/code\u003e calls \u003ccode\u003ewrite()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — hands formatted text to stdout. The terminal prints it. (Layer 1 doing the I/O for a Layer 2 program.)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003els\u003c/code\u003e calls \u003ccode\u003eexit()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — returns an exit code.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eThe kernel wakes bash\u003c/strong\u003e from \u003ccode\u003ewait()\u003c/code\u003e. Bash re-prompts.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1.  **bash parses** the line. (Layer 2 — GNU.)\n2.  **bash calls `fork()`** — a system call. The kernel clones the shell process. (Layer 1.)\n3.  In the child, **bash calls `execve(\"/usr/bin/ls\", ...)`** — the kernel replaces the child's process image with the `ls` binary. (Layer 1 carrying a Layer 2 program in.)\n4.  **`ls` calls `getdents()`** — asks the kernel to hand over directory entries. (Layer 1.)\n5.  **`ls` calls `write()`** — hands formatted text to stdout. The terminal prints it. (Layer 1 doing the I/O for a Layer 2 program.)\n6.  **`ls` calls `exit()`** — returns an exit code.\n7.  **The kernel wakes bash** from `wait()`. Bash re-prompts."},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"flowchart LR\n  A[\"1. bash parses\u003cbr/\u003e'ls'\"] --\u003e B[\"2. fork()\u003cbr/\u003ekernel clones shell\"]\n  B --\u003e C[\"3. execve\u003cbr/\u003e('/usr/bin/ls')\u003cbr/\u003echild becomes ls\"]\n  C --\u003e D[\"4. getdents()\u003cbr/\u003eread dir from kernel\"]\n  D --\u003e E[\"5. write()\u003cbr/\u003eto stdout — terminal prints\"]\n  E --\u003e F[\"6. exit()\u003cbr/\u003els returns code\"]\n  F --\u003e G[\"7. wait() wakes bash\u003cbr/\u003ere-prompt\"]\n  classDef user fill:#2a3a4a,stroke:#7aa2f7,color:#e5e5e5\n  classDef kern fill:#3a3528,stroke:#e3af68,color:#e3af68\n  class A,E,F user\n  class B,C,D,G kern"},{"kind":"p","html":"Blue = GNU userland doing its own work. Orange = system calls into the kernel. Every shell command follows this shape. When you later learn about \u003ccode\u003efork\u003c/code\u003e/\u003ccode\u003eexec\u003c/code\u003e in code practice, or processes in Mod02, or containers in Mod10 — you are just looking at richer versions of this same dance.","text":"Blue = GNU userland doing its own work. Orange = system calls into the kernel. Every shell command follows this shape. When you later learn about `fork`/`exec` in code practice, or processes in Mod02, or containers in Mod10 — you are just looking at richer versions of this same dance."},{"kind":"h3","html":"The short timeline (relative order is what&#39;s tested)","text":"The short timeline (relative order is what's tested)"},{"kind":"p","html":"You do \u003cstrong\u003enot\u003c/strong\u003e need to memorize dates for this course. You do need to know that GNU came \u003cem\u003ebefore\u003c/em\u003e Linux, and that C came \u003cem\u003ebefore\u003c/em\u003e portable UNIX. That&#39;s it. Here&#39;s the arc:","text":"You do **not** need to memorize dates for this course. You do need to know that GNU came *before* Linux, and that C came *before* portable UNIX. That's it. Here's the arc:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e1969\u003c/strong\u003e — UNIX at AT&amp;T Bell Labs (Thompson, Ritchie). Written in PDP-11 assembly; locked to one CPU.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e1973\u003c/strong\u003e — UNIX rewritten in C. Now the same source could compile on any architecture with a C compiler. This is \u003cem\u003ewhy\u003c/em\u003e UNIX spread.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e1983\u003c/strong\u003e — GNU project begins (Stallman). Goal: a free UNIX userland.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e1991\u003c/strong\u003e — Linux kernel 0.01 (Torvalds, age 21, Helsinki). GNU now has a kernel to pair with.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e1994\u003c/strong\u003e — Linux 1.0.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e2003\u003c/strong\u003e — Linux 2.6. Modern line is 5.x / 6.x.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **1969** — UNIX at AT&T Bell Labs (Thompson, Ritchie). Written in PDP-11 assembly; locked to one CPU.\n-   **1973** — UNIX rewritten in C. Now the same source could compile on any architecture with a C compiler. This is *why* UNIX spread.\n-   **1983** — GNU project begins (Stallman). Goal: a free UNIX userland.\n-   **1991** — Linux kernel 0.01 (Torvalds, age 21, Helsinki). GNU now has a kernel to pair with.\n-   **1994** — Linux 1.0.\n-   **2003** — Linux 2.6. Modern line is 5.x / 6.x."},{"kind":"diagram","title":null,"svg":"\u003csvg viewBox=\"0 0 720 220\" preserveAspectRatio=\"xMidYMid meet\"\u003e\u003cdefs\u003e\u003cmarker id=\"arrTL1\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"9\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"6\" markerHeight=\"6\" orient=\"auto\"\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M0 0 L10 5 L0 10 Z\" fill=\"#a3a3a3\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003c/marker\u003e\u003c/defs\u003e\u003ctext x=\"20\" y=\"22\" class=\"label-accent\"\u003eUNIX → GNU → Linux — 1969 to 2003\u003c/text\u003e\u003cline x1=\"40\" y1=\"120\" x2=\"700\" y2=\"120\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrTL1)\"\u003e\u003c/line\u003e\u003ctext x=\"700\" y=\"142\" text-anchor=\"end\" class=\"sub\"\u003etime →\u003c/text\u003e\u003cline x1=\"80\" y1=\"115\" x2=\"80\" y2=\"125\" class=\"arrow-line\"\u003e\u003c/line\u003e\u003ctext x=\"80\" y=\"138\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e1969\u003c/text\u003e\u003cline x1=\"160\" y1=\"115\" x2=\"160\" y2=\"125\" class=\"arrow-line\"\u003e\u003c/line\u003e\u003ctext x=\"160\" y=\"138\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e1973\u003c/text\u003e\u003cline x1=\"280\" y1=\"115\" x2=\"280\" y2=\"125\" class=\"arrow-line\"\u003e\u003c/line\u003e\u003ctext x=\"280\" y=\"138\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e1983\u003c/text\u003e\u003cline x1=\"440\" y1=\"115\" x2=\"440\" y2=\"125\" class=\"arrow-line\"\u003e\u003c/line\u003e\u003ctext x=\"440\" y=\"138\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e1991\u003c/text\u003e\u003cline x1=\"500\" y1=\"115\" x2=\"500\" y2=\"125\" class=\"arrow-line\"\u003e\u003c/line\u003e\u003ctext x=\"500\" y=\"138\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e1994\u003c/text\u003e\u003cline x1=\"640\" y1=\"115\" x2=\"640\" y2=\"125\" class=\"arrow-line\"\u003e\u003c/line\u003e\u003ctext x=\"640\" y=\"138\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e2003\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"40\" y=\"60\" width=\"120\" height=\"40\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"100\" y=\"78\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eUNIX @ Bell Labs\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"100\" y=\"92\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eThompson + Ritchie\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"170\" y=\"60\" width=\"100\" height=\"40\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"220\" y=\"78\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eUNIX in C\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"220\" y=\"92\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eportable\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"280\" y=\"60\" width=\"120\" height=\"40\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"340\" y=\"78\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eGNU project\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"340\" y=\"92\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eStallman — userland\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"410\" y=\"60\" width=\"100\" height=\"40\" class=\"box-warn\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"460\" y=\"78\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eLinux 0.01\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"460\" y=\"92\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eTorvalds (21)\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"510\" y=\"60\" width=\"80\" height=\"40\" class=\"box\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"550\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eLinux 1.0\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"600\" y=\"60\" width=\"100\" height=\"40\" class=\"box\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"650\" y=\"78\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eLinux 2.6\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"650\" y=\"92\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e→ 5.x / 6.x\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"20\" y=\"170\" class=\"sub\"\u003eTwo streams: UNIX/C (kernel lineage) and GNU (userland). Linux fused them in 1991 — kernel + GNU = &quot;GNU/Linux&quot;.\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"20\" y=\"190\" class=\"sub\"\u003eWhy C in 1973 mattered: before it, UNIX was PDP-11 assembly — locked to one CPU. After C, same source compiles anywhere.\u003c/text\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e","legend":null},{"kind":"h3","html":"Five properties the exam will ask you to name","text":"Five properties the exam will ask you to name"},{"kind":"p","html":"When a Mod01 question asks what makes Linux &quot;Linux&quot; as a system, it&#39;s fishing for these five:","text":"When a Mod01 question asks what makes Linux \"Linux\" as a system, it's fishing for these five:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMultiuser\u003c/strong\u003e — many users logged in at once, each isolated from the others.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eProtected multitasking\u003c/strong\u003e — many processes running concurrently; the kernel protects each from corrupting the others (contrast cooperative multitasking, where one bad program hangs everything).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHierarchical filesystem\u003c/strong\u003e — one tree rooted at \u003ccode\u003e/\u003c/code\u003e, not per-drive letters like Windows.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eShell = interpreter + programming language\u003c/strong\u003e — the shell isn&#39;t just a prompt; it&#39;s a full scripting language with variables, conditionals, loops. You&#39;ll exploit this in Mod05.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHundreds of small utilities\u003c/strong\u003e — the UNIX philosophy: each tool does one thing, composes via pipes. This is why Mod04&#39;s redirection matters so much.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **Multiuser** — many users logged in at once, each isolated from the others.\n-   **Protected multitasking** — many processes running concurrently; the kernel protects each from corrupting the others (contrast cooperative multitasking, where one bad program hangs everything).\n-   **Hierarchical filesystem** — one tree rooted at `/`, not per-drive letters like Windows.\n-   **Shell = interpreter + programming language** — the shell isn't just a prompt; it's a full scripting language with variables, conditionals, loops. You'll exploit this in Mod05.\n-   **Hundreds of small utilities** — the UNIX philosophy: each tool does one thing, composes via pipes. This is why Mod04's redirection matters so much."},{"kind":"p","html":"Note what&#39;s \u003cem\u003enot\u003c/em\u003e on that list: &quot;a GUI.&quot; Linux can run with no GUI at all (servers and containers do). The GUI is a distribution choice, not a defining Linux property.","text":"Note what's *not* on that list: \"a GUI.\" Linux can run with no GUI at all (servers and containers do). The GUI is a distribution choice, not a defining Linux property."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Why was rewriting UNIX in C (1973) the single most important event on that timeline?","a":"Portability. Before 1973, UNIX was PDP-11 assembly — one CPU, one machine, nowhere else. After the C rewrite, the same source code could compile on any hardware with a C compiler. That is the *only* reason UNIX (and later Linux) could spread to every architecture from mainframes to phones. Without C, Linux on your laptop doesn't happen."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Is the shell part of the kernel? Explain in terms of what each one does.","a":"No. The shell (`bash`, `zsh`, `sh`, `ksh`) is a **user program**. It reads what you type, parses it, and asks the kernel to do the real work via system calls (`fork`, `exec`, `read`, `write`). You can swap one shell for another without touching the kernel, because the shell talks to the kernel through the same public interface any other program uses."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eThe most common Mod01 MCQ trap is treating &quot;Linux&quot; as synonymous with &quot;the whole operating system.&quot; When the exam asks \u003cem\u003e&quot;what is Linux?&quot;\u003c/em\u003e, the tight answer is \u003cstrong\u003e&quot;the kernel&quot;\u003c/strong\u003e — scheduler + memory manager + drivers, no \u003ccode\u003evi\u003c/code\u003e, no \u003ccode\u003ebash\u003c/code\u003e, no \u003ccode\u003esystemd\u003c/code\u003e. Only broaden to &quot;distribution&quot; when the question explicitly frames it that way (e.g., &quot;which Linux is this&quot; asked about Fedora vs Ubuntu).\u003c/p\u003e","text":"The most common Mod01 MCQ trap is treating \"Linux\" as synonymous with \"the whole operating system.\" When the exam asks *\"what is Linux?\"*, the tight answer is **\"the kernel\"** — scheduler + memory manager + drivers, no `vi`, no `bash`, no `systemd`. Only broaden to \"distribution\" when the question explicitly frames it that way (e.g., \"which Linux is this\" asked about Fedora vs Ubuntu)."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003e&quot;Linux&quot; means three things stacked on top of each other: a kernel (scheduler + memory + drivers), GNU userland (the commands you type), and a distribution (the bootable bundle). Every Mod01 question, and a surprising amount of the rest of the course, becomes easier the moment you can name which layer is being discussed. When in doubt: kernel ≠ shell, and \u003ccode\u003els\u003c/code\u003e is not part of &quot;Linux the kernel.&quot;\u003c/p\u003e","text":"\"Linux\" means three things stacked on top of each other: a kernel (scheduler + memory + drivers), GNU userland (the commands you type), and a distribution (the bootable bundle). Every Mod01 question, and a surprising amount of the rest of the course, becomes easier the moment you can name which layer is being discussed. When in doubt: kernel ≠ shell, and `ls` is not part of \"Linux the kernel.\""}]},{"n":2,"id":"4915-lesson-filesystem-inode-directory-entry","title":"Filesystem: inode + directory entry","hook":"Every 'why can't I hard-link across drives?' answer lives in this lesson.","tags":["filesystem"],"module":"Filesystem & permissions","source":"Mod02 Ch6; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q21, Q24, Q32","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"The midterm had TWO link questions (Q24, Q58). The final will have at least one. Everything hangs on one idea: \u003cem\u003ethe filename is not part of the file\u003c/em\u003e.","text":"The midterm had TWO link questions (Q24, Q58). The final will have at least one. Everything hangs on one idea: *the filename is not part of the file*."},{"kind":"p","html":"The one idea that unlocks all link questions","text":"The one idea that unlocks all link questions"},{"kind":"p","html":"A file = \u003cstrong\u003einode + data blocks\u003c/strong\u003e. The inode stores owner, perms, timestamps, size, link count, type, block pointers — \u003cstrong\u003enever\u003c/strong\u003e the filename. A directory is a file whose data is a list of \u003ccode\u003e(inode_number, filename)\u003c/code\u003e pairs.","text":"A file = **inode + data blocks**. The inode stores owner, perms, timestamps, size, link count, type, block pointers — **never** the filename. A directory is a file whose data is a list of `(inode_number, filename)` pairs."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"analogy","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHotel analogy.\u003c/strong\u003e Inode = the room (with stuff in it). Filename = nameplate on a door pointing at a room. Hard link = second nameplate pointing at the same room. Delete one nameplate → room still there. Last nameplate removed → housekeeping cleans the room.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**Hotel analogy.** Inode = the room (with stuff in it). Filename = nameplate on a door pointing at a room. Hard link = second nameplate pointing at the same room. Delete one nameplate → room still there. Last nameplate removed → housekeeping cleans the room."},{"kind":"p","html":"Hard link vs soft link — inode view","text":"Hard link vs soft link — inode view"},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"flowchart LR\n  subgraph HL[\"HARD LINK — 2 dir entries point at SAME inode\"]\n  direction LR\n  DE1[\"Dir entry\u003cbr/\u003e'file.txt'\u003cbr/\u003einode 1234\"]\n  DE2[\"Dir entry\u003cbr/\u003e'alias.txt'\u003cbr/\u003einode 1234\"]\n  IN1[\"inode 1234\u003cbr/\u003eowner · perms\u003cbr/\u003etimestamps\u003cbr/\u003elink_count = 2\u003cbr/\u003e→ data blocks\u003cbr/\u003eNO filename\"]\n  DE1 --\u003e IN1\n  DE2 --\u003e IN1\n  end\n  subgraph SL[\"SOFT / SYMBOLIC LINK — symlink file holds path as text\"]\n  direction LR\n  DS1[\"Dir entry 'short'\u003cbr/\u003einode 9999\"]\n  IN2[\"inode 9999 (symlink)\u003cbr/\u003etype=l\u003cbr/\u003econtent='/x/real'\"]\n  DS2[\"Dir entry 'real'\u003cbr/\u003einode 5555\"]\n  IN3[\"inode 5555 (target)\u003cbr/\u003elink_count=1\u003cbr/\u003e→ data blocks\"]\n  DS1 --\u003e IN2\n  DS2 --\u003e IN3\n  IN2 -. \"resolve via pathname\" .-\u003e IN3\n  end\n  classDef hard fill:#1a2218,stroke:#9ece6a,color:#e5e5e5;\n  classDef soft fill:#201c15,stroke:#e0af68,color:#e5e5e5;\n  classDef entry fill:#1a1a1a,stroke:#262626,color:#e5e5e5;\n  class DE1,DE2,DS1,DS2,IN3 entry;\n  class IN1 hard;\n  class IN2 soft;"},{"kind":"p","html":"Hard link = second directory entry, same inode (link count = 2). Soft link = tiny file whose body is the target path as text.","text":"Hard link = second directory entry, same inode (link count = 2). Soft link = tiny file whose body is the target path as text."},{"kind":"p","html":"create a hard link — watch the inode number + link count","text":"create a hard link — watch the inode number + link count"},{"kind":"code","lang":"console","code":"$ echo \"hello\" \u003e greet.txt\n\n$ ls -li greet.txt\n131073 -rw-r--r--. 1 alex alex 6 Apr 18 10:14 greet.txt\n\n$ ln greet.txt hi.txt    # hard link — no -s\n\n$ ls -li greet.txt hi.txt\n131073 -rw-r--r--. 2 alex alex 6 Apr 18 10:14 greet.txt\n131073 -rw-r--r--. 2 alex alex 6 Apr 18 10:14 hi.txt"},{"kind":"p","html":"Both names point at inode \u003cstrong\u003e131073\u003c/strong\u003e. Link count jumped from 1 → \u003cstrong\u003e2\u003c/strong\u003e. Neither is &quot;the original&quot; — they are equal citizens of one file.","text":"Both names point at inode **131073**. Link count jumped from 1 → **2**. Neither is \"the original\" — they are equal citizens of one file."},{"kind":"p","html":"now a soft link — notice the l prefix and the arrow","text":"now a soft link — notice the l prefix and the arrow"},{"kind":"code","lang":"console","code":"$ ln -s greet.txt short\n\n$ ls -li short\n262145 lrwxrwxrwx. 1 alex alex 9 Apr 18 10:15 short -\u003e greet.txt\n\n$ cat short\nhello"},{"kind":"p","html":"Soft link has its \u003cstrong\u003eown\u003c/strong\u003e inode (262145, not 131073). First char is \u003ccode\u003el\u003c/code\u003e. Permissions always show \u003ccode\u003elrwxrwxrwx\u003c/code\u003e — the target&#39;s perms are what actually apply.","text":"Soft link has its **own** inode (262145, not 131073). First char is `l`. Permissions always show `lrwxrwxrwx` — the target's perms are what actually apply."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003ch4\u003eWalkthrough: delete the target — hard link survives, soft link dies\u003c/h4\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eState: \u003ccode\u003egreet.txt\u003c/code\u003e (inode 131073, link_count=2), \u003ccode\u003ehi.txt\u003c/code\u003e (same inode), \u003ccode\u003eshort\u003c/code\u003e (symlink → greet.txt).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003erm greet.txt\u003c/code\u003e — removes the \u003cem\u003edirectory entry\u003c/em\u003e &quot;greet.txt&quot;. Link count drops to 1. Data blocks stay — the file still has a name.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ecat hi.txt\u003c/code\u003e → hello. Hard link still works because inode 131073 is still live (link_count=1).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ecat short\u003c/code\u003e → cat: short: No such file or directory. Symlink dangles — the path &quot;greet.txt&quot; no longer resolves.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eLesson: hard link is another \u003cem\u003ename\u003c/em\u003e; soft link is another \u003cem\u003epointer to a name\u003c/em\u003e. Remove the last name and everything downstream breaks.\nExam reflex: &quot;which link keeps working after the original is deleted?&quot; → hard link. Midterm Q24.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"#### Walkthrough: delete the target — hard link survives, soft link dies\n1.  State: `greet.txt` (inode 131073, link\\_count=2), `hi.txt` (same inode), `short` (symlink → greet.txt).\n2.  `rm greet.txt` — removes the *directory entry* \"greet.txt\". Link count drops to 1. Data blocks stay — the file still has a name.\n3.  `cat hi.txt` → hello. Hard link still works because inode 131073 is still live (link\\_count=1).\n4.  `cat short` → cat: short: No such file or directory. Symlink dangles — the path \"greet.txt\" no longer resolves.\n5.  Lesson: hard link is another *name*; soft link is another *pointer to a name*. Remove the last name and everything downstream breaks.\nExam reflex: \"which link keeps working after the original is deleted?\" → hard link. Midterm Q24."},{"kind":"p","html":"7 Unix file types — first char of \u003ccode\u003els -l\u003c/code\u003e","text":"7 Unix file types — first char of `ls -l`"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003e-\u003c/code\u003e plain  ·  \u003ccode\u003ed\u003c/code\u003e directory  ·  \u003ccode\u003eb\u003c/code\u003e block special (disks)  ·  \u003ccode\u003ec\u003c/code\u003e character special (terminals)  ·  \u003ccode\u003el\u003c/code\u003e symbolic link  ·  \u003ccode\u003es\u003c/code\u003e socket  ·  \u003ccode\u003ep\u003c/code\u003e named pipe (FIFO)","text":"`-` plain  ·  `d` directory  ·  `b` block special (disks)  ·  `c` character special (terminals)  ·  `l` symbolic link  ·  `s` socket  ·  `p` named pipe (FIFO)"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"note","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhy hard links can&#39;t cross filesystems.\u003c/strong\u003e Inode numbers are scoped to one filesystem. Inode 131073 on / and inode 131073 on /boot are different files. A directory entry on / that said &quot;inode 131073 on /boot&quot; would be nonsense. \u003ccode\u003eln /boot/vmlinuz ~/link\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003eInvalid cross-device link\u003c/code\u003e. Use \u003ccode\u003eln -s\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**Why hard links can't cross filesystems.** Inode numbers are scoped to one filesystem. Inode 131073 on / and inode 131073 on /boot are different files. A directory entry on / that said \"inode 131073 on /boot\" would be nonsense. `ln /boot/vmlinuz ~/link` → `Invalid cross-device link`. Use `ln -s`."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"I run `ln /boot/vmlinuz ~/link` and get \"Invalid cross-device link\". Why?","a":"`/boot` is a separate partition with its own inode table. Hard links share inode numbers, which are only unique within one filesystem. Use `ln -s` for a symlink — it stores the path as text and crosses filesystems fine."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"I delete the target of a symlink. What does `ls -l` show?","a":"Symlink still listed with `l` type and the old arrow. Reading it (`cat`) errors with \"No such file or directory\". Hard link siblings would be unaffected because they share the inode, not a pathname."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"`ls -l` shows `lrwxrwxrwx`. Can anyone write through the link?","a":"Not necessarily. Symlink perms are cosmetic — only the target's permissions matter. If target is `-r--r--r--`, nobody can write through the symlink either."},{"kind":"p","html":"Sources: Mod02 Ch6 · Lab 2 · midterm Q24 + Q58 · Review Apr 17","text":"Sources: Mod02 Ch6 · Lab 2 · midterm Q24 + Q58 · Review Apr 17"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Does an inode contain the filename?","a":"**No.** The inode stores owner, group, permissions, timestamps, size, link count, type, and block pointers — but not the name. The filename lives in the directory entry, which maps a name to an inode number. That separation is why hard links work: two entries, one inode."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eHard links cannot cross filesystems — inode numbers are unique only per-FS, so \u003ccode\u003eln /boot/vmlinuz ~/link\u003c/code\u003e errors with \u003ccode\u003eInvalid cross-device link\u003c/code\u003e. Use \u003ccode\u003eln -s\u003c/code\u003e (symlink) for cross-FS references. Midterm Q24 bait on &quot;original deleted&quot; scenarios — hard link still works (shared inode), soft link dangles.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Hard links cannot cross filesystems — inode numbers are unique only per-FS, so `ln /boot/vmlinuz ~/link` errors with `Invalid cross-device link`. Use `ln -s` (symlink) for cross-FS references. Midterm Q24 bait on \"original deleted\" scenarios — hard link still works (shared inode), soft link dangles."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eThe inode stores metadata + block pointers; the directory entry stores the name → inode mapping. That separation makes hard links possible (many entries → one inode) and confines them to a single filesystem (inode numbers are per-FS).\u003c/p\u003e","text":"The inode stores metadata + block pointers; the directory entry stores the name → inode mapping. That separation makes hard links possible (many entries → one inode) and confines them to a single filesystem (inode numbers are per-FS)."}]},{"n":3,"id":"4915-lesson-shell-basics-it-s-a-parser-dispatcher-and-waiter","title":"Shell basics: it's a parser, dispatcher, and waiter","hook":"Once you see the shell's loop, command weirdness stops being weird.","tags":["shell"],"module":"Shell, redirection & text processing","source":"Mod01 Ch4-5, Mod04 Ch9","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"You type \u003ccode\u003eecho ~/{a,b}_$USER.txt\u003c/code\u003e at a bash prompt. Your username is \u003ccode\u003ealice\u003c/code\u003e, your home is \u003ccode\u003e/home/alice\u003c/code\u003e. Before you read further, predict the output. Write it down in your head — don&#39;t skim past this.","text":"You type `echo ~/{a,b}_$USER.txt` at a bash prompt. Your username is `alice`, your home is `/home/alice`. Before you read further, predict the output. Write it down in your head — don't skim past this."},{"kind":"p","html":"Most people guess one of two things. Some guess \u003ccode\u003e~/{a,b}_alice.txt\u003c/code\u003e (parameter expanded, brace didn&#39;t). Others guess \u003ccode\u003e~/a_alice.txt ~/b_alice.txt\u003c/code\u003e (brace happened, tilde didn&#39;t). A few get the full answer, \u003ccode\u003e/home/alice/a_alice.txt /home/alice/b_alice.txt\u003c/code\u003e, but can&#39;t explain \u003cem\u003ewhy the three expansions happen in that particular order\u003c/em\u003e.","text":"Most people guess one of two things. Some guess `~/{a,b}_alice.txt` (parameter expanded, brace didn't). Others guess `~/a_alice.txt ~/b_alice.txt` (brace happened, tilde didn't). A few get the full answer, `/home/alice/a_alice.txt /home/alice/b_alice.txt`, but can't explain *why the three expansions happen in that particular order*."},{"kind":"p","html":"The shell is not magic. It is a small pipeline that does three jobs in sequence, every single time you press Enter. Once you see those three jobs, the order drops out naturally and your guess stops being a guess.","text":"The shell is not magic. It is a small pipeline that does three jobs in sequence, every single time you press Enter. Once you see those three jobs, the order drops out naturally and your guess stops being a guess."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The three jobs: parser, dispatcher, waiter","text":"The three jobs: parser, dispatcher, waiter"},{"kind":"p","html":"Before you can reason about any shell line, you need three vocabulary words.","text":"Before you can reason about any shell line, you need three vocabulary words."},{"kind":"p","html":"A \u003cstrong\u003eparser\u003c/strong\u003e is a program that takes text and breaks it into structured pieces. When you type \u003ccode\u003egrep foo file.txt\u003c/code\u003e, the shell&#39;s parser splits your line at whitespace into three \u003cem\u003etokens\u003c/em\u003e: \u003ccode\u003egrep\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003efoo\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003efile.txt\u003c/code\u003e. Parsing also runs the \u003cem\u003eexpansions\u003c/em\u003e — the rules that rewrite things like \u003ccode\u003e$USER\u003c/code\u003e into \u003ccode\u003ealice\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e*.txt\u003c/code\u003e into a list of filenames. The output of parsing is a cleaned-up argument list, ready to hand to a program.","text":"A **parser** is a program that takes text and breaks it into structured pieces. When you type `grep foo file.txt`, the shell's parser splits your line at whitespace into three *tokens*: `grep`, `foo`, and `file.txt`. Parsing also runs the *expansions* — the rules that rewrite things like `$USER` into `alice` and `*.txt` into a list of filenames. The output of parsing is a cleaned-up argument list, ready to hand to a program."},{"kind":"p","html":"A \u003cstrong\u003edispatcher\u003c/strong\u003e is the part that decides \u003cem\u003ewhich\u003c/em\u003e program to run. The parser has handed it a first token, say \u003ccode\u003egrep\u003c/code\u003e. Is that an alias you defined? A shell function? A builtin baked into bash? An external binary somewhere in \u003ccode\u003e$PATH\u003c/code\u003e? The shell walks a fixed priority list to pick the winner. We&#39;ll come back to that list — it&#39;s the second-most-tested thing in this topic.","text":"A **dispatcher** is the part that decides *which* program to run. The parser has handed it a first token, say `grep`. Is that an alias you defined? A shell function? A builtin baked into bash? An external binary somewhere in `$PATH`? The shell walks a fixed priority list to pick the winner. We'll come back to that list — it's the second-most-tested thing in this topic."},{"kind":"p","html":"A \u003cstrong\u003ewaiter\u003c/strong\u003e — nothing to do with restaurants in the OS sense — is the part that, after the chosen command starts running, sits on a \u003ccode\u003ewait()\u003c/code\u003e system call until that command exits. It then captures the command&#39;s exit status into the variable \u003ccode\u003e$?\u003c/code\u003e (zero = success, non-zero = error) and prints the next prompt. If the command was backgrounded with \u003ccode\u003e&amp;\u003c/code\u003e, the waiter skips the wait and returns immediately.","text":"A **waiter** — nothing to do with restaurants in the OS sense — is the part that, after the chosen command starts running, sits on a `wait()` system call until that command exits. It then captures the command's exit status into the variable `$?` (zero = success, non-zero = error) and prints the next prompt. If the command was backgrounded with `&`, the waiter skips the wait and returns immediately."},{"kind":"p","html":"Three jobs: rewrite the line, pick a target, run and collect the exit code. The whole prompt loop is those three phases repeating.","text":"Three jobs: rewrite the line, pick a target, run and collect the exit code. The whole prompt loop is those three phases repeating."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"analogy","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCounter clerk.\u003c/strong\u003e You hand an order to a clerk (the shell). The clerk rewrites it using a rulebook (expansions, in a fixed order), looks up which kitchen (alias / function / builtin / binary) should cook it, forks a cook, waits for the plate, hands it back, and asks &quot;next?&quot;. That loop never changes.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**Counter clerk.** You hand an order to a clerk (the shell). The clerk rewrites it using a rulebook (expansions, in a fixed order), looks up which kitchen (alias / function / builtin / binary) should cook it, forks a cook, waits for the plate, hands it back, and asks \"next?\". That loop never changes."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The diagram","text":"The diagram"},{"kind":"p","html":"Here is the full prompt loop, drawn end to end. \u003ccode\u003eINPUT\u003c/code\u003e is what you typed; \u003ccode\u003eEXEC\u003c/code\u003e is the kernel actually running your command.","text":"Here is the full prompt loop, drawn end to end. `INPUT` is what you typed; `EXEC` is the kernel actually running your command."},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"flowchart TB\n  IN[\"INPUT: echo ~/{a,b}_$USER.txt\u003cbr/\u003e(tokenize on whitespace first)\"]\n  subgraph EXP[\"7 EXPANSIONS — in order — all exam-tested\"]\n  direction LR\n  E1[\"1. Brace\u003cbr/\u003e{a,b} → a b\"]\n  E2[\"2. Tilde\u003cbr/\u003e~ → /home/u\"]\n  E3[\"3. Param\u003cbr/\u003e$USER → alice\"]\n  E4[\"4. Arith\u003cbr/\u003e$((2+3)) → 5\"]\n  E5[\"5. Cmd subst\u003cbr/\u003e$(date) → Fri Apr 18\"]\n  E6[\"6. Word split\u003cbr/\u003eIFS, unquoted only\"]\n  E7[\"7. Pathname\u003cbr/\u003e*.txt → a.txt b.txt\"]\n  E1 --\u003e E2 --\u003e E3 --\u003e E4 --\u003e E5 --\u003e E6 --\u003e E7\n  end\n  ARGV[\"After expansions:\u003cbr/\u003eecho /home/alice/a_alice.txt /home/alice/b_alice.txt\"]\n  PREC[\"COMMAND PRECEDENCE\u003cbr/\u003ealias → keyword → function → builtin → $PATH\u003cbr/\u003ebypass: command / builtin / abs path\"]\n  EXEC[\"fork → exec → wait → prompt\u003cbr/\u003eexit status → $?\"]\n  IN --\u003e EXP\n  E7 --\u003e ARGV\n  ARGV --\u003e PREC\n  PREC --\u003e EXEC\n  classDef step fill:#1a1a1a,stroke:#262626,color:#e5e5e5;\n  classDef prec fill:#181a18,stroke:#9ece6a,color:#e5e5e5;\n  classDef exec fill:#1a1a22,stroke:#7aa2f7,color:#e5e5e5;\n  class E1,E2,E3,E4,E5,E6,E7,ARGV step;\n  class PREC prec;\n  class EXEC exec;"},{"kind":"p","html":"The middle box — the seven expansions — is where your prediction likely went wrong. It is also where every &quot;why did it do \u003cem\u003ethat\u003c/em\u003e?&quot; exam question comes from.","text":"The middle box — the seven expansions — is where your prediction likely went wrong. It is also where every \"why did it do *that*?\" exam question comes from."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The seven expansions, one at a time","text":"The seven expansions, one at a time"},{"kind":"p","html":"Before you can trace any line, you need to know what each expansion \u003cem\u003eis\u003c/em\u003e. Pre-training each one in isolation makes the ordered list obvious rather than memorized.","text":"Before you can trace any line, you need to know what each expansion *is*. Pre-training each one in isolation makes the ordered list obvious rather than memorized."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003e1. Brace expansion.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003e{a,b,c}\u003c/code\u003e becomes the three words \u003ccode\u003ea b c\u003c/code\u003e. Written with a range, \u003ccode\u003e{01..03}\u003c/code\u003e becomes \u003ccode\u003e01 02 03\u003c/code\u003e. Brace expansion is \u003cem\u003etextual\u003c/em\u003e — it looks only at the literal characters on the line. It does not peek inside variables. That last sentence is the whole trap.","text":"**1. Brace expansion.** `{a,b,c}` becomes the three words `a b c`. Written with a range, `{01..03}` becomes `01 02 03`. Brace expansion is *textual* — it looks only at the literal characters on the line. It does not peek inside variables. That last sentence is the whole trap."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003e2. Tilde expansion.\u003c/strong\u003e A leading \u003ccode\u003e~\u003c/code\u003e becomes your home directory (\u003ccode\u003e$HOME\u003c/code\u003e). \u003ccode\u003e~alice\u003c/code\u003e becomes \u003cem\u003ealice&#39;s\u003c/em\u003e home directory. Tilde only works at the start of a word or right after a \u003ccode\u003e:\u003c/code\u003e in a path list.","text":"**2. Tilde expansion.** A leading `~` becomes your home directory (`$HOME`). `~alice` becomes *alice's* home directory. Tilde only works at the start of a word or right after a `:` in a path list."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003e3. Parameter expansion.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003e$var\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003e${var}\u003c/code\u003e becomes the value of the variable \u003ccode\u003evar\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003e$USER\u003c/code\u003e becomes \u003ccode\u003ealice\u003c/code\u003e. If the variable is unset, it becomes the empty string (unless you asked for strict mode).","text":"**3. Parameter expansion.** `$var` or `${var}` becomes the value of the variable `var`. `$USER` becomes `alice`. If the variable is unset, it becomes the empty string (unless you asked for strict mode)."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003e4. Arithmetic expansion.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003e$(( 2 + 3 ))\u003c/code\u003e becomes \u003ccode\u003e5\u003c/code\u003e. The shell does integer math inside the double parens.","text":"**4. Arithmetic expansion.** `$(( 2 + 3 ))` becomes `5`. The shell does integer math inside the double parens."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003e5. Command substitution.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003e$(date)\u003c/code\u003e runs \u003ccode\u003edate\u003c/code\u003e, captures its standard output, and pastes that output back onto the line as text. Backticks \u003ccode\u003e`date`\u003c/code\u003e do the same thing but are harder to nest — prefer \u003ccode\u003e$(…)\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"**5. Command substitution.** `$(date)` runs `date`, captures its standard output, and pastes that output back onto the line as text. Backticks `` `date` `` do the same thing but are harder to nest — prefer `$(…)`."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003e6. Word splitting.\u003c/strong\u003e After the first five expansions produce text, the shell re-breaks any \u003cem\u003eunquoted\u003c/em\u003e result at the characters in \u003ccode\u003e$IFS\u003c/code\u003e (default: space, tab, newline). This is why \u003ccode\u003efoo=&quot;a b c&quot;; echo $foo\u003c/code\u003e prints three arguments but \u003ccode\u003eecho &quot;$foo&quot;\u003c/code\u003e prints one.","text":"**6. Word splitting.** After the first five expansions produce text, the shell re-breaks any *unquoted* result at the characters in `$IFS` (default: space, tab, newline). This is why `foo=\"a b c\"; echo $foo` prints three arguments but `echo \"$foo\"` prints one."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003e7. Pathname expansion (globbing).\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003e*\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e?\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003e[…]\u003c/code\u003e match filenames. \u003ccode\u003e*.txt\u003c/code\u003e becomes whatever \u003ccode\u003e.txt\u003c/code\u003e files actually exist in the current directory. If nothing matches, the pattern is left unchanged — the literal \u003ccode\u003e*.txt\u003c/code\u003e is what \u003ccode\u003eecho\u003c/code\u003e receives. (Set \u003ccode\u003eshopt -s nullglob\u003c/code\u003e to change that behavior; by default, a failed match stays literal.)","text":"**7. Pathname expansion (globbing).** `*`, `?`, and `[…]` match filenames. `*.txt` becomes whatever `.txt` files actually exist in the current directory. If nothing matches, the pattern is left unchanged — the literal `*.txt` is what `echo` receives. (Set `shopt -s nullglob` to change that behavior; by default, a failed match stays literal.)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Quoting turns expansions off. \u003cstrong\u003eSingle quotes\u003c/strong\u003e disable all seven. \u003cstrong\u003eDouble quotes\u003c/strong\u003e disable only the last two — word splitting and globbing — which is why \u003ccode\u003e&quot;$var&quot;\u003c/code\u003e is almost always what you want.","text":"Quoting turns expansions off. **Single quotes** disable all seven. **Double quotes** disable only the last two — word splitting and globbing — which is why `\"$var\"` is almost always what you want."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Tracing your prediction","text":"Tracing your prediction"},{"kind":"p","html":"Now trace the line from the opening, one expansion at a time, and watch the answer fall out.","text":"Now trace the line from the opening, one expansion at a time, and watch the answer fall out."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003ch4\u003eTrace: \u003ccode\u003eecho ~/{a,b}_$USER.txt\u003c/code\u003e (USER=alice, HOME=/home/alice)\u003c/h4\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTokenize.\u003c/strong\u003e Whitespace splits the line into two words: \u003ccode\u003eecho\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e~/{a,b}_$USER.txt\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBrace expansion\u003c/strong\u003e (step 1). \u003ccode\u003e~/{a,b}_$USER.txt\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003e~/a_$USER.txt ~/b_$USER.txt\u003c/code\u003e. Brace sees literal text — \u003ccode\u003e$USER\u003c/code\u003e has not been touched yet.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTilde expansion\u003c/strong\u003e (step 2). Each \u003ccode\u003e~\u003c/code\u003e at the start of a word becomes \u003ccode\u003e/home/alice\u003c/code\u003e: \u003ccode\u003e/home/alice/a_$USER.txt /home/alice/b_$USER.txt\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eParameter expansion\u003c/strong\u003e (step 3). \u003ccode\u003e$USER\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003ealice\u003c/code\u003e: \u003ccode\u003e/home/alice/a_alice.txt /home/alice/b_alice.txt\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSteps 4–7 (arithmetic, command substitution, word splitting, globbing) have nothing to do. The result is whitespace-separated already and has no wildcards.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDispatch.\u003c/strong\u003e First token \u003ccode\u003eecho\u003c/code\u003e walks the precedence list: alias? no. keyword? no. function? no. builtin? \u003cstrong\u003eyes\u003c/strong\u003e — bash&#39;s built-in \u003ccode\u003eecho\u003c/code\u003e handles it.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eExec.\u003c/strong\u003e Because \u003ccode\u003eecho\u003c/code\u003e is a builtin, no \u003ccode\u003efork()\u003c/code\u003e happens; the shell runs the code in-process. Output: \u003ccode\u003e/home/alice/a_alice.txt /home/alice/b_alice.txt\u003c/code\u003e.\nSwap the order of brace and parameter in your head and you&#39;d get \u003ccode\u003e/home/alice/{a,b}_alice.txt\u003c/code\u003e — brace never sees the literal \u003ccode\u003e{a,b}\u003c/code\u003e because parameter ran first and nothing expanded. The fixed order is what makes the real result land where it does.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"#### Trace: `echo ~/{a,b}_$USER.txt` (USER=alice, HOME=/home/alice)\n1.  **Tokenize.** Whitespace splits the line into two words: `echo` and `~/{a,b}_$USER.txt`.\n2.  **Brace expansion** (step 1). `~/{a,b}_$USER.txt` → `~/a_$USER.txt ~/b_$USER.txt`. Brace sees literal text — `$USER` has not been touched yet.\n3.  **Tilde expansion** (step 2). Each `~` at the start of a word becomes `/home/alice`: `/home/alice/a_$USER.txt /home/alice/b_$USER.txt`.\n4.  **Parameter expansion** (step 3). `$USER` → `alice`: `/home/alice/a_alice.txt /home/alice/b_alice.txt`.\n5.  Steps 4–7 (arithmetic, command substitution, word splitting, globbing) have nothing to do. The result is whitespace-separated already and has no wildcards.\n6.  **Dispatch.** First token `echo` walks the precedence list: alias? no. keyword? no. function? no. builtin? **yes** — bash's built-in `echo` handles it.\n7.  **Exec.** Because `echo` is a builtin, no `fork()` happens; the shell runs the code in-process. Output: `/home/alice/a_alice.txt /home/alice/b_alice.txt`.\nSwap the order of brace and parameter in your head and you'd get `/home/alice/{a,b}_alice.txt` — brace never sees the literal `{a,b}` because parameter ran first and nothing expanded. The fixed order is what makes the real result land where it does."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Brace expansion multiplies — a concrete feel","text":"Brace expansion multiplies — a concrete feel"},{"kind":"p","html":"Before the next trap, look at brace on its own so you have an intuition for it.","text":"Before the next trap, look at brace on its own so you have an intuition for it."},{"kind":"code","lang":"console","code":"$ echo {a,b}{1,2}\na1 a2 b1 b2\n\n$ echo file_{01..03}.log\nfile_01.log file_02.log file_03.log\n\n$ mkdir -p project/{src,test,docs}    # practical\n\n$ ls project\ndocs src test"},{"kind":"p","html":"Brace distributes across adjacent text — two braces next to each other give you the full 2×2 cross product. That is why brace runs \u003cem\u003efirst\u003c/em\u003e: later stages want one word per filename, and brace&#39;s job is to generate those words from a compact pattern.","text":"Brace distributes across adjacent text — two braces next to each other give you the full 2×2 cross product. That is why brace runs *first*: later stages want one word per filename, and brace's job is to generate those words from a compact pattern."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The classic order trap","text":"The classic order trap"},{"kind":"p","html":"Here is where most people&#39;s prediction breaks. What does \u003ccode\u003eecho {$HOME,$USER}\u003c/code\u003e print?","text":"Here is where most people's prediction breaks. What does `echo {$HOME,$USER}` print?"},{"kind":"p","html":"Your instinct might say: &quot;Brace makes two items, each gets expanded — I should see \u003ccode\u003e/home/alice alice\u003c/code\u003e.&quot; You are half right. The final output \u003cem\u003eis\u003c/em\u003e \u003ccode\u003e/home/alice alice\u003c/code\u003e, but not because brace cooperated with parameter expansion. It&#39;s because brace ran first, blind to \u003ccode\u003e$\u003c/code\u003e, and split the literal text into the two words \u003ccode\u003e$HOME\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e$USER\u003c/code\u003e. \u003cem\u003eThen\u003c/em\u003e parameter expansion came along later and replaced each variable with its value. The order gave you the answer you wanted, by accident of sequencing.","text":"Your instinct might say: \"Brace makes two items, each gets expanded — I should see `/home/alice alice`.\" You are half right. The final output *is* `/home/alice alice`, but not because brace cooperated with parameter expansion. It's because brace ran first, blind to `$`, and split the literal text into the two words `$HOME` and `$USER`. *Then* parameter expansion came along later and replaced each variable with its value. The order gave you the answer you wanted, by accident of sequencing."},{"kind":"p","html":"Now flip the variables around. \u003ccode\u003eecho {$USER,$HOME}_logs\u003c/code\u003e — same mechanism: brace blindly splits \u003ccode\u003e$USER\u003c/code\u003e from \u003ccode\u003e$HOME\u003c/code\u003e first (producing \u003ccode\u003e$USER_logs $HOME_logs\u003c/code\u003e), and parameter expansion then discovers \u003ccode\u003e$USER_logs\u003c/code\u003e is \u003cem\u003eone variable name\u003c/em\u003e, not \u003ccode\u003e$USER\u003c/code\u003e followed by \u003ccode\u003e_logs\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003e$USER_logs\u003c/code\u003e is probably unset, so you get an empty string and a surprise. That is a real way this trap bites.","text":"Now flip the variables around. `echo {$USER,$HOME}_logs` — same mechanism: brace blindly splits `$USER` from `$HOME` first (producing `$USER_logs $HOME_logs`), and parameter expansion then discovers `$USER_logs` is *one variable name*, not `$USER` followed by `_logs`. `$USER_logs` is probably unset, so you get an empty string and a surprise. That is a real way this trap bites."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What does `echo {$USER,$HOME}_logs` print when USER=alice and HOME=/home/alice?","a":"Brace runs first and produces the two literal words `$USER_logs` and `$HOME_logs`. Parameter expansion then looks those up. Neither variable exists by that name, so both expand to the empty string. Final output: one blank space (just what `echo` prints when given two empty arguments). The fix: put the suffix outside the braces — `echo {$USER,$HOME}` prints `alice /home/alice`, and `echo \"${USER}_logs ${HOME}_logs\"` prints `alice_logs /home/alice_logs`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Command precedence — the dispatcher&#39;s priority list","text":"Command precedence — the dispatcher's priority list"},{"kind":"p","html":"Expansions finish. The shell now has a list of words. The first word is the \u003cem\u003ecommand name\u003c/em\u003e. Precedence is the rulebook the dispatcher uses to decide which thing that name refers to.","text":"Expansions finish. The shell now has a list of words. The first word is the *command name*. Precedence is the rulebook the dispatcher uses to decide which thing that name refers to."},{"kind":"p","html":"Here are the five kinds of &quot;command&quot; you might have, in the priority order bash uses:","text":"Here are the five kinds of \"command\" you might have, in the priority order bash uses:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAlias.\u003c/strong\u003e A text substitution set up by the \u003ccode\u003ealias\u003c/code\u003e command. \u003ccode\u003ealias ls=&#39;ls --color=auto&#39;\u003c/code\u003e. Aliases are pure textual rewrite — they happen before the rest of the precedence walk.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eKeyword.\u003c/strong\u003e Reserved words the shell&#39;s grammar recognizes structurally: \u003ccode\u003eif\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ewhile\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003efor\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ecase\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003efunction\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e[[\u003c/code\u003e. You cannot shadow these.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eFunction.\u003c/strong\u003e A shell function you defined (\u003ccode\u003efoo() { …; }\u003c/code\u003e). Runs in the current shell, no fork.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBuiltin.\u003c/strong\u003e A command implemented \u003cem\u003einside\u003c/em\u003e bash itself: \u003ccode\u003ecd\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eecho\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003epwd\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eexport\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eread\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003etest\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e[\u003c/code\u003e. No fork, no exec — the code is part of the bash binary. This is why \u003ccode\u003ecd\u003c/code\u003e has to be a builtin: an external \u003ccode\u003ecd\u003c/code\u003e could not change the shell&#39;s working directory.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003e$PATH\u003c/code\u003e search.\u003c/strong\u003e The shell walks the directories in \u003ccode\u003e$PATH\u003c/code\u003e left to right, looking for an executable file by that name. First match wins. This is where \u003ccode\u003e/usr/bin/ls\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e/usr/bin/grep\u003c/code\u003e, and every other external binary live.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. **Alias.** A text substitution set up by the `alias` command. `alias ls='ls --color=auto'`. Aliases are pure textual rewrite — they happen before the rest of the precedence walk.\n2. **Keyword.** Reserved words the shell's grammar recognizes structurally: `if`, `while`, `for`, `case`, `function`, `[[`. You cannot shadow these.\n3. **Function.** A shell function you defined (`foo() { …; }`). Runs in the current shell, no fork.\n4. **Builtin.** A command implemented *inside* bash itself: `cd`, `echo`, `pwd`, `export`, `read`, `test`, `[`. No fork, no exec — the code is part of the bash binary. This is why `cd` has to be a builtin: an external `cd` could not change the shell's working directory.\n5. **`$PATH` search.** The shell walks the directories in `$PATH` left to right, looking for an executable file by that name. First match wins. This is where `/usr/bin/ls`, `/usr/bin/grep`, and every other external binary live."},{"kind":"p","html":"Three escape hatches let you bypass the walk when you know exactly what you want. \u003ccode\u003ecommand foo\u003c/code\u003e skips aliases and functions (but still checks builtin and \u003ccode\u003e$PATH\u003c/code\u003e). \u003ccode\u003ebuiltin foo\u003c/code\u003e forces the builtin, never the external binary. And an absolute path like \u003ccode\u003e/usr/bin/ls\u003c/code\u003e goes straight to the binary with no lookup at all.","text":"Three escape hatches let you bypass the walk when you know exactly what you want. `command foo` skips aliases and functions (but still checks builtin and `$PATH`). `builtin foo` forces the builtin, never the external binary. And an absolute path like `/usr/bin/ls` goes straight to the binary with no lookup at all."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Precedence in action","text":"Precedence in action"},{"kind":"code","lang":"console","code":"$ alias ls='ls --color=auto -F'\n\n$ type ls\nls is aliased to `ls --color=auto -F'\n\n$ command ls          # skip the alias\ngreet.txt hi.txt\n\n$ /usr/bin/ls         # force external binary\ngreet.txt hi.txt"},{"kind":"p","html":"The two bypasses in that session do different things. \u003ccode\u003ecommand ls\u003c/code\u003e skips the alias (and any function), then runs whatever&#39;s next — here, the external \u003ccode\u003e/usr/bin/ls\u003c/code\u003e. The absolute path goes straight to the binary, no lookup at all. \u003ccode\u003etype -a ls\u003c/code\u003e is the diagnostic tool: it lists \u003cem\u003eevery\u003c/em\u003e match of the name in precedence order, so if you ever wonder &quot;why is \u003ccode\u003els\u003c/code\u003e doing something weird&quot;, that command shows you the stack.","text":"The two bypasses in that session do different things. `command ls` skips the alias (and any function), then runs whatever's next — here, the external `/usr/bin/ls`. The absolute path goes straight to the binary, no lookup at all. `type -a ls` is the diagnostic tool: it lists *every* match of the name in precedence order, so if you ever wonder \"why is `ls` doing something weird\", that command shows you the stack."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Checkpoints","text":"Checkpoints"},{"kind":"p","html":"Each of these is testing a different surface form of the same deep idea — the order of expansions, or the precedence walk. Cover the answer, commit to a response in your head, then reveal.","text":"Each of these is testing a different surface form of the same deep idea — the order of expansions, or the precedence walk. Cover the answer, commit to a response in your head, then reveal."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"In an empty directory, what does `echo *.txt` print?","a":"The literal text `*.txt`. Pathname expansion (step 7) looks for `.txt` files, finds none, and — by default — leaves the pattern unchanged. `echo` then receives the single argument `*.txt` and prints it. If you had run `shopt -s nullglob` first, the pattern would expand to *nothing* and `echo` would print a blank line. This is the only expansion that silently passes its input through on failure; every other expansion either succeeds or produces the empty string."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You define a shell function `ls() { echo \"nope\"; }` and then run `ls`. What happens, and how do you get the real `ls` back for one invocation?","a":"The function runs — it prints `nope`. Functions (priority 3) beat builtins (4) and `$PATH` binaries (5). To run the real external once without removing the function, use `command ls` (skips aliases and functions) or the absolute path `/usr/bin/ls`. To get the function out of the way permanently, `unset -f ls`."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Why is `cd` a builtin rather than an external program at `/usr/bin/cd`?","a":"An external program runs in a forked child process. Changing that child's working directory does nothing to the parent shell's directory — the child exits and its state dies with it. `cd` must run *inside* the shell process itself, which is exactly what a builtin does. The same reason applies to `export`, `read`, `source`, and `exec`: any command that has to mutate the shell's own state must be a builtin."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You type `grep foo file.txt` and press Enter. List what the parser, the dispatcher, and the waiter each do.","a":"The **parser** tokenizes the line into `grep`, `foo`, `file.txt`; the seven expansions all run (none of the three words need rewriting here). The **dispatcher** walks the precedence list on `grep` — not an alias, not a keyword, not a function, not a builtin — and finds `/usr/bin/grep` via `$PATH`. It then `fork()`s a child and `exec()`s grep in it. The **waiter** calls `wait()` on that child, and when grep exits, stores the exit code in `$?` and prints the next prompt. Three phases, one loop, every line."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Pitfalls","text":"Pitfalls"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eA function or alias named \u003ccode\u003els\u003c/code\u003e silently shadows \u003ccode\u003e/usr/bin/ls\u003c/code\u003e. You&#39;ll see strange flags, colored output, or different sorting, and wonder if the binary is broken. Run \u003ccode\u003etype -a ls\u003c/code\u003e — it prints every match in precedence order, so the culprit is the first line. Use \u003ccode\u003ecommand ls\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003e/usr/bin/ls\u003c/code\u003e to bypass without disturbing the shadow.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"A function or alias named `ls` silently shadows `/usr/bin/ls`. You'll see strange flags, colored output, or different sorting, and wonder if the binary is broken. Run `type -a ls` — it prints every match in precedence order, so the culprit is the first line. Use `command ls` or `/usr/bin/ls` to bypass without disturbing the shadow."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eVariables inside braces don&#39;t expand. \u003ccode\u003e{$HOME,$TMPDIR}\u003c/code\u003e looks like it should give you two expanded paths, but brace expansion runs first and treats the \u003ccode\u003e$\u003c/code\u003e as literal text. Parameter expansion cleans up \u003cem\u003eafterward\u003c/em\u003e, which sometimes makes it look like it worked. When the variable name runs into adjacent characters (\u003ccode\u003e{$USER,$HOME}_logs\u003c/code\u003e), the \u003cem\u003eafterward\u003c/em\u003e stops working and you get the empty string. Put variables outside braces, or use an explicit list: \u003ccode\u003efor x in &quot;$USER&quot; &quot;$HOME&quot;; do …\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Variables inside braces don't expand. `{$HOME,$TMPDIR}` looks like it should give you two expanded paths, but brace expansion runs first and treats the `$` as literal text. Parameter expansion cleans up *afterward*, which sometimes makes it look like it worked. When the variable name runs into adjacent characters (`{$USER,$HOME}_logs`), the *afterward* stops working and you get the empty string. Put variables outside braces, or use an explicit list: `for x in \"$USER\" \"$HOME\"; do …`."},{"kind":"p","html":"Sources: Mod01 Ch5 · Mod04 Ch9 · Review Apr 17","text":"Sources: Mod01 Ch5 · Mod04 Ch9 · Review Apr 17"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eThe shell is a parser, a dispatcher, and a waiter. Parsing rewrites your line through seven expansions in a fixed order — brace, tilde, parameter, arithmetic, command substitution, word splitting, pathname. Dispatch resolves the first token by precedence — alias, keyword, function, builtin, \u003ccode\u003e$PATH\u003c/code\u003e — and \u003ccode\u003efork()\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003eexec()\u003c/code\u003es the winner. Waiting captures the exit status into \u003ccode\u003e$?\u003c/code\u003e and prints the next prompt. Every surprising shell result is a step in that pipeline you didn&#39;t trace.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"The shell is a parser, a dispatcher, and a waiter. Parsing rewrites your line through seven expansions in a fixed order — brace, tilde, parameter, arithmetic, command substitution, word splitting, pathname. Dispatch resolves the first token by precedence — alias, keyword, function, builtin, `$PATH` — and `fork()` + `exec()`s the winner. Waiting captures the exit status into `$?` and prints the next prompt. Every surprising shell result is a step in that pipeline you didn't trace."}]},{"n":4,"id":"4915-lesson-quoting-and-redirection-where-90-of-midterm-traps-live","title":"Quoting and redirection — where 90% of midterm traps live","hook":"Get this right and you skip 5 MCQ/T-F pitfalls.","tags":["redirection","shell"],"module":"Shell, redirection & text processing","source":"Mod04 Ch9-12; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q10, Q17, Q43, Q44, Q47, Q50","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"You set a variable and echo it three different ways:","text":"You set a variable and echo it three different ways:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"console","code":"$ person=jenny\n$ echo '$person'\n$ echo \"$person\"\n$ echo $person"},{"kind":"p","html":"Three commands. Same variable. Three different outputs. Before you read on, decide for yourself what each line prints. If you can predict all three, you already own the first half of this lesson; if you can&#39;t, you&#39;ve just located the gap.","text":"Three commands. Same variable. Three different outputs. Before you read on, decide for yourself what each line prints. If you can predict all three, you already own the first half of this lesson; if you can't, you've just located the gap."},{"kind":"p","html":"The answers are at the bottom of the next section. Hold the prediction in your head while you work through it.","text":"The answers are at the bottom of the next section. Hold the prediction in your head while you work through it."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Quoting decides what the shell looks at before the command runs","text":"Quoting decides what the shell looks at before the command runs"},{"kind":"p","html":"The thing to absorb first is \u003cem\u003ewhen\u003c/em\u003e the shell touches your text. The order is fixed: you type a line, the shell parses it, the shell \u003cstrong\u003eexpands\u003c/strong\u003e anything it recognizes (variables, globs, command substitutions, and four others), and \u003cem\u003eonly then\u003c/em\u003e does it hand the result to the command. By the time \u003ccode\u003eecho\u003c/code\u003e actually runs, it never sees \u003ccode\u003e$person\u003c/code\u003e — it sees \u003ccode\u003ejenny\u003c/code\u003e, or whatever the expansion produced.","text":"The thing to absorb first is *when* the shell touches your text. The order is fixed: you type a line, the shell parses it, the shell **expands** anything it recognizes (variables, globs, command substitutions, and four others), and *only then* does it hand the result to the command. By the time `echo` actually runs, it never sees `$person` — it sees `jenny`, or whatever the expansion produced."},{"kind":"p","html":"Quoting is how you tell the shell which of those expansions to skip. There are three modes, and each one disables a different amount.","text":"Quoting is how you tell the shell which of those expansions to skip. There are three modes, and each one disables a different amount."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eSingle quotes\u003c/strong\u003e (\u003ccode\u003e&#39;…&#39;\u003c/code\u003e) are the strongest off-switch. Everything between them is taken as literal text. Variables don&#39;t expand, globs don&#39;t match, command substitution doesn&#39;t run. The only thing you can&#39;t put inside single quotes is another single quote — there&#39;s no escape sequence; the first \u003ccode\u003e&#39;\u003c/code\u003e opens and the next \u003ccode\u003e&#39;\u003c/code\u003e closes, period. You reach for single quotes when you want what you typed, exactly: a regex, a sed script, a literal \u003ccode\u003e$\u003c/code\u003e sign.","text":"**Single quotes** (`'…'`) are the strongest off-switch. Everything between them is taken as literal text. Variables don't expand, globs don't match, command substitution doesn't run. The only thing you can't put inside single quotes is another single quote — there's no escape sequence; the first `'` opens and the next `'` closes, period. You reach for single quotes when you want what you typed, exactly: a regex, a sed script, a literal `$` sign."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eDouble quotes\u003c/strong\u003e (\u003ccode\u003e&quot;…&quot;\u003c/code\u003e) are a softer off-switch. They block two specific things — word splitting and globbing — but they \u003cem\u003estill allow\u003c/em\u003e \u003ccode\u003e$variable\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e$(command)\u003c/code\u003e, backticks, and backslash escapes. This is the mode you use most. \u003ccode\u003e&quot;$file&quot;\u003c/code\u003e is the right way to handle a filename that might contain spaces, because the variable still expands but the result isn&#39;t then chopped into pieces by whitespace.","text":"**Double quotes** (`\"…\"`) are a softer off-switch. They block two specific things — word splitting and globbing — but they *still allow* `$variable`, `$(command)`, backticks, and backslash escapes. This is the mode you use most. `\"$file\"` is the right way to handle a filename that might contain spaces, because the variable still expands but the result isn't then chopped into pieces by whitespace."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eNo quotes at all\u003c/strong\u003e lets all seven expansions fire — variables, globs, word splitting, the works. That&#39;s powerful when you \u003cem\u003ewant\u003c/em\u003e the shell to expand \u003ccode\u003e*.txt\u003c/code\u003e into a list of files; it&#39;s a footgun when \u003ccode\u003e$file\u003c/code\u003e happens to contain a space and your command suddenly sees two arguments instead of one.","text":"**No quotes at all** lets all seven expansions fire — variables, globs, word splitting, the works. That's powerful when you *want* the shell to expand `*.txt` into a list of files; it's a footgun when `$file` happens to contain a space and your command suddenly sees two arguments instead of one."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Why is `\"$file\"` safer than bare `$file` when `$file` might contain spaces?","a":"Both expand the variable. The bare form then runs word splitting on the result, so `my report.txt` becomes two arguments — `my` and `report.txt` — and your command misinterprets them. Double quotes expand the variable but suppress the splitting step, keeping the value as a single argument."},{"kind":"p","html":"So back to the prediction. \u003ccode\u003eecho &#39;$person&#39;\u003c/code\u003e prints the literal string \u003ccode\u003e$person\u003c/code\u003e, because single quotes block the variable expansion. \u003ccode\u003eecho &quot;$person&quot;\u003c/code\u003e prints \u003ccode\u003ejenny\u003c/code\u003e, because double quotes allow \u003ccode\u003e$\u003c/code\u003e expansion. \u003ccode\u003eecho $person\u003c/code\u003e also prints \u003ccode\u003ejenny\u003c/code\u003e, because expansion happens with bare words too — but if \u003ccode\u003e$person\u003c/code\u003e had been \u003ccode\u003ejenny smith\u003c/code\u003e, the bare version would have passed two arguments to \u003ccode\u003eecho\u003c/code\u003e and the double-quoted version one. (Midterm Q47 is exactly the single-quote case.)","text":"So back to the prediction. `echo '$person'` prints the literal string `$person`, because single quotes block the variable expansion. `echo \"$person\"` prints `jenny`, because double quotes allow `$` expansion. `echo $person` also prints `jenny`, because expansion happens with bare words too — but if `$person` had been `jenny smith`, the bare version would have passed two arguments to `echo` and the double-quoted version one. (Midterm Q47 is exactly the single-quote case.)"},{"kind":"code","lang":"console","code":"$ export person=jenny\n\n$ echo '$person'        # single: literal\n$person\n\n$ echo \"$person\"        # double: expands\njenny\n\n$ echo $person          # bare: expands + word splits + globs\njenny"},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e Single quotes can never contain a single quote — not even escaped. \u003ccode\u003e&#39;don\\&#39;t&#39;\u003c/code\u003e looks like it should work, but it doesn&#39;t: the first \u003ccode\u003e&#39;\u003c/code\u003e opens, the second \u003ccode\u003e&#39;\u003c/code\u003e closes (leaving \u003ccode\u003edon\u003c/code\u003e), and then \u003ccode\u003et&#39;\u003c/code\u003e starts a brand-new open quote that the shell waits forever to see closed. Use double quotes (\u003ccode\u003e&quot;don&#39;t&quot;\u003c/code\u003e) or the ANSI-C form \u003ccode\u003e$&#39;don\\&#39;t&#39;\u003c/code\u003e when you need an apostrophe inside.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Redirection: streams, file descriptors, and where bytes go","text":"Redirection: streams, file descriptors, and where bytes go"},{"kind":"p","html":"Before you can reason about redirection, you need three vocabulary items. Every Unix process is born with three open \u003cstrong\u003efile descriptors\u003c/strong\u003e — small integers the kernel uses to track open files. Descriptor \u003cstrong\u003e0\u003c/strong\u003e is \u003cstrong\u003estandard input\u003c/strong\u003e (stdin), the source the program reads from. Descriptor \u003cstrong\u003e1\u003c/strong\u003e is \u003cstrong\u003estandard output\u003c/strong\u003e (stdout), where normal results go. Descriptor \u003cstrong\u003e2\u003c/strong\u003e is \u003cstrong\u003estandard error\u003c/strong\u003e (stderr), where error messages go. By default all three are wired to your terminal, which is why typing and reading and seeing errors all happen in the same window.","text":"Before you can reason about redirection, you need three vocabulary items. Every Unix process is born with three open **file descriptors** — small integers the kernel uses to track open files. Descriptor **0** is **standard input** (stdin), the source the program reads from. Descriptor **1** is **standard output** (stdout), where normal results go. Descriptor **2** is **standard error** (stderr), where error messages go. By default all three are wired to your terminal, which is why typing and reading and seeing errors all happen in the same window."},{"kind":"p","html":"Redirection is the act of unwiring one of those descriptors from the terminal and pointing it at a file or another descriptor instead. The shell does this \u003cem\u003ebefore\u003c/em\u003e launching the command — the command never knows. From its point of view, it just writes to fd 1 like always; the kernel takes care of the fact that fd 1 now points at \u003ccode\u003eout.txt\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Redirection is the act of unwiring one of those descriptors from the terminal and pointing it at a file or another descriptor instead. The shell does this *before* launching the command — the command never knows. From its point of view, it just writes to fd 1 like always; the kernel takes care of the fact that fd 1 now points at `out.txt`."},{"kind":"p","html":"Here are the operators you&#39;ll see on the exam:","text":"Here are the operators you'll see on the exam:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&gt; file\u003c/code\u003e redirects stdout to \u003ccode\u003efile\u003c/code\u003e, \u003cstrong\u003etruncating\u003c/strong\u003e it first. If the file already had contents, they&#39;re gone the moment the shell parses the line — before the command even runs.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&gt;&gt; file\u003c/code\u003e redirects stdout to \u003ccode\u003efile\u003c/code\u003e in \u003cstrong\u003eappend\u003c/strong\u003e mode. Existing contents are preserved.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e2&gt; file\u003c/code\u003e redirects stderr (fd 2) to \u003ccode\u003efile\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e2&gt;&amp;1\u003c/code\u003e \u003cem\u003eduplicates\u003c/em\u003e fd 2 onto whatever fd 1 currently points to. Read it as &quot;make stderr go wherever stdout is going right now.&quot; The order this fires in is the entire trick — we&#39;ll come back to it.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&amp;&gt; file\u003c/code\u003e is a bash shortcut meaning &quot;stdout and stderr both go to \u003ccode\u003efile\u003c/code\u003e.&quot;\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e| cmd\u003c/code\u003e connects fd 1 of the left command to fd 0 of the right command — a pipe.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&lt; file\u003c/code\u003e feeds \u003ccode\u003efile\u003c/code\u003e into stdin.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&lt;&lt; EOF\u003c/code\u003e is a here-doc (multi-line literal input); \u003ccode\u003e&lt;&lt;&lt; &quot;str&quot;\u003c/code\u003e is a here-string (single string fed as stdin).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e/dev/null\u003c/code\u003e is a special &quot;discard&quot; file. Writes vanish; reads return immediately at end-of-file. The idiom \u003ccode\u003ecmd &gt; /dev/null 2&gt;&amp;1\u003c/code\u003e silences everything a command emits.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- `\u003e file` redirects stdout to `file`, **truncating** it first. If the file already had contents, they're gone the moment the shell parses the line — before the command even runs.\n- `\u003e\u003e file` redirects stdout to `file` in **append** mode. Existing contents are preserved.\n- `2\u003e file` redirects stderr (fd 2) to `file`.\n- `2\u003e&1` *duplicates* fd 2 onto whatever fd 1 currently points to. Read it as \"make stderr go wherever stdout is going right now.\" The order this fires in is the entire trick — we'll come back to it.\n- `&\u003e file` is a bash shortcut meaning \"stdout and stderr both go to `file`.\"\n- `| cmd` connects fd 1 of the left command to fd 0 of the right command — a pipe.\n- `\u003c file` feeds `file` into stdin.\n- `\u003c\u003c EOF` is a here-doc (multi-line literal input); `\u003c\u003c\u003c \"str\"` is a here-string (single string fed as stdin).\n- `/dev/null` is a special \"discard\" file. Writes vanish; reads return immediately at end-of-file. The idiom `cmd \u003e /dev/null 2\u003e&1` silences everything a command emits."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Your script writes a result to stdout and a warning to stderr. You want the result captured to `out.txt` but the warning still visible on screen. Which operator do you use?","a":"`cmd \u003e out.txt`. That redirects stdout only. Stderr was never touched, so it stays on the terminal. If you'd written `cmd &\u003e out.txt`, both streams would go to the file and you'd see nothing on screen."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003e&gt;\u003c/code\u003e is silent. There&#39;s no &quot;are you sure?&quot; prompt, no backup, no warning if \u003ccode\u003eout.txt\u003c/code\u003e already had content. The truncation happens at parse time, so even if your command exits with an error one nanosecond later, the old contents are already gone. If you want the shell to refuse to clobber an existing file, run \u003ccode\u003eset -o noclobber\u003c/code\u003e (or \u003ccode\u003eset -C\u003c/code\u003e); to override that protection on one specific line, write \u003ccode\u003e&gt;|\u003c/code\u003e instead of \u003ccode\u003e&gt;\u003c/code\u003e. Midterm Q43 and Q44 both bait the assumption that \u003ccode\u003e&gt;\u003c/code\u003e is safe.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Why \u003ccode\u003e2&gt;&amp;1\u003c/code\u003e placement is the whole trick","text":"Why `2\u003e&1` placement is the whole trick"},{"kind":"p","html":"This is the single highest-yield trap on the midterm, so it&#39;s worth slowing down. Take this command, where file \u003ccode\u003ex\u003c/code\u003e doesn&#39;t exist and file \u003ccode\u003ey\u003c/code\u003e does:","text":"This is the single highest-yield trap on the midterm, so it's worth slowing down. Take this command, where file `x` doesn't exist and file `y` does:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"cat x y \u003e hold 2\u003e&1"},{"kind":"p","html":"What ends up in \u003ccode\u003ehold\u003c/code\u003e? Predict before reading on.","text":"What ends up in `hold`? Predict before reading on."},{"kind":"p","html":"The shell processes redirections strictly left to right. It walks the line in order:","text":"The shell processes redirections strictly left to right. It walks the line in order:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&gt; hold\u003c/code\u003e — point fd 1 at the file \u003ccode\u003ehold\u003c/code\u003e. Stdout now goes to the file.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e2&gt;&amp;1\u003c/code\u003e — duplicate fd 2 onto whatever fd 1 currently points to. Fd 1 currently points to \u003ccode\u003ehold\u003c/code\u003e, so fd 2 now also points to \u003ccode\u003ehold\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. `\u003e hold` — point fd 1 at the file `hold`. Stdout now goes to the file.\n2. `2\u003e&1` — duplicate fd 2 onto whatever fd 1 currently points to. Fd 1 currently points to `hold`, so fd 2 now also points to `hold`."},{"kind":"p","html":"Both streams land in the file. When \u003ccode\u003ecat\u003c/code\u003e runs, the &quot;No such file or directory&quot; error from \u003ccode\u003ex\u003c/code\u003e and the contents of \u003ccode\u003ey\u003c/code\u003e both end up in \u003ccode\u003ehold\u003c/code\u003e, in the order they were emitted.","text":"Both streams land in the file. When `cat` runs, the \"No such file or directory\" error from `x` and the contents of `y` both end up in `hold`, in the order they were emitted."},{"kind":"p","html":"Now flip the order:","text":"Now flip the order:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"cat x y 2\u003e&1 \u003e hold"},{"kind":"p","html":"Same operators, different order. The shell walks left to right again:","text":"Same operators, different order. The shell walks left to right again:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e2&gt;&amp;1\u003c/code\u003e — duplicate fd 2 onto whatever fd 1 currently points to. Fd 1 is \u003cem\u003estill pointing at the terminal\u003c/em\u003e at this moment, because we haven&#39;t redirected it yet. So fd 2 now also points to the terminal.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&gt; hold\u003c/code\u003e — point fd 1 at \u003ccode\u003ehold\u003c/code\u003e. But fd 2 was already wired up in step 1; this redirection only moves fd 1.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. `2\u003e&1` — duplicate fd 2 onto whatever fd 1 currently points to. Fd 1 is *still pointing at the terminal* at this moment, because we haven't redirected it yet. So fd 2 now also points to the terminal.\n2. `\u003e hold` — point fd 1 at `hold`. But fd 2 was already wired up in step 1; this redirection only moves fd 1."},{"kind":"p","html":"Result: stdout goes to \u003ccode\u003ehold\u003c/code\u003e, but stderr is stuck on the terminal. The streams \u003cem\u003esplit\u003c/em\u003e, which is almost never what you want.","text":"Result: stdout goes to `hold`, but stderr is stuck on the terminal. The streams *split*, which is almost never what you want."},{"kind":"p","html":"The mental model is simple once it clicks: \u003ccode\u003e2&gt;&amp;1\u003c/code\u003e doesn&#39;t say &quot;merge stderr with stdout forever.&quot; It says &quot;copy stderr&#39;s wiring to match stdout&#39;s wiring \u003cem\u003eas of this moment\u003c/em\u003e.&quot; So you have to set up stdout&#39;s destination first, then duplicate.","text":"The mental model is simple once it clicks: `2\u003e&1` doesn't say \"merge stderr with stdout forever.\" It says \"copy stderr's wiring to match stdout's wiring *as of this moment*.\" So you have to set up stdout's destination first, then duplicate."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A script does `myprog 2\u003e&1 \u003e log.txt` and you're surprised that errors still print to your terminal. What's wrong, and how do you fix it?","a":"The `2\u003e&1` ran first, when stdout was still the terminal — so stderr was duplicated onto the terminal. Then `\u003e log.txt` moved stdout (only) to the file. Swap the order: `myprog \u003e log.txt 2\u003e&1`. Now stdout goes to `log.txt` first, and `2\u003e&1` copies that wiring onto stderr."},{"kind":"diagram","title":null,"svg":"\u003csvg viewBox=\"0 0 720 320\" preserveAspectRatio=\"xMidYMid meet\"\u003e\u003cdefs\u003e\u003cmarker id=\"arrRD\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"9\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"6\" markerHeight=\"6\" orient=\"auto\"\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M0 0 L10 5 L0 10 Z\" fill=\"#a3a3a3\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003c/marker\u003e\u003c/defs\u003e\u003ctext x=\"20\" y=\"22\" class=\"label-accent\"\u003eOrder matters — shell processes redirections left-to-right\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"20\" y=\"40\" width=\"320\" height=\"240\" class=\"box-ok\" rx=\"6\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"180\" y=\"62\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eRIGHT: cmd &gt; hold 2&gt;&amp;1\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"180\" y=\"86\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003estep 1 — &gt; hold\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"40\" y=\"100\" width=\"60\" height=\"30\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"70\" y=\"120\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003estdout\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M100 115 L200 115\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrRD)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003crect x=\"200\" y=\"100\" width=\"120\" height=\"30\" class=\"box\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"260\" y=\"120\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003ehold (file)\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"40\" y=\"140\" width=\"60\" height=\"30\" class=\"box-bad\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"70\" y=\"160\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003estderr\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M100 155 L200 155\" class=\"arrow-line dashed\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003crect x=\"200\" y=\"140\" width=\"120\" height=\"30\" class=\"box-warn\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"260\" y=\"160\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eterminal (still)\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"180\" y=\"195\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003estep 2 — 2&gt;&amp;1 copies CURRENT stdout target\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"40\" y=\"210\" width=\"60\" height=\"30\" class=\"box-bad\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"70\" y=\"230\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003estderr\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M100 225 L200 225\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrRD)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003crect x=\"200\" y=\"210\" width=\"120\" height=\"30\" class=\"box\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"260\" y=\"230\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003ehold (file)\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"180\" y=\"265\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eboth streams land in hold ✓\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"380\" y=\"40\" width=\"320\" height=\"240\" class=\"box-bad\" rx=\"6\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"540\" y=\"62\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eWRONG: cmd 2&gt;&amp;1 &gt; hold\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"540\" y=\"86\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003estep 1 — 2&gt;&amp;1 copies CURRENT stdout (terminal)\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"400\" y=\"100\" width=\"60\" height=\"30\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"430\" y=\"120\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003estdout\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M460 115 L560 115\" class=\"arrow-line dashed\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003crect x=\"560\" y=\"100\" width=\"120\" height=\"30\" class=\"box-warn\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"620\" y=\"120\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eterminal\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"400\" y=\"140\" width=\"60\" height=\"30\" class=\"box-bad\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"430\" y=\"160\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003estderr\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M460 155 L560 155\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrRD)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003crect x=\"560\" y=\"140\" width=\"120\" height=\"30\" class=\"box-warn\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"620\" y=\"160\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eterminal (stuck)\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"540\" y=\"195\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003estep 2 — &gt; hold redirects stdout only\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"400\" y=\"210\" width=\"60\" height=\"30\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"430\" y=\"230\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003estdout\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M460 225 L560 225\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrRD)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003crect x=\"560\" y=\"210\" width=\"120\" height=\"30\" class=\"box\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"620\" y=\"230\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003ehold (file)\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"540\" y=\"265\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003estderr STILL on terminal — split! ✗\u003c/text\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e","legend":null},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e A pipe (\u003ccode\u003e|\u003c/code\u003e) only carries stdout. If you write \u003ccode\u003ecmd | grep error\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003ecmd\u003c/code\u003e writes its errors to stderr, \u003ccode\u003egrep\u003c/code\u003e will never see them — they bypass the pipe and print on your terminal. To fold stderr into the pipe, write \u003ccode\u003ecmd 2&gt;&amp;1 | grep error\u003c/code\u003e. Note that here the \u003ccode\u003e2&gt;&amp;1\u003c/code\u003e \u003cem\u003ebelongs\u003c/em\u003e before the pipe, because the pipe sets up stdout&#39;s destination earlier in the parsing.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"h3","html":"\u003ccode\u003etee\u003c/code\u003e: when you want to watch \u003cem\u003eand\u003c/em\u003e save","text":"`tee`: when you want to watch *and* save"},{"kind":"p","html":"Sometimes you need a stream to do two things at once — go to a file \u003cem\u003eand\u003c/em\u003e keep flowing down a pipe so the next command can process it. The plumbing analogy is a T-shaped fitting: one input pipe, two outputs. The Unix command is named after the fitting.","text":"Sometimes you need a stream to do two things at once — go to a file *and* keep flowing down a pipe so the next command can process it. The plumbing analogy is a T-shaped fitting: one input pipe, two outputs. The Unix command is named after the fitting."},{"kind":"code","lang":"console","code":"$ ls /etc | tee etc-list.txt | wc -l\n213\n\n$ head -3 etc-list.txt\nalternatives\nbash.bashrc\ncrontab"},{"kind":"p","html":"Read the pipeline left to right. \u003ccode\u003els /etc\u003c/code\u003e writes filenames to its stdout. \u003ccode\u003etee etc-list.txt\u003c/code\u003e reads them on its stdin, writes them to \u003ccode\u003eetc-list.txt\u003c/code\u003e, \u003cem\u003eand\u003c/em\u003e re-emits them on its own stdout. \u003ccode\u003ewc -l\u003c/code\u003e reads that stream and counts the lines (213). After the pipeline finishes, you have both the count on screen and the full list saved on disk. Use \u003ccode\u003etee -a file\u003c/code\u003e if you want to append rather than overwrite, exactly like \u003ccode\u003e&gt;&gt;\u003c/code\u003e versus \u003ccode\u003e&gt;\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Read the pipeline left to right. `ls /etc` writes filenames to its stdout. `tee etc-list.txt` reads them on its stdin, writes them to `etc-list.txt`, *and* re-emits them on its own stdout. `wc -l` reads that stream and counts the lines (213). After the pipeline finishes, you have both the count on screen and the full list saved on disk. Use `tee -a file` if you want to append rather than overwrite, exactly like `\u003e\u003e` versus `\u003e`."},{"kind":"diagram","title":null,"svg":"\u003csvg viewBox=\"0 0 720 220\" preserveAspectRatio=\"xMidYMid meet\"\u003e\u003cdefs\u003e\u003cmarker id=\"arrTEE\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"9\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"6\" markerHeight=\"6\" orient=\"auto\"\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M0 0 L10 5 L0 10 Z\" fill=\"#a3a3a3\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003c/marker\u003e\u003c/defs\u003e\u003ctext x=\"20\" y=\"22\" class=\"label-accent\"\u003els /etc | tee etc-list.txt | wc -l\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"20\" y=\"80\" width=\"120\" height=\"50\" class=\"box\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"80\" y=\"108\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003els /etc\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M140 105 L240 105\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrTEE)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003ctext x=\"190\" y=\"98\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003estdout\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"240\" y=\"80\" width=\"120\" height=\"50\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"300\" y=\"108\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003etee\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"300\" y=\"124\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eT-fitting\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M360 105 L460 105\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrTEE)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003ctext x=\"410\" y=\"98\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003estdout\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"460\" y=\"80\" width=\"120\" height=\"50\" class=\"box\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"520\" y=\"108\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003ewc -l\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M580 105 L680 105\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrTEE)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003ctext x=\"640\" y=\"98\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e213\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M300 130 L300 170\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrTEE)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003ctext x=\"316\" y=\"155\" class=\"sub\"\u003eduplicate write\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"240\" y=\"170\" width=\"120\" height=\"40\" class=\"box-warn\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"300\" y=\"195\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eetc-list.txt\u003c/text\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e","legend":null},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What's `/dev/null`, and what does `cmd \u003e /dev/null 2\u003e&1` do?","a":"`/dev/null` is a special device file that throws away anything written to it (and returns immediate end-of-file when read). The redirection sends stdout to the bit-bucket, then duplicates that wiring onto stderr — so both streams are silently discarded. The command runs, but you see nothing on your terminal."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e Quoting controls \u003cem\u003ewhat the shell expands\u003c/em\u003e before the command runs — single suppresses everything, double allows \u003ccode\u003e$\u003c/code\u003e and friends, bare invites all seven expansions. Redirection controls \u003cem\u003ewhere the command&#39;s three file descriptors point\u003c/em\u003e before it launches — and the shell wires them up strictly left to right, which is why \u003ccode\u003e&gt; file 2&gt;&amp;1\u003c/code\u003e captures both streams but \u003ccode\u003e2&gt;&amp;1 &gt; file\u003c/code\u003e splits them. Internalize those two ordering rules and the whole midterm trap family collapses into one idea: the shell does its work \u003cem\u003ebefore\u003c/em\u003e the command sees anything.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"}]},{"n":5,"id":"4915-lesson-bash-scripting-essentials-only-as-deep-as-the-exam-requires","title":"Bash scripting essentials — only as deep as the exam requires","hook":"You will write a small script or function on the exam. This lesson covers only what's actually assessed: script anatomy, special parameters, control flow, and bash function form.","tags":["scripting"],"module":"Bash scripting & regex","source":"Mod09 Ch28; materials/labs/Lab9.pdf; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q59,Q60","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"Here is a bash function. Before you read on, predict what the last line prints.","text":"Here is a bash function. Before you read on, predict what the last line prints."},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"add() {\n    return $(( $1 + $2 ))\n}\nresult=$(add 3 4)\necho \"result=$result\""},{"kind":"p","html":"Most people predict \u003ccode\u003eresult=7\u003c/code\u003e. The actual output is \u003ccode\u003eresult=\u003c/code\u003e — an empty string. \u003ccode\u003e$()\u003c/code\u003e captures \u003cstrong\u003estdout\u003c/strong\u003e. \u003ccode\u003ereturn\u003c/code\u003e sets the \u003cstrong\u003eexit status\u003c/strong\u003e (\u003ccode\u003e$?\u003c/code\u003e), not stdout. The function emitted nothing to stdout, so \u003ccode\u003e$()\u003c/code\u003e captured nothing, and \u003ccode\u003eresult\u003c/code\u003e stayed empty.","text":"Most people predict `result=7`. The actual output is `result=` — an empty string. `$()` captures **stdout**. `return` sets the **exit status** (`$?`), not stdout. The function emitted nothing to stdout, so `$()` captured nothing, and `result` stayed empty."},{"kind":"p","html":"That one gap — between communicating a value and setting an exit code — is the hardest bash function trap on the exam. It falls out of understanding how scripts and functions are actually wired together. That&#39;s what this lesson builds.","text":"That one gap — between communicating a value and setting an exit code — is the hardest bash function trap on the exam. It falls out of understanding how scripts and functions are actually wired together. That's what this lesson builds."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Script anatomy — shebang, arguments, permissions","text":"Script anatomy — shebang, arguments, permissions"},{"kind":"p","html":"Every graded script starts the same way: a shebang line, optional comments, then the body.","text":"Every graded script starts the same way: a shebang line, optional comments, then the body."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003ch4\u003eBuild \u003ccode\u003egreet.sh\u003c/code\u003e from scratch: write → chmod → run → observe args\u003c/h4\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-bash\"\u003e#!/bin/bash\n# greet.sh — greets the caller with two args\necho &quot;Hello $1! You are $2 years old.&quot;\necho &quot;(script name: $0 · total args: $#)&quot;\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eMake it executable, then run it:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-console\"\u003e$ chmod +x greet.sh\n$ ./greet.sh alice 25\nHello alice! You are 25 years old.\n(script name: ./greet.sh · total args: 2)\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eTwo things to notice. \u003ccode\u003e#!/bin/bash\u003c/code\u003e on line 1 — the \u003cstrong\u003eshebang\u003c/strong\u003e — tells the kernel which interpreter to hand this file to when you \u003ccode\u003eexec\u003c/code\u003e it. Without it, the behavior depends on your current shell; the exam counts on it being there, and graded scripts lose marks without it. \u003ccode\u003echmod +x\u003c/code\u003e sets the execute permission bit: without \u003ccode\u003ex\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e./greet.sh\u003c/code\u003e returns &quot;Permission denied.&quot; Invoking via \u003ccode\u003ebash greet.sh alice 25\u003c/code\u003e bypasses the need for \u003ccode\u003ex\u003c/code\u003e because you&#39;re naming the interpreter explicitly, but the \u003ccode\u003e./\u003c/code\u003e form requires the bit.\nSource: Mod09 Ch28 · midterm Q59. Both shebang and comments carry marks on graded scripts.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"#### Build `greet.sh` from scratch: write → chmod → run → observe args\n```bash\n#!/bin/bash\n# greet.sh — greets the caller with two args\necho \"Hello $1! You are $2 years old.\"\necho \"(script name: $0 · total args: $#)\"\n```\nMake it executable, then run it:\n```console\n$ chmod +x greet.sh\n$ ./greet.sh alice 25\nHello alice! You are 25 years old.\n(script name: ./greet.sh · total args: 2)\n```\nTwo things to notice. `#!/bin/bash` on line 1 — the **shebang** — tells the kernel which interpreter to hand this file to when you `exec` it. Without it, the behavior depends on your current shell; the exam counts on it being there, and graded scripts lose marks without it. `chmod +x` sets the execute permission bit: without `x`, `./greet.sh` returns \"Permission denied.\" Invoking via `bash greet.sh alice 25` bypasses the need for `x` because you're naming the interpreter explicitly, but the `./` form requires the bit.\nSource: Mod09 Ch28 · midterm Q59. Both shebang and comments carry marks on graded scripts."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"In `./greet.sh alice 25`, what is `$0` and what is `$#`?","a":"`$0` is `./greet.sh` — the script name exactly as invoked, path included. `$#` is `2` — the count of positional arguments, not counting `$0`. If you invoked the same script as `bash greet.sh alice 25`, then `$0` would be `greet.sh` — it reflects how you called it, not the file's base name alone."},{"kind":"h3","html":"The nine special parameters — what the exam actually tests","text":"The nine special parameters — what the exam actually tests"},{"kind":"p","html":"These nine appear on every assessment. They work identically inside a script and inside a function — the context determines what they resolve to, but the names never change.","text":"These nine appear on every assessment. They work identically inside a script and inside a function — the context determines what they resolve to, but the names never change."},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eParameter\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eResolves to\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e$0\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eScript name / path as invoked\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e$1\u003c/code\u003e … \u003ccode\u003e$9\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePositional arguments 1 through 9\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e${10}\u003c/code\u003e …\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eArguments 10 and up — braces required\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e$#\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCount of positional arguments (not counting \u003ccode\u003e$0\u003c/code\u003e)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&quot;$@&quot;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAll positional args, each as a \u003cstrong\u003eseparate word\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&quot;$*&quot;\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAll positional args \u003cstrong\u003ejoined\u003c/strong\u003e into one IFS-separated string\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e$?\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eExit status of the last command (0 = success, non-zero = error)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e$$\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePID of the current shell\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e$!\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePID of the most recently backgrounded command\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Three of these generate exam errors every semester: \u003ccode\u003e$@\u003c/code\u003e vs \u003ccode\u003e$*\u003c/code\u003e (the classic distinguish), \u003ccode\u003e$?\u003c/code\u003e timing (it&#39;s overwritten after every command), and \u003ccode\u003e${10}\u003c/code\u003e syntax (braces are not optional for double-digit indices). The next two sections drill the first two.","text":"Three of these generate exam errors every semester: `$@` vs `$*` (the classic distinguish), `$?` timing (it's overwritten after every command), and `${10}` syntax (braces are not optional for double-digit indices). The next two sections drill the first two."},{"kind":"h3","html":"\u003ccode\u003e&quot;$@&quot;\u003c/code\u003e vs \u003ccode\u003e&quot;$*&quot;\u003c/code\u003e — the distinction the exam tests","text":"`\"$@\"` vs `\"$*\"` — the distinction the exam tests"},{"kind":"p","html":"The two look the same when no argument contains whitespace. The gap opens the moment one does. This script makes the difference visible:","text":"The two look the same when no argument contains whitespace. The gap opens the moment one does. This script makes the difference visible:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"console","code":"$ cat args.sh\n#!/bin/bash\necho \"count: $#\"\necho 'dollar-at (one per line):'\nfor x in \"$@\"; do echo \"  [$x]\"; done\necho 'dollar-star (one per line):'\nfor x in \"$*\"; do echo \"  [$x]\"; done\n\n$ ./args.sh \"hello world\" foo bar\ncount: 3\ndollar-at (one per line):\n  [hello world]\n  [foo]\n  [bar]\ndollar-star (one per line):\n  [hello world foo bar]"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003e&quot;$@&quot;\u003c/code\u003e preserved three separate arguments — three loop iterations, with \u003ccode\u003ehello world\u003c/code\u003e intact as one word. \u003ccode\u003e&quot;$*&quot;\u003c/code\u003e joined them all into one IFS-separated string — one iteration, the space inside \u003ccode\u003ehello world\u003c/code\u003e now indistinguishable from the separator between arguments.","text":"`\"$@\"` preserved three separate arguments — three loop iterations, with `hello world` intact as one word. `\"$*\"` joined them all into one IFS-separated string — one iteration, the space inside `hello world` now indistinguishable from the separator between arguments."},{"kind":"p","html":"The rule: \u003cstrong\u003ealways use \u003ccode\u003e&quot;$@&quot;\u003c/code\u003e unless you explicitly want a single joined string.\u003c/strong\u003e Anywhere you&#39;re forwarding arguments to another command or iterating over them, \u003ccode\u003e&quot;$*&quot;\u003c/code\u003e will silently break when a user passes a filename with a space in it.","text":"The rule: **always use `\"$@\"` unless you explicitly want a single joined string.** Anywhere you're forwarding arguments to another command or iterating over them, `\"$*\"` will silently break when a user passes a filename with a space in it."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You want a bash function to forward all its arguments to `grep`, preserving any argument that contains spaces. Which do you use — `\"$@\"` or `\"$*\"`?","a":"`\"$@\"`. It passes each argument as a separate word, so `\"hello world\"` arrives at `grep` as one two-word argument. `\"$*\"` joins everything into a single string first, which breaks argument parsing the moment any arg contains whitespace. Midterm Q60 is exactly this distinction, applied inside a function body."},{"kind":"h3","html":"\u003ccode\u003e$?\u003c/code\u003e — read it immediately or lose it","text":"`$?` — read it immediately or lose it"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003e$?\u003c/code\u003e holds the exit status of the last command. Zero means success; any non-zero value signals an error (the specific number is program-defined, but 0/non-zero is what you test in scripts).","text":"`$?` holds the exit status of the last command. Zero means success; any non-zero value signals an error (the specific number is program-defined, but 0/non-zero is what you test in scripts)."},{"kind":"code","lang":"console","code":"$ ls greet.sh; echo \"exit=$?\"\ngreet.sh\nexit=0\n\n$ ls nothing.xyz; echo \"exit=$?\"\nls: cannot access 'nothing.xyz': No such file or directory\nexit=2"},{"kind":"p","html":"The mechanic that trips people up: \u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003e$?\u003c/code\u003e is overwritten by every command.\u003c/strong\u003e Run one more command before reading \u003ccode\u003e$?\u003c/code\u003e and you get the new command&#39;s status, not the one you intended to check. If you need to act on an exit status more than one line later, capture it immediately: \u003ccode\u003estatus=$?\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"The mechanic that trips people up: **`$?` is overwritten by every command.** Run one more command before reading `$?` and you get the new command's status, not the one you intended to check. If you need to act on an exit status more than one line later, capture it immediately: `status=$?`."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Which special parameter holds the PID of the most recently backgrounded command?","a":"`$!`. Don't confuse it with `$$` (the current shell's own PID) or `$?` (last exit status). `$!` is useful when you background a long job and want to `wait` on it explicitly later, or send it a signal with `kill`."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Control flow and test operators","text":"Control flow and test operators"},{"kind":"p","html":"The four constructs the exam uses:","text":"The four constructs the exam uses:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"if [ -f file ]; then echo yes; else echo no; fi\nfor i in 1 2 3; do echo $i; done\nwhile read line; do echo \"$line\"; done \u003c input.txt\ncase \"$1\" in start) ... ;; stop) ... ;; *) ... ;; esac"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003e[ … ]\u003c/code\u003e construct (also callable as \u003ccode\u003etest\u003c/code\u003e) evaluates a condition and sets \u003ccode\u003e$?\u003c/code\u003e. Know these three groups of operators:","text":"The `[ … ]` construct (also callable as `test`) evaluates a condition and sets `$?`. Know these three groups of operators:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eFile tests:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003e-e\u003c/code\u003e exists · \u003ccode\u003e-f\u003c/code\u003e regular file · \u003ccode\u003e-d\u003c/code\u003e directory · \u003ccode\u003e-r/-w/-x\u003c/code\u003e readable/writable/executable · \u003ccode\u003e-s\u003c/code\u003e non-empty","text":"**File tests:** `-e` exists · `-f` regular file · `-d` directory · `-r/-w/-x` readable/writable/executable · `-s` non-empty"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eNumeric comparison:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003e-eq\u003c/code\u003e \u003ccode\u003e-ne\u003c/code\u003e \u003ccode\u003e-lt\u003c/code\u003e \u003ccode\u003e-le\u003c/code\u003e \u003ccode\u003e-gt\u003c/code\u003e \u003ccode\u003e-ge\u003c/code\u003e","text":"**Numeric comparison:** `-eq` `-ne` `-lt` `-le` `-gt` `-ge`"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eString comparison:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003e=\u003c/code\u003e equal · \u003ccode\u003e!=\u003c/code\u003e not equal · \u003ccode\u003e-z\u003c/code\u003e empty string · \u003ccode\u003e-n\u003c/code\u003e non-empty string","text":"**String comparison:** `=` equal · `!=` not equal · `-z` empty string · `-n` non-empty string"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Functions in bash","text":"Functions in bash"},{"kind":"p","html":"Bash function syntax: \u003ccode\u003ename() { body; }\u003c/code\u003e. There is no formal parameter list in the definition — arguments arrive through the same special parameters as a script.","text":"Bash function syntax: `name() { body; }`. There is no formal parameter list in the definition — arguments arrive through the same special parameters as a script."},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"upper() {\n    echo \"$1\" | tr 'a-z' 'A-Z'\n}\n\nupper hello    # prints: HELLO"},{"kind":"p","html":"Two mechanics you must have cold before the exam.","text":"Two mechanics you must have cold before the exam."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eMechanic 1 — no declared parameters.\u003c/strong\u003e The definition is \u003ccode\u003eupper() { … }\u003c/code\u003e, not \u003ccode\u003eupper(str)\u003c/code\u003e. You read arguments from \u003ccode\u003e$1\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e$2\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e&quot;$@&quot;\u003c/code\u003e inside the body. This is identical to how a script accesses its own arguments — which is why the nine special parameters cover both cases.","text":"**Mechanic 1 — no declared parameters.** The definition is `upper() { … }`, not `upper(str)`. You read arguments from `$1`, `$2`, `\"$@\"` inside the body. This is identical to how a script accesses its own arguments — which is why the nine special parameters cover both cases."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eMechanic 2 — \u003ccode\u003ereturn\u003c/code\u003e sets exit status, not a value.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003ereturn N\u003c/code\u003e sets \u003ccode\u003e$?\u003c/code\u003e to N (valid range 0–255) and does nothing else. To hand a computed value back to the caller, \u003ccode\u003eecho\u003c/code\u003e it and capture the output with \u003ccode\u003e$(…)\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"**Mechanic 2 — `return` sets exit status, not a value.** `return N` sets `$?` to N (valid range 0–255) and does nothing else. To hand a computed value back to the caller, `echo` it and capture the output with `$(…)`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"add() {\n    echo $(( $1 + $2 ))    # write the result to stdout\n}\n\nresult=$(add 3 4)          # $() captures stdout → result=\"7\"\necho $result               # prints: 7"},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"flowchart LR\n  A[\"caller:\\nresult=\\$(add 3 4)\"] --\u003e B[\"fork/exec\\nadd() body runs\"]\n  B --\u003e C[\"echo \\$(( 3 + 4 ))\\nwrites '7' to stdout\"]\n  C --\u003e D[\"\\$(...) captures stdout\\nresult='7'\"]\n  D --\u003e E[\"caller continues\\necho \\$result → 7\"]\n  classDef fn fill:#1a2a1a,stroke:#9ece6a,color:#e5e5e5\n  classDef cap fill:#1a1a2a,stroke:#7aa2f7,color:#e5e5e5\n  class B,C fn\n  class A,D,E cap"},{"kind":"p","html":"Inside a function, \u003ccode\u003e$0\u003c/code\u003e remains the \u003cem\u003escript\u003c/em\u003e name — not the function name — and \u003ccode\u003e$#\u003c/code\u003e counts the function&#39;s own arguments, not the script&#39;s.","text":"Inside a function, `$0` remains the *script* name — not the function name — and `$#` counts the function's own arguments, not the script's."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You write `add() { return $(( $1 + $2 )); }` and then `result=$(add 3 4); echo $result`. What prints?","a":"Nothing — `result` is empty. `return` only sets `$?`; it writes nothing to stdout. `$()` captures stdout, which is empty, so `result` gets the empty string. To get `7` into `result`, replace `return` with `echo` inside the function body."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Inside a function `foo()`, what does `$#` refer to — the script's argument count or `foo`'s?","a":"`foo`'s own argument count. Special parameters inside a function reflect that function's call context, not the outer script's. If the script was invoked with three args but you called `foo a b`, then inside `foo`, `$#` is `2`."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eOmitting quotes around \u003ccode\u003e&quot;$@&quot;\u003c/code\u003e silently splits any argument that contains whitespace into separate tokens. \u003ccode\u003efor x in $@\u003c/code\u003e (unquoted) with one argument \u003ccode\u003e&quot;hello world&quot;\u003c/code\u003e loops twice — \u003ccode\u003ehello\u003c/code\u003e, then \u003ccode\u003eworld\u003c/code\u003e — not once. The quoted form \u003ccode\u003e&quot;$@&quot;\u003c/code\u003e is correct in essentially every case; the unquoted form is a bug that hides until a filename with a space appears.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Omitting quotes around `\"$@\"` silently splits any argument that contains whitespace into separate tokens. `for x in $@` (unquoted) with one argument `\"hello world\"` loops twice — `hello`, then `world` — not once. The quoted form `\"$@\"` is correct in essentially every case; the unquoted form is a bug that hides until a filename with a space appears."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eBash scripting on the exam comes down to three things: the nine special parameters (\u003ccode\u003e$0\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e$1\u003c/code\u003e–\u003ccode\u003e$9\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e${10}+\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e$#\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e&quot;$@&quot;\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e&quot;$*&quot;\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e$?\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e$$\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e$!\u003c/code\u003e), the function form \u003ccode\u003ename() { body; }\u003c/code\u003e where arguments arrive through those same parameters, and the \u003ccode\u003ereturn\u003c/code\u003e/\u003ccode\u003eecho\u003c/code\u003e distinction — \u003ccode\u003ereturn N\u003c/code\u003e sets \u003ccode\u003e$?\u003c/code\u003e only; values travel via stdout captured with \u003ccode\u003e$(…)\u003c/code\u003e. Quote \u003ccode\u003e&quot;$@&quot;\u003c/code\u003e every time you forward or iterate arguments, and read \u003ccode\u003e$?\u003c/code\u003e before the next command overwrites it.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Bash scripting on the exam comes down to three things: the nine special parameters (`$0`, `$1`–`$9`, `${10}+`, `$#`, `\"$@\"`, `\"$*\"`, `$?`, `$$`, `$!`), the function form `name() { body; }` where arguments arrive through those same parameters, and the `return`/`echo` distinction — `return N` sets `$?` only; values travel via stdout captured with `$(…)`. Quote `\"$@\"` every time you forward or iterate arguments, and read `$?` before the next command overwrites it."}]},{"n":6,"id":"4915-lesson-system-admin-boot-runlevels-users","title":"System admin: boot, runlevels, users","hook":"Short lesson, high MCQ density.","tags":["boot"],"module":"Package management & boot","source":"Mod05 Ch10-11; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q16, Q35","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"You log into a remote server and run \u003ccode\u003erunlevel\u003c/code\u003e. It prints \u003ccode\u003e3\u003c/code\u003e. A junior admin says: \u003cem\u003e&quot;Runlevel 3 means networking is disabled — you&#39;ll need to go to runlevel 5 before you can SSH in.&quot;\u003c/em\u003e","text":"You log into a remote server and run `runlevel`. It prints `3`. A junior admin says: *\"Runlevel 3 means networking is disabled — you'll need to go to runlevel 5 before you can SSH in.\"*"},{"kind":"p","html":"Something in that statement is wrong. Before reading further, identify the error. One sentence is enough — hold your answer until the run-level section reveals it.","text":"Something in that statement is wrong. Before reading further, identify the error. One sentence is enough — hold your answer until the run-level section reveals it."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The boot chain: seven handoffs","text":"The boot chain: seven handoffs"},{"kind":"p","html":"The boot process is not one program doing everything. It is a chain of seven distinct programs, each doing a narrow job and then passing control to the next. Learning who does what collapses every boot-related MCQ into a lookup.","text":"The boot process is not one program doing everything. It is a chain of seven distinct programs, each doing a narrow job and then passing control to the next. Learning who does what collapses every boot-related MCQ into a lookup."},{"kind":"h3","html":"1. BIOS / UEFI","text":"1. BIOS / UEFI"},{"kind":"p","html":"Firmware burned into the motherboard — runs before any OS code. Its sole job: run a power-on self-test (POST), locate a bootable device, load the first 512-byte sector of that device (the \u003cstrong\u003eMBR\u003c/strong\u003e, Master Boot Record) into RAM, and jump to it.","text":"Firmware burned into the motherboard — runs before any OS code. Its sole job: run a power-on self-test (POST), locate a bootable device, load the first 512-byte sector of that device (the **MBR**, Master Boot Record) into RAM, and jump to it."},{"kind":"h3","html":"2. Bootloader (GRUB)","text":"2. Bootloader (GRUB)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Lives in the MBR and in a small partition. Presents a boot menu, reads \u003ccode\u003e/boot/grub2/grub.cfg\u003c/code\u003e, loads the compressed kernel image (\u003ccode\u003e/boot/vmlinuz-*\u003c/code\u003e) plus an initial RAM disk (\u003ccode\u003einitramfs\u003c/code\u003e) into memory, then hands control to the kernel entry point.","text":"Lives in the MBR and in a small partition. Presents a boot menu, reads `/boot/grub2/grub.cfg`, loads the compressed kernel image (`/boot/vmlinuz-*`) plus an initial RAM disk (`initramfs`) into memory, then hands control to the kernel entry point."},{"kind":"h3","html":"3. Kernel","text":"3. Kernel"},{"kind":"p","html":"Decompresses itself, initializes the CPU, memory controller, and storage drivers, mounts the root filesystem \u003cstrong\u003eread-only\u003c/strong\u003e (so \u003ccode\u003efsck\u003c/code\u003e can safely check it), then starts exactly one process — \u003cstrong\u003ePID 1\u003c/strong\u003e — and waits.","text":"Decompresses itself, initializes the CPU, memory controller, and storage drivers, mounts the root filesystem **read-only** (so `fsck` can safely check it), then starts exactly one process — **PID 1** — and waits."},{"kind":"h3","html":"4. init / systemd (PID 1)","text":"4. init / systemd (PID 1)"},{"kind":"p","html":"On modern Fedora/RHEL this is \u003cstrong\u003esystemd\u003c/strong\u003e; on older SysV systems it was \u003ccode\u003e/sbin/init\u003c/code\u003e. Either way, this process is the ancestor of every other process on the machine. It reads its configuration and decides which run level (SysV) or target unit (systemd) to reach.","text":"On modern Fedora/RHEL this is **systemd**; on older SysV systems it was `/sbin/init`. Either way, this process is the ancestor of every other process on the machine. It reads its configuration and decides which run level (SysV) or target unit (systemd) to reach."},{"kind":"h3","html":"5. rc.sysinit","text":"5. rc.sysinit"},{"kind":"p","html":"The run-level-\u003cstrong\u003eindependent\u003c/strong\u003e setup script — runs before any run-level-specific work. It mounts \u003ccode\u003e/proc\u003c/code\u003e (the kernel&#39;s virtual filesystem for process info), activates swap, runs \u003ccode\u003efsck\u003c/code\u003e on filesystems in \u003ccode\u003e/etc/fstab\u003c/code\u003e, mounts those filesystems read-write, and enables disk quotas. Every boot goes through \u003ccode\u003erc.sysinit\u003c/code\u003e regardless of target run level.","text":"The run-level-**independent** setup script — runs before any run-level-specific work. It mounts `/proc` (the kernel's virtual filesystem for process info), activates swap, runs `fsck` on filesystems in `/etc/fstab`, mounts those filesystems read-write, and enables disk quotas. Every boot goes through `rc.sysinit` regardless of target run level."},{"kind":"h3","html":"6. rc N","text":"6. rc N"},{"kind":"p","html":"Run-level-\u003cstrong\u003especific\u003c/strong\u003e. For whatever run level N was chosen, init looks inside \u003ccode\u003e/etc/rc.d/rcN.d/\u003c/code\u003e. That directory contains symlinks to service scripts in \u003ccode\u003e/etc/rc.d/init.d/\u003c/code\u003e. Scripts whose names start with \u003ccode\u003eK\u003c/code\u003e (kill) run first in numeric order to stop services that don&#39;t belong at this level; scripts starting with \u003ccode\u003eS\u003c/code\u003e (start) run next to bring up services that do. The two-digit number is the priority: \u003ccode\u003eK05innd\u003c/code\u003e stops before \u003ccode\u003eK10ntpd\u003c/code\u003e; \u003ccode\u003eS10network\u003c/code\u003e starts before \u003ccode\u003eS55sshd\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Run-level-**specific**. For whatever run level N was chosen, init looks inside `/etc/rc.d/rcN.d/`. That directory contains symlinks to service scripts in `/etc/rc.d/init.d/`. Scripts whose names start with `K` (kill) run first in numeric order to stop services that don't belong at this level; scripts starting with `S` (start) run next to bring up services that do. The two-digit number is the priority: `K05innd` stops before `K10ntpd`; `S10network` starts before `S55sshd`."},{"kind":"h3","html":"7. Login prompt","text":"7. Login prompt"},{"kind":"p","html":"A graphical display manager (\u003ccode\u003egdm\u003c/code\u003e) for run level 5, or a text \u003ccode\u003etty\u003c/code\u003e for run level 3.","text":"A graphical display manager (`gdm`) for run level 5, or a text `tty` for run level 3."},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"flowchart LR\n  BIOS[\"BIOS\u003cbr/\u003ePOST\u003cbr/\u003efind boot dev\"] --\u003e GRUB[\"MBR/GRUB\u003cbr/\u003ebootloader\u003cbr/\u003epick kernel\"]\n  GRUB --\u003e KERNEL[\"kernel\u003cbr/\u003einit hardware\u003cbr/\u003emount root RO\"]\n  KERNEL --\u003e INIT[\"init / systemd\u003cbr/\u003ePID 1\"]\n  INIT --\u003e RCSYS[\"rc.sysinit\u003cbr/\u003emount /proc, swap\u003cbr/\u003efsck, fstab\"]\n  RCSYS --\u003e RCN[\"rc N\u003cbr/\u003e/etc/rc.d/rcN.d\u003cbr/\u003eK* stop → S* start\"]\n  RCN --\u003e LOGIN[\"login\u003cbr/\u003egdm or tty\"]\n  classDef boot fill:#181822,stroke:#7aa2f7,color:#e5e5e5\n  classDef sys fill:#181a18,stroke:#9ece6a,color:#e5e5e5\n  class BIOS,GRUB,KERNEL boot\n  class INIT,RCSYS,RCN,LOGIN sys"},{"kind":"p","html":"Blue = firmware and kernel stages (no processes yet). Green = init and userland stages (PID 1 is running). The kernel-to-init handoff is the moment the machine becomes a running OS.","text":"Blue = firmware and kernel stages (no processes yet). Green = init and userland stages (PID 1 is running). The kernel-to-init handoff is the moment the machine becomes a running OS."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What is the difference between rc.sysinit and rc N in the boot sequence?","a":"`rc.sysinit` runs first and does work independent of which run level you're booting into: mounting `/proc`, activating swap, running `fsck`, mounting filesystems. `rc N` runs second and is run-level-specific: it reads `/etc/rc.d/rcN.d/` and starts or stops services for the requested level. Every boot goes through `rc.sysinit`; the particular `rc N` depends on the target."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Run levels","text":"Run levels"},{"kind":"p","html":"Back to the opening error. Runlevel 3 is \u003cstrong\u003emulti-user, text mode, with full services and full networking\u003c/strong\u003e. The junior admin confused it with runlevel 2, which is multi-user \u003cem\u003ewithout\u003c/em\u003e networking. A server at runlevel 3 is the standard headless production state — SSH works, services are running, no GUI. Runlevel 5 adds the graphical login screen; it does not add networking.","text":"Back to the opening error. Runlevel 3 is **multi-user, text mode, with full services and full networking**. The junior admin confused it with runlevel 2, which is multi-user *without* networking. A server at runlevel 3 is the standard headless production state — SSH works, services are running, no GUI. Runlevel 5 adds the graphical login screen; it does not add networking."},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"flowchart LR\n  subgraph RL[\"System V run levels — MEMORIZE (exam-tested)\"]\n    direction LR\n    L0[\"0\u003cbr/\u003ehalt\u003cbr/\u003epower off\"]\n    L1[\"1\u003cbr/\u003esingle user\u003cbr/\u003erescue / root\"]\n    L2[\"2\u003cbr/\u003emulti NO net\u003cbr/\u003eminimal\"]\n    L3[\"3\u003cbr/\u003emulti TEXT\u003cbr/\u003efull svcs, no GUI\"]\n    L4[\"4\u003cbr/\u003eunused\u003cbr/\u003ecustom\"]\n    L5[\"5\u003cbr/\u003emulti + GUI\u003cbr/\u003eX11 / GDM\"]\n    L6[\"6\u003cbr/\u003ereboot\u003cbr/\u003erestart\"]\n  end\n  classDef halt fill:#201818,stroke:#f7768e,color:#f7768e\n  classDef res fill:#201c15,stroke:#e0af68,color:#e0af68\n  classDef gray fill:#181818,stroke:#737373,color:#a3a3a3\n  classDef good fill:#1a2218,stroke:#9ece6a,color:#9ece6a\n  classDef gui fill:#181822,stroke:#7aa2f7,color:#7aa2f7\n  class L0,L6 halt\n  class L1 res\n  class L2,L4 gray\n  class L3 good\n  class L5 gui"},{"kind":"p","html":"The exam tests levels 1, 3, and 5 almost exclusively. Levels 0 and 6 are transitions (halt, reboot), not stable states. Level 2 is an edge case (networking stripped). Level 4 is unused.","text":"The exam tests levels 1, 3, and 5 almost exclusively. Levels 0 and 6 are transitions (halt, reboot), not stable states. Level 2 is an edge case (networking stripped). Level 4 is unused."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eSwitching run level now (temporary):\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003einit N\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003etelinit N\u003c/code\u003e on SysV; \u003ccode\u003esystemctl isolate multi-user.target\u003c/code\u003e on systemd. The change takes effect immediately and does not survive a reboot.","text":"**Switching run level now (temporary):** `init N` or `telinit N` on SysV; `systemctl isolate multi-user.target` on systemd. The change takes effect immediately and does not survive a reboot."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eSetting the default (permanent):\u003c/strong\u003e On SysV, edit \u003ccode\u003e/etc/inittab\u003c/code\u003e — find the \u003ccode\u003eid:3:initdefault:\u003c/code\u003e line and change the digit. With systemd: \u003ccode\u003esystemctl set-default multi-user.target\u003c/code\u003e (text) or \u003ccode\u003esystemctl set-default graphical.target\u003c/code\u003e (GUI). Check the current default with \u003ccode\u003esystemctl get-default\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"**Setting the default (permanent):** On SysV, edit `/etc/inittab` — find the `id:3:initdefault:` line and change the digit. With systemd: `systemctl set-default multi-user.target` (text) or `systemctl set-default graphical.target` (GUI). Check the current default with `systemctl get-default`."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Your workstation boots to a GUI. You want it to boot permanently to text mode. Which command do you run?","a":"`systemctl set-default multi-user.target`. This writes a symlink that systemd reads on the next boot. By contrast, `systemctl isolate multi-user.target` drops to text mode right now but the change is lost on reboot. An exam question that specifies *permanent* is always asking for `set-default`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Users and auth: two files, one split","text":"Users and auth: two files, one split"},{"kind":"p","html":"Every interactive user account exists in two files. Understanding \u003cem\u003ewhy\u003c/em\u003e there are two makes all their fields obvious rather than memorized.","text":"Every interactive user account exists in two files. Understanding *why* there are two makes all their fields obvious rather than memorized."},{"kind":"p","html":"The original design put password hashes in \u003ccode\u003e/etc/passwd\u003c/code\u003e. That file must be \u003cstrong\u003eworld-readable\u003c/strong\u003e so that programs like \u003ccode\u003els\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eps\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003eid\u003c/code\u003e can translate numeric UIDs into usernames. A world-readable hash file is a brute-force target: anyone with a copy can run an offline dictionary attack. The fix was \u003cstrong\u003eshadow passwords\u003c/strong\u003e: move the hashes into \u003ccode\u003e/etc/shadow\u003c/code\u003e (readable only by root), while leaving the non-sensitive metadata in the world-readable \u003ccode\u003e/etc/passwd\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"The original design put password hashes in `/etc/passwd`. That file must be **world-readable** so that programs like `ls`, `ps`, and `id` can translate numeric UIDs into usernames. A world-readable hash file is a brute-force target: anyone with a copy can run an offline dictionary attack. The fix was **shadow passwords**: move the hashes into `/etc/shadow` (readable only by root), while leaving the non-sensitive metadata in the world-readable `/etc/passwd`."},{"kind":"h3","html":"/etc/passwd — the public record","text":"/etc/passwd — the public record"},{"kind":"p","html":"Seven colon-separated fields per line:","text":"Seven colon-separated fields per line:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"login-name : x : UID : GID : GECOS : home-dir : shell"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eField\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eValue\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eNotes\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003elogin-name\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003ealice\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eThe username\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ex\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003ex\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eLiteral — real hash is in \u003ccode\u003e/etc/shadow\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eUID\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e1001\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRoot = 0; system accounts &lt; 1000; humans ≥ 1000\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eGID\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e1001\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePrimary group; must have a matching entry in \u003ccode\u003e/etc/group\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eGECOS\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAlice Wong\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eFreeform comment — typically the full name\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ehome-dir\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e/home/alice\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAbsolute path to home directory\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eshell\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e/bin/bash\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e/sbin/nologin\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003e/bin/false\u003c/code\u003e blocks interactive login for service accounts\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"code","lang":"console","code":"alice:x:1001:1001:Alice Wong:/home/alice:/bin/bash\ndaemon:x:2:2:Daemon:/sbin:/sbin/nologin"},{"kind":"h3","html":"/etc/shadow — the secret half","text":"/etc/shadow — the secret half"},{"kind":"p","html":"Nine colon-separated fields per line, same user order as \u003ccode\u003e/etc/passwd\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"Nine colon-separated fields per line, same user order as `/etc/passwd`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"login-name : hashed-password : last-change : min : max : warn : inactive : expire : flag"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eField\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eMeaning\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ehashed-password\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSalted hash. \u003ccode\u003e*\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003e!\u003c/code\u003e locks the account (no password login).\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003elast-change\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDays since 1970-01-01 when the password was last changed\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003emin / max\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eMin days before user may change password; max days before they must\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ewarn\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDays before expiry to warn the user\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003einactive / expire\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDays of inactivity post-expiry before account disables; absolute expiry date\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"The file is \u003cstrong\u003eowned by root, mode 0600\u003c/strong\u003e — root-only read/write, no permissions for group or other. The exam asks: which file holds hashes (\u003ccode\u003e/etc/shadow\u003c/code\u003e), and what permissions does it have (\u003ccode\u003e0600\u003c/code\u003e).","text":"The file is **owned by root, mode 0600** — root-only read/write, no permissions for group or other. The exam asks: which file holds hashes (`/etc/shadow`), and what permissions does it have (`0600`)."},{"kind":"h3","html":"umask — computing default permissions","text":"umask — computing default permissions"},{"kind":"p","html":"When a process creates a file, the kernel starts with a \u003cstrong\u003ebase permission\u003c/strong\u003e of \u003ccode\u003e0666\u003c/code\u003e (rw-rw-rw-) for files and \u003ccode\u003e0777\u003c/code\u003e (rwxrwxrwx) for directories, then strips out any bits set in the \u003cstrong\u003eumask\u003c/strong\u003e. The formula: \u003ccode\u003eactual = base AND NOT(umask)\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"When a process creates a file, the kernel starts with a **base permission** of `0666` (rw-rw-rw-) for files and `0777` (rwxrwxrwx) for directories, then strips out any bits set in the **umask**. The formula: `actual = base AND NOT(umask)`."},{"kind":"p","html":"The system-wide default umask is \u003ccode\u003e022\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"The system-wide default umask is `022`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"file:  0666 & ~022  =  0666 & 0755  =  0644   (rw-r--r--)\ndir:   0777 & ~022  =  0777 & 0755  =  0755   (rwxr-xr-x)"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003e022\u003c/code\u003e octal is \u003ccode\u003e000 010 010\u003c/code\u003e in bits — it removes the group-write bit and the other-write bit. Everyone can read what you create; only you can write it.","text":"`022` octal is `000 010 010` in bits — it removes the group-write bit and the other-write bit. Everyone can read what you create; only you can write it."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What mode does `umask 027` produce for a new file? For a new directory?","a":"`file: 0666 & ~027 = 0640` (rw-r-----). `dir: 0777 & ~027 = 0750` (rwxr-x---). Umask `027` is `000 010 111` in bits — it removes group-write, other-read, other-write, and other-execute. Group can read (and execute directories) but not write; others get nothing."},{"kind":"h3","html":"User management commands","text":"User management commands"},{"kind":"code","lang":"console","code":"$ useradd -m alice          # create user, create home dir from /etc/skel\n$ passwd alice              # set password → updates /etc/shadow\n$ chage -l alice            # list password aging info\n$ chage -M 90 alice         # require password change every 90 days\n$ userdel -r alice          # delete user AND remove home directory\n$ chown -R jack /home/jack/candy   # recursively change ownership to jack"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003echown -R\u003c/code\u003e flag is uppercase. \u003ccode\u003echown -r\u003c/code\u003e does not exist — \u003ccode\u003echown\u003c/code\u003e only has \u003ccode\u003e-R\u003c/code\u003e for recursive traversal. Midterm Q16 puts \u003ccode\u003e-r\u003c/code\u003e as a distractor; the correct answer is \u003ccode\u003e-R jack /home/jack/candy\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"The `chown -R` flag is uppercase. `chown -r` does not exist — `chown` only has `-R` for recursive traversal. Midterm Q16 puts `-r` as a distractor; the correct answer is `-R jack /home/jack/candy`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"PAM — changing auth without recompiling","text":"PAM — changing auth without recompiling"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003ePAM\u003c/strong\u003e (Pluggable Authentication Modules) decouples authentication policy from the programs that enforce it. Without PAM, every binary that checks passwords — \u003ccode\u003elogin\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003esshd\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003esudo\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003esu\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003evsftpd\u003c/code\u003e — contains its own auth code. Switching from local passwords to LDAP or Kerberos requires recompiling all of them.","text":"**PAM** (Pluggable Authentication Modules) decouples authentication policy from the programs that enforce it. Without PAM, every binary that checks passwords — `login`, `sshd`, `sudo`, `su`, `vsftpd` — contains its own auth code. Switching from local passwords to LDAP or Kerberos requires recompiling all of them."},{"kind":"p","html":"With PAM, each service has a config file at \u003ccode\u003e/etc/pam.d/&lt;service&gt;\u003c/code\u003e. That file defines a stack of PAM modules to run in sequence. Changing the auth backend means editing a text file. The binary never changes.","text":"With PAM, each service has a config file at `/etc/pam.d/\u003cservice\u003e`. That file defines a stack of PAM modules to run in sequence. Changing the auth backend means editing a text file. The binary never changes."},{"kind":"p","html":"PAM modules fall into four types:","text":"PAM modules fall into four types:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eType\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePurpose\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eauth\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eVerify the user&#39;s identity\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eaccount\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCheck account validity (expired? allowed to log in now?)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003epassword\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eChange credentials\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003esession\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSet up and tear down the session environment (mount home dir, apply resource limits, log activity)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Why does Linux use two files (`/etc/passwd` and `/etc/shadow`) instead of one?","a":"`/etc/passwd` must be world-readable so that any program can translate UIDs to usernames. If it were root-only, commands like `ls -l` and `ps aux` would show only numeric IDs. But storing password hashes in a world-readable file lets any user copy the hashes and attack them offline. Shadow passwords solve this by moving hashes to `/etc/shadow` (mode 0600, root-only), while `/etc/passwd` keeps only the non-sensitive fields that programs legitimately need."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eTwo traps appear on nearly every exam. First, \u003ccode\u003esystemctl isolate multi-user.target\u003c/code\u003e switches run level immediately but does not persist across reboot; \u003ccode\u003esystemctl set-default multi-user.target\u003c/code\u003e makes the change permanent. An exam question specifying \u003cem\u003epermanent default\u003c/em\u003e always wants \u003ccode\u003eset-default\u003c/code\u003e. Second, \u003ccode\u003echown -R\u003c/code\u003e is uppercase. \u003ccode\u003echown -r\u003c/code\u003e is not a valid flag — \u003ccode\u003echown\u003c/code\u003e only has \u003ccode\u003e-R\u003c/code\u003e for recursive. Midterm Q16 puts \u003ccode\u003e-r\u003c/code\u003e as a distractor; the correct answer is \u003ccode\u003e-R jack /home/jack/candy\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Two traps appear on nearly every exam. First, `systemctl isolate multi-user.target` switches run level immediately but does not persist across reboot; `systemctl set-default multi-user.target` makes the change permanent. An exam question specifying *permanent default* always wants `set-default`. Second, `chown -R` is uppercase. `chown -r` is not a valid flag — `chown` only has `-R` for recursive. Midterm Q16 puts `-r` as a distractor; the correct answer is `-R jack /home/jack/candy`."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eBoot is a seven-stage handoff: BIOS → GRUB → kernel → init/systemd (PID 1) → rc.sysinit (run-level-independent setup) → rc N (K* stop, S* start) → login prompt. Run levels encode which services run: 1 is single-user rescue, 3 is full multi-user text (the normal server state, networking included), 5 adds a GUI. User identity lives in \u003ccode\u003e/etc/passwd\u003c/code\u003e (7 fields, world-readable); secrets live in \u003ccode\u003e/etc/shadow\u003c/code\u003e (9 fields, mode 0600). PAM decouples authentication policy from the binaries that enforce it — swap auth backends by editing \u003ccode\u003e/etc/pam.d/&lt;service&gt;\u003c/code\u003e, no recompile needed.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Boot is a seven-stage handoff: BIOS → GRUB → kernel → init/systemd (PID 1) → rc.sysinit (run-level-independent setup) → rc N (K\\* stop, S\\* start) → login prompt. Run levels encode which services run: 1 is single-user rescue, 3 is full multi-user text (the normal server state, networking included), 5 adds a GUI. User identity lives in `/etc/passwd` (7 fields, world-readable); secrets live in `/etc/shadow` (9 fields, mode 0600). PAM decouples authentication policy from the binaries that enforce it — swap auth backends by editing `/etc/pam.d/\u003cservice\u003e`, no recompile needed."}]},{"n":7,"id":"4915-lesson-networking-ssh-ftp","title":"Networking + SSH + FTP","hook":"Networking questions on past exams repeat three core patterns. Learn them once, recognize every variant.","tags":["networking"],"module":"Networking","source":"Mod06 Ch18-19; materials/labs/Lab6.pdf","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"You have to reach a production database through a firewall. Your teammate sends you this:","text":"You have to reach a production database through a firewall. Your teammate sends you this:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"console","code":"$ ssh -L 5432:localhost:5432 ops@jump.prod"},{"kind":"p","html":"It works. Then you try to reach a \u003cem\u003edifferent\u003c/em\u003e database — \u003ccode\u003edb.prod.internal\u003c/code\u003e — on the same network. You swap \u003ccode\u003elocalhost\u003c/code\u003e for \u003ccode\u003edb.prod.internal\u003c/code\u003e in the command. The tunnel opens. The connection times out.","text":"It works. Then you try to reach a *different* database — `db.prod.internal` — on the same network. You swap `localhost` for `db.prod.internal` in the command. The tunnel opens. The connection times out."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003ePause:\u003c/strong\u003e which machine does \u003ccode\u003elocalhost\u003c/code\u003e resolve on in that command — your laptop, or the server? This is not intuition. It has a one-sentence mechanical answer. Hold your prediction; you&#39;ll confirm it at the end of the SSH tunneling section.","text":"**Pause:** which machine does `localhost` resolve on in that command — your laptop, or the server? This is not intuition. It has a one-sentence mechanical answer. Hold your prediction; you'll confirm it at the end of the SSH tunneling section."},{"kind":"p","html":"This lesson covers the three clusters the exam treats together: \u003cstrong\u003ename resolution\u003c/strong\u003e, \u003cstrong\u003eSSH\u003c/strong\u003e (plus key setup and tunneling), and \u003cstrong\u003eFTP active vs. passive\u003c/strong\u003e.","text":"This lesson covers the three clusters the exam treats together: **name resolution**, **SSH** (plus key setup and tunneling), and **FTP active vs. passive**."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Name resolution — \u003ccode\u003e/etc/hosts\u003c/code\u003e first, then DNS","text":"Name resolution — `/etc/hosts` first, then DNS"},{"kind":"p","html":"When you type \u003ccode\u003eping odyssey.scas.bcit.ca\u003c/code\u003e, the OS resolves the name before any packet leaves. The process is always two stages, always in this order:","text":"When you type `ping odyssey.scas.bcit.ca`, the OS resolves the name before any packet leaves. The process is always two stages, always in this order:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eStage 1 — \u003ccode\u003e/etc/hosts\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e (local file, no network)","text":"**Stage 1 — `/etc/hosts`** (local file, no network)"},{"kind":"p","html":"The OS reads this file first. If the name matches, it returns that IP immediately and skips the network entirely. Use it to override names for testing or point lab hostnames at the right machine.","text":"The OS reads this file first. If the name matches, it returns that IP immediately and skips the network entirely. Use it to override names for testing or point lab hostnames at the right machine."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eStage 2 — DNS\u003c/strong\u003e (network)","text":"**Stage 2 — DNS** (network)"},{"kind":"p","html":"If \u003ccode\u003e/etc/hosts\u003c/code\u003e has no match, the OS queries the resolver listed in \u003ccode\u003e/etc/resolv.conf\u003c/code\u003e. That resolver contacts the \u003ccode\u003enamed\u003c/code\u003e daemon (BIND), which performs a recursive lookup and returns an IP. Results are cached for the record&#39;s \u003cstrong\u003eTTL\u003c/strong\u003e (typically ~1 hour).","text":"If `/etc/hosts` has no match, the OS queries the resolver listed in `/etc/resolv.conf`. That resolver contacts the `named` daemon (BIND), which performs a recursive lookup and returns an IP. Results are cached for the record's **TTL** (typically ~1 hour)."},{"kind":"p","html":"The order is controlled by \u003ccode\u003e/etc/nsswitch.conf\u003c/code\u003e. The \u003ccode\u003ehosts:\u003c/code\u003e line reads \u003ccode\u003efiles dns\u003c/code\u003e — files first, DNS second. The exam asks you to name this file and this sequence.","text":"The order is controlled by `/etc/nsswitch.conf`. The `hosts:` line reads `files dns` — files first, DNS second. The exam asks you to name this file and this sequence."},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"flowchart LR\n  A[\"ping odyssey.scas.bcit.ca\"] --\u003e B{\"/etc/hosts\\nmatch?\"}\n  B -- \"yes\" --\u003e C[\"Return IP\\n(no network)\"]\n  B -- \"no\" --\u003e D[\"/etc/resolv.conf\\nresolver address\"]\n  D --\u003e E[\"named (BIND)\"]\n  E --\u003e F[\"DNS hierarchy\"]\n  F --\u003e G[\"IP returned\\ncached for TTL ≈1 hr\"]\n  classDef local fill:#2a3a2a,stroke:#9ece6a,color:#e5e5e5\n  classDef net fill:#1a2a3a,stroke:#7aa2f7,color:#e5e5e5\n  class A,B,C local\n  class D,E,F,G net"},{"kind":"p","html":"Green = local (no network). Blue = DNS (network required).","text":"Green = local (no network). Blue = DNS (network required)."},{"kind":"h3","html":"What &quot;fully-qualified&quot; means","text":"What \"fully-qualified\" means"},{"kind":"p","html":"A \u003cstrong\u003efully-qualified domain name (FQDN)\u003c/strong\u003e traces a host from root to TLD with no ambiguity:","text":"A **fully-qualified domain name (FQDN)** traces a host from root to TLD with no ambiguity:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"odyssey.scas.bcit.ca\n│      │    │   │\nhost   sub  dom TLD"},{"kind":"p","html":"The bare name \u003ccode\u003eodyssey\u003c/code\u003e only works if \u003ccode\u003e/etc/resolv.conf\u003c/code\u003e has a \u003ccode\u003esearch\u003c/code\u003e domain to complete it. Midterm Q30 asks you to recognize an FQDN — look for the full dotted chain including TLD.","text":"The bare name `odyssey` only works if `/etc/resolv.conf` has a `search` domain to complete it. Midterm Q30 asks you to recognize an FQDN — look for the full dotted chain including TLD."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You add `192.168.1.50  staging` to `/etc/hosts`, but `ping staging` still hits the wrong machine. What's wrong and how do you fix it?","a":"Check the `hosts:` line in `/etc/nsswitch.conf`. If it reads `dns files`, DNS wins and your local entry is never used. Change it to `files dns`. After that, any name in `/etc/hosts` takes priority over DNS."},{"kind":"h2","html":"SSH — one encrypted port replaced four cleartext tools","text":"SSH — one encrypted port replaced four cleartext tools"},{"kind":"p","html":"Before SSH, remote access used the &quot;R-commands&quot; and telnet — all transmitted your password and every byte of data as \u003cstrong\u003ecleartext\u003c/strong\u003e that anyone on the network could read.","text":"Before SSH, remote access used the \"R-commands\" and telnet — all transmitted your password and every byte of data as **cleartext** that anyone on the network could read."},{"kind":"p","html":"SSH (port 22) replaced them all with a single encrypted transport:","text":"SSH (port 22) replaced them all with a single encrypted transport:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eOld (cleartext)\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eSSH replacement\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eWhat it does\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003erlogin\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003etelnet\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003essh user@host\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eInteractive encrypted shell\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003ercp\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003escp src user@host:dst\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCopy files, encrypted\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eFTP-style transfer\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003esftp user@host\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eInteractive file transfer, encrypted\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"All three commands (\u003ccode\u003essh\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003escp\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003esftp\u003c/code\u003e) run over the same port 22 connection. Credentials and data are encrypted before leaving your NIC.","text":"All three commands (`ssh`, `scp`, `sftp`) run over the same port 22 connection. Credentials and data are encrypted before leaving your NIC."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A student says their FTP transfer is secure because it requires a password. What's wrong?","a":"FTP sends credentials and data in cleartext — the password appears in plaintext in the TCP stream. Authentication does not imply encryption. Midterm Q1 tests this directly. Use SFTP (port 22) or SCP instead."},{"kind":"h2","html":"SSH keys — three files, two permission checks","text":"SSH keys — three files, two permission checks"},{"kind":"p","html":"Key-based authentication is stronger than passwords: you prove identity by holding a private key whose public counterpart is pre-installed on the server. No credential travels over the network.","text":"Key-based authentication is stronger than passwords: you prove identity by holding a private key whose public counterpart is pre-installed on the server. No credential travels over the network."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eStep 1 — generate a key pair on your machine:\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Step 1 — generate a key pair on your machine:**"},{"kind":"code","lang":"console","code":"$ ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096"},{"kind":"p","html":"This creates two files:","text":"This creates two files:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eFile\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eWho sees it\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eRequired permission\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e~/.ssh/id_rsa\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYou only — never share\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e600\u003c/code\u003e (owner read/write only)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSafe to copy anywhere\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e(no restriction)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eStep 2 — install the public key on the remote host:\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Step 2 — install the public key on the remote host:**"},{"kind":"code","lang":"console","code":"$ ssh-copy-id user@remote"},{"kind":"p","html":"This appends \u003ccode\u003eid_rsa.pub\u003c/code\u003e to \u003ccode\u003e~/.ssh/authorized_keys\u003c/code\u003e on the remote. Two permissions must be exactly right or \u003ccode\u003esshd\u003c/code\u003e silently ignores the key and falls back to password auth — with no error message:","text":"This appends `id_rsa.pub` to `~/.ssh/authorized_keys` on the remote. Two permissions must be exactly right or `sshd` silently ignores the key and falls back to password auth — with no error message:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePath on remote\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eRequired permission\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e~/.ssh/\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e700\u003c/code\u003e (owner only)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e~/.ssh/authorized_keys\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e600\u003c/code\u003e (owner read/write only)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eThe silent failure:\u003c/strong\u003e if permissions are wrong, SSH accepts your password normally but rejects the key with no useful message. This is what Lab 6 tests.","text":"**The silent failure:** if permissions are wrong, SSH accepts your password normally but rejects the key with no useful message. This is what Lab 6 tests."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You ran `ssh-copy-id user@remote` and key auth still prompts for a password. Two most likely causes?","a":"(1) `~/.ssh/` on the remote has permissions wider than `700`. (2) `~/.ssh/authorized_keys` has permissions wider than `600`. Fix: `chmod 700 ~/.ssh && chmod 600 ~/.ssh/authorized_keys` on the remote. `sshd` treats a group- or world-readable key file as a security risk and ignores it entirely."},{"kind":"h2","html":"SSH tunneling — where the listener lives","text":"SSH tunneling — where the listener lives"},{"kind":"p","html":"SSH can forward arbitrary TCP connections through its encrypted channel. Four flags:","text":"SSH can forward arbitrary TCP connections through its encrypted channel. Four flags:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eFlag\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eListener lives on\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eUse case\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e-L local_port:target:target_port\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eYour machine\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReach a remote resource from your laptop\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e-R remote_port:target:target_port\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eThe SSH server\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eExpose something local through a remote port\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e-D port\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYour machine (SOCKS5 proxy)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRoute app traffic dynamically through SSH\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e-X\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e—\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eForward graphical (X11) apps to display locally\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eThe mnemonic: the letter tells you where the listener lives.\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**The mnemonic: the letter tells you where the listener lives.**"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e-L\u003c/code\u003e → \u003cstrong\u003eL\u003c/strong\u003eocal listener (your laptop)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e-R\u003c/code\u003e → \u003cstrong\u003eR\u003c/strong\u003eemote listener (the SSH server)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- `-L` → **L**ocal listener (your laptop)\n- `-R` → **R**emote listener (the SSH server)"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Resolving the opening prediction","text":"Resolving the opening prediction"},{"kind":"p","html":"In \u003ccode\u003essh -L 5432:localhost:5432 ops@jump.prod\u003c/code\u003e, your SSH client tells \u003ccode\u003ejump.prod\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"In `ssh -L 5432:localhost:5432 ops@jump.prod`, your SSH client tells `jump.prod`:"},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e&quot;When someone connects to port 5432 on me, open a connection from \u003cstrong\u003eyou\u003c/strong\u003e to \u003ccode\u003elocalhost:5432\u003c/code\u003e.&quot;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003elocalhost\u003c/code\u003e is resolved by \u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003ejump.prod\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — it means jump&#39;s own loopback, not your laptop&#39;s. That&#39;s why the first tunnel reached the database running on jump itself.","text":"`localhost` is resolved by **`jump.prod`** — it means jump's own loopback, not your laptop's. That's why the first tunnel reached the database running on jump itself."},{"kind":"p","html":"To reach \u003ccode\u003edb.prod.internal\u003c/code\u003e instead, the command must be:","text":"To reach `db.prod.internal` instead, the command must be:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"console","code":"$ ssh -L 5432:db.prod.internal:5432 ops@jump.prod"},{"kind":"p","html":"Now jump opens its connection to \u003ccode\u003edb.prod.internal:5432\u003c/code\u003e — a host that jump can reach, but you cannot directly.","text":"Now jump opens its connection to `db.prod.internal:5432` — a host that jump can reach, but you cannot directly."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You want a colleague on `ci.server` to test your local dev server at `localhost:3000`, accessible as `ci.server:9000`. Which flag?","a":"`-R`: `ssh -R 9000:localhost:3000 user@ci.server`. The listener lives on `ci.server`. When your colleague hits `ci.server:9000`, traffic tunnels back to `localhost:3000` on *your* machine. `-L` would put the listener on your laptop, which already has the server — wrong direction."},{"kind":"h2","html":"FTP — active vs. passive, and why passive won","text":"FTP — active vs. passive, and why passive won"},{"kind":"p","html":"FTP uses \u003cstrong\u003etwo separate TCP connections\u003c/strong\u003e:","text":"FTP uses **two separate TCP connections**:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eControl channel\u003c/strong\u003e (port 21) — commands\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eData channel\u003c/strong\u003e — actual file bytes\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **Control channel** (port 21) — commands\n- **Data channel** — actual file bytes"},{"kind":"p","html":"The exam question is always: who opens the data channel?","text":"The exam question is always: who opens the data channel?"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eActive mode\u003c/strong\u003e — the server calls the client back:","text":"**Active mode** — the server calls the client back:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eClient sends its IP + a high port number to the server.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eServer opens a \u003cstrong\u003enew inbound connection\u003c/strong\u003e to the client for data.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eProblem: the router has no mapping for this unsolicited inbound connection. NAT drops it. Firewalls block it.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. Client sends its IP + a high port number to the server.\n2. Server opens a **new inbound connection** to the client for data.\n3. Problem: the router has no mapping for this unsolicited inbound connection. NAT drops it. Firewalls block it."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003ePassive mode (PASV)\u003c/strong\u003e — the client opens everything:","text":"**Passive mode (PASV)** — the client opens everything:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eServer picks a high port and tells the client to connect there.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eClient opens both the control and data connections outward.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eOutbound connections pass through NAT and firewalls normally.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. Server picks a high port and tells the client to connect there.\n2. Client opens both the control and data connections outward.\n3. Outbound connections pass through NAT and firewalls normally."},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003e\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eActive\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePassive\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eData connection opened by\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eServer → Client\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eClient → Server\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNAT-compatible\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYes\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eFirewall-friendly\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYes\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eModern default\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYes\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"FTP is unencrypted in both modes. SFTP (port 22) or SCP are the correct replacements.","text":"FTP is unencrypted in both modes. SFTP (port 22) or SCP are the correct replacements."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A user behind a home router can't receive files over FTP, but passive mode fixes it. Explain the mechanism.","a":"Active mode has the FTP server open a fresh TCP connection *inbound* to the client. The router has no NAT mapping for this unsolicited inbound packet, so it drops it. Passive mode has the client open all connections outward — the router tracks those and routes replies back normally. NAT only breaks inbound connections it didn't initiate."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eIn \u003ccode\u003essh -L 5432:localhost:5432 user@bastion\u003c/code\u003e, the \u003ccode\u003elocalhost\u003c/code\u003e in the middle is resolved by \u003cem\u003ebastion\u003c/em\u003e, not your laptop. If the database is on a separate host that bastion can reach, use that host&#39;s name: \u003ccode\u003essh -L 5432:db.internal:5432 user@bastion\u003c/code\u003e. Swapping \u003ccode\u003e-L\u003c/code\u003e for \u003ccode\u003e-R\u003c/code\u003e reverses direction entirely — \u003ccode\u003e-R\u003c/code\u003e exposes something on your machine through a port on the remote.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"In `ssh -L 5432:localhost:5432 user@bastion`, the `localhost` in the middle is resolved by *bastion*, not your laptop. If the database is on a separate host that bastion can reach, use that host's name: `ssh -L 5432:db.internal:5432 user@bastion`. Swapping `-L` for `-R` reverses direction entirely — `-R` exposes something on your machine through a port on the remote."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ccode\u003e/etc/hosts\u003c/code\u003e → DNS — order from \u003ccode\u003e/etc/nsswitch.conf\u003c/code\u003e. SSH (port 22) encrypts everything: \u003ccode\u003essh\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003escp\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003esftp\u003c/code\u003e. Key auth requires \u003ccode\u003e700\u003c/code\u003e on \u003ccode\u003e~/.ssh/\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e600\u003c/code\u003e on \u003ccode\u003eauthorized_keys\u003c/code\u003e; wrong permissions cause silent fallback to passwords. \u003ccode\u003e-L\u003c/code\u003e puts the listener local, \u003ccode\u003e-R\u003c/code\u003e puts it remote — and the middle \u003ccode\u003ehost\u003c/code\u003e in \u003ccode\u003e-L port:host:port\u003c/code\u003e resolves from the server&#39;s perspective. FTP is unencrypted; passive mode works through NAT because the client opens all connections.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"`/etc/hosts` → DNS — order from `/etc/nsswitch.conf`. SSH (port 22) encrypts everything: `ssh`, `scp`, `sftp`. Key auth requires `700` on `~/.ssh/` and `600` on `authorized_keys`; wrong permissions cause silent fallback to passwords. `-L` puts the listener local, `-R` puts it remote — and the middle `host` in `-L port:host:port` resolves from the server's perspective. FTP is unencrypted; passive mode works through NAT because the client opens all connections."}]},{"n":8,"id":"4915-lesson-services-sendmail-nfs-samba-nis-ldap","title":"Services: Sendmail, NFS, Samba, NIS, LDAP","hook":"Mod07 was NOT on midterm. 10% of the final per diagnosis. Every service here owns a config file path, a daemon name, and a port — those are the MCQ hinges.","tags":["networking","editor"],"module":"Networking","source":"Mod07 Ch20-23; materials/labs/Lab7.pdf","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"Your instructor drops four tasks on you at once:","text":"Your instructor drops four tasks on you at once:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eConfigure the server so it can \u003cstrong\u003ereceive email\u003c/strong\u003e from another machine on the network.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eLet a Linux client \u003cstrong\u003emount a directory\u003c/strong\u003e on this server as if it were local.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eLet a Windows laptop \u003cstrong\u003ebrowse a shared folder\u003c/strong\u003e on this server.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eMake user accounts and passwords \u003cstrong\u003emanaged centrally\u003c/strong\u003e so a dozen machines look them up from one place.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. Configure the server so it can **receive email** from another machine on the network.\n2. Let a Linux client **mount a directory** on this server as if it were local.\n3. Let a Windows laptop **browse a shared folder** on this server.\n4. Make user accounts and passwords **managed centrally** so a dozen machines look them up from one place."},{"kind":"p","html":"Before you read on: name the Linux service that handles each task. Commit to four answers.","text":"Before you read on: name the Linux service that handles each task. Commit to four answers."},{"kind":"p","html":"The services: Sendmail (or any MTA) for email, NFS for Linux-to-Linux mounting, Samba for Windows sharing, and NIS or LDAP for central identity. This lesson builds each one from the daemon up — config file, port, and the setup sequence that fails silently when you skip a step.","text":"The services: Sendmail (or any MTA) for email, NFS for Linux-to-Linux mounting, Samba for Windows sharing, and NIS or LDAP for central identity. This lesson builds each one from the daemon up — config file, port, and the setup sequence that fails silently when you skip a step."},{"kind":"h2","html":"What every service in this module has in common","text":"What every service in this module has in common"},{"kind":"p","html":"Each of the five services follows the same four-slot pattern. As you read each section, fill in this table from memory — if you can do it without looking, you know it exam-ready.","text":"Each of the five services follows the same four-slot pattern. As you read each section, fill in this table from memory — if you can do it without looking, you know it exam-ready."},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eSlot\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eWhat to remember\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003edaemon\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eThe background process you start and enable\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003econfig file\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eThe text file you edit\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eport\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eWhat the firewall needs open; what MCQs test\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003esystemctl enable --now\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eStart \u003cem\u003eand\u003c/em\u003e survive reboots — missing \u003ccode\u003eenable\u003c/code\u003e is the most common lab failure\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003efirewall rule\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003efirewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=&lt;name&gt;\u003c/code\u003e — services work on localhost without this, then break the moment a remote machine connects\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"The exam rarely asks &quot;explain NFS in depth.&quot; It asks &quot;which port?&quot;, &quot;which config file?&quot;, &quot;what command re-exports a share without restarting?&quot; The five slots above are the answer to almost every MCQ in this module.","text":"The exam rarely asks \"explain NFS in depth.\" It asks \"which port?\", \"which config file?\", \"what command re-exports a share without restarting?\" The five slots above are the answer to almost every MCQ in this module."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Sendmail — mail between hosts","text":"Sendmail — mail between hosts"},{"kind":"p","html":"Alice on \u003cem\u003ehostA\u003c/em\u003e runs \u003ccode\u003email -s &quot;hi&quot; bob@hostB\u003c/code\u003e. What moves that message from her prompt to Bob&#39;s mailbox?","text":"Alice on *hostA* runs `mail -s \"hi\" bob@hostB`. What moves that message from her prompt to Bob's mailbox?"},{"kind":"p","html":"Three separate programs share the work. Before reading the explanation, guess which program does each job:","text":"Three separate programs share the work. Before reading the explanation, guess which program does each job:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWho composes and reads the message?\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWho sends it across the network on port 25?\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWho writes it into Bob&#39;s local mailbox file?\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- Who composes and reads the message?\n- Who sends it across the network on port 25?\n- Who writes it into Bob's local mailbox file?"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Three roles: MUA, MTA, MDA","text":"Three roles: MUA, MTA, MDA"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003cstrong\u003eMUA\u003c/strong\u003e (Mail User Agent) is what the user touches — \u003ccode\u003email\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003emutt\u003c/code\u003e, Thunderbird. It composes outbound messages and displays inbound ones. It knows nothing about routing.","text":"The **MUA** (Mail User Agent) is what the user touches — `mail`, `mutt`, Thunderbird. It composes outbound messages and displays inbound ones. It knows nothing about routing."},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003cstrong\u003eMTA\u003c/strong\u003e (Mail Transfer Agent) does the routing. It accepts a message from the MUA, opens an SMTP connection on \u003cstrong\u003eport 25\u003c/strong\u003e to the destination host, and hands the message off. \u003cstrong\u003eSendmail\u003c/strong\u003e is the MTA. The exam names sendmail specifically; postfix and exim are alternatives that work the same way.","text":"The **MTA** (Mail Transfer Agent) does the routing. It accepts a message from the MUA, opens an SMTP connection on **port 25** to the destination host, and hands the message off. **Sendmail** is the MTA. The exam names sendmail specifically; postfix and exim are alternatives that work the same way."},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003cstrong\u003eMDA\u003c/strong\u003e (Mail Delivery Agent) handles the last mile. It receives the message from the destination MTA and writes it into Bob&#39;s actual mailbox file. \u003ccode\u003eprocmail\u003c/code\u003e is the MDA in this course.","text":"The **MDA** (Mail Delivery Agent) handles the last mile. It receives the message from the destination MTA and writes it into Bob's actual mailbox file. `procmail` is the MDA in this course."},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"flowchart LR\n  U[\"Alice\u003cbr/\u003e(hostA)\"] --\u003e M1[\"MUA\u003cbr/\u003email / mutt / Thunderbird\"]\n  M1 --\u003e T1[\"MTA — sendmail\u003cbr/\u003e(hostA)\"]\n  T1 --\u003e|SMTP :25| T2[\"MTA — sendmail\u003cbr/\u003e(hostB)\"]\n  T2 --\u003e Q[\"queue\u003cbr/\u003e/var/spool/mqueue\"]\n  Q --\u003e D[\"MDA — procmail\u003cbr/\u003ewrites to mailbox\"]\n  D --\u003e MB[\"Bob's mailbox\u003cbr/\u003e/var/mail/bob\"]\n  classDef user fill:#2a3a4a,stroke:#7aa2f7,color:#e5e5e5\n  classDef mta fill:#3a3528,stroke:#e3af68,color:#e3af68\n  classDef store fill:#2d3a2d,stroke:#9ece6a,color:#9ece6a\n  class U,M1,MB user\n  class T1,T2,Q mta\n  class D store"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eRole\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eDoes what\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eExample\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eMUA\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eUser composes/reads mail\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eThunderbird, mutt, \u003ccode\u003email\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eMTA\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAccepts SMTP :25, routes, queues\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003esendmail\u003c/strong\u003e, postfix, exim\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eMDA\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eWrites message to final mailbox\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eprocmail, maildrop\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"h3","html":"The config trap — \u003ccode\u003e.mc\u003c/code\u003e is the editor, \u003ccode\u003e.cf\u003c/code\u003e is what sendmail reads","text":"The config trap — `.mc` is the editor, `.cf` is what sendmail reads"},{"kind":"p","html":"Sendmail&#39;s native config file is \u003ccode\u003esendmail.cf\u003c/code\u003e. It is machine-generated and intentionally unreadable. \u003cstrong\u003eYou never edit it directly.\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"Sendmail's native config file is `sendmail.cf`. It is machine-generated and intentionally unreadable. **You never edit it directly.**"},{"kind":"p","html":"Instead, edit the macro file \u003ccode\u003esendmail.mc\u003c/code\u003e, then compile it with \u003ccode\u003em4\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"Instead, edit the macro file `sendmail.mc`, then compile it with `m4`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"# The file you actually edit:\n/etc/mail/sendmail.mc\n\n# After every .mc change — rebuild .cf, then restart:\ncd /etc/mail && sudo make\nsudo systemctl restart sendmail"},{"kind":"p","html":"Out of the box, \u003ccode\u003esendmail.mc\u003c/code\u003e contains this line:","text":"Out of the box, `sendmail.mc` contains this line:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"DAEMON_OPTIONS(`Port=smtp,Addr=127.0.0.1, Name=MTA')dnl"},{"kind":"p","html":"The \u003ccode\u003eAddr=127.0.0.1\u003c/code\u003e clause restricts sendmail to loopback — it cannot receive external mail. That is intentional (safe default). To accept connections from other machines, remove \u003ccode\u003eAddr=127.0.0.1\u003c/code\u003e, leaving:","text":"The `Addr=127.0.0.1` clause restricts sendmail to loopback — it cannot receive external mail. That is intentional (safe default). To accept connections from other machines, remove `Addr=127.0.0.1`, leaving:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"DAEMON_OPTIONS(`Port=smtp, Name=MTA')dnl"},{"kind":"p","html":"Then rebuild, restart, and open the firewall:","text":"Then rebuild, restart, and open the firewall:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"cd /etc/mail && sudo make\nsudo systemctl restart sendmail\nsudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=smtp\nsudo firewall-cmd --reload\nss -tlnp | grep :25       # must show 0.0.0.0:25, not 127.0.0.1:25"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Aliases — edit the text, then regenerate the database","text":"Aliases — edit the text, then regenerate the database"},{"kind":"p","html":"The aliases file at \u003ccode\u003e/etc/aliases\u003c/code\u003e is plain text:","text":"The aliases file at `/etc/aliases` is plain text:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"# /etc/aliases\nroot:    kevinliang          # root's mail → kevinliang's inbox\nadmin:   root                # chaining is fine\nsupport: |/usr/bin/ticket    # pipe to a program"},{"kind":"p","html":"Here is the trap: sendmail reads a \u003cstrong\u003ebinary hash\u003c/strong\u003e (\u003ccode\u003e/etc/aliases.db\u003c/code\u003e), not the plain text file. Editing \u003ccode\u003e/etc/aliases\u003c/code\u003e is invisible to sendmail until you run:","text":"Here is the trap: sendmail reads a **binary hash** (`/etc/aliases.db`), not the plain text file. Editing `/etc/aliases` is invisible to sendmail until you run:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"sudo newaliases"},{"kind":"p","html":"Restarting sendmail is not enough. \u003ccode\u003enewaliases\u003c/code\u003e is a separate step that regenerates the hash from scratch.","text":"Restarting sendmail is not enough. `newaliases` is a separate step that regenerates the hash from scratch."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Queue and log","text":"Queue and log"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eCommand\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eDoes what\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003emailq\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eList messages queued in \u003ccode\u003e/var/spool/mqueue/\u003c/code\u003e; empty = all delivered\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003esudo sendmail -q\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eForce immediate delivery of queued messages\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e/var/log/maillog\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAuthoritative trace: every connection, delivery attempt, and failure\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You edit `/etc/aliases` to forward root's mail to your account and restart sendmail. Root mail still doesn't reach you. What did you skip?","a":"`sudo newaliases`. Sendmail reads `/etc/aliases.db` — the binary hash — not the plain text file. Restarting sendmail does not regenerate the hash. Run `newaliases` after every aliases edit, regardless of whether you restart."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"`ss -tlnp | grep :25` shows `127.0.0.1:25`. A machine on the same network tries to send you mail and it fails. What one change in `/etc/mail/sendmail.mc` fixes this?","a":"Remove `Addr=127.0.0.1` from the `DAEMON_OPTIONS` line, leaving only `Port=smtp, Name=MTA`. Then `cd /etc/mail && sudo make` to rebuild `sendmail.cf`, `sudo systemctl restart sendmail`, and `firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=smtp`. The `Addr=` clause is the loopback lock; removing it binds port 25 on all interfaces (`0.0.0.0:25`)."},{"kind":"h2","html":"NFS — Linux-to-Linux file sharing","text":"NFS — Linux-to-Linux file sharing"},{"kind":"p","html":"The server has a directory at \u003ccode\u003e/srv/data\u003c/code\u003e. You want a Linux client to see it at \u003ccode\u003e/mnt/data\u003c/code\u003e as if it were a local disk. That is NFS in one sentence.","text":"The server has a directory at `/srv/data`. You want a Linux client to see it at `/mnt/data` as if it were a local disk. That is NFS in one sentence."},{"kind":"p","html":"NFS is the simplest service in this module: one config file, one export command, one mount command. The hard constraint: \u003cstrong\u003eboth sides must be Linux\u003c/strong\u003e (or POSIX-compliant). Windows does not speak NFS natively — for Windows, use Samba.","text":"NFS is the simplest service in this module: one config file, one export command, one mount command. The hard constraint: **both sides must be Linux** (or POSIX-compliant). Windows does not speak NFS natively — for Windows, use Samba."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Server side — declaring what to export","text":"Server side — declaring what to export"},{"kind":"p","html":"The server lists everything it shares in \u003ccode\u003e/etc/exports\u003c/code\u003e. Each line names a path, a client pattern, and mount options:","text":"The server lists everything it shares in `/etc/exports`. Each line names a path, a client pattern, and mount options:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"# /etc/exports\n/srv/data       192.168.1.0/24(rw,sync,root_squash)\n/home/shared    client2.example.com(ro,sync)"},{"kind":"p","html":"After editing \u003ccode\u003e/etc/exports\u003c/code\u003e, apply the change without restarting the daemon:","text":"After editing `/etc/exports`, apply the change without restarting the daemon:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"sudo exportfs -a       # re-read /etc/exports and update the kernel export table\nsudo exportfs -v       # verify what is currently exported\nshowmount -e server    # from any machine: list the server's active exports"},{"kind":"p","html":"NFS depends on \u003ccode\u003erpcbind\u003c/code\u003e (port \u003cstrong\u003e111\u003c/strong\u003e) to advertise where NFS is listening. NFS itself uses port \u003cstrong\u003e2049\u003c/strong\u003e. Both must run:","text":"NFS depends on `rpcbind` (port **111**) to advertise where NFS is listening. NFS itself uses port **2049**. Both must run:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"sudo systemctl enable --now rpcbind nfs-server\nsudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=nfs\nsudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=rpc-bind\nsudo firewall-cmd --reload"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Client side — mounting the share","text":"Client side — mounting the share"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"# One-time mount:\nsudo mount server:/srv/data /mnt/data\n\n# Persist across reboots (/etc/fstab):\nserver:/srv/data   /mnt/data   nfs   defaults,_netdev   0 0"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You add a new export to `/etc/exports` and restart `nfs-server`. The client runs `showmount -e` but still doesn't see the new share. What command on the server applies the change without a full restart?","a":"`sudo exportfs -a`. It re-reads `/etc/exports` and updates the kernel's export table immediately. A full daemon restart is only needed when the NFS module itself needs reinitializing — not for routine export changes."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eNFS uses AUTH_SYS by default — it trusts the \u003cstrong\u003eclient&#39;s numeric UID\u003c/strong\u003e. A user with UID 1001 on the client reads server files as UID 1001, regardless of whether those accounts belong to the same person. Root is squashed to \u003ccode\u003enobody\u003c/code\u003e via \u003ccode\u003eroot_squash\u003c/code\u003e (the default), but regular users are not squashed. If UIDs differ between machines, coordinate them with NIS or LDAP.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"NFS uses AUTH_SYS by default — it trusts the **client's numeric UID**. A user with UID 1001 on the client reads server files as UID 1001, regardless of whether those accounts belong to the same person. Root is squashed to `nobody` via `root_squash` (the default), but regular users are not squashed. If UIDs differ between machines, coordinate them with NIS or LDAP."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Samba — Linux ↔ Windows file sharing","text":"Samba — Linux ↔ Windows file sharing"},{"kind":"p","html":"A Windows laptop is on the same network as your Linux server. You want the laptop to browse a shared folder using nothing but its built-in File Explorer. NFS won&#39;t work here — Windows doesn&#39;t speak NFS. \u003cstrong\u003eSamba\u003c/strong\u003e implements SMB/CIFS, the protocol Windows uses natively for file sharing.","text":"A Windows laptop is on the same network as your Linux server. You want the laptop to browse a shared folder using nothing but its built-in File Explorer. NFS won't work here — Windows doesn't speak NFS. **Samba** implements SMB/CIFS, the protocol Windows uses natively for file sharing."},{"kind":"p","html":"Samba runs two daemons:","text":"Samba runs two daemons:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eDaemon\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eHandles\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePorts\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003esmbd\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eFile and printer sharing\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e139, 445\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003enmbd\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNetBIOS name resolution (so Windows can find the server by hostname)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e137, 138\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"h3","html":"\u003ccode\u003esmb.conf\u003c/code\u003e — the whole config is here","text":"`smb.conf` — the whole config is here"},{"kind":"p","html":"Everything Samba does is controlled by \u003ccode\u003e/etc/samba/smb.conf\u003c/code\u003e. The file is divided into named sections:","text":"Everything Samba does is controlled by `/etc/samba/smb.conf`. The file is divided into named sections:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e[global]\u003c/code\u003e — server-wide settings\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eEvery other section (\u003ccode\u003e[shared]\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e[homes]\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e[printers]\u003c/code\u003e) defines one \u003cstrong\u003eshare\u003c/strong\u003e — a named resource clients connect to\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- `[global]` — server-wide settings\n- Every other section (`[shared]`, `[homes]`, `[printers]`) defines one **share** — a named resource clients connect to"},{"kind":"code","lang":"ini","code":"[global]\n   workgroup = WORKGROUP\n   server string = Lab 7 Samba Server\n   security = user\n   passdb backend = tdbsam\n   map to guest = Bad User\n\n[shared]\n   comment = Lab 7 Shared Directory\n   path = /srv/samba/shared\n   browseable = yes\n   read only = no\n   valid users = fred\n   create mask = 0664\n   directory mask = 0775"},{"kind":"p","html":"After editing, validate syntax before restarting:","text":"After editing, validate syntax before restarting:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"testparm                           # syntax-check smb.conf; prints the active config\nsudo systemctl restart smb nmb\nsudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=samba\nsudo firewall-cmd --reload"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Samba passwords are separate from Linux passwords","text":"Samba passwords are separate from Linux passwords"},{"kind":"p","html":"Creating a Linux user does not create a Samba account. The two credential stores are completely independent:","text":"Creating a Linux user does not create a Samba account. The two credential stores are completely independent:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"sudo useradd fred                  # Linux account (required first)\nsudo smbpasswd -a fred             # add fred to Samba DB and set his SMB password"},{"kind":"p","html":"Changing the Linux password with \u003ccode\u003epasswd\u003c/code\u003e does \u003cstrong\u003enot\u003c/strong\u003e update the Samba password, and vice versa. \u003ccode\u003esmbpasswd -a\u003c/code\u003e is the step most students forget in the lab.","text":"Changing the Linux password with `passwd` does **not** update the Samba password, and vice versa. `smbpasswd -a` is the step most students forget in the lab."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Testing the share","text":"Testing the share"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"smbclient //localhost/shared -U fred       # connect to the share as fred\nsmbclient -L //server -U%                  # list all shares anonymously\nsudo mount -t cifs //server/shared /mnt/samba -o username=fred,password=fredpass"},{"kind":"p","html":"From Windows: \u003ccode\u003e\\\\server-IP\\shared\u003c/code\u003e in File Explorer.","text":"From Windows: `\\\\server-IP\\shared` in File Explorer."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You create Linux user `alice`, add her to `valid users` in `smb.conf`, and restart Samba. She gets \"access denied.\" What did you forget?","a":"`sudo smbpasswd -a alice`. Samba maintains its own credential database (`tdbsam`) separate from `/etc/passwd` and `/etc/shadow`. Until you run `smbpasswd -a`, alice has no Samba credentials and authentication fails — even if she is listed in `valid users`."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eSWAT (Samba Web Administration Tool) runs on port \u003cstrong\u003e901\u003c/strong\u003e and provides a browser-based config editor. It \u003cstrong\u003eoverwrites \u003ccode\u003esmb.conf\u003c/code\u003e entirely\u003c/strong\u003e when you save, silently erasing any comments, custom sections, or manual edits not reflected in its UI. Use \u003ccode\u003etestparm\u003c/code\u003e and direct file editing in any environment where the config file matters.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"SWAT (Samba Web Administration Tool) runs on port **901** and provides a browser-based config editor. It **overwrites `smb.conf` entirely** when you save, silently erasing any comments, custom sections, or manual edits not reflected in its UI. Use `testparm` and direct file editing in any environment where the config file matters."},{"kind":"h2","html":"NIS — centralized Unix identity","text":"NIS — centralized Unix identity"},{"kind":"p","html":"You have 20 Linux servers. A user needs to log into any of them with the same username, UID, and password. Without NIS, you maintain \u003ccode\u003e/etc/passwd\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003e/etc/shadow\u003c/code\u003e on each machine separately — they drift out of sync within days.","text":"You have 20 Linux servers. A user needs to log into any of them with the same username, UID, and password. Without NIS, you maintain `/etc/passwd` and `/etc/shadow` on each machine separately — they drift out of sync within days."},{"kind":"p","html":"NIS fixes this by pushing \u003cstrong\u003emaps\u003c/strong\u003e — flat database files derived from \u003ccode\u003e/etc/passwd\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e/etc/group\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e/etc/hosts\u003c/code\u003e, and others — from a \u003cstrong\u003emaster server\u003c/strong\u003e to every client. Clients query the master instead of reading local files.","text":"NIS fixes this by pushing **maps** — flat database files derived from `/etc/passwd`, `/etc/group`, `/etc/hosts`, and others — from a **master server** to every client. Clients query the master instead of reading local files."},{"kind":"h3","html":"NIS domain ≠ DNS domain","text":"NIS domain ≠ DNS domain"},{"kind":"p","html":"This is the most common NIS confusion on exams. The NIS domain name is its own namespace, set with the \u003ccode\u003edomainname\u003c/code\u003e command. It has nothing to do with the DNS domain. A machine can simultaneously belong to NIS domain \u003ccode\u003emylab\u003c/code\u003e and DNS domain \u003ccode\u003eexample.com\u003c/code\u003e — they are completely independent. If the NIS domain name on a client doesn&#39;t match the master, queries silently return nothing.","text":"This is the most common NIS confusion on exams. The NIS domain name is its own namespace, set with the `domainname` command. It has nothing to do with the DNS domain. A machine can simultaneously belong to NIS domain `mylab` and DNS domain `example.com` — they are completely independent. If the NIS domain name on a client doesn't match the master, queries silently return nothing."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Setup","text":"Setup"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eMaster server:\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Master server:**"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"sudo ypinit -m                     # initialize master; prompts for slave server list\nsudo systemctl enable --now ypserv"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eClient — \u003ccode\u003e/etc/nsswitch.conf\u003c/code\u003e:\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Client — `/etc/nsswitch.conf`:**"},{"kind":"p","html":"On each client, \u003ccode\u003eypbind\u003c/code\u003e finds and binds to the master. The Name Service Switch file tells the system to check NIS for users, groups, and hosts:","text":"On each client, `ypbind` finds and binds to the master. The Name Service Switch file tells the system to check NIS for users, groups, and hosts:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"passwd:  files nis\ngroup:   files nis\nhosts:   files nis dns"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Query commands","text":"Query commands"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"ypcat passwd           # dump the entire NIS passwd map\nypmatch fred passwd    # look up one specific entry\nypwhich                # which NIS server am I bound to?\nyppasswd               # change your NIS password (sends the change to master)"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003e/var/yp/securenets\u003c/code\u003e restricts which IP ranges may query the server. Leaving it unconfigured exposes all maps to any host on the network.","text":"`/var/yp/securenets` restricts which IP ranges may query the server. Leaving it unconfigured exposes all maps to any host on the network."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A client is in NIS domain `labnet` but `ypcat passwd` returns empty results even though the master has users. What's the most likely cause?","a":"The client's NIS domain name doesn't match the master's. Run `domainname` on both machines — the strings must be identical. NIS doesn't fall back gracefully on a mismatch; queries return nothing. Also verify `ypbind` is running on the client and that RPC port 111 is reachable on the master."},{"kind":"h2","html":"LDAP — hierarchical directory","text":"LDAP — hierarchical directory"},{"kind":"p","html":"NIS is a flat collection of maps. That works for users and groups, but breaks down when you need to model organizational structure, nested groups, or objects with varied attributes. LDAP (Lightweight Directory Access Protocol) is the modern answer: instead of flat maps, it stores a \u003cstrong\u003etree\u003c/strong\u003e called the Directory Information Tree (DIT).","text":"NIS is a flat collection of maps. That works for users and groups, but breaks down when you need to model organizational structure, nested groups, or objects with varied attributes. LDAP (Lightweight Directory Access Protocol) is the modern answer: instead of flat maps, it stores a **tree** called the Directory Information Tree (DIT)."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Reading a Distinguished Name","text":"Reading a Distinguished Name"},{"kind":"p","html":"Every entry in the LDAP tree has a \u003cstrong\u003eDistinguished Name (DN)\u003c/strong\u003e — its unique address in the tree, built from components:","text":"Every entry in the LDAP tree has a **Distinguished Name (DN)** — its unique address in the tree, built from components:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDC\u003c/strong\u003e (Domain Component): \u003ccode\u003edc=example,dc=com\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOU\u003c/strong\u003e (Organizational Unit): \u003ccode\u003eou=People\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCN\u003c/strong\u003e (Common Name): \u003ccode\u003ecn=alice\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **DC** (Domain Component): `dc=example,dc=com`\n- **OU** (Organizational Unit): `ou=People`\n- **CN** (Common Name): `cn=alice`"},{"kind":"p","html":"A full DN looks like:","text":"A full DN looks like:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"cn=alice,ou=People,dc=example,dc=com"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eRead it right to left\u003c/strong\u003e to trace the path from tree root to leaf:","text":"**Read it right to left** to trace the path from tree root to leaf:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"dc=example,dc=com       ← root\n└── ou=People\n    └── cn=alice         ← leaf (the entry itself)"},{"kind":"p","html":"The leftmost component is always the entry itself. The rightmost is always the tree root. &quot;Alice is at the top&quot; is backwards — she is a leaf.","text":"The leftmost component is always the entry itself. The rightmost is always the tree root. \"Alice is at the top\" is backwards — she is a leaf."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Daemon and ports","text":"Daemon and ports"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eItem\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eValue\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDaemon\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eslapd\u003c/code\u003e (OpenLDAP server)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePlain LDAP port\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e389\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eLDAPS (TLS-encrypted) port\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e636\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eConfig\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eslapd.conf\u003c/code\u003e (legacy flat file) or \u003ccode\u003ecn=config\u003c/code\u003e (modern on-line config stored as LDAP entries)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"New deployments use \u003ccode\u003ecn=config\u003c/code\u003e; exam questions may reference either.","text":"New deployments use `cn=config`; exam questions may reference either."},{"kind":"h3","html":"LDIF and the four operations","text":"LDIF and the four operations"},{"kind":"p","html":"Entries are created and modified using \u003cstrong\u003eLDIF\u003c/strong\u003e (LDAP Data Interchange Format):","text":"Entries are created and modified using **LDIF** (LDAP Data Interchange Format):"},{"kind":"code","lang":"ldif","code":"dn: cn=alice,ou=People,dc=example,dc=com\nobjectClass: inetOrgPerson\ncn: alice\nsn: Smith\nuserPassword: {SSHA}..."},{"kind":"p","html":"The four operational commands:","text":"The four operational commands:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"ldapsearch -x -H ldap://server -b \"dc=example,dc=com\" \"(cn=alice)\"\nldapadd    -x -D \"cn=admin,dc=example,dc=com\" -W -f add.ldif\nldapmodify -x -D \"cn=admin,dc=example,dc=com\" -W -f mod.ldif\nldapdelete -x -D \"cn=admin,dc=example,dc=com\" -W \"cn=alice,ou=People,dc=example,dc=com\""},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"An admin reads the DN `cn=alice,ou=People,dc=example,dc=com` and says \"alice is at the top of the tree.\" Are they right?","a":"No. Read right to left: `dc=example,dc=com` is the root, `ou=People` is one level below, and `cn=alice` is the leaf. The leftmost component is always the entry itself; the rightmost is always the tree root. Alice is a leaf in the `People` branch."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Service quick-reference","text":"Service quick-reference"},{"kind":"p","html":"Every MCQ in this module is fishing for one of these four slots:","text":"Every MCQ in this module is fishing for one of these four slots:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eService\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePurpose\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eDaemon(s)\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eConfig file\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePort(s)\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSendmail\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eMail transfer\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003esendmail\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e/etc/mail/sendmail.mc\u003c/code\u003e → \u003ccode\u003e.cf\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e25 (SMTP)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNFS\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eUnix-to-Unix file share\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003erpcbind\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003enfs-server\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e/etc/exports\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e111 (RPC), 2049\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSamba\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eLinux ↔ Windows file share\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003esmbd\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003enmbd\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e/etc/samba/smb.conf\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e137/138, 139/445\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNIS\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCentralized Unix identity (flat maps)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eypserv\u003c/code\u003e (server) + \u003ccode\u003eypbind\u003c/code\u003e (client)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e/var/yp/\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003esecurenets\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e111 (RPC)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eLDAP\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eHierarchical directory\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eslapd\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eslapd.conf\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003ecn=config\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e389 / 636 (LDAPS)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eNFS and NIS both rely on \u003ccode\u003erpcbind\u003c/code\u003e at port 111. If \u003ccode\u003erpcbind\u003c/code\u003e is down, both fail simultaneously — but the error messages look different (NFS reports a mount failure; NIS reports &quot;no NIS server&quot;). Check \u003ccode\u003erpcbind\u003c/code\u003e first when either service misbehaves on a fresh install.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"NFS and NIS both rely on `rpcbind` at port 111. If `rpcbind` is down, both fail simultaneously — but the error messages look different (NFS reports a mount failure; NIS reports \"no NIS server\"). Check `rpcbind` first when either service misbehaves on a fresh install."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eEvery service here is daemon + config file + port + \u003ccode\u003esystemctl enable --now\u003c/code\u003e + firewall rule. The exam tests the steps you&#39;re most likely to skip. For Sendmail: \u003ccode\u003enewaliases\u003c/code\u003e after editing aliases; remove \u003ccode\u003eAddr=127.0.0.1\u003c/code\u003e to accept external mail. For NFS: \u003ccode\u003eexportfs -a\u003c/code\u003e to apply export changes; watch UID matching across machines. For Samba: \u003ccode\u003esmbpasswd -a\u003c/code\u003e creates the SMB credential — it is separate from the Linux account and \u003ccode\u003evalid users\u003c/code\u003e membership alone is not enough. NIS is flat maps queried over RPC; LDAP is a hierarchical DIT on port 389/636. Linux-to-Linux = NFS. Linux-to-Windows = Samba. The exam will swap those and wait.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Every service here is daemon + config file + port + `systemctl enable --now` + firewall rule. The exam tests the steps you're most likely to skip. For Sendmail: `newaliases` after editing aliases; remove `Addr=127.0.0.1` to accept external mail. For NFS: `exportfs -a` to apply export changes; watch UID matching across machines. For Samba: `smbpasswd -a` creates the SMB credential — it is separate from the Linux account and `valid users` membership alone is not enough. NIS is flat maps queried over RPC; LDAP is a hierarchical DIT on port 389/636. Linux-to-Linux = NFS. Linux-to-Windows = Samba. The exam will swap those and wait."}]},{"n":9,"id":"4915-lesson-dns-iptables-apache","title":"DNS, iptables, Apache","hook":"All three are config-file-heavy. Exam will test file locations + record types + chain names.","tags":["networking"],"module":"Networking","source":"Mod08 DNS Ch24 iptables ch25 Apache ch26.pdf","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eMotivation.\u003c/strong\u003e Three services appear on every production Linux box — and on every exam. DNS translates names to addresses. iptables decides which packets the kernel lets through. Apache serves web content. What ties them together: each is driven by a small set of config files and each has a strict vocabulary of section names, record types, or chain names the exam will probe by exact spelling. Lock in the file paths, record types, chain names, and config hierarchy and you&#39;ll handle the bulk of Module 08 MCQs on sight.","text":"**Motivation.** Three services appear on every production Linux box — and on every exam. DNS translates names to addresses. iptables decides which packets the kernel lets through. Apache serves web content. What ties them together: each is driven by a small set of config files and each has a strict vocabulary of section names, record types, or chain names the exam will probe by exact spelling. Lock in the file paths, record types, chain names, and config hierarchy and you'll handle the bulk of Module 08 MCQs on sight."},{"kind":"h3","html":"DNS / BIND","text":"DNS / BIND"},{"kind":"p","html":"What it does","text":"What it does"},{"kind":"p","html":"DNS is the internet phone book: a client asks for a name, a server returns an address. BIND is the standard DNS server on Linux. The daemon is \u003ccode\u003enamed\u003c/code\u003e; the package is \u003ccode\u003ebind\u003c/code\u003e; query tools come from \u003ccode\u003ebind-utils\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"DNS is the internet phone book: a client asks for a name, a server returns an address. BIND is the standard DNS server on Linux. The daemon is `named`; the package is `bind`; query tools come from `bind-utils`."},{"kind":"p","html":"Key paths:","text":"Key paths:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eFile / dir\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePurpose\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e/etc/named.conf\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eMain config — zones, listeners, ACLs\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e/var/named/\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eZone data files\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Resource records — the seven you must know","text":"Resource records — the seven you must know"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eType\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eMaps\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eA\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eHostname → IPv4 address\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAAAA\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eHostname → IPv6 address\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCNAME\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAlias → canonical name\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMX\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDomain → mail server (+ priority number)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eNS\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eZone → authoritative nameserver\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePTR\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eIP → hostname (reverse lookup)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSOA\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eStart of Authority — serial, refresh, expire, TTL for the zone\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Query flow","text":"Query flow"},{"kind":"p","html":"Your resolver either has a cached answer or it queries outward: root servers → TLD servers → the zone&#39;s authoritative server. That ladder is \u003cstrong\u003eiterative\u003c/strong\u003e resolution. When your local name server does the climbing on your behalf and hands you the final answer, that is \u003cstrong\u003erecursive\u003c/strong\u003e resolution. Port \u003cstrong\u003e53 UDP\u003c/strong\u003e for normal queries, \u003cstrong\u003e53 TCP\u003c/strong\u003e for zone transfers and large responses.","text":"Your resolver either has a cached answer or it queries outward: root servers → TLD servers → the zone's authoritative server. That ladder is **iterative** resolution. When your local name server does the climbing on your behalf and hands you the final answer, that is **recursive** resolution. Port **53 UDP** for normal queries, **53 TCP** for zone transfers and large responses."},{"kind":"p","html":"Validate and query","text":"Validate and query"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"named-checkconf                              # syntax-check /etc/named.conf\nnamed-checkzone example.com /var/named/example.com.zone\ndig example.com A                            # query A record\nnslookup example.com                         # interactive or one-shot\nhost example.com                             # quick lookup"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003ch4\u003eMinimal forward zone — from config to live query\u003c/h4\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDeclare the zone in \u003ccode\u003e/etc/named.conf\u003c/code\u003e:\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode\u003ezone &quot;example.com&quot; IN {\n    type master;\n    file &quot;example.com.zone&quot;;\n};\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCreate \u003ccode\u003e/var/named/example.com.zone\u003c/code\u003e:\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode\u003e$ORIGIN example.com.\n$TTL 86400\n@   IN  SOA  ns1.example.com. admin.example.com. (\n                2024010101 ; serial\n                3600       ; refresh\n                900        ; retry\n                604800     ; expire\n                300 )      ; negative TTL\n    IN  NS   ns1.example.com.\nns1 IN  A    192.168.1.10\nwww IN  A    192.168.1.20\nftp IN  CNAME www.example.com.\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eValidate: \u003ccode\u003enamed-checkzone example.com /var/named/example.com.zone\u003c/code\u003e → must print \u003ccode\u003eOK\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eReload: \u003ccode\u003esystemctl reload named\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eTest: \u003ccode\u003edig @192.168.1.10 www.example.com A\u003c/code\u003e → returns \u003ccode\u003e192.168.1.20\u003c/code\u003e.\nEach line in the zone file is one resource record. The \u003ccode\u003e@\u003c/code\u003e is shorthand for the zone origin. The SOA record is mandatory — without it \u003ccode\u003enamed-checkzone\u003c/code\u003e rejects the file.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"#### Minimal forward zone — from config to live query\n1. Declare the zone in `/etc/named.conf`:\n   ```\n   zone \"example.com\" IN {\n       type master;\n       file \"example.com.zone\";\n   };\n   ```\n2. Create `/var/named/example.com.zone`:\n   ```\n   $ORIGIN example.com.\n   $TTL 86400\n   @   IN  SOA  ns1.example.com. admin.example.com. (\n                   2024010101 ; serial\n                   3600       ; refresh\n                   900        ; retry\n                   604800     ; expire\n                   300 )      ; negative TTL\n       IN  NS   ns1.example.com.\n   ns1 IN  A    192.168.1.10\n   www IN  A    192.168.1.20\n   ftp IN  CNAME www.example.com.\n   ```\n3. Validate: `named-checkzone example.com /var/named/example.com.zone` → must print `OK`.\n4. Reload: `systemctl reload named`.\n5. Test: `dig @192.168.1.10 www.example.com A` → returns `192.168.1.20`.\nEach line in the zone file is one resource record. The `@` is shorthand for the zone origin. The SOA record is mandatory — without it `named-checkzone` rejects the file."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Which daemon name does BIND use, and where is its main config file?","a":"Daemon is `named`. Main config is `/etc/named.conf`. Zone data files live under `/var/named/`."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A PTR record maps an IP back to a hostname. Which record maps a hostname to an IPv4 address, and which maps it to an IPv6 address?","a":"**A** record for IPv4, **AAAA** record for IPv6. PTR is the reverse direction and lives in a separate reverse-lookup zone (under `in-addr.arpa` for IPv4)."},{"kind":"h3","html":"iptables","text":"iptables"},{"kind":"p","html":"How the kernel sees traffic","text":"How the kernel sees traffic"},{"kind":"p","html":"Every packet passing through the Linux kernel moves through \u003cstrong\u003enetfilter\u003c/strong\u003e hooks. \u003ccode\u003eiptables\u003c/code\u003e programs those hooks using \u003cstrong\u003etables\u003c/strong\u003e and \u003cstrong\u003echains\u003c/strong\u003e.","text":"Every packet passing through the Linux kernel moves through **netfilter** hooks. `iptables` programs those hooks using **tables** and **chains**."},{"kind":"p","html":"Three tables:","text":"Three tables:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003efilter\u003c/strong\u003e — the default. Allow or deny packets destined for or passing through this host.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003enat\u003c/strong\u003e — Network Address Translation. Rewrite source or destination addresses.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003emangle\u003c/strong\u003e — packet modification (TTL, TOS marking). Rarely needed for basic firewalling.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **filter** — the default. Allow or deny packets destined for or passing through this host.\n- **nat** — Network Address Translation. Rewrite source or destination addresses.\n- **mangle** — packet modification (TTL, TOS marking). Rarely needed for basic firewalling."},{"kind":"p","html":"Five chains (not every chain exists in every table):","text":"Five chains (not every chain exists in every table):"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eChain\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eWhen it runs\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePREROUTING\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBefore the routing decision — incoming packets\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eINPUT\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePackets destined for a local process\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eFORWARD\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePackets being routed through (not local)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOUTPUT\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePackets from a local process going out\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePOSTROUTING\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAfter the routing decision — outgoing packets\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"diagram","title":null,"svg":"\u003csvg viewBox=\"0 0 720 280\" preserveAspectRatio=\"xMidYMid meet\"\u003e\u003cdefs\u003e\u003cmarker id=\"arrIPT\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"9\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"6\" markerHeight=\"6\" orient=\"auto\"\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M0 0 L10 5 L0 10 Z\" fill=\"#a3a3a3\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003c/marker\u003e\u003c/defs\u003e\u003ctext x=\"20\" y=\"22\" class=\"label-accent\"\u003eiptables — tables × chains × targets\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"120\" y=\"60\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003ePREROUTING\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"260\" y=\"60\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eINPUT\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"380\" y=\"60\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eFORWARD\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"500\" y=\"60\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eOUTPUT\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"620\" y=\"60\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003ePOSTROUTING\u003c/text\u003e\u003cline x1=\"40\" y1=\"68\" x2=\"700\" y2=\"68\" class=\"arrow-line\"\u003e\u003c/line\u003e\u003ctext x=\"20\" y=\"100\" class=\"label\"\u003efilter\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"80\" y=\"80\" width=\"80\" height=\"32\" class=\"box\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003crect x=\"220\" y=\"80\" width=\"80\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-accent\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"260\" y=\"100\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e✓\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"340\" y=\"80\" width=\"80\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-accent\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"380\" y=\"100\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e✓\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"460\" y=\"80\" width=\"80\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-accent\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"500\" y=\"100\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e✓\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"580\" y=\"80\" width=\"80\" height=\"32\" class=\"box\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"20\" y=\"140\" class=\"label\"\u003enat\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"80\" y=\"120\" width=\"80\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-warn\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"120\" y=\"140\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eDNAT ✓\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"220\" y=\"120\" width=\"80\" height=\"32\" class=\"box\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003crect x=\"340\" y=\"120\" width=\"80\" height=\"32\" class=\"box\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003crect x=\"460\" y=\"120\" width=\"80\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-warn\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"500\" y=\"140\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e✓\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"580\" y=\"120\" width=\"80\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-warn\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"620\" y=\"140\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eSNAT ✓\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"20\" y=\"180\" class=\"label\"\u003emangle\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"80\" y=\"160\" width=\"80\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-bad\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"120\" y=\"180\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e✓\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"220\" y=\"160\" width=\"80\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-bad\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"260\" y=\"180\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e✓\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"340\" y=\"160\" width=\"80\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-bad\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"380\" y=\"180\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e✓\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"460\" y=\"160\" width=\"80\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-bad\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"500\" y=\"180\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e✓\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"580\" y=\"160\" width=\"80\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-bad\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"620\" y=\"180\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e✓\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"20\" y=\"225\" class=\"sub\"\u003eTargets: ACCEPT · DROP · REJECT · LOG · SNAT · DNAT · MASQUERADE\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"20\" y=\"245\" class=\"sub\"\u003eCommon: filter/INPUT to firewall the host. nat/PREROUTING for DNAT (port-forward in). nat/POSTROUTING for SNAT/MASQUERADE (out to internet).\u003c/text\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e","legend":null},{"kind":"p","html":"Targets","text":"Targets"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eACCEPT\u003c/strong\u003e — let the packet through\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDROP\u003c/strong\u003e — silently discard; sender receives no response and must wait for timeout\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eREJECT\u003c/strong\u003e — discard and send an ICMP error back immediately\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eLOG\u003c/strong\u003e — write to kernel log, continue evaluating rules\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSNAT\u003c/strong\u003e — rewrite source address (outbound NAT, static IP uplink)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDNAT\u003c/strong\u003e — rewrite destination address (port forwarding inbound)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMASQUERADE\u003c/strong\u003e — SNAT variant for dynamic IPs (e.g., DHCP uplink)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **ACCEPT** — let the packet through\n- **DROP** — silently discard; sender receives no response and must wait for timeout\n- **REJECT** — discard and send an ICMP error back immediately\n- **LOG** — write to kernel log, continue evaluating rules\n- **SNAT** — rewrite source address (outbound NAT, static IP uplink)\n- **DNAT** — rewrite destination address (port forwarding inbound)\n- **MASQUERADE** — SNAT variant for dynamic IPs (e.g., DHCP uplink)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Rule mechanics","text":"Rule mechanics"},{"kind":"p","html":"Rules in a chain are evaluated \u003cstrong\u003etop to bottom; first match wins\u003c/strong\u003e. If no rule matches, the chain&#39;s \u003cstrong\u003epolicy\u003c/strong\u003e applies (typically ACCEPT on a freshly installed system).","text":"Rules in a chain are evaluated **top to bottom; first match wins**. If no rule matches, the chain's **policy** applies (typically ACCEPT on a freshly installed system)."},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"iptables -A CHAIN            # Append rule (end of chain)\niptables -I CHAIN            # Insert rule (top of chain)\niptables -D CHAIN            # Delete matching rule\niptables -L -v -n            # List all rules (verbose, numeric IPs)\niptables -F CHAIN            # Flush — delete all rules in chain\niptables -P CHAIN TARGET     # Set default policy for chain"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003ch4\u003eBuilding a minimal host firewall — allow SSH in, drop the rest\u003c/h4\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAllow packets belonging to already-established sessions (without this, existing connections break):\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-bash\"\u003eiptables -A INPUT -m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAllow loopback — local services communicate over \u003ccode\u003elo\u003c/code\u003e:\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-bash\"\u003eiptables -A INPUT -i lo -j ACCEPT\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAllow SSH only from the internal network:\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-bash\"\u003eiptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -s 10.0.0.0/8 -j ACCEPT\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDefault-deny everything else inbound:\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-bash\"\u003eiptables -A INPUT -j DROP\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eVerify: \u003ccode\u003eiptables -L INPUT -v -n\u003c/code\u003e. Rules appear in order. An SSH attempt from \u003ccode\u003e10.0.0.5\u003c/code\u003e hits rule 3 → ACCEPT. An SSH attempt from \u003ccode\u003e8.8.8.8\u003c/code\u003e falls through all rules → hits DROP at the bottom.\nOrder is not cosmetic — if you put the DROP in step 1, nothing ever reaches step 3.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"#### Building a minimal host firewall — allow SSH in, drop the rest\n1. Allow packets belonging to already-established sessions (without this, existing connections break):\n   ```bash\n   iptables -A INPUT -m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT\n   ```\n2. Allow loopback — local services communicate over `lo`:\n   ```bash\n   iptables -A INPUT -i lo -j ACCEPT\n   ```\n3. Allow SSH only from the internal network:\n   ```bash\n   iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -s 10.0.0.0/8 -j ACCEPT\n   ```\n4. Default-deny everything else inbound:\n   ```bash\n   iptables -A INPUT -j DROP\n   ```\n5. Verify: `iptables -L INPUT -v -n`. Rules appear in order. An SSH attempt from `10.0.0.5` hits rule 3 → ACCEPT. An SSH attempt from `8.8.8.8` falls through all rules → hits DROP at the bottom.\nOrder is not cosmetic — if you put the DROP in step 1, nothing ever reaches step 3."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You want internet traffic arriving on port 80 forwarded to an internal server at 192.168.1.100. Which table, chain, and target do you use?","a":"Table **nat**, chain **PREROUTING**, target **DNAT**. PREROUTING fires before the routing decision, so you rewrite the destination while the kernel can still route it correctly. Example: `iptables -t nat -A PREROUTING -p tcp --dport 80 -j DNAT --to-destination 192.168.1.100:80`"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What is the practical difference between DROP and REJECT for an attacker scanning your host?","a":"**DROP** gives the scanner no signal — the connection times out silently, which slows scanning and reveals less. **REJECT** sends an ICMP error back immediately, confirming the host exists. DROP is the common choice on external-facing firewalls; REJECT is friendlier on internal networks where you want misconfigurations to fail fast."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Apache","text":"Apache"},{"kind":"p","html":"Daemon and config","text":"Daemon and config"},{"kind":"p","html":"Daemon: \u003ccode\u003ehttpd\u003c/code\u003e. Main config: \u003ccode\u003e/etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf\u003c/code\u003e. Default document root: \u003ccode\u003e/var/www/html\u003c/code\u003e. Port \u003cstrong\u003e80\u003c/strong\u003e HTTP, \u003cstrong\u003e443\u003c/strong\u003e HTTPS.","text":"Daemon: `httpd`. Main config: `/etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf`. Default document root: `/var/www/html`. Port **80** HTTP, **443** HTTPS."},{"kind":"p","html":"The config file has three logical regions in a strict inheritance hierarchy:","text":"The config file has three logical regions in a strict inheritance hierarchy:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eGlobal\u003c/strong\u003e — server-wide settings: \u003ccode\u003eListen\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eLoadModule\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eServerRoot\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMain Server\u003c/strong\u003e — defaults applied to any request not matched by a VirtualHost: \u003ccode\u003eServerName\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eDocumentRoot\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eDirectoryIndex\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eVirtualHosts\u003c/strong\u003e — \u003ccode\u003e&lt;VirtualHost *:80&gt;\u003c/code\u003e blocks, one per site; override Main Server settings for that hostname.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. **Global** — server-wide settings: `Listen`, `LoadModule`, `ServerRoot`.\n2. **Main Server** — defaults applied to any request not matched by a VirtualHost: `ServerName`, `DocumentRoot`, `DirectoryIndex`.\n3. **VirtualHosts** — `\u003cVirtualHost *:80\u003e` blocks, one per site; override Main Server settings for that hostname."},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"flowchart TD\n  G[\"Global\u003cbr/\u003eListen 80 / 443\u003cbr/\u003eLoadModule · ServerRoot\"]\n  M[\"Main Server\u003cbr/\u003eServerName · DocumentRoot\u003cbr/\u003edefaults for unmatched hosts\"]\n  V1[\"&lt;VirtualHost *:80&gt;\u003cbr/\u003esite-a.com\"]\n  V2[\"&lt;VirtualHost *:80&gt;\u003cbr/\u003esite-b.com\"]\n  D1[\"&lt;Directory /var/www/a&gt;\u003cbr/\u003eAllowOverride · Require\"]\n  D2[\"&lt;Directory /var/www/b&gt;\u003cbr/\u003eAllowOverride · Require\"]\n  H[\".htaccess\u003cbr/\u003eper-folder overrides\u003cbr/\u003e(if AllowOverride set)\"]\n  G --\u003e M\n  M --\u003e V1\n  M --\u003e V2\n  V1 --\u003e D1\n  V2 --\u003e D2\n  D1 -.allows.-\u003e H\n  classDef g fill:#2a3a4a,stroke:#7aa2f7,color:#e5e5e5\n  classDef m fill:#3a3528,stroke:#e3af68,color:#e3af68\n  classDef d fill:#2d3a2d,stroke:#9ece6a,color:#9ece6a\n  class G g\n  class M,V1,V2 m\n  class D1,D2,H d"},{"kind":"p","html":"Inheritance flows down: Global → Main → each VirtualHost → each \u003ccode\u003e&lt;Directory&gt;\u003c/code\u003e → optional \u003ccode\u003e.htaccess\u003c/code\u003e. More specific blocks override less specific.","text":"Inheritance flows down: Global → Main → each VirtualHost → each `\u003cDirectory\u003e` → optional `.htaccess`. More specific blocks override less specific."},{"kind":"p","html":"Per-directory access control","text":"Per-directory access control"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003e&lt;Directory&gt;\u003c/code\u003e blocks control access to filesystem paths. Two key directives:","text":"`\u003cDirectory\u003e` blocks control access to filesystem paths. Two key directives:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eAllowOverride\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — if set to anything other than \u003ccode\u003eNone\u003c/code\u003e, Apache looks for a \u003ccode\u003e.htaccess\u003c/code\u003e file in that directory on every request and applies it. Set to \u003ccode\u003eNone\u003c/code\u003e for performance (avoids a filesystem stat per request).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eRequire\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — who may access. \u003ccode\u003eRequire all granted\u003c/code\u003e (public), \u003ccode\u003eRequire valid-user\u003c/code\u003e (authenticated users only), \u003ccode\u003eRequire ip 10.0.0.0/8\u003c/code\u003e (IP-restricted).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **`AllowOverride`** — if set to anything other than `None`, Apache looks for a `.htaccess` file in that directory on every request and applies it. Set to `None` for performance (avoids a filesystem stat per request).\n- **`Require`** — who may access. `Require all granted` (public), `Require valid-user` (authenticated users only), `Require ip 10.0.0.0/8` (IP-restricted)."},{"kind":"p","html":"Authentication with htpasswd","text":"Authentication with htpasswd"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"htpasswd -c /etc/httpd/.htpasswd alice   # -c creates new file (overwrites if exists)\nhtpasswd /etc/httpd/.htpasswd bob        # add user to existing file"},{"kind":"p","html":"In the \u003ccode\u003e&lt;Directory&gt;\u003c/code\u003e block that needs protection:","text":"In the `\u003cDirectory\u003e` block that needs protection:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"AuthType Basic\nAuthName \"Restricted\"\nAuthUserFile /etc/httpd/.htpasswd\nRequire valid-user"},{"kind":"p","html":"Useful commands","text":"Useful commands"},{"kind":"code","lang":"bash","code":"httpd -S          # list all configured virtual hosts and their source file + line\nhttpd -t          # syntax-check httpd.conf without restarting\nsystemctl reload httpd    # reload config without dropping active connections"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"example","html":"\u003ch4\u003eTwo sites on one server using named virtual hosts\u003c/h4\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAdd two VirtualHost blocks (in \u003ccode\u003ehttpd.conf\u003c/code\u003e or an include file):\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode\u003e&lt;VirtualHost *:80&gt;\n    ServerName site-a.com\n    DocumentRoot /var/www/a\n&lt;/VirtualHost&gt;\n&lt;VirtualHost *:80&gt;\n    ServerName site-b.com\n    DocumentRoot /var/www/b\n&lt;/VirtualHost&gt;\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCreate document roots: \u003ccode\u003emkdir -p /var/www/{a,b}\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDrop an \u003ccode\u003eindex.html\u003c/code\u003e in each directory.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eRun \u003ccode\u003ehttpd -S\u003c/code\u003e — both vhosts should appear in the output with their \u003ccode\u003eServerName\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eDocumentRoot\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eApache matches the incoming \u003ccode\u003eHost:\u003c/code\u003e header to \u003ccode\u003eServerName\u003c/code\u003e. A request for \u003ccode\u003esite-a.com\u003c/code\u003e lands in \u003ccode\u003e/var/www/a\u003c/code\u003e; a request for \u003ccode\u003esite-b.com\u003c/code\u003e lands in \u003ccode\u003e/var/www/b\u003c/code\u003e. An unrecognized hostname falls back to the Main Server section.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"#### Two sites on one server using named virtual hosts\n1. Add two VirtualHost blocks (in `httpd.conf` or an include file):\n   ```\n   \u003cVirtualHost *:80\u003e\n       ServerName site-a.com\n       DocumentRoot /var/www/a\n   \u003c/VirtualHost\u003e\n   \u003cVirtualHost *:80\u003e\n       ServerName site-b.com\n       DocumentRoot /var/www/b\n   \u003c/VirtualHost\u003e\n   ```\n2. Create document roots: `mkdir -p /var/www/{a,b}`.\n3. Drop an `index.html` in each directory.\n4. Run `httpd -S` — both vhosts should appear in the output with their `ServerName` and `DocumentRoot`.\n5. Apache matches the incoming `Host:` header to `ServerName`. A request for `site-a.com` lands in `/var/www/a`; a request for `site-b.com` lands in `/var/www/b`. An unrecognized hostname falls back to the Main Server section."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A `\u003cDirectory\u003e` block has `AllowOverride None`. A `.htaccess` file exists in that directory. What does Apache do with it?","a":"Apache ignores it entirely — the file is not even read. To enable per-directory overrides, set `AllowOverride All` (or a specific directive list) in the `\u003cDirectory\u003e` block for that path."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"`httpd -S` shows your second VirtualHost is missing. What two things do you check first?","a":"Run `httpd -t` — a syntax error in the VirtualHost block causes it to be skipped silently. Also verify the `ServerName` directive is present inside the block; Apache cannot register an anonymous vhost."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall.\u003c/strong\u003e iptables rules are evaluated top-to-bottom and \u003cstrong\u003efirst match wins\u003c/strong\u003e. A common mistake is appending an ACCEPT rule for a specific port \u003cem\u003eafter\u003c/em\u003e a blanket DROP rule already in the chain — the DROP fires first and the ACCEPT is never reached. Always append permissive rules before the default-deny, or use \u003ccode\u003e-I\u003c/code\u003e to insert at the top of the chain. Run \u003ccode\u003eiptables -L INPUT -v -n --line-numbers\u003c/code\u003e to see the current order before adding rules.","text":"**Pitfall.** iptables rules are evaluated top-to-bottom and **first match wins**. A common mistake is appending an ACCEPT rule for a specific port *after* a blanket DROP rule already in the chain — the DROP fires first and the ACCEPT is never reached. Always append permissive rules before the default-deny, or use `-I` to insert at the top of the chain. Run `iptables -L INPUT -v -n --line-numbers` to see the current order before adding rules."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway.\u003c/strong\u003e DNS, iptables, and Apache each follow the same pattern: one main config file, a strict hierarchy of sections or chains, and a small vocabulary of keywords you cannot abbreviate or reorder. For the exam know: daemon names (\u003ccode\u003enamed\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ehttpd\u003c/code\u003e), config paths (\u003ccode\u003e/etc/named.conf\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e/etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf\u003c/code\u003e), the seven DNS record types by abbreviation and direction, the three iptables tables and five chains, which table+chain pair handles DNAT (nat/PREROUTING) vs SNAT (nat/POSTROUTING), and the three Apache config sections in their inheritance order (Global → Main → VirtualHost → Directory → .htaccess).","text":"**Takeaway.** DNS, iptables, and Apache each follow the same pattern: one main config file, a strict hierarchy of sections or chains, and a small vocabulary of keywords you cannot abbreviate or reorder. For the exam know: daemon names (`named`, `httpd`), config paths (`/etc/named.conf`, `/etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf`), the seven DNS record types by abbreviation and direction, the three iptables tables and five chains, which table+chain pair handles DNAT (nat/PREROUTING) vs SNAT (nat/POSTROUTING), and the three Apache config sections in their inheritance order (Global → Main → VirtualHost → Directory → .htaccess)."},{"kind":"p","html":"Sources: Mod08 DNS Ch24 iptables ch25 Apache ch26.pdf","text":"Sources: Mod08 DNS Ch24 iptables ch25 Apache ch26.pdf"}]},{"n":10,"id":"4915-lesson-containers-pods-kubernetes","title":"Containers, Pods, Kubernetes","hook":"All of Quiz 4 was K8s. Expect similar weight on final. This lesson is the anchor.","tags":["kubernetes"],"module":"Kubernetes & containers","source":"Mod10A-E; materials/labs/Lab9.pdf, Lab10.pdf; materials/past-exams/comp4915_quiz4.md","blocks":[{"kind":"h2","html":"Start here — one concrete scenario, then we generalize","text":"Start here — one concrete scenario, then we generalize"},{"kind":"p","html":"&quot;Zeus&#39; Zap&quot; is an energy-drink company. Their product is a three-tier web app:","text":"\"Zeus' Zap\" is an energy-drink company. Their product is a three-tier web app:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eFront end\u003c/strong\u003e — static JavaScript served by Nginx.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMiddle\u003c/strong\u003e — two Python microservices hosted by Django.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBackend\u003c/strong\u003e — CockroachDB listening on port 6379, backed by persistent storage.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **Front end** — static JavaScript served by Nginx.\n- **Middle** — two Python microservices hosted by Django.\n- **Backend** — CockroachDB listening on port 6379, backed by persistent storage."},{"kind":"p","html":"A junior engineer tries to run the whole thing on one Linux box with plain \u003ccode\u003edocker run\u003c/code\u003e:","text":"A junior engineer tries to run the whole thing on one Linux box with plain `docker run`:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"console","code":"$ docker run -t -i ui             -p 80:80\n$ docker run -t -i microservice-a -p 8080:8080\n$ docker run -t -i microservice-b -p 8081:8081\n$ docker run -t -i cockroach      -p 6379:6379"},{"kind":"p","html":"Before reading on, predict what goes wrong on day two. Write down everything you can think of, or say &quot;I&#39;m not sure yet.&quot;","text":"Before reading on, predict what goes wrong on day two. Write down everything you can think of, or say \"I'm not sure yet.\""},{"kind":"p","html":"Four things go wrong, and each one drags in a feature of Kubernetes:","text":"Four things go wrong, and each one drags in a feature of Kubernetes:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePort 80 is already bound\u003c/strong\u003e by something else on the host. You need \u003cem\u003eservice-aware load balancing\u003c/em\u003e — a stable front door that survives port conflicts.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eThe DB container dies.\u003c/strong\u003e Its replacement gets a new IP. Every microservice that cached the old IP now fails. You need \u003cem\u003eservice discovery\u003c/em\u003e that follows containers when they move.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eThe DB moves to another host.\u003c/strong\u003e Its data does not move with it. You need \u003cem\u003estorage that follows the process\u003c/em\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eOne microservice forks a million goroutines\u003c/strong\u003e and starves the others. You need \u003cem\u003eresource limits the kernel actually enforces\u003c/em\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. **Port 80 is already bound** by something else on the host. You need *service-aware load balancing* — a stable front door that survives port conflicts.\n2. **The DB container dies.** Its replacement gets a new IP. Every microservice that cached the old IP now fails. You need *service discovery* that follows containers when they move.\n3. **The DB moves to another host.** Its data does not move with it. You need *storage that follows the process*.\n4. **One microservice forks a million goroutines** and starves the others. You need *resource limits the kernel actually enforces*."},{"kind":"p","html":"Kubernetes is the answer to all four. But the answer is not magic cloud glue — it is three old Linux kernel features (\u003cstrong\u003enamespaces\u003c/strong\u003e, \u003cstrong\u003ecgroups\u003c/strong\u003e, \u003cstrong\u003echroot / pivot_root\u003c/strong\u003e) plus a scheduler and a handful of reconcile loops on top. Once you see those three kernel features, the rest of Kubernetes — pods, pause, kubelet, CNI, QoS — stops being a vocabulary list and becomes predictable.","text":"Kubernetes is the answer to all four. But the answer is not magic cloud glue — it is three old Linux kernel features (**namespaces**, **cgroups**, **chroot / pivot_root**) plus a scheduler and a handful of reconcile loops on top. Once you see those three kernel features, the rest of Kubernetes — pods, pause, kubelet, CNI, QoS — stops being a vocabulary list and becomes predictable."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The infrastructure-drift problem — why declarative config wins","text":"The infrastructure-drift problem — why declarative config wins"},{"kind":"p","html":"Before containers, a production server was &quot;a pet.&quot; Someone SSH&#39;d in, \u003ccode\u003eapt install\u003c/code\u003e&#39;d a Java version, dropped jars in \u003ccode\u003e/opt\u003c/code\u003e, tweaked \u003ccode\u003esysctl.conf\u003c/code\u003e, edited \u003ccode\u003e/etc/httpd/conf\u003c/code\u003e. Six months later nobody remembers which change did what. When the server dies, its replacement does not behave the same. This is \u003cstrong\u003einfrastructure drift\u003c/strong\u003e: the real configuration of a running system slowly diverges from any document that describes it. Apps that used to work stop working, and no one knows why.","text":"Before containers, a production server was \"a pet.\" Someone SSH'd in, `apt install`'d a Java version, dropped jars in `/opt`, tweaked `sysctl.conf`, edited `/etc/httpd/conf`. Six months later nobody remembers which change did what. When the server dies, its replacement does not behave the same. This is **infrastructure drift**: the real configuration of a running system slowly diverges from any document that describes it. Apps that used to work stop working, and no one knows why."},{"kind":"p","html":"Kubernetes fixes drift by writing \u003cem\u003eeverything\u003c/em\u003e down in YAML and putting a kernel-scale robot in charge of enforcing it:","text":"Kubernetes fixes drift by writing *everything* down in YAML and putting a kernel-scale robot in charge of enforcing it:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eEvery running thing — a pod, a service, a volume, a network rule — is an \u003cstrong\u003eAPI object\u003c/strong\u003e. Each object has \u003ccode\u003eapiVersion\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ekind\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003emetadata\u003c/code\u003e, and a \u003ccode\u003espec\u003c/code\u003e that says what you \u003cem\u003ewant\u003c/em\u003e. A \u003ccode\u003estatus\u003c/code\u003e block shows what is actually there.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eYou write YAML and hand it to \u003ccode\u003ekubectl apply\u003c/code\u003e. The YAML goes to \u003ccode\u003ekube-apiserver\u003c/code\u003e, which stores it in \u003ccode\u003eetcd\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eA set of reconcile loops watches \u003ccode\u003eetcd\u003c/code\u003e and works to make status match spec. Pod disappears → loop schedules a new one. Spec says three replicas and you count two → loop creates one more.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- Every running thing — a pod, a service, a volume, a network rule — is an **API object**. Each object has `apiVersion`, `kind`, `metadata`, and a `spec` that says what you *want*. A `status` block shows what is actually there.\n- You write YAML and hand it to `kubectl apply`. The YAML goes to `kube-apiserver`, which stores it in `etcd`.\n- A set of reconcile loops watches `etcd` and works to make status match spec. Pod disappears → loop schedules a new one. Spec says three replicas and you count two → loop creates one more."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You run `kubectl apply -f pod.yaml` and the target node is already overloaded. Kubernetes schedules the pod somewhere else. Which component detected the overload, and which one wrote the replacement binding?","a":"`kube-scheduler` watches apiserver for Pending pods and scores each node (resource fit, taints, affinity). It picks a healthier node and writes the binding back to `etcd` via apiserver. The chosen node's **kubelet** sees \"pod assigned to me\" on its watch and starts work via the runtime."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Three Linux primitives — the whole tower rests on these","text":"Three Linux primitives — the whole tower rests on these"},{"kind":"p","html":"Every container on every Linux host on earth is built on three kernel features:","text":"Every container on every Linux host on earth is built on three kernel features:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eNamespaces\u003c/strong\u003e — give the process an isolated \u003cem\u003eview\u003c/em\u003e of kernel resources (its own PID tree, its own network, its own hostname).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ecgroups\u003c/strong\u003e — \u003cem\u003ecap\u003c/em\u003e what the process can actually consume (CPU, memory, I/O, PIDs).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003echroot / pivot_root\u003c/strong\u003e — restrict which files the process can \u003cem\u003esee\u003c/em\u003e by re-rooting its filesystem.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. **Namespaces** — give the process an isolated *view* of kernel resources (its own PID tree, its own network, its own hostname).\n2. **cgroups** — *cap* what the process can actually consume (CPU, memory, I/O, PIDs).\n3. **chroot / pivot_root** — restrict which files the process can *see* by re-rooting its filesystem."},{"kind":"p","html":"Kubernetes adds the scheduler, \u003ccode\u003eetcd\u003c/code\u003e, apiserver, and reconcile loops on top. But the isolation itself is still these three primitives, running inside the kernel of every worker node. The scheduler decides \u003cem\u003ewhere\u003c/em\u003e a container runs; the three primitives decide \u003cem\u003ewhat it can see and use\u003c/em\u003e.","text":"Kubernetes adds the scheduler, `etcd`, apiserver, and reconcile loops on top. But the isolation itself is still these three primitives, running inside the kernel of every worker node. The scheduler decides *where* a container runs; the three primitives decide *what it can see and use*."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAnalogy — apartment building.\u003c/strong\u003e Namespaces are the walls (you can&#39;t see the neighbor&#39;s rooms). cgroups are the utility meters (you can&#39;t use more power than you rented). chroot is the front door (once inside, you don&#39;t know the rest of the building exists).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"Linux namespaces — isolate the view","text":"Linux namespaces — isolate the view"},{"kind":"p","html":"A \u003cstrong\u003enamespace\u003c/strong\u003e is a kernel feature that gives a process its own private slice of a global resource. Inside the namespace, the process sees only what was placed in that namespace — the host&#39;s version is hidden.","text":"A **namespace** is a kernel feature that gives a process its own private slice of a global resource. Inside the namespace, the process sees only what was placed in that namespace — the host's version is hidden."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eEight types exist\u003c/strong\u003e (all exam-tested):","text":"**Eight types exist** (all exam-tested):"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eName\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eIsolates\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eKernel since\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePID\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eprocess IDs — own PID 1\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e3.8\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eNET\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003enetwork interfaces, routing, iptables, ports\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e3.0\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMNT\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003emount points — own view of the filesystem tree\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e3.8\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUTS\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ehostname, NIS domain name\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e3.0\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIPC\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSystem V IPC, POSIX queues\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e3.0\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUSER\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eUID/GID mapping — unprivileged host user can be root inside\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e3.8\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCGROUP\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eview of the cgroup hierarchy\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e4.6\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTIME\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eboot and monotonic clock offset\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e5.6\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Tools that operate on namespaces:","text":"Tools that operate on namespaces:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eunshare --&lt;flag&gt; program\u003c/code\u003e — run \u003ccode\u003eprogram\u003c/code\u003e in a fresh namespace.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ensenter -t &lt;pid&gt; -n -m …\u003c/code\u003e — join an existing process&#39;s namespaces by PID.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003elsns\u003c/code\u003e — list every namespace on the host.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- `unshare --\u003cflag\u003e program` — run `program` in a fresh namespace.\n- `nsenter -t \u003cpid\u003e -n -m …` — join an existing process's namespaces by PID.\n- `lsns` — list every namespace on the host."},{"kind":"p","html":"In Lab 10 §13 you ran \u003ccode\u003ensenter -at 1847 /bin/sh\u003c/code\u003e and entered the exact namespaces of a running container process — bypassing \u003ccode\u003ekubectl\u003c/code\u003e entirely and going straight to the kernel.","text":"In Lab 10 §13 you ran `nsenter -at 1847 /bin/sh` and entered the exact namespaces of a running container process — bypassing `kubectl` entirely and going straight to the kernel."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You open a shell inside a container and run `ps aux`. You see exactly two processes: PID 1 (your app) and PID 2 (ps itself). On the node outside, the very same app process has PID 1847. Which namespace produces this effect, and why does the PID differ?","a":"The **PID namespace**. Each PID namespace has its own process tree starting at PID 1. The kernel transparently maps host-side PID 1847 to container-side PID 1 — one process, two PID numbers depending on which namespace you observe from. Lab 10 §21 confirmed this: inside the pod, `ps` showed two processes; on the node, `ps aux` showed the same `sleep` as PID 1847."},{"kind":"h2","html":"cgroups — cap what the process consumes","text":"cgroups — cap what the process consumes"},{"kind":"p","html":"A \u003cstrong\u003ecgroup\u003c/strong\u003e (control group) is a kernel accounting and enforcement mechanism. You place a set of processes into a cgroup, then set hard caps on what resources they may use:","text":"A **cgroup** (control group) is a kernel accounting and enforcement mechanism. You place a set of processes into a cgroup, then set hard caps on what resources they may use:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCPU\u003c/strong\u003e — \u003cem\u003eshares\u003c/em\u003e (soft weight under contention) and \u003cem\u003equotas\u003c/em\u003e (hard throttle via CFS bandwidth control: N ms of CPU per 100 ms period, then the scheduler freezes the process).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMemory\u003c/strong\u003e — hard limit; the OOM killer fires when the process exceeds it.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eI/O\u003c/strong\u003e — read/write bandwidth per block device.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePIDs\u003c/strong\u003e — maximum number of processes in the group.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **CPU** — *shares* (soft weight under contention) and *quotas* (hard throttle via CFS bandwidth control: N ms of CPU per 100 ms period, then the scheduler freezes the process).\n- **Memory** — hard limit; the OOM killer fires when the process exceeds it.\n- **I/O** — read/write bandwidth per block device.\n- **PIDs** — maximum number of processes in the group."},{"kind":"p","html":"Two generations of the API coexist: \u003cstrong\u003ev1\u003c/strong\u003e uses a separate hierarchy per subsystem (one tree for CPU, another for memory); \u003cstrong\u003ev2\u003c/strong\u003e unifies everything under \u003ccode\u003e/sys/fs/cgroup/\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003ekind\u003c/code\u003e uses v2; current OKD uses v1. Check with \u003ccode\u003emount | grep cgroup\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Two generations of the API coexist: **v1** uses a separate hierarchy per subsystem (one tree for CPU, another for memory); **v2** unifies everything under `/sys/fs/cgroup/`. `kind` uses v2; current OKD uses v1. Check with `mount | grep cgroup`."},{"kind":"p","html":"Kubernetes uses cgroups to enforce the \u003ccode\u003eresources.requests\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003eresources.limits\u003c/code\u003e on a pod. \u003cstrong\u003eRequests\u003c/strong\u003e feed the scheduler (placement); \u003cstrong\u003elimits\u003c/strong\u003e feed the kernel (runtime enforcement).","text":"Kubernetes uses cgroups to enforce the `resources.requests` and `resources.limits` on a pod. **Requests** feed the scheduler (placement); **limits** feed the kernel (runtime enforcement)."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A pod has `resources.limits.cpu: 100m`. You run `dd if=/dev/zero of=/dev/null` inside it. On the node you observe ~10% CPU usage, even though the node has spare capacity. Why exactly 10%?","a":"`100m` = 100 millicores = 0.1 CPU. The CFS bandwidth controller gives the cgroup a budget of 10 ms per 100 ms scheduling period. Once the 10 ms is spent, the process is throttled regardless of available CPU. Lab 10 §19 reproduced this exactly — `dd` pegged at ~10% while the node was otherwise idle."},{"kind":"h2","html":"chroot / pivot_root — the filesystem jail (and why it is not enough alone)","text":"chroot / pivot_root — the filesystem jail (and why it is not enough alone)"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003echroot\u003c/strong\u003e changes a process&#39;s root directory to a subdirectory. After \u003ccode\u003echroot /jail /bin/bash\u003c/code\u003e, the process believes \u003ccode\u003e/jail\u003c/code\u003e is \u003ccode\u003e/\u003c/code\u003e — it cannot \u003ccode\u003ecd ..\u003c/code\u003e past the new root or read files outside the subtree. Container runtimes use \u003ccode\u003epivot_root\u003c/code\u003e (atomic, more robust) but the effect is the same.","text":"**chroot** changes a process's root directory to a subdirectory. After `chroot /jail /bin/bash`, the process believes `/jail` is `/` — it cannot `cd ..` past the new root or read files outside the subtree. Container runtimes use `pivot_root` (atomic, more robust) but the effect is the same."},{"kind":"p","html":"Lab 10 taught an important \u003cem\u003enegative\u003c/em\u003e result: \u003cstrong\u003echroot alone is not isolation.\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"Lab 10 taught an important *negative* result: **chroot alone is not isolation.**"},{"kind":"p","html":"In §7a you entered the jail and ran \u003ccode\u003eps aux\u003c/code\u003e. You expected only jail processes. You saw fifty — including \u003ccode\u003eetcd\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003ekube-apiserver\u003c/code\u003e. The reason: chroot restricts only the filesystem view. The PID namespace was still shared with the host, and \u003ccode\u003e/proc\u003c/code\u003e was bind-mounted in from the host, so \u003ccode\u003eps\u003c/code\u003e read the real kernel process table.","text":"In §7a you entered the jail and ran `ps aux`. You expected only jail processes. You saw fifty — including `etcd` and `kube-apiserver`. The reason: chroot restricts only the filesystem view. The PID namespace was still shared with the host, and `/proc` was bind-mounted in from the host, so `ps` read the real kernel process table."},{"kind":"p","html":"Combine all three — a \u003cstrong\u003eMNT\u003c/strong\u003e namespace with \u003ccode\u003epivot_root\u003c/code\u003e, a \u003cstrong\u003ePID\u003c/strong\u003e namespace, and \u003cstrong\u003ecgroups\u003c/strong\u003e — and the process lives in what feels like its own machine while the kernel enforces strict resource caps. \u003cstrong\u003eThat combination is the definition of &quot;container.&quot;\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"Combine all three — a **MNT** namespace with `pivot_root`, a **PID** namespace, and **cgroups** — and the process lives in what feels like its own machine while the kernel enforces strict resource caps. **That combination is the definition of \"container.\"**"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"In Lab 10 you entered a chroot jail and ran `ps aux`. You expected only jail processes but saw ~50, including `kube-apiserver`. What did you miss, and how is it fixed in a real container?","a":"chroot restricts the filesystem root but doesn't touch the PID namespace. Because `/proc` was bind-mounted into the jail from the host, `ps` read the real process table. Real containers add a **PID namespace** (`unshare --pid`) plus a **MNT namespace** that supplies its own `/proc`, making host processes invisible."},{"kind":"h2","html":"OCI images — what actually gets shipped","text":"OCI images — what actually gets shipped"},{"kind":"p","html":"A \u003cstrong\u003econtainer image\u003c/strong\u003e is the frozen filesystem-and-metadata that the runtime unpacks and runs. The spec is the \u003cstrong\u003eOpen Container Initiative\u003c/strong\u003e (OCI) image format. An image is a stack of tar-file \u003cstrong\u003elayers\u003c/strong\u003e plus a manifest saying which layer is the base, which goes on top, and what command to run.","text":"A **container image** is the frozen filesystem-and-metadata that the runtime unpacks and runs. The spec is the **Open Container Initiative** (OCI) image format. An image is a stack of tar-file **layers** plus a manifest saying which layer is the base, which goes on top, and what command to run."},{"kind":"p","html":"Docker was one runtime that produces and consumes OCI images. \u003ccode\u003econtainerd\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ecri-o\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003erunc\u003c/code\u003e are the runtimes Kubernetes actually uses today (Docker&#39;s direct K8s integration was deprecated). The Dockerfile grammar (\u003ccode\u003eFROM\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eRUN\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eCOPY\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eCMD\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eENTRYPOINT\u003c/code\u003e) is the most common way to \u003cem\u003eproduce\u003c/em\u003e an image, but Kubernetes itself never runs \u003ccode\u003edocker\u003c/code\u003e. It asks the CRI runtime to pull the image and start a container.","text":"Docker was one runtime that produces and consumes OCI images. `containerd`, `cri-o`, and `runc` are the runtimes Kubernetes actually uses today (Docker's direct K8s integration was deprecated). The Dockerfile grammar (`FROM`, `RUN`, `COPY`, `CMD`, `ENTRYPOINT`) is the most common way to *produce* an image, but Kubernetes itself never runs `docker`. It asks the CRI runtime to pull the image and start a container."},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eQuiz 4 Q2 — container images use the OCI format.\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"h2","html":"The Pod — a group of containers that share \u003cem\u003esome\u003c/em\u003e namespaces","text":"The Pod — a group of containers that share *some* namespaces"},{"kind":"p","html":"A \u003cstrong\u003ePod\u003c/strong\u003e is Kubernetes&#39;s smallest deployable unit. One pod is one or more containers that \u003cem\u003eshare\u003c/em\u003e a carefully chosen subset of Linux namespaces:","text":"A **Pod** is Kubernetes's smallest deployable unit. One pod is one or more containers that *share* a carefully chosen subset of Linux namespaces:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eShared across the whole pod\u003c/strong\u003e: NET, IPC, UTS.\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSame network interface, same IP, same hostname. Containers reach each other on \u003ccode\u003elocalhost\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePer container\u003c/strong\u003e: MNT, PID. Each container ships its own rootfs image and its own process tree.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **Shared across the whole pod**: NET, IPC, UTS.\n  - Same network interface, same IP, same hostname. Containers reach each other on `localhost`.\n- **Per container**: MNT, PID. Each container ships its own rootfs image and its own process tree."},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"flowchart LR\n  subgraph POD[\"POD — shares NET / IPC / UTS\"]\n    direction LR\n    PAUSE[\"pause\u003cbr/\u003eholds NET/IPC/UTS ns\u003cbr/\u003eowns the pod IP\"]\n    APP1[\"app-1\u003cbr/\u003ejoins pause ns\u003cbr/\u003eown MNT + own PID\"]\n    APP2[\"app-2\u003cbr/\u003ejoins pause ns\u003cbr/\u003eown MNT + own PID\"]\n  end\n  APP1 \u003c-- localhost --\u003e APP2\n  APP1 \u003c-- localhost --\u003e PAUSE\n  APP2 \u003c-- localhost --\u003e PAUSE\n  classDef pause fill:#201c15,stroke:#e0af68,color:#e0af68\n  classDef app fill:#1a2218,stroke:#9ece6a,color:#9ece6a\n  class PAUSE pause\n  class APP1,APP2 app"},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eApartment analogy.\u003c/strong\u003e The \u003cstrong\u003epause container\u003c/strong\u003e signs the lease — it is the first container created in the pod, and it holds the NET/IPC/UTS namespace file descriptors open. Other containers in the pod are roommates who move into the same apartment: they share the kitchen (NET), the mail slot (IPC), and the doorbell (UTS). Each has their own bedroom (MNT) and their own to-do list (PID). If the lease-holder walks out, the apartment dissolves — kill pause and the whole pod is recreated.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What is the pause container's job? (Quiz 4 Q10)","a":"Almost nothing — deliberately. It is the first container created in every pod. Its only job is to hold the NET, IPC, and UTS namespace file descriptors open so later containers in the pod can join them. It also receives the pod IP from the CNI plugin. If pause dies, the pod loses its namespace anchor and is recreated."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Pod bootstrap — five steps from YAML to running app","text":"Pod bootstrap — five steps from YAML to running app"},{"kind":"p","html":"This is the single most-tested sequence. Memorize the order and what primitive each step uses.","text":"This is the single most-tested sequence. Memorize the order and what primitive each step uses."},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"flowchart LR\n  S1[\"1. Schedule\u003cbr/\u003escheduler binds\u003cbr/\u003epod → node\"]\n  S2[\"2. Pause\u003cbr/\u003econtainerd unshares\u003cbr/\u003eNET/IPC/UTS\"]\n  S3[\"3. CNI\u003cbr/\u003eplugin assigns pod IP\u003cbr/\u003einto pause NET ns\"]\n  S4[\"4. Init\u003cbr/\u003einit containers join ns\u003cbr/\u003erun to exit 0\"]\n  S5[\"5. App\u003cbr/\u003eapp containers join\u003cbr/\u003eNET/IPC/UTS\"]\n  S1 --\u003e S2 --\u003e S3 --\u003e S4 --\u003e S5\n  classDef blue fill:#181822,stroke:#7aa2f7,color:#e5e5e5\n  classDef amber fill:#201c15,stroke:#e0af68,color:#e0af68\n  classDef gray fill:#181818,stroke:#262626,color:#e5e5e5\n  classDef green fill:#181a18,stroke:#9ece6a,color:#9ece6a\n  class S1 blue\n  class S2 amber\n  class S3 gray\n  class S4,S5 green"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSchedule.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003ekubectl apply\u003c/code\u003e sends the manifest to apiserver, which validates and writes a \u003ccode\u003ePending\u003c/code\u003e pod to etcd. \u003ccode\u003ekube-scheduler\u003c/code\u003e watches etcd, scores every node (resource fit + taints + affinity), picks one, and writes the binding back. The chosen node&#39;s kubelet is watching apiserver and sees &quot;this pod is mine.&quot;\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePause container.\u003c/strong\u003e kubelet asks the CRI runtime (containerd) to pull and start the \u003cstrong\u003epause\u003c/strong\u003e image. containerd calls \u003ccode\u003eunshare\u003c/code\u003e to create fresh NET, IPC, and UTS namespaces, starts the tiny pause binary inside them, and returns a container ID. Pause blocks waiting for a signal and does nothing else.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCNI.\u003c/strong\u003e kubelet invokes the configured CNI plugin (Calico, Cilium, Flannel, kindnet, …). The plugin allocates a pod IP from the cluster CIDR, creates a virtual-Ethernet (\u003ccode\u003eveth\u003c/code\u003e) pair, drops one end inside pause&#39;s NET namespace with the IP assigned, and hooks the other end to the node&#39;s bridge or routing table. The pod now has a \u003cstrong\u003ecluster-routable IP\u003c/strong\u003e reachable from any node without NAT. Lab 9 §20 showed the pod&#39;s \u003ccode\u003eresolv.conf\u003c/code\u003e pointing to CoreDNS at \u003ccode\u003e10.96.0.10\u003c/code\u003e — CNI sets that per-pod nameserver at this step.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eInit containers.\u003c/strong\u003e Any \u003ccode\u003einitContainers\u003c/code\u003e launch one at a time. Each joins pause&#39;s NET/IPC/UTS but gets its own MNT. They must exit 0 before the next starts. Used for migrations, secret fetching, any setup that must complete before the app.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eApp containers.\u003c/strong\u003e Finally the containers you care about start. Each joins pause&#39;s NET/IPC/UTS and gets its own MNT/PID. Because they all share NET, they talk to each other on \u003ccode\u003elocalhost\u003c/code\u003e — the pod IP is the address on their shared \u003ccode\u003eeth0\u003c/code\u003e inside pause&#39;s NET namespace.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1. **Schedule.** `kubectl apply` sends the manifest to apiserver, which validates and writes a `Pending` pod to etcd. `kube-scheduler` watches etcd, scores every node (resource fit + taints + affinity), picks one, and writes the binding back. The chosen node's kubelet is watching apiserver and sees \"this pod is mine.\"\n2. **Pause container.** kubelet asks the CRI runtime (containerd) to pull and start the **pause** image. containerd calls `unshare` to create fresh NET, IPC, and UTS namespaces, starts the tiny pause binary inside them, and returns a container ID. Pause blocks waiting for a signal and does nothing else.\n3. **CNI.** kubelet invokes the configured CNI plugin (Calico, Cilium, Flannel, kindnet, …). The plugin allocates a pod IP from the cluster CIDR, creates a virtual-Ethernet (`veth`) pair, drops one end inside pause's NET namespace with the IP assigned, and hooks the other end to the node's bridge or routing table. The pod now has a **cluster-routable IP** reachable from any node without NAT. Lab 9 §20 showed the pod's `resolv.conf` pointing to CoreDNS at `10.96.0.10` — CNI sets that per-pod nameserver at this step.\n4. **Init containers.** Any `initContainers` launch one at a time. Each joins pause's NET/IPC/UTS but gets its own MNT. They must exit 0 before the next starts. Used for migrations, secret fetching, any setup that must complete before the app.\n5. **App containers.** Finally the containers you care about start. Each joins pause's NET/IPC/UTS and gets its own MNT/PID. Because they all share NET, they talk to each other on `localhost` — the pod IP is the address on their shared `eth0` inside pause's NET namespace."},{"kind":"p","html":"Lab 10 §12 confirmed the process hierarchy on the node: \u003ccode\u003econtainerd-shim (PID 1780) → pause (1810), sleep (1847)\u003c/code\u003e. Pause and the app container are siblings under the same shim, exactly steps 2 and 5.","text":"Lab 10 §12 confirmed the process hierarchy on the node: `containerd-shim (PID 1780) → pause (1810), sleep (1847)`. Pause and the app container are siblings under the same shim, exactly steps 2 and 5."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Cluster anatomy — control plane + workers","text":"Cluster anatomy — control plane + workers"},{"kind":"p","html":"Strip names away and a Kubernetes cluster is two layers of machines.","text":"Strip names away and a Kubernetes cluster is two layers of machines."},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"flowchart TB\n  subgraph CP[\"CONTROL PLANE (1 or 3 nodes for HA)\"]\n    direction LR\n    API[\"kube-apiserver\u003cbr/\u003eREST · auth · only external door\"]\n    ETCD[\"etcd\u003cbr/\u003ekey/value store\u003cbr/\u003esingle source of truth\"]\n    SCHED[\"kube-scheduler\u003cbr/\u003ebinds Pending pods → nodes\"]\n    CTRL[\"kube-controller-manager\u003cbr/\u003ereconcile loops\"]\n  end\n  subgraph WN[\"WORKER NODE (many)\"]\n    direction TB\n    KUBELET[\"kubelet\u003cbr/\u003enode agent (Quiz 4 Q1)\"]\n    KPROXY[\"kube-proxy\u003cbr/\u003eService routing via iptables\"]\n    CRUN[\"container runtime\u003cbr/\u003econtainerd / cri-o\"]\n    POD1[\"Pod A\"]\n    POD2[\"Pod B\"]\n    KUBELET --\u003e CRUN\n    CRUN --\u003e POD1\n    CRUN --\u003e POD2\n  end\n  SCHED -. bind pod→node .-\u003e KUBELET\n  KUBELET \u003c-- watch/status --\u003e API\n  API \u003c--\u003e ETCD\n  classDef cp fill:#181822,stroke:#7aa2f7,color:#e5e5e5\n  classDef node fill:#1a1a1a,stroke:#262626,color:#e5e5e5\n  class API,ETCD,SCHED,CTRL cp\n  class KUBELET,KPROXY,CRUN,POD1,POD2 node"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eControl plane — &quot;the brain.&quot;\u003c/strong\u003e Runs on one or three &quot;control plane nodes&quot; (OKD runs three for fault tolerance).","text":"**Control plane — \"the brain.\"** Runs on one or three \"control plane nodes\" (OKD runs three for fault tolerance)."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ekube-apiserver\u003c/code\u003e — HTTP REST server, the only external entry point. Every other component talks through it.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eetcd\u003c/code\u003e — distributed key/value store. The \u003cem\u003eonly\u003c/em\u003e place cluster state lives. Lose etcd, lose the cluster.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ekube-scheduler\u003c/code\u003e — watches for Pending pods, scores nodes, writes the binding.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ekube-controller-manager\u003c/code\u003e (k-c-m) — runs every reconcile loop (ReplicaSet, Node, Job, …). Cloud-specific bits are being split into \u003ccode\u003ecloud-controller-manager\u003c/code\u003e (c-c-m) so Kubernetes stays vendor-neutral. \u003cstrong\u003eQuiz 4 Q5.\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- `kube-apiserver` — HTTP REST server, the only external entry point. Every other component talks through it.\n- `etcd` — distributed key/value store. The *only* place cluster state lives. Lose etcd, lose the cluster.\n- `kube-scheduler` — watches for Pending pods, scores nodes, writes the binding.\n- `kube-controller-manager` (k-c-m) — runs every reconcile loop (ReplicaSet, Node, Job, …). Cloud-specific bits are being split into `cloud-controller-manager` (c-c-m) so Kubernetes stays vendor-neutral. **Quiz 4 Q5.**"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eWorker node — &quot;the muscle.&quot;\u003c/strong\u003e One Linux box per node, running:","text":"**Worker node — \"the muscle.\"** One Linux box per node, running:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ekubelet\u003c/code\u003e — the agent. Watches apiserver for pods assigned to this node, tells the runtime via \u003cstrong\u003eCRI\u003c/strong\u003e (Container Runtime Interface) to create containers, and tells the \u003cstrong\u003eCNI\u003c/strong\u003e (Container Networking Interface) plugin to wire them into the pod network. Reports status back to apiserver. \u003cstrong\u003eQuiz 4 Q1.\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ekube-proxy\u003c/code\u003e — implements Service routing. Writes iptables (or IPVS) rules on the node so traffic to a Service&#39;s ClusterIP is load-balanced across backing pods.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003econtainer runtime — \u003ccode\u003econtainerd\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003ecri-o\u003c/code\u003e. Actually calls \u003ccode\u003eunshare\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003epivot_root\u003c/code\u003e to make containers.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003esystemd\u003c/code\u003e on top, running kubelet and the runtime as services.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- `kubelet` — the agent. Watches apiserver for pods assigned to this node, tells the runtime via **CRI** (Container Runtime Interface) to create containers, and tells the **CNI** (Container Networking Interface) plugin to wire them into the pod network. Reports status back to apiserver. **Quiz 4 Q1.**\n- `kube-proxy` — implements Service routing. Writes iptables (or IPVS) rules on the node so traffic to a Service's ClusterIP is load-balanced across backing pods.\n- container runtime — `containerd` or `cri-o`. Actually calls `unshare` and `pivot_root` to make containers.\n- `systemd` on top, running kubelet and the runtime as services."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What is the kubelet's role? (Quiz 4 Q1)","a":"It is the agent on each worker node. It watches apiserver for pods assigned to its node, tells the container runtime via CRI to pull images and start containers, and reports health back. It is **not** the scheduler (which picks nodes) and **not** the controller-manager (which runs reconcile loops). Kubelet is the node-side executor."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Pod YAML — the smallest complete example","text":"Pod YAML — the smallest complete example"},{"kind":"code","lang":"yaml","code":"apiVersion: v1              # core API group — stable\nkind: Pod                   # resource type\nmetadata:\n  name: web\n  namespace: default        # K8s namespace — NOT a Linux namespace (see Pitfall)\n  labels:\n    app: web                # Services find pods through labels\nspec:                       # DESIRED STATE starts here (Quiz 4 Q6: image lives here)\n  containers:\n  - name: nginx\n    image: nginx:1.25       # OCI image reference (Quiz 4 Q2: OCI format)\n    ports:\n    - containerPort: 80\n    resources:\n      requests:             # cgroups minimum — scheduler uses this for placement\n        cpu: 100m           # 0.1 CPU\n        memory: 128Mi\n      limits:               # cgroups hard cap — OOM-killed if memory exceeded\n        cpu: 500m\n        memory: 512Mi\nstatus: {}                  # system-written; leave empty in your YAML"},{"kind":"p","html":"Because requests ≠ limits here, this pod is \u003cstrong\u003eBurstable\u003c/strong\u003e QoS. Lab 9 §19b: each pod gets its own IP from the cluster CIDR (e.g. \u003ccode\u003e10.244.0.5\u003c/code\u003e) — that IP lives on \u003ccode\u003eeth0\u003c/code\u003e inside pause&#39;s NET namespace. \u003cstrong\u003eQuiz 4 Q6\u003c/strong\u003e: the container image goes in \u003ccode\u003espec.containers[].image\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Because requests ≠ limits here, this pod is **Burstable** QoS. Lab 9 §19b: each pod gets its own IP from the cluster CIDR (e.g. `10.244.0.5`) — that IP lives on `eth0` inside pause's NET namespace. **Quiz 4 Q6**: the container image goes in `spec.containers[].image`."},{"kind":"h2","html":"QoS classes — derived from the YAML, decide who dies first","text":"QoS classes — derived from the YAML, decide who dies first"},{"kind":"p","html":"QoS is \u003cstrong\u003enot\u003c/strong\u003e something you declare. Kubernetes \u003cem\u003ederives\u003c/em\u003e it from the resource fields you wrote. Under memory pressure, lower-class pods are evicted first.","text":"QoS is **not** something you declare. Kubernetes *derives* it from the resource fields you wrote. Under memory pressure, lower-class pods are evicted first."},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eClass\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eRule\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eEvicted\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eGuaranteed\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eevery container has CPU \u003cem\u003eand\u003c/em\u003e memory \u003ccode\u003erequests == limits\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003elast\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBurstable\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eat least one container has a request or limit set, but doesn&#39;t meet Guaranteed\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003emiddle\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBestEffort\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ezero containers have any requests or limits\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003efirst\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"code","lang":"yaml","code":"# Guaranteed — CPU AND memory, requests equal limits, EVERY container\nrequests: {cpu: 500m, memory: 256Mi}\nlimits:   {cpu: 500m, memory: 256Mi}"},{"kind":"code","lang":"yaml","code":"# Burstable — set, but not equal (or only one resource specified)\nrequests: {cpu: 100m, memory: 128Mi}\nlimits:   {cpu: 500m, memory: 512Mi}"},{"kind":"code","lang":"yaml","code":"# BestEffort — nothing under resources on any container\n# (no resources block at all)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Lab 10 §21 tested all three classes end-to-end: \u003ccode\u003ekubectl get po core-k8s -o jsonpath=&#39;{.status.qosClass}&#39;\u003c/code\u003e returned \u003ccode\u003eBestEffort\u003c/code\u003e for the pod with no resources set.","text":"Lab 10 §21 tested all three classes end-to-end: `kubectl get po core-k8s -o jsonpath='{.status.qosClass}'` returned `BestEffort` for the pod with no resources set."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A pod spec has `requests.cpu: 100m` but no limits at all. What QoS class does Kubernetes assign?","a":"**Burstable.** At least one request is set → not BestEffort. But without limits, requests ≠ limits → not Guaranteed. Burstable is the middle class, evicted after BestEffort pods."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Workload controllers — which object runs which kind of workload","text":"Workload controllers — which object runs which kind of workload"},{"kind":"p","html":"A raw Pod is unmanaged. If it crashes, nothing recreates it. Lab 9 §18 confirmed this: the standalone \u003ccode\u003ecore-k8s\u003c/code\u003e pod, once deleted, was gone; the nginx Deployment&#39;s pods were immediately replaced by the ReplicaSet controller.","text":"A raw Pod is unmanaged. If it crashes, nothing recreates it. Lab 9 §18 confirmed this: the standalone `core-k8s` pod, once deleted, was gone; the nginx Deployment's pods were immediately replaced by the ReplicaSet controller."},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eController\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eShape\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eWhen to use\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDeployment\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003emanages a \u003cstrong\u003eReplicaSet\u003c/strong\u003e that manages N identical pods\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003estateless apps, rolling updates — most common (Quiz 4 Q4)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDaemonSet\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eexactly one pod per node, automatic on new nodes\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003enode-local agents: log shippers, node exporters, CNI plugins (Quiz 4 Q8)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eStatefulSet\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eordinal pod names (\u003ccode\u003edb-0\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003edb-1\u003c/code\u003e), stable DNS, persistent volumes\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003edatabases, queues\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eJob\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eruns until every pod exits 0, retries on failure\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eone-shot batch work\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCronJob\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eschedules a Job on a cron expression (\u003ccode\u003e&quot;0 2 * * *&quot;\u003c/code\u003e)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ebackups, nightly reports\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Which Kubernetes object runs exactly one pod on every node? (Quiz 4 Q8)","a":"**DaemonSet.** The controller automatically schedules its pod onto any new node that joins the cluster. All CNI plugins in the lab (kindnet, etc.) run as DaemonSets."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Services + CNI — how pods get found and reached","text":"Services + CNI — how pods get found and reached"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eEvery pod gets its own IP\u003c/strong\u003e from the cluster CIDR, reachable from any node without NAT. That is the CNI plugin&#39;s job at bootstrap step 3.","text":"**Every pod gets its own IP** from the cluster CIDR, reachable from any node without NAT. That is the CNI plugin's job at bootstrap step 3."},{"kind":"p","html":"A bare pod IP is not useful long-term: pods die and get new IPs. \u003cstrong\u003eServices\u003c/strong\u003e solve this by giving a stable virtual IP in front of a set of pods selected by label. Three service types:","text":"A bare pod IP is not useful long-term: pods die and get new IPs. **Services** solve this by giving a stable virtual IP in front of a set of pods selected by label. Three service types:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eClusterIP\u003c/strong\u003e (default) — a virtual IP reachable only inside the cluster. \u003ccode\u003ekube-proxy\u003c/code\u003e writes iptables rules so packets to the ClusterIP are DNAT&#39;d to one of the backing pod IPs.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eNodePort\u003c/strong\u003e — every node listens on a fixed high port (default range 30000–32767) and forwards to the same backing pods. Gives external reach without a cloud LB.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eLoadBalancer\u003c/strong\u003e — asks the cloud (via \u003ccode\u003ec-c-m\u003c/code\u003e) to provision an external load balancer whose backend is the NodePort. Production front door.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **ClusterIP** (default) — a virtual IP reachable only inside the cluster. `kube-proxy` writes iptables rules so packets to the ClusterIP are DNAT'd to one of the backing pod IPs.\n- **NodePort** — every node listens on a fixed high port (default range 30000–32767) and forwards to the same backing pods. Gives external reach without a cloud LB.\n- **LoadBalancer** — asks the cloud (via `c-c-m`) to provision an external load balancer whose backend is the NodePort. Production front door."},{"kind":"p","html":"Common CNI providers:","text":"Common CNI providers:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCalico\u003c/strong\u003e — L3 BGP routing, no overlay, NetworkPolicy support. Scales well.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCilium\u003c/strong\u003e — eBPF in the kernel, L7-aware policies, can replace \u003ccode\u003ekube-proxy\u003c/code\u003e entirely.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eFlannel\u003c/strong\u003e — VXLAN overlay. Simple, no NetworkPolicy.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAntrea\u003c/strong\u003e — OVS-based, uses OpenFlow rules (L2 bridging).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ekindnet\u003c/strong\u003e — what \u003ccode\u003ekind\u003c/code\u003e clusters use by default.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **Calico** — L3 BGP routing, no overlay, NetworkPolicy support. Scales well.\n- **Cilium** — eBPF in the kernel, L7-aware policies, can replace `kube-proxy` entirely.\n- **Flannel** — VXLAN overlay. Simple, no NetworkPolicy.\n- **Antrea** — OVS-based, uses OpenFlow rules (L2 bridging).\n- **kindnet** — what `kind` clusters use by default."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003ekind\u003c/code\u003e&#39;s default subnets are a useful mental model:","text":"`kind`'s default subnets are a useful mental model:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eNodes\u003c/strong\u003e on \u003ccode\u003e172.18.x.x\u003c/code\u003e (Docker bridge).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eServices\u003c/strong\u003e on \u003ccode\u003e10.96.x.x\u003c/code\u003e (ClusterIP range).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePods\u003c/strong\u003e on \u003ccode\u003e10.244.x.x\u003c/code\u003e (cluster CIDR).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **Nodes** on `172.18.x.x` (Docker bridge).\n- **Services** on `10.96.x.x` (ClusterIP range).\n- **Pods** on `10.244.x.x` (cluster CIDR)."},{"kind":"p","html":"Lab 9 §10g showed \u003ccode\u003eregistry.k8s.io/pause:3.9\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003ekindnet\u003c/code\u003e in the node&#39;s image list — the CNI plugin runs as a DaemonSet (one per node) and wires the pod network every time a new pod bootstraps.","text":"Lab 9 §10g showed `registry.k8s.io/pause:3.9` and `kindnet` in the node's image list — the CNI plugin runs as a DaemonSet (one per node) and wires the pod network every time a new pod bootstraps."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Interacting with a cluster — the kubectl starter kit","text":"Interacting with a cluster — the kubectl starter kit"},{"kind":"code","lang":"console","code":"$ kubectl get pods\nNAME              READY   STATUS      RESTARTS   AGE\nweb-5c9f-abcd     1/1     Running     0          2m\nweb-5c9f-efgh     1/1     Running     0          2m\nworker-job-x7q2   0/1     Completed   0          5m\n\n$ kubectl describe pod web-5c9f-abcd\nName:       web-5c9f-abcd\nNamespace:  default\nNode:       worker-2/10.0.0.12\nStatus:     Running\nIP:         10.244.1.47\nContainers:\n  nginx:\n    Image:      nginx:1.25\n    State:      Running\n    Requests:   cpu: 100m, memory: 128Mi\n    Limits:     cpu: 500m, memory: 512Mi\nEvents:\n  Scheduled   2m   default-scheduler   Successfully assigned to worker-2\n  Pulling     2m   kubelet             Pulling image \"nginx:1.25\"\n  Started     2m   kubelet             Started container nginx\n\n$ kubectl logs web-5c9f-abcd\n2026/04/18 10:14:03 [notice] worker processes starting\n\n$ kubectl get po core-k8s -o jsonpath='{.status.qosClass}'\nBestEffort"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003ekubectl exec -t -i &lt;pod&gt; -- &lt;cmd&gt;\u003c/code\u003e runs a command inside the pod — useful combined with \u003ccode\u003ensenter\u003c/code\u003e on the node when you want to see what the kernel sees.","text":"`kubectl exec -t -i \u003cpod\u003e -- \u003ccmd\u003e` runs a command inside the pod — useful combined with `nsenter` on the node when you want to see what the kernel sees."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Checkpoints","text":"Checkpoints"},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Name the 8 Linux namespaces.","a":"PID, NET, MNT, UTS, IPC, USER, CGROUP, TIME. The first five are the ones application containers use for isolation; USER lets an unprivileged host user map to root inside the namespace; CGROUP and TIME are newer and less commonly tested but still on the list."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Why do containers in the same pod share NET but not MNT?","a":"Shared NET is the whole point of the pod — sidecar containers (Envoy, log shippers) can hit the app on `localhost`, and Services have a single IP to load-balance to. But each container ships with its own rootfs image, so sharing MNT would defeat the point. Each container keeps its own MNT namespace so each sees its own filesystem."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Lab 10 §21 observed three pods with different QoS classes. State the rule.","a":"**Guaranteed** = CPU and memory, `requests == limits`, for every container. **Burstable** = at least one resource set, but not all-equal. **BestEffort** = nothing set. Evicted in reverse order (BestEffort first). `core-k8s` with no resources came back as `BestEffort` from `kubectl get po core-k8s -o jsonpath='{.status.qosClass}'`."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A Node fails. What does Kubernetes do?","a":"kubelet stops reporting healthy; apiserver marks the node off-line so the scheduler stops placing new pods there; the Node controller schedules existing pods for deletion and rescheduling onto other nodes; kube-proxy on surviving nodes updates iptables so Services no longer send traffic to the dead node's pods. Attached persistent storage is detached and re-attached at the new pod location."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Pitfalls","text":"Pitfalls"},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003cem\u003eLinux\u003c/em\u003e namespace ≠ \u003cem\u003eKubernetes\u003c/em\u003e namespace. A Linux namespace is one of the eight kernel isolation primitives — a process-level construct. A Kubernetes namespace is a virtual cluster partition (\u003ccode\u003edefault\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ekube-system\u003c/code\u003e, …), just a label for grouping API objects. They share only the word. Quiz 4 set this up as a trap — a question about &quot;namespaces&quot; required knowing which kind was being asked.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e QoS class is \u003cem\u003ederived\u003c/em\u003e from the spec, not declared. \u003ccode\u003eGuaranteed\u003c/code\u003e requires every container in the pod to have equal requests and limits for every resource it lists. Miss one container, list CPU but omit memory, or have requests ≠ limits on any resource — and you drop to \u003ccode\u003eBurstable\u003c/code\u003e. No requests or limits at all on any container → \u003ccode\u003eBestEffort\u003c/code\u003e, first to be OOM-killed under node pressure.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e chroot alone is not isolation. Lab 10 §7a saw 50 host processes from inside a chroot jail because \u003ccode\u003e/proc\u003c/code\u003e was bind-mounted from the host. Real containers combine \u003ccode\u003epivot_root\u003c/code\u003e with a PID namespace \u003cstrong\u003eand\u003c/strong\u003e a MNT namespace that supplies its own \u003ccode\u003e/proc\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePitfall:\u003c/strong\u003e kubelet does not schedule pods. kube-scheduler picks the node; kubelet only executes what apiserver tells it to run. Don&#39;t confuse the two on Q1-style questions.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"},{"kind":"html","html":"\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e Kubernetes is three Linux primitives — \u003cstrong\u003enamespaces\u003c/strong\u003e (isolate view), \u003cstrong\u003ecgroups\u003c/strong\u003e (cap consumption), \u003cstrong\u003echroot / pivot_root\u003c/strong\u003e (restrict filesystem) — plus a scheduler and reconcile loops on top. The \u003cstrong\u003epause container\u003c/strong\u003e holds a pod&#39;s shared NET/IPC/UTS namespaces so siblings can join them. The \u003cstrong\u003ekubelet\u003c/strong\u003e is the node-side executor that applies those primitives via CRI and CNI. \u003cstrong\u003eQoS class\u003c/strong\u003e is derived from resource fields and decides eviction order. \u003cstrong\u003eDaemonSet\u003c/strong\u003e puts exactly one pod on every node. Know those four concepts cold and Quiz 4&#39;s ten questions become pattern-matching you have already done.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e"}]},{"n":11,"id":"4915-lesson-exam-craft-how-the-instructor-tests","title":"Exam craft — how the final tests","hook":"Meta-lesson. Use it in the exam room.","tags":["linux"],"module":"Misc / editors / misc topics","source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md + comp4915_quiz3.md + comp4915_quiz4.md","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"Here are three questions pulled directly from the midterm. Commit to an answer for each before reading further — fix it in your head:","text":"Here are three questions pulled directly from the midterm. Commit to an answer for each before reading further — fix it in your head:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eQ8.\u003c/strong\u003e The Linux command that displays the system manual for most utilities is called:\nA) \u003ccode\u003edisp\u003c/code\u003e &nbsp; B) \u003ccode\u003einfo\u003c/code\u003e &nbsp; C) \u003ccode\u003eman\u003c/code\u003e &nbsp; D) \u003ccode\u003emozilla\u003c/code\u003e &nbsp; E) \u003ccode\u003esysman\u003c/code\u003e","text":"**Q8.** The Linux command that displays the system manual for most utilities is called:\nA) `disp` &nbsp; B) `info` &nbsp; C) `man` &nbsp; D) `mozilla` &nbsp; E) `sysman`"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eQ16.\u003c/strong\u003e How do you make jack the owner of all files under \u003ccode\u003e/home/jack/candy\u003c/code\u003e?\nA) \u003ccode\u003echown -changes jack /home/jack/candy\u003c/code\u003e &nbsp; B) \u003ccode\u003echown -R jack /home/jack/candy\u003c/code\u003e &nbsp; C) \u003ccode\u003echmod u+rwx /home/jack/candy\u003c/code\u003e &nbsp; D) \u003ccode\u003echown -r jack /home/jack/candy\u003c/code\u003e &nbsp; E) \u003ccode\u003echmod a+rwx jack /home/jack/candy\u003c/code\u003e","text":"**Q16.** How do you make jack the owner of all files under `/home/jack/candy`?\nA) `chown -changes jack /home/jack/candy` &nbsp; B) `chown -R jack /home/jack/candy` &nbsp; C) `chmod u+rwx /home/jack/candy` &nbsp; D) `chown -r jack /home/jack/candy` &nbsp; E) `chmod a+rwx jack /home/jack/candy`"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eQ43.\u003c/strong\u003e One of the nice things about Unix is that if you accidentally try to overwrite a file using redirection, you will get a warning so you will not lose data.\nTrue / False","text":"**Q43.** One of the nice things about Unix is that if you accidentally try to overwrite a file using redirection, you will get a warning so you will not lose data.\nTrue / False"},{"kind":"p","html":"Hold those answers. Now for the harder question: \u003cstrong\u003ewhat do these three have in common structurally?\u003c/strong\u003e They test three completely different topics — man pages, \u003ccode\u003echown\u003c/code\u003e flags, redirection. But the mechanism that trips people in each one is the same kind of trap. And that trap appears, in some form, in almost every MCQ and T/F on the exam.","text":"Hold those answers. Now for the harder question: **what do these three have in common structurally?** They test three completely different topics — man pages, `chown` flags, redirection. But the mechanism that trips people in each one is the same kind of trap. And that trap appears, in some form, in almost every MCQ and T/F on the exam."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The exam is a finite set of molds","text":"The exam is a finite set of molds"},{"kind":"p","html":"The midterm isn&#39;t random. Across the 37 MCQs, 10 T/F questions, and 10 short-answer questions, the traps fall into five families that repeat across every module. Once you can name the family, you&#39;ve defused the question&#39;s hardest part — what remains is whether you know the underlying fact.","text":"The midterm isn't random. Across the 37 MCQs, 10 T/F questions, and 10 short-answer questions, the traps fall into five families that repeat across every module. Once you can name the family, you've defused the question's hardest part — what remains is whether you know the underlying fact."},{"kind":"p","html":"This also changes how you budget time. The 100-minute exam carries 144 marks: 74 in MCQs (2 marks each), 10 in T/F (1 mark each), 30 in short answer (3 marks each), and 30 in essays (10 marks each). One MCQ is worth 2 marks. One essay is worth 10 — the same as five MCQs. The students who run out of time spend 5–6 minutes wrestling with one MCQ they&#39;ve never seen and arrive at the essays with 8 minutes left. Knowing the trap families is how you read a question in 30 seconds and move on.","text":"This also changes how you budget time. The 100-minute exam carries 144 marks: 74 in MCQs (2 marks each), 10 in T/F (1 mark each), 30 in short answer (3 marks each), and 30 in essays (10 marks each). One MCQ is worth 2 marks. One essay is worth 10 — the same as five MCQs. The students who run out of time spend 5–6 minutes wrestling with one MCQ they've never seen and arrive at the essays with 8 minutes left. Knowing the trap families is how you read a question in 30 seconds and move on."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Trap family 1 — fake command names","text":"Trap family 1 — fake command names"},{"kind":"p","html":"Q8 is the cleanest example. The five options are \u003ccode\u003edisp\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003einfo\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eman\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003emozilla\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003esysman\u003c/code\u003e. Three of them — \u003ccode\u003edisp\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003emozilla\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003esysman\u003c/code\u003e — are not Linux commands. They&#39;re invented noise. \u003ccode\u003emozilla\u003c/code\u003e is a browser; \u003ccode\u003esysman\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003edisp\u003c/code\u003e don&#39;t exist in the standard toolset. \u003ccode\u003einfo\u003c/code\u003e is real (it&#39;s a GNU documentation viewer), but it&#39;s not the command that covers &quot;most utilities&quot; — \u003ccode\u003eman\u003c/code\u003e is. Two genuine commands, one correct, two distractors that sound authoritative, two that are pure invention.","text":"Q8 is the cleanest example. The five options are `disp`, `info`, `man`, `mozilla`, `sysman`. Three of them — `disp`, `mozilla`, `sysman` — are not Linux commands. They're invented noise. `mozilla` is a browser; `sysman` and `disp` don't exist in the standard toolset. `info` is real (it's a GNU documentation viewer), but it's not the command that covers \"most utilities\" — `man` is. Two genuine commands, one correct, two distractors that sound authoritative, two that are pure invention."},{"kind":"p","html":"This pattern reappears on every test. Q33 in the same midterm asks which command changes your login shell; the options include \u003ccode\u003enewsh\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003echngsh\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003echlg\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ecs\u003c/code\u003e, and \u003ccode\u003echsh\u003c/code\u003e. The recognition rule: if you&#39;ve never typed an option and can&#39;t connect it to a naming pattern, the prior probability that it&#39;s fake is high. You don&#39;t need to know every command — you need to recognize the real ones and eliminate the rest.","text":"This pattern reappears on every test. Q33 in the same midterm asks which command changes your login shell; the options include `newsh`, `chngsh`, `chlg`, `cs`, and `chsh`. The recognition rule: if you've never typed an option and can't connect it to a naming pattern, the prior probability that it's fake is high. You don't need to know every command — you need to recognize the real ones and eliminate the rest."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"The options for \"which command changes your login shell?\" are: `newsh`, `chngsh`, `chlg`, `cs`, `chsh`. Three are invented. Which is real, and how do you eliminate the others?","a":"`chsh` (E). It follows the same pattern as `chown` (change owner), `chmod` (change mode), `chgrp` (change group) — two-letter prefix meaning \"change,\" followed by a one- or two-letter abbreviation for what's being changed. None of the others match that pattern or appear in any lab or module. When you see a cluster of options, look for the one that fits a known naming convention; the rest are filler."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Trap family 2 — flag-case swaps and near-miss syntax","text":"Trap family 2 — flag-case swaps and near-miss syntax"},{"kind":"p","html":"Q6 and Q16 both belong here. The wrong options look almost right — they differ by exactly one character, one flag, or one argument position.","text":"Q6 and Q16 both belong here. The wrong options look almost right — they differ by exactly one character, one flag, or one argument position."},{"kind":"p","html":"For Q6 (\u003ccode\u003efind\u003c/code\u003e): option A is \u003ccode\u003efind -name foo\u003c/code\u003e — missing the required path argument. Option D is \u003ccode\u003efind / foo\u003c/code\u003e — has the path but is missing the \u003ccode\u003e-name\u003c/code\u003e flag. Option C, \u003ccode\u003efind / -name foo\u003c/code\u003e, is correct: path first, then the flag, then the argument. If you have this command memorized precisely, you pick C in under 10 seconds. If you&#39;re fuzzy, options A and C look nearly identical.","text":"For Q6 (`find`): option A is `find -name foo` — missing the required path argument. Option D is `find / foo` — has the path but is missing the `-name` flag. Option C, `find / -name foo`, is correct: path first, then the flag, then the argument. If you have this command memorized precisely, you pick C in under 10 seconds. If you're fuzzy, options A and C look nearly identical."},{"kind":"p","html":"For Q16 (\u003ccode\u003echown\u003c/code\u003e): options B and D are \u003ccode\u003echown -R jack\u003c/code\u003e versus \u003ccode\u003echown -r jack\u003c/code\u003e. Linux flags are case-sensitive. \u003ccode\u003e-R\u003c/code\u003e is the recursive flag for \u003ccode\u003echown\u003c/code\u003e; \u003ccode\u003e-r\u003c/code\u003e is not a valid \u003ccode\u003echown\u003c/code\u003e flag on modern Linux. The same trap appears with \u003ccode\u003egrep -v\u003c/code\u003e (invert match) versus \u003ccode\u003egrep -w\u003c/code\u003e (match whole word) — both are real flags, but only one answers &quot;search \u003cem\u003efor\u003c/em\u003e the word superman.&quot; The heuristic: when two options differ by only a flag or its case, explicitly ask yourself what each flag does before picking.","text":"For Q16 (`chown`): options B and D are `chown -R jack` versus `chown -r jack`. Linux flags are case-sensitive. `-R` is the recursive flag for `chown`; `-r` is not a valid `chown` flag on modern Linux. The same trap appears with `grep -v` (invert match) versus `grep -w` (match whole word) — both are real flags, but only one answers \"search *for* the word superman.\" The heuristic: when two options differ by only a flag or its case, explicitly ask yourself what each flag does before picking."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Two options for a `grep` question are: B) `grep -v superman SuperHeroes` and D) `grep superman SuperHeroes`. The question asks you to search *for* the word \"superman\". Which is correct, and why is B a trap?","a":"D. The `-v` flag inverts the match — it prints every line that does *not* contain \"superman.\" Option B is a near-miss: it looks like \"verbose\" or \"verify\" to someone who only half-remembers the flag. The exam regularly pairs a bare command with a flagged variant when the flag means the opposite of what you want. When you see that pairing, ask what the flag does before selecting it."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Trap family 3 — T/F with &quot;always&quot;, &quot;warns&quot;, &quot;only&quot;, &quot;never&quot;","text":"Trap family 3 — T/F with \"always\", \"warns\", \"only\", \"never\""},{"kind":"p","html":"Q43 is the canonical instance. The statement says you &quot;will get a warning&quot; before \u003ccode\u003e&gt;\u003c/code\u003e overwrites a file. The answer is \u003cstrong\u003eFALSE\u003c/strong\u003e — \u003ccode\u003e&gt;\u003c/code\u003e silently truncates at parse time, before the command even runs. Q44 is the exact mirror: &quot;redirecting output to a file \u003cem\u003ecan\u003c/em\u003e destroy an existing file without error messages&quot; — \u003cstrong\u003eTRUE\u003c/strong\u003e. These two appear back-to-back in the midterm because students who answer Q43 wrong tend to contradict themselves on Q44.","text":"Q43 is the canonical instance. The statement says you \"will get a warning\" before `\u003e` overwrites a file. The answer is **FALSE** — `\u003e` silently truncates at parse time, before the command even runs. Q44 is the exact mirror: \"redirecting output to a file *can* destroy an existing file without error messages\" — **TRUE**. These two appear back-to-back in the midterm because students who answer Q43 wrong tend to contradict themselves on Q44."},{"kind":"p","html":"The tell for this family is a modal word in the stem: &quot;always&quot;, &quot;never&quot;, &quot;warns&quot;, &quot;prompts&quot;, &quot;only&quot;, &quot;automatically&quot;. Universal claims are almost always false on this exam; qualified claims are usually true. A statement that says the system \u003cem\u003edoes something protective by default\u003c/em\u003e — warns you, asks for confirmation, refuses to overwrite — is almost always the trap. Unix tools are designed for pipelines and scripts; they do not hold your hand.","text":"The tell for this family is a modal word in the stem: \"always\", \"never\", \"warns\", \"prompts\", \"only\", \"automatically\". Universal claims are almost always false on this exam; qualified claims are usually true. A statement that says the system *does something protective by default* — warns you, asks for confirmation, refuses to overwrite — is almost always the trap. Unix tools are designed for pipelines and scripts; they do not hold your hand."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"T/F: `\u003e` warns before overwriting an existing file.","a":"FALSE. `\u003e` silently clobbers the destination the moment the shell parses the line — before the command runs, before you can stop it. The old file content is gone immediately. To prevent accidental clobbering you must explicitly enable `set -o noclobber`; then the shell rejects `\u003e` on existing files and you use `\u003e|` to force an overwrite. This is Q43 in the midterm; the word \"warns\" is the bait — no warning is issued under any default configuration."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Trap family 4 — concept-definition precision","text":"Trap family 4 — concept-definition precision"},{"kind":"p","html":"MCQs on \u003ccode\u003ePPID\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eFQDN\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ePAM\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ebit-bucket\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003esuperuser\u003c/code\u003e, and similar terms test the exact definition, not a rough paraphrase. Q26 asks what PPID stands for; the five options are &quot;person process ID,&quot; &quot;protected process ID,&quot; &quot;private process ID,&quot; &quot;protected parent ID,&quot; and &quot;parent process ID.&quot; All five are plausible-sounding. Only E is correct: \u003cstrong\u003eparent process ID\u003c/strong\u003e.","text":"MCQs on `PPID`, `FQDN`, `PAM`, `bit-bucket`, `superuser`, and similar terms test the exact definition, not a rough paraphrase. Q26 asks what PPID stands for; the five options are \"person process ID,\" \"protected process ID,\" \"private process ID,\" \"protected parent ID,\" and \"parent process ID.\" All five are plausible-sounding. Only E is correct: **parent process ID**."},{"kind":"p","html":"The distinction matters technically: the \u003cem\u003eparent\u003c/em\u003e is the process that called \u003ccode\u003efork()\u003c/code\u003e to create the current process. When you run a command from bash, bash is the parent; the command is the child. \u003ccode\u003e$PPID\u003c/code\u003e in a script is the PID of the shell that launched the script — not any other kind of &quot;protected&quot; or &quot;private&quot; relationship. For Q30 (\u003ccode\u003eFQDN\u003c/code\u003e): the answer is &quot;fully qualified hostname,&quot; not just &quot;hostname&quot; — \u003ccode\u003eodyssey.infosys.bcit.ca\u003c/code\u003e is the FQDN; \u003ccode\u003eodyssey\u003c/code\u003e alone is just the hostname.","text":"The distinction matters technically: the *parent* is the process that called `fork()` to create the current process. When you run a command from bash, bash is the parent; the command is the child. `$PPID` in a script is the PID of the shell that launched the script — not any other kind of \"protected\" or \"private\" relationship. For Q30 (`FQDN`): the answer is \"fully qualified hostname,\" not just \"hostname\" — `odyssey.infosys.bcit.ca` is the FQDN; `odyssey` alone is just the hostname."},{"kind":"p","html":"For this family, paraphrase fails. &quot;PPID means parent&quot; is recoverable; &quot;PPID means parent process ID&quot; is the exact answer the mark scheme checks.","text":"For this family, paraphrase fails. \"PPID means parent\" is recoverable; \"PPID means parent process ID\" is the exact answer the mark scheme checks."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Quiz 3 Q5 asks: \"In bash, what exit status indicates success?\" Options include \"0\", \"1\", \"anything nonzero, but 1 is the convention\", and \"-1\". Which is correct and why does option A exist as a trap?","a":"**0**. By Unix convention, a process exits 0 to signal success and any nonzero value to signal an error. The shell stores this in `$?`. Option A (\"anything nonzero, but 1 is the convention\") has the polarity exactly backwards — it's the answer for a student who remembers \"0 is false in most programming languages\" and mistakenly maps that to exit codes. The trap works because it sounds like a careful, nuanced answer."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Trap family 5 — short-answer exactness","text":"Trap family 5 — short-answer exactness"},{"kind":"p","html":"Short-answer questions require exact output or exact command syntax. The instruction on the midterm cover sheet is explicit: each short answer is worth 3 marks, and the answer key shows precise strings.","text":"Short-answer questions require exact output or exact command syntax. The instruction on the midterm cover sheet is explicit: each short answer is worth 3 marks, and the answer key shows precise strings."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eQ50\u003c/strong\u003e — the redirection output question. After running \u003ccode\u003ecat x y 1&gt;hold 2&gt;&amp;1\u003c/code\u003e where \u003ccode\u003ex\u003c/code\u003e doesn&#39;t exist and \u003ccode\u003ey\u003c/code\u003e contains &quot;This is y&quot;, what does \u003ccode\u003ecat hold\u003c/code\u003e show? The answer is both the error \u003cem\u003eand\u003c/em\u003e the file contents:","text":"**Q50** — the redirection output question. After running `cat x y 1\u003ehold 2\u003e&1` where `x` doesn't exist and `y` contains \"This is y\", what does `cat hold` show? The answer is both the error *and* the file contents:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"cat: x: No such file or directory\nThis is y"},{"kind":"p","html":"The shell processes \u003ccode\u003e1&gt;hold\u003c/code\u003e first (stdout goes to the file), then \u003ccode\u003e2&gt;&amp;1\u003c/code\u003e (stderr is duplicated onto whatever stdout currently points to — the file). Both streams land in \u003ccode\u003ehold\u003c/code\u003e, in emission order. If the operators were reversed — \u003ccode\u003e2&gt;&amp;1 1&gt;hold\u003c/code\u003e — stderr would be wired to the terminal first, and then only stdout would move to the file. The wrong answers here are: &quot;just the error message,&quot; &quot;just the file contents,&quot; or &quot;nothing, because x doesn&#39;t exist.&quot; All three are partial truths. The exact answer is both lines in the order they were emitted.","text":"The shell processes `1\u003ehold` first (stdout goes to the file), then `2\u003e&1` (stderr is duplicated onto whatever stdout currently points to — the file). Both streams land in `hold`, in emission order. If the operators were reversed — `2\u003e&1 1\u003ehold` — stderr would be wired to the terminal first, and then only stdout would move to the file. The wrong answers here are: \"just the error message,\" \"just the file contents,\" or \"nothing, because x doesn't exist.\" All three are partial truths. The exact answer is both lines in the order they were emitted."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eQ56/Q57\u003c/strong\u003e — glob matching. The directory contains \u003ccode\u003elibby1.jpg\u003c/code\u003e through \u003ccode\u003elibby12.jpg\u003c/code\u003e and \u003ccode\u003elibby1.txt\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"**Q56/Q57** — glob matching. The directory contains `libby1.jpg` through `libby12.jpg` and `libby1.txt`."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003elibby1*.jpg\u003c/code\u003e matches \u003ccode\u003elibby1.jpg\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003elibby10.jpg\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003elibby11.jpg\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003elibby12.jpg\u003c/code\u003e — every \u003ccode\u003e.jpg\u003c/code\u003e file whose name begins with \u003ccode\u003elibby1\u003c/code\u003e. The \u003ccode\u003e*\u003c/code\u003e matches zero or more characters, so \u003ccode\u003elibby1.jpg\u003c/code\u003e itself (zero extra characters after \u003ccode\u003elibby1\u003c/code\u003e) is included.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003elibby[6-8].jpg\u003c/code\u003e matches exactly \u003ccode\u003elibby6.jpg\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003elibby7.jpg\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003elibby8.jpg\u003c/code\u003e — character class \u003ccode\u003e[6-8]\u003c/code\u003e matches exactly one character in the range 6–8, so \u003ccode\u003elibby10.jpg\u003c/code\u003e is excluded.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- `libby1*.jpg` matches `libby1.jpg`, `libby10.jpg`, `libby11.jpg`, `libby12.jpg` — every `.jpg` file whose name begins with `libby1`. The `*` matches zero or more characters, so `libby1.jpg` itself (zero extra characters after `libby1`) is included.\n- `libby[6-8].jpg` matches exactly `libby6.jpg`, `libby7.jpg`, `libby8.jpg` — character class `[6-8]` matches exactly one character in the range 6–8, so `libby10.jpg` is excluded."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Which files does `libby1*.jpg` match from `libby1.jpg` through `libby12.jpg` plus `libby1.txt`?","a":"`libby1.jpg`, `libby10.jpg`, `libby11.jpg`, `libby12.jpg`. The `*` matches zero or more characters, so `libby1.jpg` is included (the `*` matches the empty string). `libby1.txt` is excluded because `.jpg` doesn't match `.txt`. The common wrong answer is \"libby10, 11, 12 only\" — students read `1*` as \"1 followed by at least one more character,\" but `*` explicitly allows zero characters."},{"kind":"h2","html":"Essays: what the mark scheme rewards","text":"Essays: what the mark scheme rewards"},{"kind":"p","html":"The three essay questions are worth 10 marks each — the same as five MCQs combined. A rough but complete answer here is worth far more than the MCQ you&#39;ve been staring at for four minutes.","text":"The three essay questions are worth 10 marks each — the same as five MCQs combined. A rough but complete answer here is worth far more than the MCQ you've been staring at for four minutes."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eQ58 — compare/contrast hard and soft links\u003c/strong\u003e: The mark scheme rewards structural coverage. Use parallel bullets or a two-column layout, one row per dimension: how it&#39;s created (\u003ccode\u003eln\u003c/code\u003e vs \u003ccode\u003eln -s\u003c/code\u003e), what happens when the original is deleted (hard link survives because it points to the inode; soft link breaks because it points to the path), whether it works across filesystems (hard: same filesystem only; soft: any path), what \u003ccode\u003els -l\u003c/code\u003e shows (hard link shares the inode number with the original; soft link shows an \u003ccode\u003e-&gt;\u003c/code\u003e arrow), and whether directories can be linked (hard: generally not allowed; soft: yes). Five dimensions, five marks, one per covered point.","text":"**Q58 — compare/contrast hard and soft links**: The mark scheme rewards structural coverage. Use parallel bullets or a two-column layout, one row per dimension: how it's created (`ln` vs `ln -s`), what happens when the original is deleted (hard link survives because it points to the inode; soft link breaks because it points to the path), whether it works across filesystems (hard: same filesystem only; soft: any path), what `ls -l` shows (hard link shares the inode number with the original; soft link shows an `-\u003e` arrow), and whether directories can be linked (hard: generally not allowed; soft: yes). Five dimensions, five marks, one per covered point."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eQ59 — write a script\u003c/strong\u003e: Three things the mark scheme checks: the \u003ccode\u003e#!/bin/bash\u003c/code\u003e shebang on line 1 (without it the script is &quot;incomplete&quot; in the instructor&#39;s rubric), command substitution with \u003ccode\u003e$(pwd)\u003c/code\u003e to capture the working directory, and quoting: \u003ccode\u003eecho &quot;Your working directory is $(pwd)&quot;\u003c/code\u003e. The double quotes keep the path intact if it contains spaces. One line of code is the entire answer.","text":"**Q59 — write a script**: Three things the mark scheme checks: the `#!/bin/bash` shebang on line 1 (without it the script is \"incomplete\" in the instructor's rubric), command substitution with `$(pwd)` to capture the working directory, and quoting: `echo \"Your working directory is $(pwd)\"`. The double quotes keep the path intact if it contains spaces. One line of code is the entire answer."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eQ60 — write a function\u003c/strong\u003e: The target answer is \u003ccode\u003eps aux | grep &quot;$1&quot;\u003c/code\u003e wrapped in a function body. Two mark-bearing details: quote \u003ccode\u003e$1\u003c/code\u003e so the argument survives word splitting, and use \u003ccode\u003eps aux\u003c/code\u003e — not bare \u003ccode\u003eps\u003c/code\u003e — because the question specifies the full process list.","text":"**Q60 — write a function**: The target answer is `ps aux | grep \"$1\"` wrapped in a function body. Two mark-bearing details: quote `$1` so the argument survives word splitting, and use `ps aux` — not bare `ps` — because the question specifies the full process list."},{"kind":"h2","html":"The time plan that consistently works","text":"The time plan that consistently works"},{"kind":"p","html":"You have 100 minutes and 144 marks — just under 42 seconds per mark. The allocation that lets you finish:","text":"You have 100 minutes and 144 marks — just under 42 seconds per mark. The allocation that lets you finish:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMCQs (40 min)\u003c/strong\u003e: 1.5 minutes average per question. Any MCQ that runs past 2 minutes gets your best guess and a flag; you return to it in the buffer.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eT/F (8 min)\u003c/strong\u003e: These should be under 45 seconds each if you&#39;ve internalized the trap families.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eShort answer (25 min)\u003c/strong\u003e: 3 minutes each. The answer is exact — don&#39;t over-explain.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eEssays (22 min)\u003c/strong\u003e: Spend 7 minutes on the compare/contrast (the structure carries it), 5 minutes on the one-liner script, 10 minutes on the function with a brief explanation.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBuffer (5 min)\u003c/strong\u003e: Return to flagged MCQs only. Write a guess for anything still open.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"- **MCQs (40 min)**: 1.5 minutes average per question. Any MCQ that runs past 2 minutes gets your best guess and a flag; you return to it in the buffer.\n- **T/F (8 min)**: These should be under 45 seconds each if you've internalized the trap families.\n- **Short answer (25 min)**: 3 minutes each. The answer is exact — don't over-explain.\n- **Essays (22 min)**: Spend 7 minutes on the compare/contrast (the structure carries it), 5 minutes on the one-liner script, 10 minutes on the function with a brief explanation.\n- **Buffer (5 min)**: Return to flagged MCQs only. Write a guess for anything still open."},{"kind":"p","html":"The students who miss this timeline sacrifice essay time to rescue a stuck MCQ. One MCQ is worth 2 marks. One essay with a rough outline is worth 5–6 marks.","text":"The students who miss this timeline sacrifice essay time to rescue a stuck MCQ. One MCQ is worth 2 marks. One essay with a rough outline is worth 5–6 marks."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"pitfall","html":"\u003cp\u003eLeaving MCQs blank costs you nothing extra — there is no negative marking. If you&#39;ve spent more than 90 seconds on a question, write down your best guess, flag it in the margin, and keep moving. With five options you can almost always eliminate two on pure logic (fake command names, impossible flag values), which puts you at 33–50% odds on the remainder. An informed guess beats a blank every time, and the 5-minute buffer at the end is for returning to flags — not for staring at a question you still don&#39;t know cold.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"Leaving MCQs blank costs you nothing extra — there is no negative marking. If you've spent more than 90 seconds on a question, write down your best guess, flag it in the margin, and keep moving. With five options you can almost always eliminate two on pure logic (fake command names, impossible flag values), which puts you at 33–50% odds on the remainder. An informed guess beats a blank every time, and the 5-minute buffer at the end is for returning to flags — not for staring at a question you still don't know cold."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003eThe midterm draws from five trap families — fake command names, flag-case swaps, T/F universal-claim bait, concept-definition precision, and exact-syntax short answers — and they repeat across every module. Recognizing the family costs two seconds; not recognizing it can cost four minutes. Budget 40 minutes for MCQs, 25 for short answers, and 22 for essays; never sacrifice an essay to rescue a stuck MCQ.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"The midterm draws from five trap families — fake command names, flag-case swaps, T/F universal-claim bait, concept-definition precision, and exact-syntax short answers — and they repeat across every module. Recognizing the family costs two seconds; not recognizing it can cost four minutes. Budget 40 minutes for MCQs, 25 for short answers, and 22 for essays; never sacrifice an essay to rescue a stuck MCQ."}]}],"practice":[{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":1,"id":"4915-code-shell-script-print-working-directory-on-one-line","title":"Shell script: print working directory on one line","lang":"bash","tags":["shell","scripting"],"source":"Mod09 Ch28; materials/labs/Lab9.pdf; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q59","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eWrite a complete shell script that prints \u003ccode\u003eYour working directory is\u003c/code\u003e followed by your current working directory, all on one line. Include shebang.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"#!/bin/bash\n# your code here","solution":"#!/bin/bash\necho \"Your working directory is $(pwd)\"","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSource\u003c/strong\u003e: Mod09 Ch28 + Lab 9. Needs shebang (1 mark), correct quoting (1 mark), command substitution (1 mark). \u003ccode\u003e$(pwd)\u003c/code\u003e preferred over backticks. Common wrong: \u003ccode\u003eecho Your working directory is $(pwd)\u003c/code\u003e without quotes — an unquoted path with spaces gets re-split by the shell, and a leading literal-less string loses whitespace formatting; the marker docks for &quot;not one clean line&quot;.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":2,"id":"4915-code-bash-function-grep-processes","title":"Bash function: grep processes","lang":"bash","tags":["text-processing","scripting","processes"],"source":"Mod09 Ch28; materials/labs/Lab9.pdf; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q60","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eWrite a bash function named \u003ccode\u003epsgrep\u003c/code\u003e that takes one parameter and prints processes from \u003ccode\u003eps aux\u003c/code\u003e output containing that parameter. Exclude the grep process itself from the output.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"psgrep() {\n    # your code\n}","solution":"psgrep() {\n    ps aux | grep \"$1\" | grep -v grep\n}","why_html":"\u003cp\u003eFunction syntax (2 marks), \u003ccode\u003eps aux\u003c/code\u003e pipe (1), \u003ccode\u003e&quot;$1&quot;\u003c/code\u003e quoted to handle spaces (1), \u003ccode\u003egrep -v grep\u003c/code\u003e to exclude self-match (2). Alternative: \u003ccode\u003egrep [p]attern\u003c/code\u003e trick.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":4,"id":"4915-code-iptables-allow-ssh-from-subnet-drop-rest","title":"iptables: allow SSH from subnet, drop rest","lang":"bash","tags":["networking"],"source":"Mod08 Ch25; materials/labs/Lab8.pdf","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eWrite iptables commands to (1) allow established connections, (2) allow SSH only from 10.0.0.0/8, (3) drop all other inbound.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"# INPUT chain rules\niptables -F INPUT\n# your rules","solution":"iptables -F INPUT\niptables -A INPUT -i lo -j ACCEPT\niptables -A INPUT -m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT\niptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -s 10.0.0.0/8 -j ACCEPT\niptables -A INPUT -j DROP","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSource\u003c/strong\u003e: Mod08 Ch25 + Lab 8. Allow loopback, allow ESTABLISHED (so responses work), allow SSH from subnet only, DROP everything else. Order matters — rules evaluated top-down; the SSH allow must \u003cem\u003eprecede\u003c/em\u003e the terminal \u003ccode\u003e-j DROP\u003c/code\u003e. Common wrong: writing \u003ccode\u003e-A\u003c/code\u003e after \u003ccode\u003e-P INPUT DROP\u003c/code\u003e without an explicit allow — the default DROP catches the SSH packet and you lock yourself out.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":5,"id":"4915-code-pod-qos-class-from-yaml","title":"Pod QoS class from YAML","lang":"bash","tags":["kubernetes"],"source":"Mod10D; materials/labs/Lab10.pdf; materials/past-exams/comp4915_quiz4.md","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eGiven this pod spec, identify the QoS class and explain why:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-yaml\"\u003eresources:\n  requests: {cpu: 250m, memory: 128Mi}\n  limits:   {cpu: 500m, memory: 512Mi}\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e","starter":"QoS class: ?\nReasoning:","solution":"QoS class: Burstable\nReasoning: Has BOTH requests and limits set for CPU and memory → not BestEffort. requests != limits for either resource → not Guaranteed. Therefore Burstable.","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSource\u003c/strong\u003e: Mod10D CGroups + Lab 10. Decision tree: NO requests+NO limits=BestEffort. All requests==limits=Guaranteed. Anything else=Burstable. Eviction order under memory pressure: BestEffort first, then Burstable, then Guaranteed. Common wrong: calling this &quot;Guaranteed&quot; because both requests and limits are set — Guaranteed requires requests \u003cem\u003eequal\u003c/em\u003e limits for every container and every resource; merely having both present is Burstable.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":6,"id":"4915-code-write-smb-conf-minimal-share","title":"Write smb.conf minimal share","lang":"bash","tags":["linux"],"source":"Mod07 Ch23; materials/labs/Lab7.pdf","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eWrite a minimal smb.conf that exposes /srv/public as share name &#39;public&#39;, writable, guest not allowed.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"[global]\n  workgroup = WORKGROUP\n  security  = user\n\n# add share section","solution":"[global]\n  workgroup = WORKGROUP\n  security  = user\n\n[public]\n  path = /srv/public\n  browseable = yes\n  writable = yes\n  guest ok = no","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSource\u003c/strong\u003e: Mod07 Ch23 + Lab 7. Section header in [brackets]. Required: path, writable. browseable makes it visible in network browser. guest ok=no forces user auth. Test with \u003ccode\u003etestparm\u003c/code\u003e. Common wrong: omitting the \u003ccode\u003e[public]\u003c/code\u003e section header and dropping share directives under \u003ccode\u003e[global]\u003c/code\u003e — samba silently treats them as global options and the share never appears in \u003ccode\u003esmbclient -L\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":7,"id":"4915-code-create-ssh-local-tunnel","title":"Create SSH local tunnel","lang":"bash","tags":["networking"],"source":"Mod06 Ch18; materials/labs/Lab6.pdf","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eYou need to access postgres on db.internal:5432, but only bastion.example.com is reachable from outside. Write the ssh command to forward local port 5432 through bastion.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"# your ssh command","solution":"ssh -L 5432:db.internal:5432 user@bastion.example.com","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSource\u003c/strong\u003e: Mod06 Ch18 + Lab 6. \u003ccode\u003e-L local_port:remote_host:remote_port\u003c/code\u003e. psql then connects to \u003ccode\u003elocalhost:5432\u003c/code\u003e which traverses the SSH tunnel to db.internal:5432 via bastion. Add \u003ccode\u003e-N -f\u003c/code\u003e to background without shell. Common wrong: swapping \u003ccode\u003e-L\u003c/code\u003e for \u003ccode\u003e-R\u003c/code\u003e — \u003ccode\u003e-R\u003c/code\u003e makes the \u003cem\u003ebastion\u003c/em\u003e listen and forwards back to your laptop, which is the opposite direction and exposes your host instead of reaching the DB.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":8,"id":"4915-code-nfs-export-a-directory-and-mount-it","title":"NFS: export a directory and mount it","lang":"bash","tags":["networking"],"source":"Mod07 Ch22; materials/labs/Lab7.pdf","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eExport \u003ccode\u003e/srv/data\u003c/code\u003e read-write to clients on \u003ccode\u003e10.0.0.0/24\u003c/code\u003e. Show the server-side commands and the client-side mount command.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"# server /etc/exports line:\n\n# server apply + firewall:\n\n# client mount command:","solution":"# /etc/exports:\n/srv/data 10.0.0.0/24(rw,sync,no_subtree_check)\n\n# server apply:\nsudo exportfs -ra\nsudo systemctl enable --now nfs-server\nsudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=nfs\nsudo firewall-cmd --reload\n\n# client:\nshowmount -e server.local\nsudo mount -t nfs server.local:/srv/data /mnt/data","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSource\u003c/strong\u003e: Mod07 Ch22 + Lab 7. Grading: exports syntax with client CIDR + options (2), exportfs -ra to apply without bouncing the daemon (1), firewall service=nfs (1), mount syntax server:/path local/path (2). \u003ccode\u003eshowmount -e\u003c/code\u003e is the canonical verify step. Common wrong: putting a space between the CIDR and the \u003ccode\u003e(options)\u003c/code\u003e — \u003ccode\u003e10.0.0.0/24 (rw,sync)\u003c/code\u003e is parsed as &quot;export to 10.0.0.0/24 \u003cem\u003ewith default options\u003c/em\u003e, then apply (rw,sync) to world&quot; — a silent security hole that makes the share world-writable.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":9,"id":"4915-code-samba-share-a-directory-to-user-fred-lab-7","title":"Samba: share a directory to user fred (Lab 7)","lang":"bash","tags":["networking"],"source":"Mod07 Ch23; materials/labs/Lab7.pdf","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eWrite a minimal \u003ccode\u003esmb.conf\u003c/code\u003e exposing \u003ccode\u003e/srv/public\u003c/code\u003e as a share \u003ccode\u003e[public]\u003c/code\u003e, writable, only user \u003ccode\u003efred\u003c/code\u003e allowed. Then list the exact commands to create fred as a Samba user.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"# /etc/samba/smb.conf:\n\n# user creation commands:","solution":"# /etc/samba/smb.conf\n[global]\n  workgroup = WORKGROUP\n  security  = user\n\n[public]\n  path = /srv/public\n  browseable = yes\n  writable = yes\n  guest ok = no\n  valid users = fred\n\n# user creation\nsudo useradd fred\nsudo smbpasswd -a fred\nsudo testparm\nsudo systemctl enable --now smb nmb","why_html":"\u003cp\u003eGrading: global section present with security=user (1), share section name in brackets (1), path + writable + guest ok=no (1), useradd AND smbpasswd -a (2 — common trap: one without the other), testparm before restart (1).\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":10,"id":"4915-code-nis-set-up-a-master-server","title":"NIS: set up a master server","lang":"bash","tags":["networking"],"source":"Mod07 Ch21; materials/labs/Lab7.pdf","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eInitialize a NIS master for domain \u003ccode\u003einfosec\u003c/code\u003e, restrict clients to \u003ccode\u003e192.168.1.0/24\u003c/code\u003e, and start the daemons. Show the command sequence.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"# domain + securenets + init + daemons","solution":"sudo nisdomainname infosec\necho 'NISDOMAIN=infosec' | sudo tee -a /etc/sysconfig/network\necho '255.255.255.0 192.168.1.0' | sudo tee /var/yp/securenets\nsudo systemctl enable --now rpcbind ypserv\nsudo /usr/lib64/yp/ypinit -m","why_html":"\u003cp\u003eGrading: set NIS domain (1), persist in /etc/sysconfig/network (1), /var/yp/securenets with netmask+network (2 — common trap: forgetting or inverting the netmask/network order), start rpcbind + ypserv (1), ypinit -m LAST (1, since it reads the domain set in step 1).\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":11,"id":"4915-code-sendmail-receive-external-mail-lab-7","title":"Sendmail: receive external mail (Lab 7)","lang":"bash","tags":["networking"],"source":"Mod07 Ch20; materials/labs/Lab7.pdf","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eSendmail is installed but only accepts loopback. Make it accept mail from external hosts. List every command and config edit needed, in order.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"# steps:","solution":"# 1. edit /etc/mail/sendmail.mc — change:\n# DAEMON_OPTIONS(`Port=smtp,Addr=127.0.0.1, Name=MTA')dnl\n# to:\n# DAEMON_OPTIONS(`Port=smtp, Name=MTA')dnl\n\n# 2. rebuild sendmail.cf from the .mc:\ncd /etc/mail\nsudo make\n\n# 3. add domain to local-host-names:\necho 'host.example.com' | sudo tee -a /etc/mail/local-host-names\n\n# 4. open firewall:\nsudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=smtp\nsudo firewall-cmd --reload\n\n# 5. restart:\nsudo systemctl restart sendmail\n\n# 6. verify:\nss -tlnp | grep :25   # should show 0.0.0.0:25","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSource\u003c/strong\u003e: Mod07 Ch20 + Lab 7. Grading: remove \u003ccode\u003eAddr=127.0.0.1\u003c/code\u003e in .mc (2), \u003ccode\u003ecd /etc/mail &amp;&amp; sudo make\u003c/code\u003e to regenerate .cf (2 — the #1 skipped step), local-host-names entry (1), firewall service=smtp (1), systemctl restart (1), ss verify (1). Editing .cf directly = zero marks (sendmail regenerates .cf from .mc). Common wrong: editing \u003ccode\u003e/etc/mail/sendmail.cf\u003c/code\u003e directly and restarting — changes work until the next \u003ccode\u003emake\u003c/code\u003e in \u003ccode\u003e/etc/mail\u003c/code\u003e silently overwrites them from the unchanged \u003ccode\u003e.mc\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":12,"id":"4915-code-identify-file-type-from-ls-l","title":"Identify file type from ls -l","lang":"bash","tags":["linux"],"source":"Mod02 Ch6","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eGiven:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-bash\"\u003ebrw-rw---- 1 root disk 8, 0 Apr 18 /dev/sda\ncrw-rw-rw- 1 root root 1, 3 Apr 18 /dev/null\nlrwxrwxrwx 1 root root    7 Apr 18 /bin -&gt; usr/bin\n-rw-r--r-- 1 root root  256 Apr 18 /etc/hostname\ndrwxr-xr-x 2 root root 4096 Apr 18 /etc\nsrw-rw---- 1 root mysql  0 Apr 18 /var/run/mysqld.sock\nprw-r--r-- 1 root root   0 Apr 18 /tmp/pipe\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWhat is each file type?\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"/dev/sda: ?\n/dev/null: ?\n/bin: ?\n/etc/hostname: ?\n/etc: ?\nmysqld.sock: ?\n/tmp/pipe: ?","solution":"/dev/sda: block special (b)\n/dev/null: character special (c)\n/bin: symbolic link (l)\n/etc/hostname: plain file (-)\n/etc: directory (d)\nmysqld.sock: socket (s)\n/tmp/pipe: named pipe / FIFO (p)","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSource\u003c/strong\u003e: Mod02 Ch6 + Lab 2. 7 types total. First char of ls -l line: - plain, d dir, b block, c char, l symlink, s socket, p pipe. Common wrong: confusing \u003ccode\u003eb\u003c/code\u003e (block, buffered — whole disks, partitions) with \u003ccode\u003ec\u003c/code\u003e (character, unbuffered — \u003ccode\u003e/dev/null\u003c/code\u003e, TTYs); the mnemonic is &quot;block = storage, char = stream&quot;.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":13,"id":"4915-code-ssh-tunnel-local-vs-remote-forward","title":"SSH tunneling — local vs remote forward","lang":"bash","tags":["ssh","networking","tunneling"],"source":"materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q34; materials/labs/Lab6.pdf; Mod06 Ch18","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eA PostgreSQL database runs on \u003ccode\u003edb.internal:5432\u003c/code\u003e inside a private network. You cannot reach \u003ccode\u003edb.internal\u003c/code\u003e directly from your laptop, but you can SSH to \u003ccode\u003ebastion.example.com\u003c/code\u003e (on the same private network as db.internal). Write the SSH command that makes \u003ccode\u003elocalhost:5432\u003c/code\u003e on your laptop transparently tunnel to \u003ccode\u003edb.internal:5432\u003c/code\u003e through the bastion.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eSketch the packet path so you can see which side of the tunnel evaluates the destination hostname.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"# Topology:\n#\n#   Laptop (you)            Bastion (gateway)          Private network\n#   ─────────────           ─────────────────          ────────────────\n#   localhost:5432          ??? encrypted tunnel ???   db.internal:5432\n#\n# Your task: write the ssh -L command, then describe which\n# host resolves \"db.internal\".\n\nssh ___:___:___ ___@___","solution":"# ssh -L \u003clocal_port\u003e:\u003cremote_host\u003e:\u003cremote_port\u003e \u003cuser\u003e@\u003cgateway\u003e\nssh -L 5432:db.internal:5432 user@bastion.example.com\n\n# Packet path:\n#   app → laptop:5432 (local listener) --encrypted--\u003e bastion\n#                                                     │\n#                                                     └─\u003e db.internal:5432\n#\n# The \"db.internal\" in the -L argument is resolved by the bastion,\n# not by your laptop. That's why the tunnel works even though your\n# laptop's DNS cannot resolve db.internal.","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSource\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003ematerials/past-exams/midterm.md Q34\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ematerials/labs/Lab6.pdf\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eMod06 Ch18\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMechanism\u003c/strong\u003e. \u003ccode\u003e-L local_port:remote_host:remote_port\u003c/code\u003e creates a \u003cem\u003elocal\u003c/em\u003e forward. Your laptop binds \u003ccode\u003elocal_port\u003c/code\u003e on 127.0.0.1 and accepts connections. Anything the laptop receives on that port is wrapped in the SSH session and unwrapped at the bastion, which then opens a plain TCP connection to \u003ccode\u003eremote_host:remote_port\u003c/code\u003e \u003cem\u003efrom the bastion&#39;s perspective\u003c/em\u003e. That last detail is why you can tunnel to hosts only the bastion can reach.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eContrast with \u003ccode\u003e-R\u003c/code\u003e (remote forward): bastion listens, laptop forwards. Use \u003ccode\u003e-L\u003c/code\u003e when you need to \u003cem\u003ereach\u003c/em\u003e an inside service from outside; use \u003ccode\u003e-R\u003c/code\u003e when you need to \u003cem\u003eexpose\u003c/em\u003e a local service to the inside.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCommon wrong approach\u003c/strong\u003e. Writing \u003ccode\u003essh -L db.internal:5432:5432 user@bastion\u003c/code\u003e — the argument order is \u003ccode\u003elocal_port:remote_host:remote_port\u003c/code\u003e, not \u003ccode\u003eremote_host:local_port:remote_port\u003c/code\u003e. The parser accepts the first field as a port number; a hostname there is a syntax error. Another common mistake: assuming your laptop resolves \u003ccode\u003edb.internal\u003c/code\u003e via its own DNS. It does not — the bastion does.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":14,"id":"4915-code-iptables-packet-flow-and-chain-traversal","title":"iptables — packet flow and chain traversal","lang":"bash","tags":["iptables","firewall","networking"],"source":"Mod08 Ch25; materials/labs/Lab8.pdf; mock-exam.yaml q22","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eBuild a default-deny INPUT chain with three explicit allows:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eInbound SSH from the \u003ccode\u003e10.0.0.0/24\u003c/code\u003e subnet.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eInbound HTTP (port 80) from anywhere.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eReplies to the host&#39;s outbound connections (\u003ccode\u003eESTABLISHED,RELATED\u003c/code\u003e).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eDrop everything else. Then trace two test packets through the chain: a TCP packet to port 22 from \u003ccode\u003e10.0.0.5\u003c/code\u003e, and a TCP packet to port 3306 from \u003ccode\u003e192.168.1.1\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"# Set default policy:\niptables -P INPUT ___\n\n# Rule 1 — SSH from trusted subnet\niptables -A INPUT ___\n\n# Rule 2 — HTTP from anywhere\niptables -A INPUT ___\n\n# Rule 3 — established connections (response traffic)\niptables -A INPUT ___\n\n# Decision tree:\n#\n#   [ inbound packet ]\n#           │\n#   ┌───────┴───────┐\n#   │  INPUT chain  │\n#   │  rule 1?  ────┼──→ match → ACCEPT\n#   │  rule 2?  ────┼──→ match → ACCEPT\n#   │  rule 3?  ────┼──→ match → ACCEPT\n#   │  (no match)   │\n#   └───────┬───────┘\n#           │\n#      default policy: ???\n#           │\n#        DROP / ACCEPT","solution":"iptables -P INPUT DROP\niptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -s 10.0.0.0/24 -j ACCEPT\niptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -j ACCEPT\niptables -A INPUT -m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT\n\n# Trace 1: TCP/22 from 10.0.0.5\n#   rule 1? dport 22 AND src in 10.0.0.0/24 → MATCH → ACCEPT (done)\n#\n# Trace 2: TCP/3306 from 192.168.1.1\n#   rule 1? dport 22 → no   (dport mismatch)\n#   rule 2? dport 80 → no   (dport mismatch)\n#   rule 3? state ESTABLISHED → no   (new connection)\n#   end of chain → default policy DROP → packet dropped","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSource\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eMod08 Ch25 iptables.pdf\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ematerials/labs/Lab8.pdf\u003c/code\u003e, mock-exam.yaml q22.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMechanism\u003c/strong\u003e. iptables evaluates rules top-to-bottom within a chain. The \u003cem\u003efirst\u003c/em\u003e rule whose match conditions all succeed fires its target (ACCEPT, DROP, REJECT, or a jump) and the rest of the chain is skipped. If no rule matches, the chain&#39;s default policy applies — set with \u003ccode\u003e-P CHAINNAME POLICY\u003c/code\u003e. A default-deny (\u003ccode\u003eDROP\u003c/code\u003e) policy with explicit allows is the textbook firewall pattern because new services never leak through by default.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe \u003ccode\u003eESTABLISHED,RELATED\u003c/code\u003e rule is what lets outbound connections receive their replies. Without it, you could open a TCP connection from the host but the return SYN-ACK would hit the default DROP and the connection would hang.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCommon wrong approaches\u003c/strong\u003e:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAppending an allow rule after a terminal DROP at the bottom.\u003c/strong\u003e The DROP fires first; new rules below it are unreachable. Insert with \u003ccode\u003e-I\u003c/code\u003e (insert at top) or renumber.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eForgetting the \u003ccode\u003e-p tcp\u003c/code\u003e when using \u003ccode\u003e--dport\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e iptables requires the protocol match to unlock port matching. \u003ccode\u003eiptables -A INPUT --dport 22 ...\u003c/code\u003e errors out.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUsing the wrong policy chain.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003e-P OUTPUT DROP\u003c/code\u003e instead of \u003ccode\u003e-P INPUT DROP\u003c/code\u003e silently blocks all \u003cem\u003eoutgoing\u003c/em\u003e traffic while leaving the host wide open to inbound. Policy name matters.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":15,"id":"4915-code-iptables-output-default-deny-allow-dns-https","title":"iptables — OUTPUT default-deny, allow DNS + HTTPS","lang":"bash","tags":["iptables","firewall","networking","egress"],"source":"Mod08 Ch25; materials/labs/Lab8.pdf","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eLock down a host&#39;s \u003cem\u003eoutbound\u003c/em\u003e traffic. Set the \u003ccode\u003eOUTPUT\u003c/code\u003e chain to default-deny, then allow only:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDNS queries (UDP port 53) to any resolver.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eHTTPS (TCP port 443) to any host.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eReplies on established connections (so inbound-initiated traffic can be answered).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eLoopback (so local services on the box don&#39;t break).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eDrop everything else outbound. Trace an outbound TCP/22 (SSH) packet to some external host through the chain.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"# Default policy on OUTPUT:\niptables -P OUTPUT ___\n\n# Allow loopback (lo interface):\niptables -A OUTPUT ___\n\n# Allow replies on ESTABLISHED,RELATED:\niptables -A OUTPUT ___\n\n# Allow DNS:\niptables -A OUTPUT ___\n\n# Allow HTTPS:\niptables -A OUTPUT ___","solution":"iptables -P OUTPUT DROP\niptables -A OUTPUT -o lo -j ACCEPT\niptables -A OUTPUT -m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT\niptables -A OUTPUT -p udp --dport 53 -j ACCEPT\niptables -A OUTPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -j ACCEPT\n\n# Trace: outbound TCP SYN to port 22 on some external host\n#   -o lo?                 no   (not loopback)\n#   ESTABLISHED,RELATED?   no   (this IS the new connection's SYN)\n#   udp dport 53?          no   (tcp, not udp)\n#   tcp dport 443?         no   (dport 22)\n#   end of chain → default policy DROP → packet dropped","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSource\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eMod08 Ch25 iptables.pdf\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ematerials/labs/Lab8.pdf\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMechanism\u003c/strong\u003e. OUTPUT governs packets \u003cem\u003eoriginating\u003c/em\u003e on this host. A default-deny OUTPUT policy is an egress firewall — even if an attacker gets code execution, they cannot phone home unless the destination port is in your allow list. DNS on UDP/53 is almost always required (without it, name resolution breaks and every subsequent rule matching by hostname fails). HTTPS on TCP/443 covers package repos, updates, and typical web egress. \u003ccode\u003eESTABLISHED,RELATED\u003c/code\u003e lets the host answer \u003cem\u003einbound\u003c/em\u003e connections it already accepted (e.g. replies to a client that connected to your SSH server).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eLoopback is special: systemd, D-Bus, and many local services talk over \u003ccode\u003elo\u003c/code\u003e. Forgetting \u003ccode\u003e-o lo -j ACCEPT\u003c/code\u003e will lock up local IPC in surprising ways.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCommon wrong approaches\u003c/strong\u003e:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAllowing only TCP/53 and not UDP/53.\u003c/strong\u003e DNS uses UDP for normal queries; TCP is only a fallback for large responses and zone transfers. UDP/53 is the one you need; leaving it out means every resolver lookup hangs until timeout.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eForgetting the \u003ccode\u003eESTABLISHED,RELATED\u003c/code\u003e rule.\u003c/strong\u003e Outbound SYN to 443 is allowed, but the returning ACK never hits an OUTPUT rule at all (it&#39;s inbound) — \u003cem\u003ehowever\u003c/em\u003e, any outbound follow-up packet on that conntrack flow does. Without the state rule, once the TCP handshake completes, subsequent outbound segments on the flow match no explicit rule and get dropped by policy, stalling the connection mid-request.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSetting \u003ccode\u003e-P OUTPUT DROP\u003c/code\u003e before writing the allow rules.\u003c/strong\u003e The moment the policy flips, your current shell&#39;s outbound ACKs (e.g. back to your SSH client) are dropped and you lose the session. Write the allow rules first, flip the policy last.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":16,"id":"4915-code-ssh-remote-forward-expose-local-service-through-bastion","title":"SSH remote forward — expose a local service through a bastion","lang":"bash","tags":["ssh","networking","tunneling"],"source":"materials/labs/Lab6.pdf; materials/past-exams/midterm.md Q34; Mod06 Ch18","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eYou are running a small webhook receiver on your laptop at \u003ccode\u003elocalhost:5000\u003c/code\u003e. A teammate on the internal network needs to hit it from \u003ccode\u003ebastion.example.com\u003c/code\u003e, but your laptop is behind NAT and has no public address. You already have SSH access \u003cem\u003eto\u003c/em\u003e the bastion.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWrite the SSH command that makes \u003ccode\u003ebastion.example.com:5000\u003c/code\u003e forward back to your laptop&#39;s \u003ccode\u003elocalhost:5000\u003c/code\u003e. Then describe the direction of the tunnel.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"# Topology:\n#\n#   Laptop (you, behind NAT)    Bastion (public)           Teammate\n#   ─────────────────────       ──────────────────         ─────────\n#   localhost:5000              bastion:5000 (listens) ←── curl bastion:5000\n#\n# Your task: write the ssh -R command, then describe\n# which side does the listening.\n\nssh ___:___:___ ___@___","solution":"# ssh -R \u003cbastion_listen_port\u003e:\u003claptop_target_host\u003e:\u003claptop_target_port\u003e \u003cuser\u003e@\u003cbastion\u003e\nssh -R 5000:localhost:5000 user@bastion.example.com\n\n# Packet path:\n#   teammate → bastion:5000 (bastion's listener)\n#           --encrypted back through the existing SSH session--\u003e\n#                                                   laptop\n#                                                     │\n#                                                     └─\u003e localhost:5000 (your webhook)\n#\n# \"localhost\" in the -R argument is resolved on the LAPTOP,\n# not on the bastion — it refers to the laptop's own loopback.","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSource\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003ematerials/labs/Lab6.pdf\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ematerials/past-exams/midterm.md Q34\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eMod06 Ch18\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMechanism\u003c/strong\u003e. \u003ccode\u003e-R bastion_port:target_host:target_port\u003c/code\u003e creates a \u003cem\u003eremote\u003c/em\u003e forward. The SSH \u003cem\u003eserver\u003c/em\u003e (bastion) binds \u003ccode\u003ebastion_port\u003c/code\u003e and accepts connections. Anything it receives is pushed back through the already-open SSH session to your laptop, which then opens a plain TCP connection to \u003ccode\u003etarget_host:target_port\u003c/code\u003e \u003cem\u003efrom the laptop&#39;s perspective\u003c/em\u003e. That last detail — target resolution happens on the originating side — is the mirror of \u003ccode\u003e-L\u003c/code\u003e. In \u003ccode\u003e-L\u003c/code\u003e, the remote (bastion) resolves; in \u003ccode\u003e-R\u003c/code\u003e, the local (laptop) resolves.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThis is how you expose a service from behind NAT without opening a port on your router. The outbound SSH session is the only connection your laptop initiates; the bastion reuses it in reverse.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eBy default OpenSSH binds the \u003ccode\u003e-R\u003c/code\u003e listener to \u003ccode\u003e127.0.0.1\u003c/code\u003e on the bastion, so only the bastion itself can reach the forwarded port. To let the teammate connect from a third machine, either connect \u003cem\u003efrom\u003c/em\u003e the bastion (\u003ccode\u003essh user@bastion\u003c/code\u003e then \u003ccode\u003ecurl localhost:5000\u003c/code\u003e), or set \u003ccode\u003eGatewayPorts yes\u003c/code\u003e in the bastion&#39;s \u003ccode\u003esshd_config\u003c/code\u003e and use \u003ccode\u003essh -R 0.0.0.0:5000:localhost:5000 ...\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCommon wrong approaches\u003c/strong\u003e:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUsing \u003ccode\u003e-L\u003c/code\u003e instead of \u003ccode\u003e-R\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003e-L\u003c/code\u003e makes \u003cem\u003eyour laptop\u003c/em\u003e listen and forwards connections \u003cem\u003eout\u003c/em\u003e to a remote host. That is the opposite direction — teammates still cannot reach you.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eExpecting \u003ccode\u003ebastion:5000\u003c/code\u003e to be reachable from outside the bastion without \u003ccode\u003eGatewayPorts\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e Default OpenSSH binds \u003ccode\u003e-R\u003c/code\u003e to \u003ccode\u003e127.0.0.1\u003c/code\u003e on the server, so \u003ccode\u003ecurl bastion.example.com:5000\u003c/code\u003e from a third host fails with connection refused even though the tunnel is &quot;up&quot;.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eReading the argument as \u003ccode\u003elaptop_port:bastion_host:bastion_port\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/strong\u003e The field order is \u003ccode\u003eremote_listen_port:local_target_host:local_target_port\u003c/code\u003e. The target is resolved on the side that originated the SSH session (the laptop), not on the bastion.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"kind":"code","variant":"starter-solution","n":17,"id":"4915-code-nfs-live-remount-ro-without-unmount","title":"NFS — live remount to read-only without unmounting","lang":"bash","tags":["nfs","mount","remount","filesystem"],"source":"Mod07 Ch21; materials/labs/Lab7.pdf","prompt_html":"\u003cp\u003eA production NFS export \u003ccode\u003e/srv/exports/reports\u003c/code\u003e is currently mounted read-write on a client at \u003ccode\u003e/mnt/reports\u003c/code\u003e. You need to switch it to read-only \u003cem\u003ewithout unmounting\u003c/em\u003e — there are open file handles you cannot kill. Then flip it back to read-write.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eShow the client-side commands and explain why \u003ccode\u003eumount\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003emount -o ro\u003c/code\u003e would be wrong here.\u003c/p\u003e","starter":"# Check current mount options:\n___\n\n# Flip to read-only in place:\nsudo mount ___\n\n# Verify:\n___\n\n# Flip back to read-write:\nsudo mount ___","solution":"# Check current state\nmount | grep /mnt/reports\n#   server:/srv/exports/reports on /mnt/reports type nfs (rw,...)\n\n# Remount read-only — keeps handles open, changes mode in kernel\nsudo mount -o remount,ro /mnt/reports\n\n# Verify\nmount | grep /mnt/reports\n#   server:/srv/exports/reports on /mnt/reports type nfs (ro,...)\n\n# Writes now fail without closing handles:\ntouch /mnt/reports/foo            # → Read-only file system\n\n# Flip back\nsudo mount -o remount,rw /mnt/reports","why_html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSource\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eMod07 Ch21 NFS.pdf\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ematerials/labs/Lab7.pdf\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMechanism\u003c/strong\u003e. \u003ccode\u003emount -o remount,&lt;opts&gt;\u003c/code\u003e tells the kernel to re-parse the options on an \u003cem\u003ealready-mounted\u003c/em\u003e filesystem. No unmount happens — open file descriptors stay valid, the superblock stays in place, only the mount flags change. For NFS this flips the client VFS from RW to RO semantics; subsequent \u003ccode\u003ewrite(2)\u003c/code\u003e calls fail with \u003ccode\u003eEROFS\u003c/code\u003e immediately.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eContrast with \u003ccode\u003eumount\u003c/code\u003e: it requires every open handle on the mount to be closed (or fails with \u003ccode\u003eDevice or resource busy\u003c/code\u003e). Killing processes to free handles is often impossible on a production box — log shippers, long-running reports, stateful writers would lose data. \u003ccode\u003eremount\u003c/code\u003e sidesteps that entirely.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe target path (\u003ccode\u003e/mnt/reports\u003c/code\u003e) must be given; options alone are not enough. \u003ccode\u003eremount\u003c/code\u003e also requires at least one existing option or source to match — the simplest form is \u003ccode\u003emount -o remount,&lt;new-flags&gt; &lt;mountpoint&gt;\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCommon wrong approaches\u003c/strong\u003e:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003eumount /mnt/reports &amp;&amp; mount -o ro ...\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e — fails with \u003ccode\u003etarget is busy\u003c/code\u003e if anything holds the mount. Even if it succeeds, open file descriptors on the original mount become stale (ESTALE on NFS) and the application crashes.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eEditing \u003ccode\u003e/etc/fstab\u003c/code\u003e and rebooting\u003c/strong\u003e — works, but is strictly a last resort: it takes the entire client offline, which is much worse than a brief mode flip.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ccode\u003emount -o ro /mnt/reports\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e without \u003ccode\u003eremount\u003c/code\u003e — treated as a new mount request; fails with \u003ccode\u003ealready mounted\u003c/code\u003e or silently stacks a second mount on the same path depending on kernel version.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eExpecting \u003ccode\u003eremount,ro\u003c/code\u003e to demote open write handles\u003c/strong\u003e — it does not. A process that already has the file open \u003ccode\u003eO_RDWR\u003c/code\u003e can keep writing until it closes and re-opens; \u003ccode\u003eremount,ro\u003c/code\u003e only blocks \u003cem\u003enew\u003c/em\u003e writes. Close-then-reopen is the enforcement point.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"}],"cheatSheet":null};
